<HEADLINE>
OLOWOKANDI WILL GET FIRST START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To finesse the politics of playing time, a coach
will emphasize the benefits of an individual finishing _ as opposed
to starting _ a game. But when his team is finished almost before
it starts, a coach may be forced to make alterations.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason why Los Angeles Clippers coach Chris Ford will
start rookie center Michael Olowokandi in tonight's game at
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you don't get off to a good start,'' Ford said, ``you've
got to consider changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: In the Clippers first three games _ all losses _
they have been outscored by an average of 31.3 to 21.3 in the
opening quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is hoping Olowokandi, who produced career highs in points
(17) and rebounds (9) in Wednesday's loss at Vancouver, can make a
difference in his first NBA start. The ex-Pacific star has yet to
experience NBA life with his team in the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the change is the corresponding matchup
bonus; the Suns start 7-foot-2 Luc Longley at center, then send him
to the sidelines in favor of 6-foot-10 forward Danny Manning.
</P>
<P>
   With Olowokandi coming off the bench in the first half of last
Friday's Suns victory at the Sports Arena, the matchup with Manning
was a difficult one for the 7-foot Clipper. But Olowokandi did have
some success with the slower Longley when the two hooked up in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the matchup with Longley is better for Michael,''
Ford said of Olowokandi, who managed three of his five made
field-goal attempts last Friday when Longley was on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   In three games, Olowokandi has averaged 14.3 points and 7
rebounds per game while making 15 of 30 field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Injury report: Forward Rodney Rogers, whose right knee sprain
kept him out of the Chicago and Vancouver games, practiced Thursday
and is expected to play in Phoenix. Rogers had 11 points and 11
rebounds in the season opener with the Suns. Maurice Taylor, who
has started in Rogers' absence, is expected to do the same tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Brian Skinner said his injured left knee is responding to
treatment, and the power forward from Baylor should return within a
week to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only been eight days, guys,'' Skinner said before
providing a convoluted analogy. ``God created the world in seven.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, it's D-minus: In the opening loss to Phoenix, the
Clippers lost the defensive-transition footrace with the Suns'
frontcourt. In the Chicago game, the team was pitiful on the
defensive boards.
</P>
<P>
   So, what did Ford's Clippers not do on defense in Vancouver?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy with the way we gave up middle penetration,''
Ford said. ``After breaking down the film, we counted 17 times that
we gave up the middle; they (Grizzlies) scored 14 times.''
</P>
<P>
   A long way from 16: If you're wondering, Ford isn't even close
to matching his predecessor's record for Clippers coaching
futility.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Bill Fitch began his L.A. run by coaching 16
consecutive defeats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
