<HEADLINE>
LPGA TOUR IS JUST KIDS' STUFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. _ On a multicolored rug emblazoned with the
alphabet, 4-year-old Cori Inkster is putting the roof on a Lego
tower as tall as herself. On a high chair, 1-year-old Drew Killeen
is pawing the remains of an afternoon snack.
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, Kaitland Currier and William Dormann, both 3,
are waking from naps. Just in time: William's mother has arrived to
pick him up.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded as we are by tiny chairs and tables, plastic toys and
horse dolls, Dr. Suess books and Crayon drawings, it's easy to
forget this is not just any child-care center and these are not
just any children.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Presidential Suite of a hotel not far from Oakmont
Country Club, and it has been converted into a day-care facility
during the Valley of the Stars Championship, this week's LPGA Tour
stop. These are some of America's best-traveled pre-schoolers.
</P>
<P>
   Look closer and you see that ``The Cat in the Hat'' rests next
to a copy of Golf World magazine in the book rack.
</P>
<P>
   And that the U.S. map taped to the wall comes with a moveable
``We Are Here'' arrow pointing to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   And that across the room hangs a tournament pairings sheet with
the names and tee times of the kids' favorite players highlighted.
Dana Dormann is highlighted, as are Juli Inkster, Cindy
Figg-Currier, Denise Killeen and a handful of other golfing moms.
</P>
<P>
   Normal kids? Sure they are, except for their precocious grasp of
the concept of room service and their tendency to snap their Legos
together in the shapes of the airports and hotels with which
they're so familiar.
</P>
<P>
   It's been seven years since the LPGA became the first
professional sports association to offer full-time child-care
services to its players, shipping a two-person staff and a
truckload of toys and educational material from town to town, where
they set up in hotel rooms, schools and churches.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, there were about a dozen kids in the service, said
Tony Verive, who bears the unique title of ``LPGA children's
development director.'' Now, there are about 50.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 44 LPGA players have a total of 74 kids _ about 50 of
whom use the service _ and four players are expecting.
</P>
<P>
   This is a light week, with eight kids in the room. During the
summer, roll call will include as many as 24 little Alexas,
Barrons, Erinns and Zacharys, ranging in age from 4 months to 9
years.
</P>
<P>
   The parents pay less than $100 a week for the service sponsored
by Smucker's (all that peanut butter and jelly!). A small price,
considering that for many, no child care would mean either no kids
or no golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It affected my decision to have a child,'' said Cindy
Figg-Currier, who shot a 2-under-par 70 in Friday's first round to
tie for seventh behind leader Annika Sorenstam (67). ``Once the
child care was announced, I got pregnant.''
</P>
<P>
   The real estate business keeps Figg-Currier's husband, Patrick,
home in Austin, Texas, while Cindy is touring. That's a typical
LPGA family, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some players can afford nannies and don't need the service. At
least one has a nanny and uses the service anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the nanny mostly for the weeks that we're home (in
West Palm Beach, Fla.),'' said Catrin Nilsmark, mother of
16-month-old Tuva, after she shot a 68 to tie for second. ``Out
here, it's so convenient to use the day care.''
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA loves to see the child-care service written about. The
news that many of its players are wives and mothers helps to erase
the tour's most tiresome image problem.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the program's biggest impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's OK to be able to travel and have kids,'' said the
Golf Channel's Donna Caponi, who won 24 tour events in a playing
career that ended in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA program is unique no longer. The PGA has one, allowing
wives to follow players on the course without worrying about crying
children. The WNBA has one. Non-sports businesses increasingly
recognize the need for child care.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it's not the ideal family life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when you say, `Why am I doing this?' ''
Figg-Currier said. ``(The kids) say, `I want to go to !ital!my!off!
house and be with my friends!' Kaitland's real close to her dad,
and last night when we hung up the phone after talking to him,
there was a quivering lip.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're real troopers,'' she said of the LPGA kids, ``because
it can be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   But Verive said there might actually be benefits to the extended
touring: The kids exhibit better-than-normal verbal skills, no
doubt thanks to the limited education Verive and assistant Allison
Strandquest provide. And they have no shortage of friends, since
their classmates are mostly the same from city to city.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the same nannies and the same toys every week. That
(stability) is sometimes lacking in our vagabond lifestyles,'' Dana
Dormann said.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty normal under the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Now get up, William. Your mom's back from the course.
</P>
</TEXT>
