<HEADER>
A4081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-1STLD-WR     02-13 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE VERDICT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 2ndtake, 1st graf in section under subhead `Order in the
Senate' to add phrase on Lott's post-acquittal comments. Minor
editorial refinements throughout. No other changes. ) (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Feb. 13:
</P>
<P>
   In a season of frailty, the Constitution has prevailed once
again.
</P>
<P>
   It remains the great anchor rock of the Republic, enduring
through partisan storms in the Congress, immune in the end to even
so large and unpredicted a betrayal as a president's dereliction of
duty.
</P>
<P>
   If history were written on the same principles that govern news
articles, that would be the lead of the sad story of William
Jefferson Clinton and how he was spared to finish his second term.
Neither the cheapness of Clinton's liaison with Monica Lewinsky nor
the zealotry of some of his opponents should cause us to overlook
the grandeur and symmetry of the constitutional template that on
Friday produced the acquittal of the president on two articles of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The Process
</P>
<P>
   Alarmists had argued that allowing the legal and constitutional
processes to deal with Clinton's offenses would do irreparable harm
to the political system. We had long believed that far greater harm
would flow from some kind of enablers' compact by which Congress
and the public agreed to ignore Clinton's disrespect of the
presidency, his obvious lies and his clumsy efforts to tamper with
the legal process. Although first the House and then the Senate
refused to adopt the resolution of censure advocated in this space,
we celebrate the outcome for making a point that is more important
and more lasting than this presidency. That point is simply that
American history has not yet produced a governmental conundrum that
could not be solved by careful adherence to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The President's Words
</P>
<P>
   It is to be hoped that Clinton's brief and somber Rose Garden
response to the acquittal will set the tone for the days ahead, for
it contained an admission heretofore missing in the serial evasions
and blame-layings that brought him to such a low pass. At long
last, he apologized ``for what I said and did to trigger these
events and the great burden they have imposed on the Congress and
on the American people.'' Clinton has been years too slow to
acknowledge that whatever the excesses of the other players _ some
of whom may yet be punished by the voters or the law _ this buck
started and stopped with the president.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Clinton found out on Dec. 6, 1997, that Ms.
Lewinsky was on the witness list in the Paula Jones case. He had 42
days before his sworn deposition on Jan. 17, 1998, to figure out a
way to avoid lying under oath. But his premeditated decision to lie
threw everything out of whack. The nation's legal system is not
designed to deal with blatantly irrational conduct, in this case a
calculated decision to violate the law by the person with the
utmost constitutional authority to uphold it. In the Rose Garden on
Friday, in an appearance of 82 seconds, Clinton got it at last. He
did ``trigger these events,'' and not just by reckless sexual
conduct. He plunged himself and the nation into crisis by turning
his White House into a factory for the weaving, stitching and
patching of a fabric of lies that was bound to unravel no matter
how many workers Clinton put to the task.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Starr's Exit
</P>
<P>
   We shall never know, probably, just what the man thought he was
doing, or why, by the agencies of courage and truth, he could not
extricate himself. Perhaps he does not know himself. But if he is
willing to continue this reality-based contrition and get back to
the legislative business he has outlined, he deserves certain
benefits. One has to do with the future of the investigation by the
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr. That future needs to be, in a
word, short.
</P>
<P>
   Any thought by Starr of indicting the president now or after
2000 or through the use of sealed indictments would be, in
political terms, offensive to the Constitution, and in personal
terms, nutty. Starr heard that Friday from his biggest supporter in
Congress, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., and he had better listen. This
matter has been adjudicated in the manner prescribed by the Framers
of the Constitution. As an investigation and prosecutorial matter
involving Starr, it is over. The charges were not of a magnitude to
warrant removal, and that having failed, they are not of a scale to
justify either the prosecution of a sitting president or pursuit of
a former one. If Congress wants to consider resolutions of censure
or petitions or other instruments of condemnation, they may do so
without the independent counsel's services.
</P>
<P>
   As for other investigative targets, Starr needs to indict them
or clear them and begin closing his operation. Meanwhile, the
investigation authorized into his prosecutorial techniques must
proceed according to normal Justice Department procedures. The
question of whether he lied to Attorney General Janet Reno about
contacts with Paula Jones' lawyers is a serious one. If he did, he
must be examined with the same rigor applied to the investigation
of Clinton's offenses. However that comes out, the main business
with which Starr was entrusted has been settled by the House and
Senate, and it is time for him to return to the private labors to
which he seemed so powerfully attracted.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The House's Blunders
</P>
<P>
   To commend the following of constitutional design is not to
dismiss the mistakes that prevented an earlier solution to this
matter. Those failures began in the House, where the Republican
majority too quickly succumbed to Starr's overly conclusionary
initial findings. Hyde, the Judiciary chairman, and Robert
Livingston, the would-be speaker, wasted many opportunities to
guide the Republicans toward a censure resolution that seemed from
the start more proportional to Clinton's offenses than impeachment
and removal. Their mistakes could be laid to bad judgment, but our
vote goes for cowardice. They were both intimidated by the majority
whip, Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Texas, into supporting impeachment. If the
House managers want to blame someone for their defeat, they could
do worse than DeLay. More than any other person, he created the
atmosphere that sent them across the Capitol to argue a case that
was not strong enough to meet the constitutional standard for
removing a president.
</P>
<P>
   The managers varied widely in their abilities. Asa Hutchinson,
R-Ark., was devastating, George Gekas, R-Pa., looked irrelevant,
and Ed Bryant, R-Tenn., was easily outpointed by Ms. Lewinsky. But
all seemed infected by the decorum of the Senate and perhaps even
by the somber, focused argument of their chief adversary, White
House Counsel Charles Ruff. The managers could never recover,
however, from Hyde's defining strategic blunder. Having ruled out
fact witnesses as unnecessary in the House, he could not sell the
argument that they were suddenly essential in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Order in the Senate
</P>
<P>
   The Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, R-Miss., and his
Democratic counterpart, Tom Daschle, D-S.D., obviously learned from
watching the House. They firmly defeated early efforts by Hyde and
the House managers to set the rules for the Senate trial. As a
result, the Senate proceedings were fair and dignified and never
seemed out of control, even though Lott's remarks about the
president after his acquittal were ill advised. Given the fact that
it was obvious from the start that the 67 votes for removal were
not there, Lott did a solid job of containing the frustrations and
incendiary instincts of the most conservative members of his
caucus. He could not, however, prevent Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas,
from performing with his usual smarmy disingenuousness.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm blocked the bipartisan censure movement. He described his
motives as constitutional, but they were clearly based on tactics.
He wanted to prevent moderate Republican senators from opting for
censure before the final vote, and he also wanted to deny Democrats
the ability to say during the 2000 campaign that they had delivered
a just punishment to their own president.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the remarkably prescient Framers of the Constitution
could reach forward in time to invest every senator with good
judgment. But their design was vindicated in remarkable ways. The
Senate, with its longer terms and smaller membership, was intended
to be a cistern from which the water of wisdom could be drawn in a
dry time, and so it was. They intended that making the chief
justice the presiding officer would add another element of balance,
and William Rehnquist did more than fulfill that role with his
calm, taciturn rulings. He also resisted admirably the temptation
to make himself an actor rather than a stage manager in this drama.
</P>
<P>
   What Will Endure
</P>
<P>
   As the curtain fell in windy Washington, it seemed more than
ever a drama of tragical lineament. That is to say, the conflict
that swirled all round the stage originated from the conflict
within the protagonist's mind. Clinton and his constituents must
look there for even a partial understanding of the hash he has made
of his one and only presidency. Given what has been wasted, it is
understandable that Clinton would be drawn to blame a conspiracy
rather than his own addiction to reckless pleasures and bad advice.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the end, we still believe that Clinton's tragedy is a
personal rather than a general one. With respect, we disagree with
Arthur Schlesinger Jr.'s conclusion that because America has had a
weak president it now has a weakened presidency. The people
stepping forward from both parties to compete for the office look
capable of treating it with honor. And Congress has just
demonstrated that an impeachment based solely on partisanship
cannot succeed under a process that, like the presidency itself, is
founded on so steadfast a rock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
