<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 STANLEY GILLETTE, 81, CLOTHING INDUSTRY EXECUTIVE  
 MIDI GARTH, 83, CHOREOGRAPHER AND DANCER  
 ALBERT B. HUDES, 75, FUND-RAISER FOR OPERA  
 IRWIN WATSON, 70, TV AND CLUB COMEDIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stanley C. Gillette, a former clothing industry
executive, died on Feb. 4 at his home in New York City. He was 81
years old.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was prostate cancer, said his wife, Joan.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette joined Phillips-Jones, the manufacturer of Van Heusen
brand shirts and other men's wear, in 1947 as a regional sales
manager. He rose to the position of vice president in charge of
sales in 1954 and was named a director the next year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, Gillette was promoted to vice president for marketing
at the company, a family-held corporation that changed its name to
Phillips-Van Heusen in 1957. As vice president for marketing, he
was responsible for sales, advertising and marketing. Gillette was
named executive vice president of Phillips and president of Van
Heusen Co., a subsidiary, in 1963, positions he held for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette left Phillips in 1975 to become chairman and president
of McGregor-Doniger, a men's sportswear manufacturer. In 1979, he
joined Ship 'n Shore, part of General Mills Fashion Group, as
chairman and president, where he was also a vice president of
General Mills.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Gillette left General Mills to start a management
consulting company. He retired in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Gillette attended City College, Columbia University and New York
University. He worked in the apparel industry in New York after
serving in World War II in the Army medical corps before he joined
Phillips-Jones.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by a daughter, Patty
Gillette of Sleepy Hollow, N.Y.; a son, Richard, of Forestville,
Calif.; four grandchildren, and one great-grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   Midi Garth, 83, Choreographer and Dancer
</P>
<P>
   Midi Garth, a modern-dance choreographer and performer known for
her individuality, died on Jan. 28 at the Jewish Home and Hospital
in Manhattan. She was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garth came to prominence in the mid-1950s with dances
notable for a spareness and precision of gesture unusual in a time
of literary and psychological dances. She later established a small
ensemble but was best known for solos like her signature 1959
``Anonymous,'' in which movements were whispered rather than
shouted, as Don McDonagh put it in his ``Complete Guide to Modern
Dance.'' Dressed in black with her head covered, Ms. Garth
alternated between twitches and aimless swaying, driven, it seemed,
by the sound of a metronome.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garth was much praised in the 1950s. John Martin, writing in
The New York Times, described her as ``a dancer born and bred, with
a natural gift for movement'' and ``a single-mindedness that
commands and holds the attention.'' But by the late 1960s and into
the late '70s, when Ms. Garth performed infrequently, her dances
were described as cold and obscure.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Garth, who was born in New York, studied at the New Dance
Group and at the Martha Graham school, where her teachers included
Louis Horst. Her greatest influence was Sybil Shearer, with whom
she worked in Chicago. Ms. Garth also taught dance.
</P>
<P>
   No immediate family members survive.
</P>
<P>
   Albert B. Hudes, 75, Fund-Raiser for Opera
</P>
<P>
   Albert Beryl Hudes, who organized galas that raised millions of
dollars for the New York City Opera and March of Dimes Birth Defect
Foundation, died Monday at his home in Manhattan. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   He had suffered from a bone-marrow cancer called multiple
myeloma and from chronic kidney failure, said his friend and
co-executor, Stephen Kirschenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Hudes (pronounced HEW-dees) held degrees from Harvard and Yale
and was a foreign service officer in the 1950s. After a corporate
career in the 1960s and '70s, he served as director of development
for City Opera and as a consultant to the March of Dimes.
</P>
<P>
   Beverly Sills, the chairwoman of Lincoln Center and former
general director of City Opera, credited Hudes with having raised
$1 million for the opera in a single night _ Oct. 27, 1980 _ at a
farewell gala on the occasion of her final performance as an opera
singer. Patrons paid up to $1,000 a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jennifer L. Howse, president of the March of Dimes, said the
Gourmet Galas organized by Hudes in the 1980s were the ``premier
fund-raising events'' for the charity, typically raising $750,000
in a night.
</P>
<P>
   Hudes is survived by his sister, Ethel Linn of Coconut Creek,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin Watson, 70, TV and Club Comedian
</P>
<P>
   Irwin C. Watson, a comedian who appeared frequently on
television in the 1950s and '60s and in nightclubs throughout the
country, died on Feb. 1 at the Winter Park Memorial Hospital in
Orlando, Fla. He was 70 and lived in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, said his wife, Edlyne O. Watson.
</P>
<P>
   Watson belonged to the generation of black comedians that
included Redd Foxx and Slappy White, with whom he performed.
</P>
<P>
   He was a familiar presence on the television shows of Johnny
Carson, Ed Sullivan, Mike Douglas and many others. He also
performed with singers, including Sammy Davis Jr., Bobby Darin,
Dakota Staton, Shirley Bassey, Gladys Knight, Aretha Franklin and,
most recently, Natalie Cole.
</P>
<P>
   He also appeared at most of the major resort hotels in the
Catskills and Poconos.
</P>
<P>
   Watson toured West Africa in 1981. He performed on Norwegian
American Cruise Line ships up to the time of his death.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by two children, Rodwin
and Regina, of Brooklyn, and two sisters, Bernice O'Neil of
Brooklyn and Cynthia Thorp of Barbados.
</P>
</TEXT>
