<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGSNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS START TO FEEL INVINCIBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ It remains to be seen whether the Los
Angeles Kings' dramatic comeback Thursday against Philadelphia will
be remembered as the event that turned their season around or
simply a pleasant break in a year rife with disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   They'll begin to find out at 6:30 tonight when they play host to
the Dallas Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the mood around the Kings clearly was lighter than it
recently has been, the result of a three-goal rally in the final
3:08 Thursday night that turned a 3-1 deficit against the Flyers
into a 4-3 victory. Jozef Stumpel scored the game-winner with
0:00.3 on the clock with a 60-foot blast that deflected off Flyers
defenseman Eric Desjardins and through the pads of goalie Ron
Hextall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big difference I notice is the atmosphere in the dressing
room,'' coach Larry Robinson said following Friday's practice at
the Forum. ``Everybody is kind of upbeat, laughing and giggling.
It's great to be able to go home and be able to feel great about
something for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Rob Blake said, ``You can just see the excitement.
It's a huge difference. But the thing is we've got to build off it.
You can see the excitement. There hasn't been that much of it
around here for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory over the Flyers moved the Kings (19-29-4) to within
four points of Edmonton in the race for the eighth and final
playoff berth in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was similar to a 5-4 victory over Detroit on March
31, 1979, in which they rallied with goals in the final 2:57 by
Butch Goring, Charlie Simmer and Mike Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings became only the second team this decade to win a game
with a goal in the last second. Pierre Turgeon scored with one
second left to give Montreal a 4-3 victory over Toronto on Oct. 21,
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have scored the game-winner with one second left two
other times in their history. Ross Lonsberry scored with one second
left in a 5-4 victory over the New York Rangers on Jan. 28, 1970,
and Steve Kasper scored in the last second of a 6-5 victory over
Vancouver on Oct. 13, 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers weren't the only ones surprised by the Kings'
comeback. After Thursday's game, Kings media relations director
Mike Altieri returned to his office and turned on the television
just in time to hear Channel 13 report on its sports report that
the Kings had lost to the Flyers 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Even deal: Two forwards who have appeared in a combined 50 games
this season and have failed to score a single goal changed uniforms
when the Kings traded left wing Eric Lacroix to the New York
Rangers for center Sean Pronger, a former member of the Mighty
Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings acquired Lacroix, 27, from Colorado in October for
center Roman Vopat and a 1999 sixth-round draft choice. In 34 games
this season, Lacroix has recorded one assist.
</P>
<P>
   Pronger, 27, is the older brother of St. Louis Blues star
defenseman Chris Pronger. Sean Pronger began the season in the
Pittsburgh Penguins' organization, but was traded to the Rangers in
November. He had three assists in 16 games with New York.
</P>
<P>
   Murray close: Robinson said right wing Glen Murray, sidelined
since Jan. 2 with a torn medial collateral ligament in his right
knee, might return to the lineup as soon as Monday, when the Kings
play host to the Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who began skating Monday, was more cautious in his
prediction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally my decision, how my leg feels and if I feel good
enough,'' Murray said, adding that a return Monday against the
Ducks hardly is carved in stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``But (returning) next week, I've kind of carved in stone,''
said Murray, who plays on the power play, kills penalties and is
second in scoring on the Kings with 28 points despite missing the
past 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Defenseman Mark Visheau, sidelined with a congenital
urinary tract obstruction, is expected to undergo surgery next week
and miss the rest of the season.... Winger Steve McKenna skated
Friday for the first time since suffering an abdominal strain on
Dec. 9.... Winger Sandy Moger was struck by a puck and suffered a
broken nose about 30 seconds after scoring his goal Thursday night.
He said he can play wearing a shield, but Robinson said he might
hold Moger out of the lineup tonight to give him a rest.... Andrew
Felix and Kimberly Decker of Huntington Beach are scheduled to be
married tonight at the Forum before the third period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
