<HEADLINE>
UCLA FALLS TO STANFORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA's grasp on the Pacific-10 Conference women's
race has slipped.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Lindsey Yamasaki's 3-point basket with 3.8 seconds
remaining lifted Stanford to an 87-84 victory over the 12th-ranked
Bruins on Friday night at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   That basket also dropped UCLA (18-6, 10-2) into a first-place
tie with Oregon. Stanford (13-9, 9-2), also drew closer with its
sixth straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal got a career-best 34 points and 39 minutes from
senior Regan Frueur. Her previous high was 23. Carolyn Moos added
17 points and 11 rebounds, and Yamasaki had 14.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins got 22 points each from Maylana Martin and LaCresha
Flannigan. Crescenta Valley High graduate Michelle Greco added 11
points.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA made up a 13-point deficit in the final seven minutes,
tying the score at 84 on a Flannigan free throw with 25.8 seconds
to play. The Bruins also cut a 12-point halftime deficit down to
one earlier in the half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
