<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-HURRICANE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS ONLY HOPE THIS IS BOTTOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Home not-so-sweet home.
</P>
<P>
   Another goal for Brian Leetch. Alas, however, another game with
only one goal. And in the end, another numbing defeat for the
Rangers at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   After their 3-1 loss to the Carolina Hurricanes Friday night,
the Rangers (20-25-7 over all, 11-12-2 at home) are a game below
.500 at the Garden this season and a season-high five games under
.500 over all.
</P>
<P>
   Home-ice advantage?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been no advantage wherever we've been,'' said Leetch, the
Rangers' captain.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's defeat, coupled with Washington's victory over
the Devils, dropped the Rangers into 12th place in the Eastern
Conference, ahead of only the lowly Islanders and the pitiful Tampa
Bay Lightning. Eight conference teams make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible,'' Wayne Gretzky said of the Rangers' play at
home. ``And I think we should be extremely embarrassed by it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have scored one goal or less in 21 games this
season, so Friday night they went out and acquired a gritty forward
in Eric Lacroix. Trouble is, he has not scored a goal this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lacroix's an aggressive hockey player,'' Coach John Muckler
said. ``He works hard. He's an initiator, a grinding type of
player, which is something we need.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Rangers really need is more goals. Curtis Leschyshyn,
in the first period, and Sami Kapanen, in the second, each scored
on weird deflections for Carolina. And after skating through a
pedestrian first 40 minutes, the Rangers trailed, 2-0, after two
periods.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the Rangers were able to level 20 shots on
Carolina goaltender Arturs Irbe before the second intermission. But
shots are not goals. And because most of them came from long range,
and went straight into Irbe's body, there were very few rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Things have become so bad at home for the Rangers that when the
public address announcer announced the last minute of play in the
second period, some fans started cheering. Others began to jeer
Petr Nedved, who has just two goals in his last 17 games. And when
the period ended, the fans _ predictably _ showered the Rangers
with boos.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the hard-hitting defenseman Jeff
Beukeboom was kneed in the back of the head by Martin Gelinas in
the final two minutes of the period and did not return. Beukeboom,
who complained of dizziness, will be re-evaluated Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Leetch briefly rallied the Garden crowd 40 seconds into the
final period with his third goal in three games (after Leetch had
gone 23 games without a goal). But Bates Battaglia put the game
away for Carolina at 8 minutes 30 seconds of the period by chopping
a high pass from Ray Sheppard out of mid-air and past Mike Richter
for a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Leetch's goal was the only bright spot for the Rangers. It was
set up by Todd Harvey, who made a Gretzky-ish pirouette and curl
down left wing, before passing to Leetch at the top of the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Leetch blasted a slap shot off Irbe and into the net. Harvey had
an assist in his first appearance after missing 10 games with a
sprained medial collateral ligament in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   The goal _ Leetch's ninth of the season _ moved the defenseman
into a tie for 18th place on the Rangers' goal-scoring list with
Tomas Sandstrom at 173. But even though the Rangers fired 31 shots
on Irbe, Leetch's goal was their only one.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Rangers can't even score on the power play. They went 0
for 5 Friday night and are 5 for their last 52 over their last 12
games. With only 30 games left in the regular season, the Rangers
are in real danger of missing the playoffs again.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's discouraging is that we have to as a team understand
and realize that we're fortunate enough to be in a position where
we are still battling for a playoff spot,'' said an obviously
miffed Gretzky, who was double-shifted at times on Friday night.
``And we just keep giving games away. And it's always the same
way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' said Richter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's brutal,'' Mathieu Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   During the game, the Rangers announced that they had traded
center SEAN PRONGER to the Los Angeles Kings for left wing ERIC
LACROIX, the son of Colorado General Manager PIERRE LACROIX. It was
the second time this season Lacroix has been traded. His father
dealt him earlier after Lacroix _ who requested the deal _ had
played just seven games this season with the Avalanche. In 34
games, Lacroix has no goals and one assist with a minus-7 rating.
In a television interview, Rangers President NEIL SMITH
characterized Lacroix, 27, as ``a third- or fourth-liner; a
hustling, hard-checking player.''
</P>
<P>
   For Pronger, too, it was the second trade this season. He was
acquired from Pittsburgh on Nov. 25 with PETR NEDVED and CHRIS
TAMER for ALEKSEI KOVALEV and HARRY YORK. In 16 games this season,
14 with the Rangers, Pronger has no goals and three assists with a
minus-3 rating. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 0059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
