<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-CAPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS DROP THEIR THIRD STRAIGHT AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In their attempt to get back in rhythm
playing in front of their fans, the Devils have been trying just
about everything. For Friday's encounter against the Washington
Capitals, for example, the Devils even eliminated the traditional
morning skate.
</P>
<P>
   But as in the previous two games here, losses to Toronto and
Vancouver, the Devils had a great deal of difficulty playing at
home Friday night and endured their third consecutive loss at
Continental Arena, 3-2, to the Capitals. The loss extended the
Devils' streak without a victory at home to five games (0-4-1) and
gave the Capitals their sixth consecutive victory, their longest
winning streak in six years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the bright spots for the Devils in the previous two
losses _ and in the nine games before that _ had been their
efficiency in killing penalties.
</P>
<P>
   But that ability failed on Friday. The Devils entered the game
having allowed just one goal on 37 manpower advantages for the
opposition over the last 11 games, but in the second period they
allowed the Capitals two power-play goals 2 minutes 22 seconds
apart. It proved costly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The special teams didn't do well tonight,'' said goalie Martin
Brodeur, who faced 21 shots, ``but you don't win anything in the
regular season. We're going through a tough stretch right now. It's
frustrating, but we showed some improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   The power-play goals came after Petr Bondra opened the scoring
for the Capitals 3:54 into the game during confusion in front of
Brodeur. Then Lyle Odelein tied it at 1-1, 5:44 into the second
period, from high in the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Bulis put the Capitals ahead by 2-1 when he scored the first
power-play goal 7:14 into the period. He beat Brodeur with a clean
shot to the near post from the top of the right circle.
</P>
<P>
   The second power-play goal came after a crisp exchange between
Bulis and Steve Konowalchuk in limited space near Brodeur.
Konowalchuk got the return pass for his 11th goal of the season,
from close range on the right 9:26 into the period.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Pederson brought the Devils within 3-2 with his eighth
goal of the season when he converted Sykora's pass from the left
side with 7:07 left in the second period. It was the last bright
moment in the game for the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, who are 11-11-5 at home and 29-18-6 over all, showed
some improvement, but they failed to play with a high level of
intensity until the third period, especially in the late stages of
the period.
</P>
<P>
   They had a marvelous opportunity to tie the score after they
were awarded a man advantage with 1:16 left, when Washington's
Andrei Nokolishin was penalized for delay of game by gloving the
puck, and the Devils pulled Brodeur to have six skaters against
four.
</P>
<P>
   Randy McKay scored what appeared to be a goal in the frantic
final moments with 18.9 seconds left, but the whistle had blown and
the official said that Mark Tinordi of Washington had covered the
puck with his glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was behind the goal on the other side,'' McKay said of the
referee, Terry Gregson. ``He was in no position to see.''
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   The losing streak at home is starting to reflect on the
attendance. A crowd of 14,111 showed up for the game, rather poor
on a Friday night against a rival in the Eastern Conference. . . .
With Carolina visiting Saturday night, Coach ROBBIE FTOREK gave BOB
CARPENTER the night off. &UR;  &LR;  ... SERGEI BRYLIN &UR;  &LR; and KEVIN DEAN were
the scratches for the Devils. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
