<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-PREDATORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREDATORS GOALIE SMOTHERS ISLANDERS' SCORING CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ If there is a new reality for the Islanders,
it is not so different from the old reality.
</P>
<P>
   The work ethic that the team's new coach, Bill Stewart, tried to
hammer home following its lackluster effort against Washington
might have taken root, but it did not work Friday night. Despite
what Stewart called 17 dead-on scoring chances, it was the
expansion Nashville Predators who skated away with the 2-1 victory
at Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville goalie Mike Dunham, with 40 saves, had a brilliant
game, making spectacular stop after spectacular stop, particularly
during a feverish third period in which the Islanders tried
desperately to score _ to no avail. They dropped to 16-33-5, and
with 28 games left in the regular season they are 16 points from
the last playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we played pretty hard,'' said Stewart, who is 3-4-2
since taking over as coach from Mike Milbury. ``We had 41 shots on
goal. We had numerous scoring chances. Unfortunately, we didn't put
the puck in the net. We created enough scoring chances to come away
with more than one goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with Kenny Jonsson, their top defenseman and power-play
leader, back in the lineup, the Islanders were unable to take
advantage of a number of opportunities in the first two periods.
</P>
<P>
   Having gone 2 for 45 on power plays during Jonsson's nine-game
absence with a sprained knee, the Islanders scored Friday while
skating with a two-man advantage. The goal came 9 minutes 40
seconds into the game.
</P>
<P>
   With right wing Tom Fitzgerald (interference) and the center
Sebastien Bordeleau (obstruction-holding) in the penalty box and
the Predator defense keying on Jonsson, Trevor Linden fielded a
bullet pass across the goal mouth from Craig Janney and banged the
puck past Dunham for his 13th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Dunham signaled what kind of a game he was going
to have with a dazzling glove save on a hard shot by right wing
Mariusz Czerkawski that would have given the Islanders a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the difference,'' Stewart said of Dunham, formerly a
backup with the Devils. ``He made numerous first stops and second
stops. Their goaltender outdueled our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the first period, with the Predators having just killed
off power play No. 4, Nashville center Cliff Ronning beat Islanders
goalie Felix Potvin on his stick side to tie the game. The goal
came at 16:37.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Predators were outshot by the Islanders, 26-17,
through the first two periods, they were able to take advantage of
Potvin even as the Islanders continued to be frustrated by Dunham.
</P>
<P>
   At 14:06 of the second period, right wing Sergei Krivakrasov
picked up a pass from Ronning and knocked the off-balance shot
through Potvin's legs to a chorus of boos from the announced crowd
of 10,324. That goal gave the Predators a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders continued to pepper Dunham through the final
period, especially on power play No. 6, at 12:40, but there was no
getting anything past the 26-year-old goalie, who is 12-12-2 this
season. Potvin dropped to 1-6-1 in eight games since the Islanders
obtained him in a trade with Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look reality in the face and move on,'' Stewart
said. ``We're looking for respectability around the league, and
wins do that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
