<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-WOMEN'S-BASKETBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REIGN IN MAINE GOES ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Take a look at the University of Maine now and at the same point
last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Bears are 17-5 and leading the America East Conference
_ as they were last season. And their leading scorer once again
averages more than 23 points per game and ranks in the top four
nationally in scoring.
</P>
<P>
   But grab your magnifying glass and you'll see that these Black
Bears are vastly different than last season's NCAA Tournament team.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is Cindy Blodgett, the school's all-time leading scorer and
the NCAA's fourth all-time leading scorer
</P>
<P>
   In Blodgett's place is junior Jamie Cassidy, who stands 7 inches
taller than her predecessor. But don't tell her that she took
Blodgett's place, because she didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole team has to fill her shoes, it's not just me,''
Cassidy said. ``Its definitely different because we have more ball
movement this year and we're harder to defend. I still miss playing
with her, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Cassidy, who averaged 17.6 points last season as a sophomore and
averages 23.4 points per game this season _ fourth in the nation _
has 15 games this season with 20 or more points. She scored 41
points against Middle Tennessee. She has led the Black Bears in
scoring 18 times and in rebounding 14 times.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the numbers, her argument about the team _ not her _
filling Blodgett's shoes has merit; junior guard Amy Vachon is
fourth in the nation in assists, averaging 8.2 per game, and two
other players average in double figures in points.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one replaces Cindy, but I knew Jamie would have a banner
year,'' Maine coach Joanne Palombo-McCallie said. ``She is the
prototype post player. She's naturally comfortable with her back to
the basket, but she is a great passer and has the ability to go by
people.''
</P>
<P>
   As her game grows, maybe Cassidy's name will become as
synonymous with Maine basketball as Blodgett's was.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flattering because she's a great player, but we've gotten
tired of it,'' Cassidy said. ``It seems like every question is
about her, and just because she isn't here, people expected us not
to be as good.''
</P>
<P>
   The players are different, but the results stay the same.
SPOTLIGHT: VIRGINIA TECH'S TERE WILLIAMS
</P>
<P>
   Despite growing up in Chapel Hill, N.C., home of North Carolina,
Virginia Tech forward Tere Williams grew up dreaming of one day
playing for Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had it all planned out: Duke would sign her and she
would finish her basketball career as a Blue Devil. One problem:
Duke backed off during her senior year and the dream was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Those dashed dreams have turned into a nightmare for schools
that wavered on her, because Williams has become the Hokies'
leading scorer and rebounder the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Duke backed off, I was thinking I would get an academic
scholarship and go there,'' Williams said. ``I didn't know where
Virginia Tech was or that they were 9-22 the year before I got
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-11 Williams was the Atlantic-10 co-rookie of the year
last season as the Hokies made the NCAA Tournament, advancing to
the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought this would happen,'' Williams said. ``What
freshman thinks they're going to lead their team in scoring? I
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, she has improved her scoring (16.4) and rebounding
(7.8) to team highs for No. 11 Tech (22-1 before its game
yesterday) which is having its best season ever. Those are nice
statistics, but Williams has her mind on something larger. The
Final Four perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going the distance,'' Williams said. ``I've never
played in a title game ever, and somewhere along the line I want to
play in one. That's going the distance.''
JUNIOR COLLEGE RUSH
</P>
<P>
   In about two weeks, coaches will begin the annual rush for the
top junior college players.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, which has five teams ranked in the top 10 in the latest
Top 25 National Junior College Athletic Association poll, has some
of the top JC players in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Yalika Barnes of top-ranked Trinity Valley has signed with
Alabama, and Tyler Junior College guard Stacy Goudeau has signed
with Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The real prize, however, might be 5-8 guard Karlita Washington
of eighth-ranked Howard College.
</P>
<P>
   ``What sets her apart is that she can create her own shot off
the dribble and she's a good enough shooter to play the two-guard
spot at the Division I level,'' said Lady Hawks coach Matt Corkery,
whose team is 23-2.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, who signed with Nebraska after completing her high
school career in Washington, D.C., is being recruited by Rutgers,
Old Dominion, Kansas, Florida and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   She averages more than 20 points per game and cannot sign a
letter of intent until the first week of April.
BABY FEST '99
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State coach Charli Turner Thorne gave birth to her first
child, Conor Troy, at 3:55 a.m. Tuesday in Tempe, Ariz. He weighed
8 pounds, 3 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old coach returned to practice Thursday to prepare
the Sun Devils to play archrival Arizona today.
</P>
<P>
   Before ASU's game against Washington on Feb. 6 _ her due date _
Thorne said: ``I asked them to inspire me. After the game I went
back in and told them that they had inspired me and now I'm ready
to push.''
</P>
<P>
   About two hours before Thorne's delivery, in the same hospital,
ASU associate director of athletics Sandy Hatfield Clubb gave birth
to her first child, Tristan Lee.
HIRE ME
</P>
<P>
   Sam Jankovich, Cal State-Northridge interim director of
athletics, says he has a problem: He isn't sure whether coach
Frozena Jerro will coach next season.
</P>
<P>
   Here's your answer: Hire her.
</P>
<P>
   Jerro, given the basketball job on an interim basis in November
after Mike Abraham resigned amid federal drug trafficking charges,
is one victory from leading the Matadors (14-6, 8-2 in the Big Sky)
to a school record for victories in a season in Division I.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a great barometer,'' Jankovich said. ``We're going to
get the best basketball coach we can get, but yet, they're going to
have to compare to her, and that's a pretty good comparison. We're
going to have her as the person everyone has to measure up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Two possible factors working against her are age _ she's 27 _
plus that she is two years removed from coaching at a junior high
school.
Games To Watch
Today's Games
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 Connecticut (21-3, 14-1) at No. 8 Old Dominion (18-3,
12-0), 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, if the Huskies lose, perhaps they won't be impervious
to receiving votes outside the top five.
</P>
<P>
   No. 6 Notre Dame (20-2, 12-2) at No. 9 Rutgers (21-4, 13-1), 1
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers must win to have keep pace with UConn for the Big East
title. Sunday's games
</P>
<P>
   No. 1 Tennessee (22-1, 11-0) at No. 17 Auburn (18-4, 8-3), 2
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Good news for the Lady Tigers: after the Lady Vols nearly lost
to Vanderbilt, expect them to be more focused.
</P>
<P>
   No. 14 North Carolina (22-5, 9-4) vs. No. 18 Virginia (17-6,
10-3), noon.
</P>
<P>
   The Tar Heels are one game back of UVA for second place in the
ACC. Tuesday's games
</P>
<P>
   No. 16 Iowa St. at No. 21 Kansas, 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are tied for second place in the Big 12, but Kansas
is prone to late-game collapses.
</P>
