<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SCHEDULE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHEDULE TO PICK UP FOR STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Brett Hull had a great idea earlier in the
season.
</P>
<P>
   At least he thought it was a great idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said that what the NHL needs to do is have you
play every other night for the entire season,'' the Stars winger
said. ``I think that's what all players want, just a nice
consistent pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheduling conflicts and travel problems aside, Hull's plan
sounds like a perfect scenario. And that's exactly what the Stars
will face for the remainder of the season. At least in principle.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars play their final 34 games over 66 days, beginning last
night in a late game against the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim at the
Arrowhead Pond. And while there are back-to-back situations and
relatively long homestands followed by relatively long road trips,
the Stars say they're happy about the pace and ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sitting around doesn't do anyone any good,'' Stars
defenseman Craig Ludwig said of a 10-game span in which the Stars
played only one game. ``We've always played well when we play a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ludwig has a point. The Stars rolled up their franchise-best
15-game unbeaten streak earlier in the season when they played
those games in 33 nights. They are 12-0-4 in back-to-back games and
last season were 23-11-2 when playing on consecutive nights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to play well when we get in a groove,'' Stars center
Mike Modano said. ``That's just who we are as a team. For the past
three years we've been a team that likes to play every other day,
that doesn't think about the next game or the last game, just the
game we're playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock prepared for the ensuing onslaught
when the Stars play their next 13 games in 22 days by allowing them
to take two days off without skating in Newport Beach, Calif. While
Hitchcock said the team might have short-term rust because of the
off days, he said he believes they will be better off in the long
run.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to restingat the beginning of the final flurry,
Hitchcock also has prescribed rest days within the schedule.
Players like Guy Carbonneau, 38, and Ludwig, 37, will likely get
some practice days off and possibly a game or two of rest. With
center Brian Skrudland out 4 to 6 weeks with torn rib cartilage,
Carbonneau will become an even more important member of the fourth
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look at things like that and keep close tabs on it
as the days go on,'' Hitchcock said. ``We might have to give some
days off or switch the lineups around. That said, we are in the
business of winning and we're going to put the lineup out there
that has the best chance of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he hasn't decided whether he should bring in
extra players from the Michigan K-Wings to add depth. Left wingers
Jason Botterill, Jamie Wright, Dave Roberts and Jon Sim are
candidates to join the team. But Hitchcock said he doesn't want to
bring in players and let them sit the way defenseman Sergey Gusev
has.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to be here, we want them to play,'' Hitchcock
said. ``Wherever they are, we want them to be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Stick around enough during this schedule and there should be
playing time for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to go,'' defenseman and captain Derian Hatcher
said. ``We've been waiting for this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
