r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES_ARENA-AZR     02-13 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_ARENA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURKE WON'T STAY AT AWA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coyotes owner Richard Burke, responding to reports about a
possible $10 million renovation plan to America West Arena, said he
has no intention of keeping his NHL team at the downtown Phoenix
arena beyond the 2000-2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   That is when the club's five-year lease agreement with the
building ends, and it's also the time Burke expects the Coyotes to
begin play in a new 20,000-seat hockey arena that would be the
centerpiece of Los Arcos redevelopment project in south Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   A reconfiguration plan to America West Arena, which would
address the 4,500 sight-obstructed seats at hockey games, will be
unveiled in less than two weeks, sources told ``The Arizona
Republic'' on Wednesday. The sources also said the plan has been
endorsed by the city of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Burke, however, said the Coyotes never have been contacted or
consulted on any new renovation plans. He also questioned whether
the plan actually exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it and I don't care at this point,'' he said.
``For the record, we've never got a proposal from them about
anything. Not one single time in two years have we received
anything regarding improvements for us at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, we've already made it clear we cannot go down two
different routes at the same time. We're committed to the Los Arcos
project. There are no alternatives at America West Arena. Our lease
there is up in 2{ years. Los Arcos is the only option available to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Solving the sight-obstructed seat problem, Burke said, isn't
enough to keep the team's interests at America West. The hockey
club, which will lose an estimated $4 million or more this season,
doesn't reap enough revenue streams through luxury suits or signage
to financially continue operating out of the downtown arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't stay there. Financially, it just doesn't make any
sense,'' Burke said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a Michigan architecture firm developed a $20 million
renovation plan that was designed to eliminate most of the
obstructed-view seats. But it would have required shutting down the
arena for at least two summers, and arena management deemed it too
costly.
</P>
<P>
   Arena management, a subsidiary of the Suns organization, sought
to develop a cheaper alternative but hasn't revealed details.
</P>
<P>
   NHL Commissioner Gary Bettman, the man who helped broker a deal
between the arena and the then-Winnipeg Jets/Burke, said he backs
the Coyotes' pursuit of a new arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any question that no major league team
could survive long term in America West Arena under the current
circumstances,'' Bettman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Bettman said the obstructed-view seats and lease conflicts _
such as exclusivity clauses that prevent the Coyotes from selling
some sponsorships _ make the arena unworkable for a hockey team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're more gate dependent than the other leagues. While our
network (television) revenues have increased 12-fold in the last
five years, we're still lagging behind the other leagues by a
contract or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke said the Los Arcos arena ``will get done,'' but he openly
worries if the project is being sabotaged by outsiders. He
questioned the timing of various rumors that have circulated at key
points along the project's path, including talk this week that he
may be on the verge of selling the Coyotes' franchise _ a month
before a referendum vote on the arena issue.
</P>
<P>
   Burke vehemently denied the rumor Thursday night. He has been
seeking potential investment parters, however, since co-owner
Steven Gluckstern sold his share in the Coyotes back to Burke last
year to become an owner of the New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no earthly idea where these things come from and I
don't care,'' Burke said. ``It isn't important to me. I'd just
appreciate whoever's doing it to stop.'' &QL; 
Staff writer Kent Somers contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
