<SLUG> BC-OLY-CASSTEVENS-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPICS' BIG STENCH WILL LINGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Posing as a member of the International Olympic
Committee is the only way to travel.
</P>
<P>
   I flew here . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``First class,'' the flight attendant said.
</P>
<P>
   Winking, she ushered me from the back of the main cabin to the
front of the plane, where she informed an elderly woman that 1A was
``my'' seat. She would have to sit somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The chardonnay was delightful.
</P>
<P>
   During lunch, I hardly noticed what sounded like a cane rapping
angrily against the inside of the toilet door.
</P>
<P>
   A limo driver waiting at the gate held a sign: ``Mr.
Samaranch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's me,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   At the hotel, the bellman put away my luggage and opened the
drapes in the presidential suite. ````Anything'' else, sir?''
</P>
<P>
   I tipped him $5.
</P>
<P>
   He gave me $500 in change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some extra towels?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, thanks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How about a Rolex? Need a nose job? Free root canal? Jazz
tickets? Maybe a fur coat for the wife?''
</P>
<P>
   It is fortunate that the Winter Olympics won't begin until 2002.
This community will need three years to clean up its house and its
image and its air.
</P>
<P>
   Corruption produces an odor, like rotten meat. The foul smell
may never completely go away.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to say who is more despicable, the Salt Lake
people who did everything they could to buy the Olympics or the IOC
members whose votes were for sale.
</P>
<P>
   If you think the Starr Report was offensive, try reading the
300-page ethics panel report.
</P>
<P>
   Before Salt Lake City was awarded the Winter Games, bid
committee members provided cash, free vacations including Super
Bowl trips and free medical treatment to at least 24 IOC members
and their families.
</P>
<P>
   One executive loaned the wife of an IOC member $30,000. He
transferred the money from his children's trust account.
</P>
<P>
   The son of an IOC member from Swaziland received $110,000 in
tuition and living expenses from the bid committee while attending
the University of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   During visits to Salt Lake, IOC members and families went on
shopping sprees. They charged host committee credit cards $268 for
lawn equipment, $524 for a violin, $673 for doorknobs.
</P>
<P>
   At one department store, IOC delegates spent $7,054 for
fragrances. ``Eau de'' ``phew''. &QL;  &QL; 
Family fun &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Claude Ganga is a first-ballot nominee for induction into
the Olympic Scandal Hall of Fame. He is a gold medalist. Ganga
apparently didn't have one hand out; he had both.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ethics report, the Salt Lake committee spent
$250,000 on the IOC member and his family. On visits here, Ganga
even brought his mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   The Ganga family took full advantage of Salt Lake's
comprehensive health plan. Jean-Claude was treated, free of charge,
for hepatitis. His mother-in-law underwent a hip replacement
operation. His wife had cosmetic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Claude and eight other IOC members have resigned or been
expelled. Three others are under investigation. One received a
warning. Another died, maybe from embarrassment. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   IOC guidelines called for members to to accept gifts worth no
more than $150. President Juan Antonio Samaranch accepted a limited
edition rifle worth $9,000. What kind of example is he? &QL;  &QL; 
Man at the top &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch allowed the abuses of power to go unchecked. One-fifth
of his membership has been implicated in the bribes-for-votes
scandal. Yet the leader of this five-ring circus hasn't offered to
step down himself.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, it seems, there is a new revelation into wrongdoing.
No wonder John Hancock Insurance canceled $20 million in TV ads to
protest the IOC's handling of the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   What should be done to those with dirty hands? Resignations and
expulsions aren't enough. They should be ``punished,'' especially
old Jean-Claude.
</P>
<P>
   In 2002, I'd make him judge ice dancing. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 0149EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
