</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-SANFRANCISCO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE FALLS TO USF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Among the 3,509 in War Memorial Gym on Friday
was a certain San Francisco resident dressed in jeans and a light
blue shirt. Although best known for his acting and comedy routines,
he likely found no humor in the sloppy, grinding game he witnessed
from the top row.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Robin Williams probably saw better basketball on Ork
than he did in San Francisco's 56-44 victory over Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   This was worse than Patch Adams. The Waves committed a
season-high 27 turnovers and shot a season-low 31 percent from the
field. Leading scorer Jelani Gardner made 1 of 11 shots and
committed five turnovers. Forward Kelvin Gibbs, the No. 2 scorer,
was 0 for 5 and had six turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys that this may be the most discouraging loss
since we've been here,'' said third-year Pepperdine coach Lorenzo
Romar. ``We've never been in a position with this much at stake. If
we have a successful weekend, we go home with a chance to play for
the conference championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Waves (17-9, 8-3) trail Gonzaga by two games with
three remaining. The Bulldogs may have the regular-season title
secured before they visit Pepperdine next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves' season _ and postseason _ hinges on their ability to
purge this defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems this has been a pretty resilient group,'' Romar said.
``We lost to Gonzaga pretty good (last month) and won our next
(six). We lost to Loyola Marymount (last week), and the next night
we played our best game of the year (against LMU).''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco had lost 15 of its previous 17 and wasn't much
better Friday. The Dons committed 16 turnovers and shot 42.2
percent from the field, but they executed when it counted _
outscoring Pepperdine 7-2 to break the game open in the final
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Senior guard Gerald Zimmerman, fully recovered from a right
wrist injury that kept him out of four recent games, led the Dons
with 23 points and staked them to a 21-9 lead with several early
baskets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, we have bad starts,'' Dons coach Phil Matthews said.
``This was very important for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Waves held USF without a field goal for eight minutes to
start the second half and took their first lead with 12:28 left.
But instead of capitalizing, Pepperdine snoozed. Its offense shut
down, plagued by a series of bad passes and ill-timed shots, and
its defense softened, allowing the Dons to convert back-to-back
layups and take a 42-35 lead with 7:18 left.
</P>
<P>
   A timeout appeared to settle the Waves, who closed to 44-40 on
Gardner's 3-pointer from them left wing _ his only basket _ and
Gibbs' free throws.
</P>
<P>
   But the inspiration did not last. Pepperdine committed turnovers
on three of its next four possessions.
</P>
<P>
   With under two minutes left, Zimmerman dribbled past Tommie
Prince, slashed down the right side and scored a layup despite Marc
McDowell's foul. The three-point play gave the Dons a 51-42 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 0151EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4107 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-CSUN-CROWE-LADN     02-13 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CSUN-CROWE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN'S CROWE WANTS ONE MORE SHOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He wasn't a member of the team. He did not
participate in any practices.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1995, Jason Crowe was a student at Wayne State
University in Detroit. A part-time student, he claims. A full-time
student, the NCAA says.
</P>
<P>
   So when Crowe comes off the bench for the Cal State Northridge
men's basketball team tonight against Montana State, he may be
playing in his final home game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to look at this as my last game in front of this
crowd,'' Crowe said. ``Coach (Bobby) Braswell always says to treat
each game like it might be your last.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the NCAA, Crowe is completing his ninth semester.
College athletes are granted five years _ 10 semesters _ to play
four. That would give Crowe just one more semester of eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN is petitioning the NCAA to grant Crowe an extra semester,
making him available for all of next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely feel I have a good case,'' Crowe said. ``For two
reasons. One, I was a part-time student at Wayne State. Second, I
didn't participate in any practices with the team. I wasn't on the
team. I didn't gain any advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Inglewood High in 1994 (where he was a
teammate of current Boston Celtic Paul Pierce), Crowe attended
Wayne State for two semesters. In the fall, he took nine units; in
the spring 11.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA generally regards students taking 12 units to be
full-time. Crowe also took a ``withdrawal'' from a class that
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe, who is scheduled to earn his degree in mathematics next
December, didn't know about the oversight until last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of his college career reads like a travelogue. In 1995,
Crowe transferred to L.A. Trade Tech, a junior college, where he
averaged 21 points and seven assists for one season.
</P>
<P>
   Then he transferred to American University in Washington D.C.
But Crowe left American even though he ``fell in love with the
school and the atmosphere,'' after coach Chris Knoche was fired. He
enrolled at CSUN, where he sat out the 1997-98 season because of
the NCAA's rule on four-year transfer students.
</P>
<P>
   His constant movement in college has taken a toll; he has
started just five of the Matadors' 23 games and is averaging 4.1
points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I'm not putting up big-time numbers, I'm starting
to understand what I can accomplish at this university,'' Crowe
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing only 18 minutes per game, Crowe is second on the
team in assists with 86.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely has been solid for us,'' CSUN coach Bobby
Braswell said. ``Jason is willing to do whatever you ask him to do.
Every time he steps out on the floor he gives 100 percent; he gives
us a lot of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowe was hard on himself after going 0 for 6 from the field in
the Matadors' 74-68 loss to Montana on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Crowe missed two layups and two free throws, all in the final 10
minutes. He played despite a 103-degree fever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I hurt the team by playing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the NCAA decision on his petition looming, he said he
didn't have a choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never want to miss a game,'' he said. ``I don't want to lose
my spot in the rotation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
