<HEADLINE>
BRUINS BURNED BY CALGARY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ They had played giant killer in their last
game, going into Colorado to face the red-hot Avalanche, who had
won 12 straight.
</P>
<P>
   The Flames played David to their Goliath Tuesday night and ended
the impressive streak.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, former Bruin coach Brian Sutter's young team won
its third in a row, as Jarome Iginla tipped in a shot with 3.4
seconds left in regulation to give Calgary a 4-3 victory over the
Bruins that ended the visitor's modest three-game unbeaten streak
(2-0-1).
</P>
<P>
   Flames right wing Valeri Bure scored a power-play goal against
the league's best penalty killers at 14:19 of the third period to
give the Flames a 3-2 lead, but Joe Thornton tied it at 18:55 as
the game appeared headed into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins struck first when left wing Sergei Samsonov tallied
his 19th goal midway through the opening period. Samsonov collected
the puck in the neutral zone and zoomed up the right side, teeing
up a slapper from high in the right circle that sailed past goalie
Fred Brathwaite at 7:54. The bad news was that Samsonov was lost
late in the second period after running into his own teammate in
open ice.
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov said it's a charley horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw (Jason Allison),'' said Samsonov, who left the building
on crutches. ``I was trying to get out of the way. But somehow I
hit his knee. It was pretty bad, I guess. It tightened up right
away. I couldn't move my leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Samsonov has been on a decent offensive clip of late, although
he had his point streak snapped at three games Tuesday night
against Edmonton. He has four goals and 5 points in his last five
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had other chances in the period in which they outshot
the Flames, 11-6. During a Calgary power play, Rob DiMaio picked
off a pass by defenseman Cale Hulse in the Boston zone and took off
down the ice with Anson Carter on a two-on-none. DiMaio made a move
and tried a backhander from the slot, but the goalie gloved it. The
Flames turned up the heat in the second, tying the game and then
taking the lead during a 21-second span.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary, which outshot Boston, 15-9, pulled even during a power
play at 5:02. Defenseman Phil Housley moved the puck up to right
wing Theo Fleury at the right point. Fleury relayed the puck to
left wing Cory Stillman, who skated down the slot and beat goalie
Byron Dafoe with a backhander at the right post.
</P>
<P>
   The Flames went up, 2-1, on a fluky goal at 5:23. Defenseman
Chris O'Sullivan fired the puck to Stillman, who appeared to fan on
his shot. The puck caromed off the end boards and right out to
defenseman Denis Gauthier in front. Gauthier put it past Dafoe for
his first NHL goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave them the game, we gave them two goals in the second
period,'' said a very unhappy coach Pat Burns. ``One on a bad
change. We battled back to tie the game and we lose our coverage
and they get a goal. It's very disappointing.'' Allison pulled the
Bruins even at 2-2 on the power play at 14:57. Defenseman Mattias
Timander, just summoned from Providence to take the place of Darren
Van Impe, who suffered a separated shoulder against the Oilers,
dumped the puck in at the left side of the blue line. Allison
stripped the puck from defenseman Steve Smith along the right-wing
boards and then darted in toward the net, burying it past
Brathwaite for his 15th goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
