<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ President Clinton plans to announce
on Saturday that he will send U.S. troops to Kosovo as part of a
peacekeeping force to be formed if an agreement is reached among
the warring parties, administration officials and diplomats said on
Friday. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-ARAFAT (Jerusalem) _ Arafat said he's interested in a
Palestinian-Jordan confederation. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ Transcripts of phone conversations of
the oligarch/tycoon Boris Berezovsky give an inside look at the
Russian power war. He leans on President Yeltsin's daughter for a
tax break, plants stories with his media outlets and tries to
influence a parliamentary document. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-TURKEY (Istanbul, Turkey) _ Turkey reassured the United
States on Friday that, despite a visit Monday by Tariq Aziz, the
Iraqi foreign minister, Turkey will continue to let the U.S. use
its base there to attack Iraq. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-VALENTINE (TERNI, Italy) _ Terni, an ailing, unromantic
town of steel mills and chemical plants, has one claim to fame: the
shrine of St. Valentine. For the last few years, Terni has labored
to recast itself as the international city of love. But this St.
Valentine's day, Terni is mainly becoming known as the city of
hate. By Alessandra Stanley. With graphic.
</P>
