of negligent marketing practices, is likely to encourage many more
lawsuits using the same legal approach. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SUSPECT-MEMORIAL (New York) _ The pine coffin holding the
body of Amadou Diallo, the West African immigrant killed by police
gunfire, became the centerpiece of both an emotion-fraught memorial
service Friday and a furious demonstration against racism and Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   AIRCRASH-RESTAURANT (Baltimore) _ Patrick Turner plans to
convert a failed bar in Baltimore into the Crash Cafe, a culinary
monument to mayhem, with cars and motorcycles to wrapped around
poles and video screens showing train collisions. But the idea of
honoring chaos and carnage does not sit well with everyone. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSING-SEGREGATION (Chicago) _ The federal government is
achieving its stated goal of helping more minorities go from being
renters to being owners. Across the United States, blacks in this
decade have bought their first homes faster than any other racial
group. But the goal of stable, integrated neighborhoods remains
elusive, 31 years after passage of the Fair Housing Act. By Bill
Dedman. With photos.
</P>
