<P>
   IMPEACH-RDP (Washington) _ The Senate on Friday acquitted
President William Jefferson Clinton on two articles of impeachment,
falling short of even a majority vote on either of the charges
against him, perjury and obstruction of justice. By Alison
Mitchell. With photo and roll call and chronology graphics.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (Washington) _ Bill Clinton has survived, again.
After the Senate found him not guilty on two articles of
impeachment, he tried Friday to contend with two inescapable
questions: At what cost, and for what purpose? By James Bennet and
Jim Broder. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MANAGERS (Washington) _ The lead prosecutor of the
impeachment trial, Rep. &UR;  &LR; Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said on Friday that he
believed Kenneth Starr should not indict President Clinton now that
the Senate has acquitted him. Other House Republicans also
expressed a need to move on, while reaffirming the legitimacy of
their decision to impeach the president in December. By Lizette
Alvarez. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ There are those who think it will
end up as Much Ado About Nothing, at least as far as the country,
its political culture and its institutions of government are
concerned. But Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr., the eminent historian,
begs to differ. A news analysis by R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CENSURE (Washington) _ Soon after the Senate failed to
convict President Clinton on Friday, the alternative of censure
died as well. Censure died in part because most Republicans and a
handful of Democrats said such a censure would violate the
separation of powers between the executive and legislative
branches, set a bad precedent for future Congresses, have no
lasting impact and prolong the unpopular scandal. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-DEFECT (Washington) _ A dwindling band of moderates
joined with a few mavericks Friday to block the Republicans from an
important victory _ a simple majority in a chamber they control on
one of its most-watched votes in history. A look at the 10
Republicans who broke ranks on at least one of the impeachment
votes. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-GOLDBERG (Undated) _ Linda Tripp now portrays her friend
Lucianne Goldberg as a master puppeteer who not only urged Mrs.
Tripp to turn over her tapes of Monica Lewinsky to the independent
counsel, but who told Mrs. Tripp to reveal Ms. Lewinsky's affair
with President Clinton to lawyers for Paula Jones. Ms. Goldberg, a
New York literary agent and a self-described Clinton hater, said
Friday that everything Mrs. Tripp says is true. By Elisabeth
Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIPP (Washington) _ Linda Tripp says she told Kenneth
Starr's agents in January 1998 that she was talking to lawyers for
Paula Jones. Starr has said he had no idea she was involved in the
Jones case. By Jill Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-VOICES (Madison, N.J.) _ In this suburban community of
