<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4112 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-RITTS-B     02-13 1598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-RITTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RITTS PROVED AN ENERGETIC LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His name rhymes with glitz, which is fitting because Jim Ritts
is all of that. Energetic and flashy, Ritts stepped down as
commissioner of the LPGA last week, and the general feeling was not
of disappointment that he didn't stay the promised 10 years, but of
surprise that he hung around for three.
</P>
<P>
   Ritts has been named CEO of a new Internet venture called
Digital Entertainment Network and he will be living the
power-lunch, cell-phone life in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Rating Ritts's job performance is a muddled task. Some say he
should be given credit for adding more tournaments, nearly doubling
the purses, and getting far greater television exposure. But
critics will sneer that his greatest attribute was impeccable
timing, that he arrived to find corporate America tripping over
itself to get a piece of this white-hot sport, that he was blessed
to have The Golf Channel and all of its empty air time waiting at
his door, that much of the LPGA Tour's success can be traced to a
foundation put down by Ritts's predecessor, Charlie Mechem.
</P>
<P>
   The truth probably sits somewhere in the middle. Whereas Mechem
was genuinely embraced by the players, Ritts kept his distance and,
in fact, probably ruffled feathers by not catering to the stars.
Mechem used a fatherly style and made lots of friends. Ritts was
the leader out front, a self-described ``evangelist'' for the sport
always looking to shake a hand or answer a question if he thought
it helped the cause.
</P>
<P>
   When fires were burning out of control in Florida last summer,
Ritts and many LPGA Tour officials were in Kohler, Wis., attending
the US Women's Open at Blackwolf Run. Ritts was constantly in
motion in and around the media tent, monitoring the fires via
phone, discussing the situation, talking about going to Florida if
need be. He was in command mode, but he had time to talk about the
LPGA Tour returning to Pleasant Valley in 1999, though his answers
danced circles around the questions.
</P>
<P>
   Soon his attention drifted to another part of the room and
someone was holding a phone, pointing to it. Ritts stood up,
excused himself, and said he had to run.
</P>
<P>
   He meant it, too, for he sprinted to the phone. Funny to see a
leader of such a slow-paced sport in such a hurry. But, apparently,
Ritts is at his best when on the move.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   To her many friends on the LPGA Tour, Amy Alcott is known as
``Hollywood.'' So it was not lost on Alcott that her entrance into
the LPGA Tour Hall of Fame was announced at a press conference in
Los Angeles, not far from where she was raised and still lives.
During a round of golf at her home course last Wednesday, Alcott
got some playful kidding from a few members _ celebrities, of
course. ``I walked by Richard Crenna, Bob Newhart, Mike Connors,
and Dick Martin and they asked if they could have their picture
taken with me,'' said Alcott. The next day, Pat Bradley did the
honors and introduced the newest member of the Hall of Fame. ``We
have spent too much time on the one that Amy didn't get rather than
on all those that she did win,'' said Bradley, herself a Hall of
Famer, referring to the old criteria, under which Alcott was one
win shy of eligibility. Since Alcott has not won since 1991, she
has heard the question many, many times. ``I have gotten tired of
hearing, `Come on, Amy, you can win that one more.' '' Revision of
the criteria was a long time coming, and both Alcott and Beth
Daniel deserve their Fame. So do veterans such as Judy Rankin,
Donna Caponi, Jane Blalock, and Marlene Hagge, all of whom
registered more than 20 victories. But since they weren't active in
1998, they cannot become eligible under the new criteria, so their
future Hall of Fame hopes will fall to a veteran's committee. As
for those players closest to meeting the new Hall of Fame
requirements (27 points, with at least one major championship, one
Player of the Year, or one Vare trophy), Annika Sorenstam appears a
lock. It isn't so much a question of points (she's at 24) as it is
years (she's in her sixth on Tour and needs at least 10). Laura
Davies (22 points) is another good bet, but Hollis Stacy (also 22)
seems a long shot despite her three US Women's Open titles. Stacy
has not won since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   What happens to these stars when they go Down Under? Two weeks
ago, Ernie Els blew a fourth-round lead and lost the Heineken
Classic, then last Sunday, Bernhard Langer played like anything
other than the polished professional that he is. He led the Greg
Norman Holden International by five shots with nine to play and
appeared poised to win for the first time since 1997 _ until he
began impersonating a 14-handicapper down the stretch. At the 18th,
a par 3 of 225 yards, Langer hit his tee shot into a bunker and
flew the green with his blast out. He chipped within 9 feet and
needed that to force a playoff _ but he never got a chance because
of a mental error that is hard to fathom. Langer marked his ball,
cleaned it, but before re-placing the ball, he removed his marker.
Immediately he knew he had erred and the two-time Masters champ
asked for an official. The ruling: A one-shot penalty, meaning he
was putting for 5, not 4, and there was no chance for a tie.
Understandably ruffled, Langer then two-putted for a triple-bogey
to cap off a round of 80 . . . Tom Kite can relate. The 1997 US
Ryder Cup captain posted an 80 Thursday in the first round of the
Buick Invitational, one shot worse than an amateur named Tim
Mickelson, brother of Phil . . . Ah, to be young, fearless, and
capable of toasting a 3-iron 220 yards: Australian Aaron Baddeley,
who opened eyes last summer by advancing to the finals of the US
Junior Amateur, shot a 70 Thursday at the Australian Masters, while
Spanish sensation Sergio Garcia posted a 68 at the Dubai Desert
Classic . . . Brad Faxon and Billy Andrade, who have teamed to
raise more than $1.6 million for charities in their home state of
Rhode Island, have been named winners of the Charles Bartlett Award
for unselfish contributions to society. They will be honored April
7 at the Golf Writers Association of America annual banquet in
Augusta, Ga., an evening that also will be special to Ken Venturi.
The 1964 US Open winner and longtime CBS golf analyst will receive
the PGA Lifetime Achievement Award in Journalism . . . The US Golf
Association has extended special exemptions to Nancy Lopez and Jane
Geddes for this year's US Women's Open (June 3-6) at Old Waverly GC
in West Point, Miss. . . . Belated birthday wishes to Byron Nelson,
who celebrated his 87th in a fashion that can only make one smile:
He and his wife, Peggy, played some golf (specifically, nine holes
twice). Proof that it truly is a game for life.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are on sale for the Massachusetts Golf Association's
annual spring conference, March 9 at The Westin at Copley Place. It
will have a Ryder Cup theme with The Golf Channel's Peter Kessler
coming in, along with Will Mann, president of the PGA of America;
Rees Jones, noted architect; and John Cornish, general chair at The
Country Club for the Ryder Cup. There also will be call-ins from
Mark O'Meara and Gene Sarazen. For information, call 781-449-3000 .
. . The MGA continues to expand and strengthen its commitment to
junior golf. Last summer, four camps helped introduce nearly 1,500
children to the game, and those programs will continue this year in
Boston, Springfield, Worcester, and Lowell. The MGA has added a
fourth continuing education program for youngsters in Cambridge,
Allston, and Brighton to those that already exist in Chelsea,
Springfield, and Worcester. This newest program, under the
direction of Bob Carey, head pro at Fresh Pond in Cambridge, is
held at Harvard and staffed by members of the golf team. Students
in the Harvard program meet once a week through the winter, and
when spring arrives, they will be encouraged to participate in
weekly clinics at Fresh Pond. The camps and continuing education
program represent an investment of nearly $110,000 by the MGA . . .
George S. Cohen of Springfield, a longtime member at Crestview CC
(where he has won six club championships), has been named winner of
the MGA Frank H. Sellman Distinguished Service Award. He will be
honored at the spring conference . . . Rick DePamphilis, a PGA
Master Professional who teaches at Sun 'n Air Driving Range in
Danvers, will host a series of free winter seminars Monday nights
Feb. 22-March 29 at King's Grant Inn, Route 128 in Danvers. Call
978-774-8180 for information . . . Arthur Cornwell, the first head
pro at the Country Club of Halifax and for many years a teaching
pro at Rockland GC, died of a heart attack while attending the
recent PGA Merchandise Show in Orlando. He was 76 . . . If you are
wondering how some of baseball's finest will spend their Monday
before the All-Star Game at Fenway Park, look for many of them at
Salem CC in Peabody . . . It's provincial, yes, but here's a salute
to Globe colleague Paul Szep for his moment in the spotlight at
last week's AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am. The Pulitzer
Prize-winning cartoonist made four birdies _ the real ones, no net
jobs _ at Pebble Beach, including Nos. 5-6-7, and together with
Greg Kraft's sizzling 66, the pair led at 13 under through the
opening round. They got it as low as 19 under the next day, but the
magic was swept away in those Pacific gusts at Spyglass and
Kraft/Szep missed the cut by two shots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
