<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-TUPA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGNING TUPA GIVES THE JETS A PUNTER AND A QUARTERBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just hours after the National Football League's free-agency
period began Friday, the Jets filled one of their needs, signing
Tom Tupa, one of the league's better directional punters who has
also had a long career as a backup quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa, 33, a Cleveland native and former Ohio State star who
spent two seasons punting for the Cleveland Browns, was reportedly
eager to return to Cleveland with the expansion Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa, who has made 13 starts as an NFL quarterback, spent the
last three seasons of an 11-year career with the New England
Patriots. He becomes another Patriot player lured by Jets Coach
Bill Parcells. Tupa played for the Patriots in 1996 and 1997,
Parcells' last two seasons as New England's head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Since his first NFL season, Tupa has averaged 44.4 yards a punt.
His quarterback skills and his size _ 6 feet 4 inches and 220
pounds _ make him a constant threat to execute some special teams
trickery.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets used three punters last season: Nick Gallery, Brian
Hansen and John Kidd. Gallery was waived after the opening game.
Tupa ranked seventh in the NFL last season with an average of 44.5
yards. He was tied for 12th in the league with a net average of
35.4 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells had another card to play in his sales pitch: Tupa also
played for the Jets' defensive coordinator, Bill Belichick, during
his two seasons with the Browns in 1994 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It addresses what I feel was one of our primary needs,''
Parcells said of Tupa's signing. ``He's an outstanding punter and
our coaching staff is pleased to be reunited with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Cornrich, Tupa's agent, said the decisive factor in his
client's decision was being reunited with Parcells and Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom probably could have gotten more money elsewhere,''
Cornrich said. ``But he got the opportunity to go to the Super Bowl
with those two before and he feels it was the greatest experience
of his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Tupa was drafted out of Ohio State as a quarterback in the third
round by the Phoenix Cardinals. He was used exclusively as a backup
quarterback for the next six seasons except for six punts in the
1989 season. He was not a full-time punter until 1994 with
Cleveland.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
