<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-1999 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARRETT'S HEALTHY, RARING TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
 TOP 10-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ On the eve of the Daytona 500, there are 9
million reasons why Jeff Gordon should be the top choice on
everyone's ballot to nab a third straight NASCAR Winston Cup
championship.
</P>
<P>
   And only two why he shouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett and Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   With apologizes to Mark Martin, who, if not for Gordon's
spectacular season, easily would have captured last year's driving
crown, Jarrett is ``The'' ``Arizona Republic'' pick to knock Gordon
off stock-car racing's pedestal.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   Although Martin posted impressive numbers last season, which
included seven wins and 22 top-five finishes, Jarrett also
displayed moments of brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett shrugged off gall bladder surgery near season's end and
twice finished runner-up in the final two races. He also won three
races during the season and produced 19 top-five finishes.
</P>
<P>
   What hurt Jarrett was a rotten start, finishing 34th at the
Daytona 500 and 40th at Las Vegas, the third stop on the 33-race
season, and a rotten finish except for the second-place efforts.
</P>
<P>
   What hurt worse was Jarrett's body, thanks to an ill-performing
gall bladder that finally was removed in a Phoenix hospital a week
after the season ended.
</P>
<P>
   Although he didn't realize it at the time, Jarrett now knows he
wasn't 100 percent healthy all season.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is. And, boy, does he feel renewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we really have a championship team,'' Jarrett said.
``Even though (Gordon) is the best in the business and has all of
the right people in the right places, we're not giving up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know they can be beaten.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are even more reasons why ``The Republic'' is selecting
Jarrett to upset Gordon and capture the Winston Cup championship.
After Jarrett, in order, are ``The Republic's'' other nine choices
to complete the top 10. &QL; 
1.  &UR; DALE JARRETT
</P>
<P>
   1998: 3rd (3 wins, $4,019,657)
</P>
<P>
   Why in the name of Richard Petty would any sane person bet
against Gordon?
</P>
<P>
   And if not Gordon, why not Mark Martin?
</P>
<P>
   Call it a hunch.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Jarrett and other Ford teams were debuting an
unproven Taurus. Although most Ford teams spent much of the
preseason crying foul, telling anyone with a notepad and a
microphone how they would be the turtle against the Chevrolet hare,
it didn't turn out so badly, now did it?
</P>
<P>
   And with a year's worth of knowledge tucked away inside their
lap-top computers, Ford teams should be even stronger in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Jarrett bleeds undeniable talent. He twice has won the
Daytona 500 when a lot of top drivers never have, including Martin,
Rusty Wallace and Terry Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it certainly wouldn't be the first time ``The
Republic'' was wrong. A year ago in this space, Jeff Burton was
tabbed the predicted winner.
</P>
<P>
   Oops. &QL; 
2.  &UR; JEFF GORDON
</P>
<P>
   1998: (1st, $9,306,584)
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, baby. How's that for going out on a limb?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it really is going out on a limb not to select Gordon
to make it four championships over the past five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   There is absolutely no reason to believe Gordon won't be as
strong in 1999. None. Zippo. ``Nada.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gordon realizes one or two drivers dominating the
circuit is not good for the overall health of the sport, you think
that's going to stop him from pressing the pedal to the metal?
</P>
<P>
   Gordon even has more incentive this season with the return of
team owner Rick Hendrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to return Rick to victory lane,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   So, then, why bet against Gordon and the Rainbow Warriors?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, when was the last time a driver won three
successive titles?
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt? Nah.
</P>
<P>
   Petty? Nope.
</P>
<P>
   Cale Yarborough did it from 1975-77, but is the only driver in
the 50-year history of NASCAR to do so.
</P>
<P>
   And as good as Gordon is, all good things must eventually come
to an end, right?
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Chevy teams are expected to receive a
newly-designed Monte Carlo in late May, but late word is it may be
delayed until next season. If instead it arrives in May, will it be
as sleek and powerful as the present model? Only time will tell.
</P>
<P>
   And one last reason not to pick Gordon . . .
</P>
<P>
   It's just too easy. &QL; 
3.  &UR; MARK MARTIN
</P>
<P>
   1998: (2nd, $4,309,006)
</P>
<P>
   Take a straw vote as to who fans would like to see sitting at
the Waldorf-Astoria head table during the season-ending awards
banquet in New York City and I'll bet you a shiny new can of
Valvoline it's Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Despite never having grabbed NASCAR's brass ring, Martin is the
people's champion. No one is more respected, well-liked _ and yes,
that includes Bill Elliott _ than Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Folks, the man doesn't have an ornery bone in his body.
</P>
<P>
   Gut instinct suggests Martin should at least be picked as high
as second. But that would mean sliding Gordon to third or Gordon to
first and Jarrett to third.
</P>
<P>
   Helllp! &QL; 
4.  &UR; JEFF BURTON
</P>
<P>
   1998: (2 wins, $2,626,987)
</P>
<P>
   One of these years, this guy is going to blow the doors off the
competition. But when?
</P>
<P>
   Burton has as much talent as anyone and drives for one of the
circuit's best teams, yet can't seem to deliver that breakthrough
season.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, it will happen. It just won't happen this season. &QL; 
5.  &UR; BOBBY LABONTE
</P>
<P>
   1998: (2 wins, $2,980,052)
</P>
<P>
   Yes, this is Pontiac's best team, and with the addition of
promising rookie Tony Stewart, Labonte will have even more
ammunition on NASCAR's battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   But something tells me it may take another year or two before
Joe Gibbs' team is ready to seriously challenge for the title.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is Labonte keeps taking steps upward. Baby steps,
but steps nonetheless. Two years ago, he finished seventh. Last
year, it was sixth following two wins.
</P>
<P>
   This year? See you in November. &QL; 
6.  &UR; RUSTY WALLACE
</P>
<P>
   1998: (1 win, $2,667,889)
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who is notorious for making bold predictions, is
keeping his mouth shut this preseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make any predictions this year,'' Wallace
said. ``None.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wallace appeared mostly upbeat at the preseason media
tour hosted by Charlotte Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's some reason for optimism. Wallace did end a
miserably long losing streak by winning at Phoenix International
Raceway last season.
</P>
<P>
   And he's been one of the fastest drivers at Daytona
International Speedway. &QL; 
7.  &UR; JEREMY MAYFIELD
</P>
<P>
   1998: (1 win, $2,332,034)
</P>
<P>
   It took only one season and Mayfield already is talking like his
teammate Wallace. But make no mistake. Mayfield indeed has the
potential to become a weekly threat.
</P>
<P>
   He broke into the win column last season and even led the points
race near the midway point of the season. But Mayfield faded during
the second half. The question is, which half will show up in 1999? &QL; 
8.  &UR; DALE EARNHARDT
</P>
<P>
   1998: (1 win, $2,990,749)
</P>
<P>
   This might be too high. But it shouldn't be too low.
</P>
<P>
   Although Earnhardt still has more talent than a lot of drivers
will attain in a lifetime, the sad truth is he is much, much closer
to the end of his career than the start.
</P>
<P>
   So, Earnhardt likely will have to settle with remaining tied
with Richard Petty for the circuit's all-time lead in driving
titles (seven).
</P>
<P>
   But not for long.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Gordon? &QL; 
9.  &UR; TERRY LABONTE
</P>
<P>
   1998: (1 win, $2,054,034)
</P>
<P>
   Only three years ago, Labonte was the toast of NASCAR, having
captured the driving title ahead of teammate Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   But he dropped to ninth last season, and preseason
prognosticators don't believe it's a certainty he'll crack this
season's top 10.
</P>
<P>
   He will, but just barely.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte is too careful with equipment to not be a top-10
contender.
</P>
<P>
   Still, just as Martin and Burton are the focus at Roush Racing,
so is Gordon at Hendrick Motorsports. &QL; 
10.  &UR; BOBBY HAMILTON
</P>
<P>
   1998: (1 win, $2,089,566)
</P>
<P>
   Something tells me Mike Skinner's name should go here.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well.
</P>
<P>
   What could hurt Hamilton is he is without a teammate. Still,
Hamilton packs a lot of savvy underneath those racing britches. And
he feels good about the upcoming season.
</P>
<P>
   Don't, however, be surprised if Skinner, Ken Schrader or Jimmy
Spencer grabs the 10th spot. I won't. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
