<HEADLINE>
CARDS OPEN TALKS WITH BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cardinals turned their attention to trying to re-sign
offensive tackle Lomas Brown on Friday as the NFL's free-agency
period opened.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's agent, Lamont Smith, met with Cardinals officials Friday
in Tempe, but both sides described the negotiations as preliminary.
</P>
<P>
   The team did sign former Colts offensive tackle Derek West, who
wasn't in the league last year.
</P>
<P>
   It also talked to a representative of former place-kicker
Michael Husted, who became an unconditional free agent when the
Tampa Bay Buccaneers cut him Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, the Cardinals continued to talk to the agent of
outside linebacker Jamir Miller, who became an unrestricted free
agent after the team chose to put the franchise tag on wide
receiver Rob Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cardinals wanted us to know they they want to re-sign
him,'' said Miller's agent, Steve Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Moore remains stunned the Cardinals placed the franchise
designation on him but is confident he can reach contract terms
with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Moore had hoped to become an unrestricted free agent on Friday.
But the Cards restricted his movement by making him their franchise
player, enabling them to match any offer.
</P>
<P>
   The question is how hard the Cardinals will try to re-sign
Miller. There is no doubt they won't pay the $6.5 million a year
Baltimore paid middle linebacker Ray Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   It is likely the Cardinals would be willing to pay about $5
million a year, which is more than the five-year, $22.5 million
deal the Miami Dolphins re-signed middle linebacker Zack Thomas to
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said there were three other teams that have shown the most
interest in Miller. Baker wouldn't specify the teams, but
Indianapolis officials have expressed their desire to try to land
Miller, the Cardinals' leading tackler last season.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams who seem to have interest in Miller are Carolina,
Minnesota and expansion Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the Vikings said Miller wouldn't be a high
priority because they have to re-sign four of their own free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   If Miller leaves, the most attractive outside linebackers in
free agency for the Cardinals to go after would be Anthony Davis of
the Kansas City Chiefs and Roman Phifer of the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is considered one of the top offensive tackles available
in free agency, but he isn't expected to be highly sought after
because he will be 35 next season and is in his 15th season.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals reportedly offered Brown a one-year deal worth
about $3.5 million late last season, but he would like to sign for
two years.
</P>
<P>
   He has said often he wants to remain with the Cardinals because
of the emergence of second-year quarterback Jake Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   West (6-foot-8, 312 pounds), a fifth-round draft pick of the
Colts in 1995, remained with the team through the 1997 season. He
played for the Rhein Fire of NFL Europe last year and was an
all-league selection.
</P>
<P>
   Husted, who has been with the Buccaneers since 1993, has been
one of the league's most consistent kickers and has a strong leg.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is at one of the top teams on our list,'' said his
agent, Glenn Schwartzmann. ``It's a very attractive situation. I
think Michael would be a great addition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have no kickers on their roster after not making a
qualifying offer to Joe Nedney, who still is recovering from a torn
anterior cruciate ligament in his kicking (left) leg. Nedney's
replacement, Chris Jacke, is an unconditional free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Nedney and Jacke combined to win six Cardinals games last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was one of four high-profile receivers to get the
franchise tag placed on him. The others were San Francisco's
Terrell Owens, Cincinnati's Carl Pickens and Green Bay's Antonio
Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll just sit back and see what happens,'' Moore said Friday.
``Now, I'm not in a situation of power. It has all been taken away.
I won't be afforded the option to look elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals decided to place the franchise tag on Moore
instead of Miller after not being able to come to contract terms
with Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised early in the week when I heard they were
thinking about doing it to me,'' Moore said of the franchise
designation. ``I thought it was a little absurd. Then, when I was
franchised, it wasn't like I was oh-so-disappointed or heartbroken.
It was just that I was upset with the numbers (put) on the table by
the Cardinals.''
</P>
<P>
   The team offered a three-year contract worth a little under $5
million a year, which would have allowed Moore to make about $6
million next season.
</P>
<P>
   Moore wanted a four-year deal and was unhappy with the
Cardinals' reported signing bonus offer of $2.4 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 0216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
