<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY_GRIFFITHS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREGNANCY TO SIDELINE GRIFFITHS FOR ENTIRE MERCURY SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mercury starting power forward Michelle Griffiths is pregnant
and will miss the WNBA season.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old Australian has left her Italian team. Her leave
is said to be at a doctor's request even though she is only five
weeks into her pregnancy. She averaged 14.2 points and 5.2 rebounds
in 23 games with Famila Schio, in third place two weeks before the
Italian Final Four playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The baby, a first child for Griffiths and her husband, Steve, is
due in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously my first reaction is this is great for them,''
Mercury Vice President Seth Sulka said Friday. ``It's much more
important than basketball. As far as the team goes, it's secondary
to me. We'll figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it hurt to lose a starter? Yes. But I'd rather hear
positive news about Michelle Griffiths as opposed to hearing (point
guard) Michele Timms was injured in her Australian league and
wouldn't be back for the season. That would be a tougher position
to fill. The one position where we have depth is power forward.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the league runner-up Mercury hopes to slide
6-foot-3 Jennifer Gillom, second to Houston's Cynthia Cooper in
Most Valuable Player voting, to power forward and use 6-8 Maria
Stepanova as the starting center.
</P>
<P>
   They would be backed by 6-5 Marlies Askamp (center) and 6-1 Toni
Foster (power forward), providing neither is lost should the WNBA
use an expansion draft to help stock the Orlando Miracle and
Minnesota Lynx.
</P>
<P>
   An expansion draft has not yet been scheduled as the league
negotiates with the new players union to reach a collective
bargaining agreement. The availability of former American
Basketball League players to the WNBA complicates all draft
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-1 Griffiths joined the Mercury for its second season
after the 1998 World Championships. When Foster, the 1997 starting
power forward, went on the injured list because of a stress
fracture in her leg, Griffiths was promoted.
</P>
<P>
   She played in all 30 regular-season games, starting 25, and
averaged 9.2 points and 4.4 rebounds. Her nine steals against Utah
on July 27 is a record for the 2-year-old league.
</P>
<P>
   In the WNBA playoffs, she averaged 12.3 points and 6.5 rebounds,
including her single-game highs for rebounds (12) and points (24)
in the Finals against the Houston Comets.
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths' official status will be suspended, like that of
Houston center Polina Tzekova, who did not report last season due
to a family illness.
</P>
<P>
   She has a year left on her WNBA contract and will remain with
the Mercury unless she is left unprotected and selected should an
expansion draft occur. The pregnancy, of course, takes away from
her value as an expansion target.
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths and Timms are members of the Australian National Team
that won bronze medals at the 1996 Olympics and '98 World
Championships. They and Mercury backup point guard Kristi Harrower,
also on the World team, hope to represent Australia at the 2000
Olympics in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   WNBA officials, preoccupied with current issues, have yet to
address how the league's 2000 schedule will be adjusted to
accommodate preparations for the Olympics, Sept. 15-Oct. 1. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 0216EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
