<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4118 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERFAN-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      02-13 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERFAN-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIMSUIT FEVER HITS AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   My vote for least-read ``Sports Illustrated'' story of all time:
a three-way tie between E.M. Swift's tale of sailing, Franz Lidz's
chronicle of a wild Caribbean bar and William Nack's profile of
Richard Branson in this week's issue.
</P>
<P>
   Not the regular issue.
</P>
<P>
   The swimsuit issue.
</P>
<P>
   (I figure at least a few people will read Austin Murphy's story
about applying body paint to supermodels, based on the subject
matter alone.)
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the swimsuit issue is back, and packed with plenty of flesh
to excite or offend, depending upon how you feel about this kind of
thing. The best part of the whole thing is the raft of letters it
generates, half from ``a college student in chilly Minnesota who is
really warmed up by the issue,'' the other half from ``a mother of
three who was greatly offended by your poor taste. This is
outrageous. It has nothing to do with sports. P.S. I think that
purple Teletubby is gay, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Time was, the swimsuit issue was just a few pages of scantily
clad models thrown into the middle of a regular winter issue of
``Sports Illustrated.'' But no more. Now there is an extra issue
devoted entirely to beautiful women wearing (and sometimes not
wearing) bathing suits.
</P>
<P>
   And frankly, it smacks of overkill. The swimsuit issue in the
old days was like a good bikini _ it left a little something to the
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The current swimsuit issue is more than 200 pages of bikinis and
body paint, broken up every now and then with the occasional
article that no one will read anyway (see above).
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that the issue has nothing to recommend it.
There are, of course, pages and pages of beautiful women in
incredibly expensive bathing suits (Rebecca Romijn-Stamos sports a
chain-link number the size of a Handi-Wipe on the cover that goes
for ``$80''0), although the idea of anyone actually swimming in
them is laughable.
</P>
<P>
   The feature in which professional athletes _ including the Suns'
Tom Gugliotta _ pose in swimsuits with their spouses returns. (By
the way, if Joe Montana needs money, it looks as if he's a prime
candidate for a Rogaine ad.)
</P>
<P>
   The body-painting section is quite the optical illusion. You'd
never know you were looking at naked women until . . . wait, isn't
that . . . uh, never mind.
</P>
<P>
   And if you read the groan-inspiring, bad-pun introduction at the
beginning of the magazine, which takes the place of a proper table
of contents, you will find the following joke buried in a footnote:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Virgin Islands, discovered by Columbus in 1493, were named
in honor of Saint Ursula, a ninth-century martyr who supposedly
rounded up 11,000 virgins for a pilgrimage to Rome and was killed
by Huns on her return trip. That expedition was the largest
gathering of virgins on record until a ``Star'' ``Trek'' convention
in Indianapolis in 1997.''
</P>
<P>
   (Rim shot.)
</P>
<P>
   Another highlight: Many of the advertisers tailor their ads to
the issue, but none as effectively or hilariously as Sony. Its ad
for the Digital Handycam on page 111 shows a slob of a man who
makes Gilbert Brown look like Spike Lee lounging in the surf
wearing a, yuck, Speedo. Above, it says, ``Pizza. Pork rinds. Beer.
Put him on the cover, dammit. Because he's never looked better.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most people probably won't see the ad, since on the
facing page is a picture of ``Tamara'' looking for all the world
like the winner of a wet T-shirt contest at a spring-break bar.
</P>
<P>
   Is it sports? Nah. Is it interesting? Absolutely. Should you buy
it? Like all other questions touching on morality, the answer is up
to you. But if you decide to, you might haul out that old lie
people used to tell when they picked up a copy of ``Playboy'': ``I
only get it for the articles.''
</P>
<P>
   No one will believe you, of course. But Swift, Lidz, Nack and
Murphy will thank you. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
