<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR_DAYTONA_PETTYS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR GETTING READY FOR YET ANOTHER PETTY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ They are so much alike. And as different.
</P>
<P>
   It began with Lee Petty, patriarch, champion of the first
Daytona 500 in 1959. Although he is one of NASCAR's first heroes,
Petty, who with 55 career victories is No. 7 on the all-time
winning list, would rather mow the lawn than discuss NASCAR with
the media.
</P>
<P>
   Few know for certain why Petty, who refused to attend his own
introduction into the International Motorsports Hall of Fame,
remains disgruntled with the sanctioning body. He just is.
</P>
<P>
   Next came son Richard Petty, who is to stock-car racing what the
Louvre is to art museums. Richard Petty, a record-tying seven-time
driving champion, has 200 career victories, a feat likely to never
be toppled.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's grandson Kyle Petty, who not only remembers the
band Jefferson Airplane, he probably could have been one of its
guitarists. Unlike most NASCAR racers, including dad Richard, who
rarely is seen without his trademark cowboy boots and hat, Kyle
Petty has pierced ears, wears a pony tail and would prefer riding a
Harley-Davidson motorcycle to some Winston Cup venues rather than
airplane or automobile transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can grow a pony tail, but the earrings are out,'' Richard
Petty joked.
</P>
<P>
   And, now, here comes fourth-generation driver Adam Petty, who at
age 18 will make his NASCAR Busch Grand National debut today at
Daytona International Speedway, where he will start in the 11th
row.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take pride in having four generations of Pettys in this
sport, but it's almost like taking pride in being in the ``Guinness
Book of World Records'' for having the longest fingernails or
something,'' Kyle Petty said. ``It's just an oddity, man.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `What's wrong with that freak family. They've got
four of them keep wanting to do that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   What does Adam Petty say?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Kyle Petty clone without the hair and earrings,'' said
Adam of his father, who starts Sunday's Daytona 500 in the 12th
row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't let him have a pony tail, anyway,'' Kyle said.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Short hair or long hair, Adam Petty appears to possess the
unmistakable Petty genes to one day lift him to the Winston Cup
level.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Petty already has won an American Speed Association race,
which occurred two weeks before his 18th birthday last June. The
win made him the youngest driver ever to do so, snapping the
previous mark held by Mark Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, Adam Petty made his Automobile Racing Club
of America debut at Charlotte Motor Speedway, and won. At age 18
years and three months, he also became ARCA's youngest winner,
surpassing the previous record held by, uh, Kyle Petty, who was 18
years and eight months when he captured the Daytona 200 in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has a phenomenal amount of talent,'' Kyle Petty
said. ``It amazes me. But it's what he does with that talent. Right
now, he's so single minded and so focused on it that there's not a
ceiling on how far he can go. The sky's the limit for a kid like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Proud father yakking about a son? Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   But Grandpa Richard, not one to shy away from speaking the
truth, no matter who it might or might not upset, said he also
believes his grandson has the potential for a bright future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adam can definitely be better than Kyle,'' Richard said.
``He's more dedicated at what he's doing now. He's more focused. I
think he's seen how daddy done and how great granddaddy did. Right
now, racing full time is on his mind. As long as he keeps his head
screwed on right, he can go far.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyle Petty, 38, who is known for his off-track charitable
efforts toward fund-raising and recently was named True Value Man
of the Year, finished 30th in last year's final standings. He twice
finished as high as fifth (1992-93), but never has won more than
two races in a single season and only has one victory over the past
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Was it difficult being the son of Richard Petty, and if so, what
will that mean for Adam Petty? More comparisons?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go back and read the old newspapers, Richard Petty was
always Lee Petty's son,'' Kyle said. ``He (Richard) went through
that stage, then he found out who he was. He was Richard Petty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went through the same stage. I went through a lot of down
times, then all of a sudden, people said, `Well, that's Kyle. He's
just different than Richard.' Well, Richard was different than Lee
and Adam came along and he's different than all three of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all look different and are totally different people. We're
not clones of each other. The only way we're cloned and the gene
that's the same in all of us is our love of the sport. We just love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam shares the same love, not only for the sport, but for his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my dad has had a great career,'' Adam said. ``He's
touched a lot of people's hearts and he's been there for a lot of
people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great race car driver. A lot of drivers out there today
still haven't won a race and my dad has won (eight). I look up to
my dad a whole lot because he's always been there for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Kyle, who was a third-generation driver attempting to
follow in the footsteps of two famous Pettys before him, however,
Richard Petty believes grandson Adam won't face as much adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky. I was able to beat everything my father did. And
I feel like with Adam, he'll do a lot better than Kyle because Kyle
was a third-generation driver trying to break away from what his
father and grandfather did. With Adam, I think he's not trying to
break away. He's trying to do what his father did. I think that
will help him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Adam won't try and be anyone but himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I do have a lot to live up to,'' Adam said. ``My
grandfather has done a whole lot and my dad has done a whole lot.
If I can do half of what they've done, I'll be very happy.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
