<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BET THE HOUSE  
 HALF-BAKED IDEAS ON `BIG DANCE' 
</HEADLINE>
 PREVIEW-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than a month remains until the 64-team NCAA Tournament
field is announced, seeded and bracketed on March 7, followed by
the whining of teams that don't make it. The end of the regular
season is in sight. But the speculation season is just starting to
heat up.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the small matter in our nation's capital has, at long
last, been put to rest, we can finally focus our attention on
what's really important: Who's going to get into the tournament,
where will they be seeded and where will they play?
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is, who knows? If you think you're going to
find out here, think again. Go read the Senate roll-call votes, or
something. The fact is, no one can say for sure, not even the Web
site wise guys, nor the foremost, supreme authorities on everything
and anything, i.e., the talk show hosts.
</P>
<P>
   What can be promised in this space, however, is guessing and
half-baked theories, along with a solemn promise: Beyond this
sentence, you will see no further reference to teams being ``on the
bubble'' for ``the Big Dance.'' As we prepare for this century's
final Final Four, to be played in St. Petersburg, Fla., amid folks
born in the ``previous ''century, we aim for a cliche-free
millennium. In fact, isn't the phrase Final Four getting old? How
about something new and hip for 2000 and beyond, like ``Phat
Four''?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, there are some raging questions out there, and we'll do
our best to answer them. But remember, all this is one upset away
from being rendered entirely meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Question: Who will be the four No. 1 seeds?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: Well, you've got Duke, which could beat out the Suns
for an NBA playoff spot. Then there is Connecticut, which is pretty
darned good, too, and the way it's playing right now, Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: That's only three. What about the other one?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: You had to notice that. The hot pick currently is Michigan
State, which has won 10 straight Big Ten games. But don't rule out
Cincinnati, despite its mini-slump; Stanford, which has a chance if
it wins the rest; and teams like Kentucky and Maryland, if they do
well between now and the conference tournaments, and then win them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Where will the selection committee locate the No. 1 seeds?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: There's a heated debate going on. Should Duke, by virtue of
being the overall top seed, be rewarded and sent to the East
Regional, where it can play in Charlotte, N.C.? Or should the NCAA
maintain some geographic credibility and put UConn in the East,
where it can open in nearby Boston?
</P>
<P>
   The team not sent to the East likely would play in the South.
That would put Michigan State in the Midwest. What's left, Auburn
to the West? Sounds good to me. But so does any other scenario.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, speaking of the NCAA and geography, the two words
are mutually exclusive. Half of the South regional will be played
in that bastion of mint juleps, magnolias and antebellum mansions,
Indianapolis. At the same time, first and second round games of the
Midwest regional will be played in the capital of America's
heartland, New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: What about the rest of the seeded teams?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: Assuming Michigan State and Auburn are No. 1s, you've got
Stanford, Cincinnati, Maryland and Kentucky as potential No. 2
seeds. Three-seeds look like North Carolina, St. John's, Wisconsin
and a Utah team coming up fast on the outside. Strongly resembling
No. 4 seeds right now are UCLA, Arizona, Ohio State and another
team surging to a strong finish, Temple.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Temple? Are you sure?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: Of course not. Remember what I said about guessing and
half-baked theories?.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: What other teams might crack the top four seeds, depending
on how they finish?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: Miami (Fla.), Iowa, and maybe about a half-dozen others. And
thanks for adding, ``depending on how they finish.'' Sounds like we
both like to shop at Butt-Covering `R' Us.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Shouldn't that be a backward `R'?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: Yes, but someone borrowed the Russian keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Can we please be serious? Where's Kansas?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: To answer the first question, absolutely. To answer the
second, if you check a map, you'll see it's dead smack in the
middle of the country. Sorry. As for its celebrated basketball
program, we can't see it being higher than a No. 6 seed. And maybe
lower, the way things are going.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: So what's with the Pac-10? Four teams and that's it?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: It sure looks that way. Washington, playing better than
anyone in the conference right now, should join Stanford, UCLA and
Arizona. The only other possibilities are California and Arizona
State. Cal, even though it beat Southern California on Thursday,
doesn't look like it's going to pass chemistry this season. ASU
needs to finish 5-1 to have a shot, and that includes road games at
Cal and Stanford, and UCLA at home. The Sun Devils can do it, but,
pardon the expression, don't bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: There's a lot of talk about eight of the 11 Big Ten teams
making the field of 64. What of it?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: First of all, that's a lot of numbers for one sentence. But
let's take a look. Michigan State, Wisconsin, Ohio State, Indiana,
Minnesota, Purdue and Iowa are in or close to being in. Then you've
got Northwestern on the bub . . . Ooops. Northwestern is, uh, on
the edge. Yeah, that's it, on the edge. Do they make it? A definite
maybe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Some are saying the Atlantic Coast Conference is ``down''
this year. Just what does ``down'' mean, and who makes the
tournament?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: According to Vitale's New World Dictionary, ``down'' means
when a conference thought by many to have invented college
basketball, or at least perfected it to such a point where the game
anywhere else might as well not be played, suddenly has a bunch of
average teams, just like everybody else. Having said that, as many
as six ACC teams might get in, including the likes of Georgia Tech
and Florida State. But let's hope not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: Quickly, some other conferences.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: That's not a question. What are you, a TV reporter? But
we'll overlook that. From the not-so-Big 12, there are Texas,
Missouri, Kansas, Oklahoma and Nebraska. The Southeastern
Conference has Auburn, Kentucky, Florida, Mississippi and
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   From the Big East, it's UConn, Miami, St. John's, Syracuse,
Villanova and for fans of the acclaimed HBO series about a
fictitious organized crime family in New Jersey, ``The Sopranos'' _
Rutgers. The disappointing Atlantic 10 has Temple and we'll also
say George Washington because Monday is President's Day. But not
Xavier. The last Western Athletic Conference as we know it will
provide Utah, plus New Mexico and maybe Fresno State and maybe
Nevada-Las Vegas and maybe Tulsa. Conference-USA is Cincinnati,
UNC-Charlotte and, by virtue of the NCAA changing its mind,
Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   One interesting development is the surging Missouri Valley
Conference. Evansville, Southwest Missouri State and Bradley are
all tournament-worthy. College of Charleston is in, even if it
somehow tanks the Southern Conference tournament. Murray State
might be in the same position in the Ohio Valley Conference, but it
had better win the tournament to safely override the prejudice
against teams named ``Murray.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: What about the other conferences, like the Patriot League
and the Colonial Athletic Association?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A: I'm afraid we're out of space. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 0219EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
