<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4121 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES_BURKE-AZR     02-13 2258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_BURKE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARENA BATTLE LATEST OF MANY FOR BURKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a young boy in Marietta, Ga., Richard Burke competed with
everyone _ friends, two younger brothers and, most often, himself.
Even a walk to school became a contest. Today's trip had to be
faster than yesterday's.
</P>
<P>
   As a businessman in Minneapolis, Burke refused to acknowledge
defeat, even when his fledgling health care company was struggling
and he didn't know how he was going to meet the payroll. He
persevered and turned it into one of the nation's largest HMOs,
making millions in the process.
</P>
<P>
   And as owner of the Phoenix Coyotes, Burke is stubbornly focused
on proving that the NHL team can thrive in the desert, despite
arena disputes and the team's lackluster history on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   His profile in the community has expanded in recent months, as a
dispute over obstructed-view seats and lease conditions at America
West Arena has led the Coyotes to become a partner in a proposed
arena venture of their own, on the site of Scottsdale's Los Arcos
Mall.
</P>
<P>
   It's a battle that the 55-year-old Burke expects to win.
</P>
<P>
   For him, life has always included a scoreboard. Quarterly
reports and marathon times. Share prices and number of quail shot.
Buyouts and hockey games.
</P>
<P>
   Burke admits that his competitiveness isn't always a bright,
shining attribute, and there have been times when he wished to be
different. ``As a young boy, I was always setting a bar with
everything,'' he said. ``Working out, running, tennis, hunting,
fishing. I look back on it and I'm a little appalled that there was
so little inclination to just enjoy something just for the sake of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He's gotten better at that, but losing is still abhorrent to
him. It still confounds him that his 3-year-old son, Brendan, can
skate and he can't. He has tried and suffered a broken ankle in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   It drove him nuts the day Taylor, his oldest son, finally beat
him in tennis. And when he and Taylor hunt quail, Burke always
tries to get the inside position to get a split-second advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never fought fair,'' said Taylor, 27, the Coyotes assistant
general manager. ``We'd get in wrestling matches and he found a way
to win even if it meant playing dirty. I think he was more
competitive with us than he was in his business life.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke guesses that his competitiveness comes from his mother,
whom he describes as ``a very intense person.'' His father, he
said, was very easygoing.
</P>
<P>
   Burke's father was an engineer with the government, and the
family was secure, but not wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nicest present my parents gave to me is that I started
grade school with the same group of kids that I graduated high
school with,'' said Burke, who had two younger brothers.
</P>
<P>
   His competitiveness isn't readily apparent when you meet Burke.
He wears wire-rimmed glasses and speaks in an even, measured voice.
He gives the impression of being as serene as the farmland
surrounding his 25,000-square-foot home that sits on about 500
acres in Medina, Minn., just west of Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, he never sits still long. He sleeps just three to
four hours a night. He has run marathons, sometimes training on a
treadmill in the wee hours. He has several business interests,
although hockey is clearly the most important. And he and his
second wife, Jude, have three children _ Brendan and 20-month old
twins Ian and Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   He did not come to Arizona to retire and live off the interest
of his fortune, estimated a few years ago to be about $70 million
(and that was before the stock market took off).
</P>
<P>
   ``Being successful and having something like (United Healthcare)
work is probably just three-quarters being lucky,'' he said. The
other quarter is ``not taking no for an answer and not being
willing to fall on your face.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times where it probably would have (failed) if I
had not been as competitive and as unwilling to stay down,'' he
said. &QL; 
To believe that three-quarters of Burke's success is luck or timing
is to sell him short, say those close to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the most unbelievable capacity to juggle 20 balls in
the air and be OK with it, because he can focus in,'' said Juanita
Burke, Richard's first wife and the mother of Taylor and Ryan, a
25-year-old who works on Wall Street. ``When roadblocks are thrown
up, he finds a way around them. On the third roadblock, I would
say, `This is not meant to be.' He would say, `There has to be a
way.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The accomplishments came with a price, however. Burke made
enemies, particularly among Minneapolis area doctors who were
opposed to an HMO telling them what they could charge.
</P>
<P>
   Burke was also accused of a conflict of interest because he was
the president and CEO of both United Healthcare and Physicians
Health Plan of Minnesota, then the largest client of United
Healthcare.
</P>
<P>
   Burke was the medical community's poster child for everything
that was wrong with managed care, and in the late 1980s, doctors
revolted against his control. The dispute eventually was mediated
by the state. Burke remained in charge. The doctors were given a
stronger voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not a lot of doctors who will say a lot of nice
things about him,'' said Doug Leatherdale, a close friend of
Burke's and a longtime board member at United Healthcare. ``He
clearly rubs some people the wrong way.'' &QL; 
Burke's juggling act didn't last forever, and inevitably a few of
the balls fell. His devotion to success and his doggedness took a
personal toll. He blames himself for his divorce in 1979 from
Juanita, his high school sweetheart, whom he married in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably two things responsible for that,'' he said.
``One was me not being grown-up enough to keep it from happening.
And the second was probably just business and how I tend to go
about things, regrettably, all or nothing. I didn't have enough
balance in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The divorce was bitter at first as the couple tried to reach a
financial settlement. How to spend time with the two boys was never
an issue, however. Richard bought a house close to Juanita's and
the boys were free to stay at either place. There were no arguments
over visitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you get older, you realize how difficult it is to end a
relationship of that significance,'' Taylor said, ``and to . . .
make sure their kids grew up in an environment that allowed them to
live their lives the same way as before was a tremendous
commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke and Juanita eventually became close friends, and Juanita,
who hasn't remarried, spends holidays with Burke's new family and
the two older boys.
</P>
<P>
   At the Burkes' home in Paradise Valley, the plastic toys of
toddlers are scattered about the patio, symbols, courtesy of
Fisher-Price and Playskool, of what Burke believes: that one life
is really is made up of many lives.
</P>
<P>
   He and Jude met about 10 years ago on a blind date. Both enjoyed
the outdoors and travel and immediately hit it off. She worked for
Honeywell in the employee counseling department, and Burke
remembers calling her one time from Russia, where he was traveling
with Ryan, who speaks Russian fluently.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me she was going to start a subsidiary for this
company, United Healthcare, and asked me, had I ever heard of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   They eventually married, and Jude worked for United until about
two years ago as the couple began to raise a family. It's been fun,
Taylor said, to watch his father so excited about his younger
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at him and told him he was crazy,'' Taylor said of
reaction to his father having more children. ``He said, `You don't
understand, I enjoyed it so much the last time.' He thought it was
tremendous he had the opportunity to do it again.'' &QL; 
It was a new life, one far away both in time and personal
commitment from United Healthcare. There, Burke had grown weary and
was run down physically and emotionally because of the demands.
</P>
<P>
   He retired as CEO in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first six months, I tried to get myself back
together,'' he said. ``I had always taken care of myself, but I was
getting to the point where I was starting to wear down. I didn't
have the foggiest idea what I was going to do. I just knew I was
going to do something different and get my head sorted out and my
priorities back in order. And hopefully, I was going to do
something that would let me live awhile. Because with the pace I
was on, that wasn't going to be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   He was approached by some acquaintances in Minneapolis about
buying the Winnipeg Jets of the NHL and moving them to Minnesota.
But when a lease arrangement couldn't be reached with the Target
Center in Minneapolis, Burke and his partner, Steven Gluckstern,
decided to move to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   They were confident their deal with America West Arena and
landlord Jerry Colangelo would generate enough revenue to make the
Coyotes financially viable.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't long before Burke and Gluckstern butted heads with
Colangelo, perhaps the most powerful man in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Burke, who later bought out Gluckstern when the partner decided
to buy the NHL's New York Islanders, contends details of the lease
were interpreted by Colangelo and those in his organization in ways
that hurt the Coyotes. Colangelo believes the Coyotes have a
sweetheart deal at America West Arena. He and Burke no longer
speak.
</P>
<P>
   It's not in Burke's nature to back away from a fight, and he
could have challenged the lease in court, or put more pressure on
the city of Phoenix, which owns the arena, to intervene. But Burke
decided leaving America West Arena was a more pragmatic
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Burke and the Coyotes are pursuing a new arena in Scottsdale as
part of the redevelopment plans for Los Arcos Mall. Officials from
America West Arena and the city are pursuing renovation plans that
would ease some of the seating problems, but Burke is committed to
moving into a new arena. And he thinks the area can support two
arenas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to compete with everything, and with some
things it's not appropriate,'' Burke said. ``In this sense (the
arena issue), it's not a zero sum game. I think there is room for
both of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm obviously not pleased with the way some things have been
handled, but you have to have the maturity to look at it and figure
out what's the best way to handle it. And having a confrontation
doesn't serve a whole lot of purpose or get us to where we want to
get.''  &QL; 
Getting an arena built is never an easy task, however.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed 20,000-seat, state-of-the-art arena will sit below
ground. If built, it would be surrounded by a conference, retail
and entertainment complex that would take in 92 acres at one of the
Valley's busiest intersections.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes and Burke have pledged to chip in about $100 million
for the $624 million project. Developers want state sales tax
revenues to pay for about a third of the project, but they have
said that the arena portion will be paid for with private money.
</P>
<P>
   There is significant opposition to the Scottsdale development. A
group called NO PUCKS _ Neighborhoods Organized to Prevent Unwanted
Community Killing in Scottsdale _ is protesting the development.
But even their lawyer and spokesman, Alan Kaufman, gets along well
with Burke.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very intelligent, sophisticated, articulate and a
successful man,'' Kaufman said. ``That doesn't mean I agree with
him. (The arena) is a waste of taxpayer money. I'd rather put the
money into schools. Burke and his team have adequate resources to
pay for their own house.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke had been reluctant at first to enter the arena business,
but he thinks it's the only way his hockey franchise, which he said
has lost money each year, will become financially viable. He has
embraced the pursuit of an arena, and friends say it's unwise to
bet against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a better prognosticator than anybody I've seen in
business,'' said Rick Powell, a close friend and the CEO of First
Cash Financial Services, which is based in Arlington, Texas, and
operates a chain of pawn shops and check cashing stores. Burke owns
about 2 million shares in the company, worth around $26 million,
depending on market fluctuations .
</P>
<P>
   Powell said, ``He's not a particularly patient person and he
would like to see things materialize right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's taken some time, but Burke is adjusting to a business where
success is judged after each of 82 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really an oddity and it's one that as a competitive
person I don't know how well suited I am for it,'' he said. ``In
business, if you're running a public company, the measurement of
whether you're smart or stupid comes every quarter. In between you
have a little latitude to be smart or stupid. In this business,
it's goes day to day and game to game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for me to sit in the stands on nights we stink.''
</P>
<P>
   The hockey team stinks less often now. The Coyotes are 28-13-10,
and are a legitimate contender to advance far into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Burke is confident things will improve for the Coyotes off the
ice, too, and that eventually the Coyotes will be playing in their
own arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard is not a Jerry Jones or a Colangelo or a (George)
Steinbrenner from an ego standpoint,'' Powell said, ``but the
wealth the man possesses, both in a dollar sense and in knowledge,
would rival anybody's. I would rather be on his side than
anybody's. I don't know just how, but he always wins.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
