<SLUG> BC-POLY-TAINER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM EFFORT KEEPS COMPANY IN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ A team effort by local and state officials plus a
$1million loan convincd plastics manufacturer Poly-Tainer Inc. to
spurn relocation offers from three Western states and expand
locally, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Poly-Tainer employs 240 workers and will add 72 new jobs, 60 of
them full-time, to the payroll during this year. The company will
also consolidate operations, spread out among three buildings, to a
100,000-square-foot facility in the Simi Valley community northwest
of Los Angeles by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old company, one of the West Coast's largest
independent manufacturers of molded plastic products, had received
attractive pitches from communities in Utah, Arizona and Nevada.
Those three states were popular destinations for companies fleeing
California during the early part of the 1990s because of its
prolonged economic slump and cool attitude toward business.
</P>
<P>
   In response, California created so-called red teams that
included private and public sector officials with special skills to
address retention efforts on a case-by-case basis. Such a team was
brought into play to woo Poly-Tainer.
</P>
<P>
   That helped turn the situation in California's favor, said
company President Paul Strong.
</P>
<P>
   Team members included officials from the Ventura County Solid
Waste Management Department, &UR;  &LR; Southern California Edison and the
state Employment Development Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed us very clearly that California is indeed a great
place to do business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the loan, with terms at 5.6 percent for 10 years,
the package included funds to cover a portion of new workers'
salaries during training and five years of discounted electrical
rates from Southern California Edison.
</P>
<P>
   This was one of the deal's key elements, Strong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``California utilities are expensive compared to other states,''
Strong said.
</P>
<P>
   Edison spokesman Grant F. Thomas said the red team program is
designed for situations like those faced by Poly-Tainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's for attraction of businesses outside of California . . .
and retaining those that are definitely looking to go to another
state,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   David Goldstein, an analyst with the waste management
department, said Poly-Tainer's expansion will enable the company to
increase its use of recycled plastics to 700 tons a year from 300
tons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just not any old business retention. This is the
retention and expansion of a important company for recycling,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Gabler, Simi Valley's assistant city manager, said
Poly-Tainer is an important cog in the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've very pleased with the outcome of this. The company has
been a longtime major employer in the city, and you don't want to
lose any employer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Poly-Tainer makes plastic bottles, toys, canteens, golf
sand-trap rakes and cosmetic containers. The privately held company
had $12 million in annual sales in 1997, company officials said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
X X X  &QL;
</P>
