A4125 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-STARS-LADN     02-13 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-STARS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS FALL TO STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Some things just aren't in the stars for the Anaheim
Mighty Ducks, and beating the Dallas Stars appears to be one of
those things.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights after defeating the mighty Philadelphia Flyers,
Anaheim had an opportunity to do something even more impressive _
defeat Dallas and complete a sweep of the two teams with the most
points in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   For 47 minutes they skated stride for stride with the Stars,
only to fall behind on a fluke goal by Jaime Langenbrunner and wind
up losing yet another game to Dallas, 3-2, before 16,230 at the
Pond on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat snapped the Ducks' four-game winning streak and
prevented them from moving past St. Louis, into fifth place in the
Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's chance for a rare win over Dallas all but ended when
Langenbrunner skated down the right wing and fired a shot that
deflected off the stick of Anaheim defenseman Pascal Trepanier and
then the skate of Ducks defenseman Jaime Pushor at 7:26 of the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull gave the Stars a 3-1 lead at 8:56 when he converted
Mike Modano's centering pass from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg was pleased with his team's
effort, but he refused to blame the loss on a bad bounce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lucky bounce, he said. ``But we turned the puck over
in the neutral zone. You make a mistake against those guys and it
will cost you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably two or three plays cost us the game. We turned the
puck over once and relaxed on the third goal.
</P>
<P>
   Tomas Sandstrom gave the Ducks one last chance when he scored
with 23.9 seconds left, but it turned out to Anaheim's last gasp
and the Ducks fell to 4-17-1 in their last 22 games against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get them, we still have a few more cracks at them, said
Hartsburg, whose team fell to 21-23-9. ``We played them a lot
better than we did a month ago (a 3-1 loss on Jan. 15).
</P>
<P>
   Sandstrom, who scored his seventh goal of the season in the
final minute, said the Ducks can take something positive out of
their last two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It proves we can play with them (the league's best teams), he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg agreed, but warned that the Ducks can only do so if
they play their ``best each game. We can't drop off at all.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have the NHL's No. 2 ranked power play, while the
Ducks are No. 3 and first at home. And both units had plenty of
chances to show off their abilities as referee Kerry Fraser kept
both penalty killing units on edge by calling 12 minor penalties in
the first 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks were 1-for-5 (Teemu Selanne's 25th goal in the first
period, while Dallas was 1-for-3 in the opening period (a
deflection by Jere Lethinen) and 0-for-4 in the second.
</P>
<P>
   As they did against Philadelphia the Ducks stormed out of the
gate. Anaheim recorded seven of the game's first eight shots,
forcing Dallas goalie Ed Belfour to come with some big saves early.
</P>
<P>
   On Anaheim's first power play of the night Belfour stopped Steve
Rucchin from the slot, Fredrik Olausson's rebound bid and shot from
the point by Ruslan Salei.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of jump, said Sandstrom. ``If we could have got a
goal then ... but it's a 60-minute game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference tonight was Belfour, said Hartsburg. ``Belfour
was better than Vanbiesbrouck was (on Wednesday).
</P>
<P>
   Dallas broke on top with a power play goal after being outshot
12-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' fourth shot -- a blast from the left circle by Darryl
Sydor -- was deflected by Lethinen just inside the left post at
13:07.
</P>
<P>
   The tied the game on their fourth power play, scoring on a
two-man advantage with 51 seconds left in the opening period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, despite being down by two skaters, didn't allow the
Ducks to get organized, let alone get a shot off until there were
13 seconds left on the two man disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   But Selanne took things into his own hands -- and feet -- by
blowing around Modano at center ice and beating Belfour high on the
glove side with a 40-footer.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim goalie Guy Hebert picked up his third career assist on
the play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
