<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 08:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4135 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NEXT14-COX     02-13 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NEXT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TURNING TO NEW BATTLE FOR POLICY IDEALS
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If it's true, as Winston Churchill once said, that
nothing's quite so exhilarating as being shot at and missed,
President Clinton is unquestionably a man revitalized.
</P>
<P>
   As he steps from the impeachment cross hairs, he'll need all his
newfound vigor.
</P>
<P>
   After a year spent fighting Republican efforts to remove him
from office, Clinton has vowed to get down to the work his
constituents elected him to do: gut the Republican tax cut plan,
keep Al Gore in the White House and help Democrats win back the
Congress in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to go into full public policy gear,'' said Michael
Genovese, political science professor at Loyola Marymount
University in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's in some ways an act of desperation,'' said Genovese,
author of ''The Paradoxes of the American Presidency,'' published
two months ago. ''He knows he has a very limited time to reclaim
the voice of history.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton can't wipe the stain of scandal from his legacy. He
would certainly like it to fade a bit, though, against a background
of achievement.
</P>
<P>
   He can do little without working with the Republicans who
control the House and the Senate, all but a handful of whom have
judged him guilty of perjury and obstruction of justice and have
voted to end his presidency over it.
</P>
<P>
   Given the partisan rancor of the impeachment proceedings, it's
not easy to imagine where Clinton might begin to build a new bridge
from 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue to Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts questioned how much he would even try.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clinton's going to be mad,'' said presidential scholar Shirley
Anne Warshaw of Gettysburg College in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Warshaw, who has written a study of Clinton's staff, expects
relations to be strained, if not hostile, between the
administration and the more aggressive Republican impeachment
advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ''My feeling is that he is going to cut out the knees of some of
these people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, at least, White House aides insist Clinton's not a man
to carry a grudge, particularly against those whose cooperation he
must win if he is to govern.
</P>
<P>
   This is, after all, a country with a rich tradition of co-opting
former enemies once the shooting's over.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the nation of the Marshall Plan,'' said White House
political counselor Paul Begala, referring to the huge infusion of
foreign aid the United States sent to help rebuild Germany after
World War II. ''I think there's something fundamental about the
American public that is committed to progress.''
</P>
<P>
   No one denies that it will take time for Clinton to rebuild his
credibility among congressional Republicans, a task that's
essential if he's to deal constructively with them on the central
tax and budget issues where disagreement is sharpest.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president's going to have to work hard at talking about
the
</P>
<P>
   issues and the agenda,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said
Friday, just hours after the Senate voted to acquit Clinton. ''He
will work hard. He will reach out across party lines.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll first have to peer over the battle lines already drawn by
Democrats and Republicans over the most traditional of political
conflicts: the annual budget debate.
</P>
<P>
   Amid projections of federal budget surpluses adding up to $4.4
trillion over the next 15 years, Clinton has proposed funneling
$2.7 trillion into the Social Security program.
</P>
<P>
   The retirement and disability program is accumulating money at
the moment, but is on track to begin paying out more in benefits
than it collects from payroll taxes by 2013. Clinton has said his
plan would save the program, which sends a monthly check to one out
of every six Americans, until 2055.
</P>
<P>
   He has proposed devoting more than $600 billion of the
anticipated surplus to shore up Medicare, the federal health
insurance program for retirees, and another $500 billion over the
next decade and a half to create federally subsidized savings
accounts for lower-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   He has proposed using most of what's left of the projected
surplus for education and defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, though, have other ideas. They've called for
across-the-board income tax cuts ranging from 10 percent to 14
percent, plans Clinton has vowed to oppose.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their approach would squander the surplus,'' said Begala. ''It
would reward consumption rather than savings and reward
disproportionately those who are already succeeding.''
</P>
<P>
   The great debate will likely begin in earnest the last week of
February, after Congress returns from next week's recess.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to steal a march on his Republican foes, Clinton plans to
showcase his Social Security scheme at a White House event this
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's issue-a-day approach to governance is one reason he's
emerging from his impeachment ordeal with his popularity intact.
Recent polls by the Gallup Organization of Princeton, N.J., show
his job approval rating at 67 percent, remarkably high for a
second-term president, and the constant focus on bread-and-butter
issues appears to be countering any perception of a lame-duck
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The White House expects Clinton's poll numbers to slip in the
weeks ahead, as a public that has been largely turned off by the
impeachment effort no longer sees the imperative of rallying around
a president under siege.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton's popularity remains the top drawing card for
Democrats, who have called on him to travel to New Hampshire this
Thursday to help raise money in preparation for critical primaries
in the run-up to next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's event _ coming auspiciously on the seventh
anniversary of the primary that set Clinton on course for the White
House _ kicks off the start of a busy season for Clinton, who hopes
to strengthen the presidential campaign of Gore and fellow
Democrats seeking House and Senate seats.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got about a day a month over the next five months devoted
to party-building and fund raising,'' said Lockhart, adding that
the best thing Clinton can do for his fellow Democrats is to
advance his agenda for the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think, ultimately, it's the best politics,'' said Lockhart,
''that, if we get a lot done and we move forward to the year 2000
with a strong presidential candidate and strong senatorial and
congressional candidates around the country, campaigning on
Democratic ideas, ideas that the president leads the Democratic
Party with, the Democrats will do quite well.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
