<HEADER>
A4180 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON-NY     02-13 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS DOUBLY VEXED IN THE STRONGHOLD OF LIVINGSTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-AFTERMATH, IMPEACH-STARR,
IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-POLITICIANS, IMPEACH-SOCIETY, IMPEACH-REAX,
IMPEACH-LEGACY-REVIEW, EDIT-IMPEACH-AFTERMATH, DOWD-COLUMN) 
(bl) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   METAIRIE, La. _ Even at the giddy height of Carnival, as nightly
Mardi Gras parades roll past the strip malls and suburban homes
that make up Rep. Bob Livingston's district, many people in this
Republican stronghold are almost gloomy. Not only did they lose
their conservative champion to the Washington sex scandals, but now
President Clinton himself has been acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of angry people in this district over what is
going on,'' said Roger Villere, a Republican national committeeman
who works as a florist on Veteran's Boulevard, the traffic-choked
commercial spine of this New Orleans suburb. ``Every day I have 7,
8, 10 people call and say, `We don't know what people these polls
are talking to.'''
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to his high national job approval ratings, Clinton is
all but despised in this very conservative district, and his
acquittal Friday was doubly vexing because of Livingston's demise.
Poised for elevation from chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee to speaker of the House, Livingston announced his
resignation in December, after his own past extramarital affairs
had surfaced in the heat of the impeachment debate, and officially
leaves Congress this month. Now perhaps no district in the country
has lost more from the entire scandal than Louisiana's 1st.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bittersweet?'' said Rick Legendre, who runs Livingston's local
office but is now shopping a resume. ``I don't know of any
sweetness to it at all if you are referring to Bob. It appears so
unfair that Newt Gingrich is gone, that Bob is gone and that the
president still stands.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Legendre sat in the congressman's office as two
secretaries shuffled papers. The telephones never rang, and
Legendre said he had stopped watching the news or reading
newspapers since December. So he indulged in a game of ``what might
have been.'' The Speakership, he said, was like winning the
lottery. What was once Livingston's imminent ascension had helped
speed plans, for example, to build a Defense Department technology
center at the nearby University of New Orleans, bringing 1,200
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only does it hurt the district, it hurts the entire
state,'' he said of Livingston's fall. ``As Appropriations
chairman, Bob helped the state tremendously. One can only imagine
what he could have done as Speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the misshapen 1st District, which was gerrymandered to
include most of the white suburbs of New Orleans, will rank last in
House Republican seniority once Livingston leaves office Feb. 28. A
special election to replace him is set for May, and the Republican
candidacy of the former Klan leader David Duke, who once
represented part of the area in the state Legislature, has further
embarrassed local Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Many here are disgusted with both Clinton and his Republican
adversaries. ``Our country is the worse for it,'' said Jim Loyd,
55, a retiree waiting for his wife inside a local shopping mall.
Loyd described himself as a ``reactionary'' who voted for
conservative Republicans only because he had no better alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``What have they demonstrated recently that shows that the
Republicans are in control?'' he said. ``They're not. And the
reason is the moderate Republicans are voting Democratic, and they
should be held accountable for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Few of more than 40 people interviewed throughout the district
condemned Livingston for his affairs, considering them private,
family matters. But many were critical of Clinton's cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a better person than Clinton,'' Michelle Trosclair, 46,
said of the congressman after finishing lunch at Bozo's restaurant
with her mother, Jo Hug. ``At least he did admit it and moved on.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hug sympathized with Livingston's decision to resign, though
she felt a little betrayed. ``He should have stuck it out,'' she
said, for the greater good of the district. Of her fellow
Republicans, she said: ``They don't have any gumption. The
Democrats outsmarted the Republicans. They made fools out of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone condemned Clinton, who won 37 percent of the vote
here in 1996. ``I'd like to see Hillary as President for the next
four years and then have Clinton come back for eight years after
that,'' said Gaston Rodrigue, 77, who was with his wife, Rita, at
the Morning Call coffee shop. ``If all the politicians who
committed adultery resigned, you wouldn't have nobody left.''
</P>
<P>
   But Villere, the Republican committeeman, seemed more typical of
voters here, lambasting Clinton for his indiscretions and Senate
Republicans for what he deemed their cowardice.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got scared because of the polls,'' he said, ``and they
got scared because of the incredible pressure they were getting
from the radical left.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Decker, 32, eating lunch at Lakeside Mall, seethed at
the mention of Clinton. ``If I perjured myself, I would go to
jail,'' said Ms. Decker, a loan officer at a car dealership. ``I
recently had a deposition, and my attorney said, `No matter what
you do, tell the truth.' And that wasn't even a grand jury.''
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, nibbling on a chicken sandwich, Angela Langdon, a
49-year-old piano teacher, said she found something honorable in
Livingston's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate adultery,'' she said, ``but you've got to hand it to
Bob Livingston. To me, he's honest, he's not a hypocrite. Maybe he
fell in one way, but in another way he set a terrific example. I
don't know why Clinton got away with all this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But George Rome does not think Clinton necessarily got away with
anything. ``His legacy will be that he's the first impeached
president of his generation,'' said Rome, a 50-year-old retiree.
``He's got to live with that for the rest of his life. If they
can't find him guilty, I'll settle for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's office declined requests for an interview with him.
The special election to fill his seat is scheduled for May 1, with
an expected runoff between the top two finishers May 29. There are
six candidates, with Duke's presence already generating some
publicity if not voter passion. In a splintered field, local
Republicans say, Duke could advance to a runoff, but he is given
little chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana voters are known for a sense of humor, which could
influence the election. One candidate is a wealthy ophthalmologist,
considered a serious contender, and her full name, believe it or
not, is Monica Monica.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
