<HEADER>
A4182 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-VLADIVOSTOK-AR     02-13 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-VLADIVOSTOK-ART-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON RUSSIA'S FAR-EAST FRINGE, UNREALPOLITIK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VLADIVOSTOK, Russia _ Jutting over Golden Horn Bay, this
rough-and-tumble port city is the wildest outpost in Russia's wild
east. A closed, militarized city during the Cold War, Vladivostok
has long been a den of intrigue and hardship.
</P>
<P>
   But these days it is also the daffiest place in Russia. The
former mayor claims to have extrasensory powers. Local elections
have been invalidated 15 times. The mental hospital even released
some of its patients after squabbling officials allowed its budget
to run dry.
</P>
<P>
   So the news that the autocratic governor, Yevgeny Nazdratenko,
has received a mysterious $1 million prize for his work as one of
the world's great leaders seemed par for the course. The accolade
was issued by the ``World Aristocratic Academy,'' an organization
whose only known address is a post-office box in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   The magnanimous governor has promised to distribute the proceeds
to the needy before the gubernatorial election in December.
</P>
<P>
   And while critics mutter that the prize is no more than a goofy
vote-buying scheme, swarms of pensioners, who survive on as little
as $25 a month, are clamoring for their share. They swamped a local
theater where the governor's aides were taking applications for the
money.
</P>
<P>
   It all added up to just another week in Vladivostok, Russia's
main Pacific port and an object lesson in how hard it can be to
raise a democratic society out of the ruins of the Soviet empire.
</P>
<P>
   With the fetters of state control off, Vladivostok's new-found
freedoms have dissolved into political farce, an especially bizarre
version of the tragicomic ``Winter's Tale'' now playing across
Russia. The nation's ailing president goes to work so rarely that
his trips to the Kremlin prompt urgent news bulletins.
</P>
<P>
   And Alexander Lebed, a Siberian governor and presidential
hopeful, seemed to typify the punchy, touchy national mood when he
lost control recently in front of television cameras and harangued
a local businessman with bleeped-out expletives.
</P>
<P>
   In Vladivostok, as across Russia, the political ironies might
raise more laughs if they did not have such dire consequences for
the residents.
</P>
<P>
   Like this richly endowed country, Vladivostok ought to be better
off. Perched on the edge of Russia, it has a huge port, a fishing
industry and timber. Its neighbors are China, Japan and Korea. A
snazzy new Korean-owned hotel reflects its proximity to potentially
lucrative Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
   With rolling hills that evoke images of San Francisco,
Vladivostok is also a magnet for painters attracted by the sweeping
vistas, as well as a wellspring of ``Vlad Pop,'' Russia's brand of
alternative rock music.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese markets, once strictly outlawed within the city limits,
have cropped up, befitting a region that sits on the ruins of
ancient Manchurian civilizations. Even in the days of the Soviet
Union, Vladivostok's port status gave it a window on the world.
</P>
<P>
   The independent spirit of the city seems to be captured by the
families and couples taking weekend strolls on the frozen waters of
the city's bay.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these people say they are sick of the region's political
soap opera, which has pitted the authoritarian Nazdratenko against
Viktor Cherepkov, the former mayor, who was disqualified from
running for re-election in September by officials loyal to the
governor and then was removed from his post in December by
presidential decree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all on our own,'' said Alexander, 57, a former welder
who did not want to give his last name, as he ice-fished on the
bay. The bucket of small fish he catches on a good day helps him
supplement his monthly pension of 560 rubles, or $25.
</P>
<P>
   But try as many do, it is hard to forget about politics. After
all, it is not every city that is festooned with banners like
``Vladivostok Is Not a Psychiatric Ward'' _ a sly dig at
Cherepkov's eccentricity _ or ``City, Wake Up From the Hypnosis.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the political struggle is straightforward. Who
will dominate Russia's Far East? Will it be the government of the
Primoriye region run by Nazdratenko, or the city of Vladivostok,
Cherepkov's former fief, which is the major business center of the
area and home to almost one-third of Primoriye's 2.3 million
people?
</P>
<P>
   But that simple power struggle is vastly complicated by the
strange personalities involved.
</P>
<P>
   First there is Cherepkov, the owlish former director of a
military laboratory, who served as Vladivostok's mayor off and on
for the last seven years. He claims to have used his mental powers
to produce more than 520 inventions, including one that cures
female infertility.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is extra sense?'' he mused in an interview in a hospital,
where he was unwinding before a new bout of politicking. ``It is
someone who has capabilities others do not have. I never sleep more
than three or four hours. I compete with computers to see who has
more in his memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Cherepkov's years as mayor were unusual. Convinced
that the regional administration should be paying more for the
upkeep of the city, Cherepkov slashed financing for vital services.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of apartment blocks were left without heat. Orphanages
ran low on food. Elevator maintenance was stopped. As stocks of
medicine were exhausted, the local mental hospital even began
releasing patients. The city's former main psychiatrist said he was
forced out of his job after he privately recommended that Cherepkov
be ``tested.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cherepkov won the loyalty of many voters by fixing the
traffic-clogged roads, a major preoccupation for drivers who zip
around in used Japanese automobiles, the steering wheels fixed
incongruously on the right.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy-handed methods employed by Nazdratenko to prevent
Cherepkov from running for re-election as mayor also transformed
him into a martyr in the eyes of many city residents, who would
like to see him run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Nazdratenko runs his domain with his own
idiosyncrasies. Flouting Primoriye's special environmental
regulations, last year he bestowed the skin of an endangered
Siberian tiger on Alexander Lukashenko, the autocrat who rules
Belarus, more than 5,000 miles and eight time zones to the West.
</P>
<P>
   Nazdratenko quarreled relentlessly with President Boris
Yeltsin's team of market reformers until they were ousted in the
wake of last August's financial crisis. And his deputy, Konstantin
Tolstoshein, still speaks disparagingly of the ``Yids'' who
launched Russia's capitalist reforms.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in the white marble administration building,
which towers over the port, Tolstoshein dismissed reports of vast
corruption within the administration as a sinister and potentially
mortal conspiracy by Russia's secret services.
</P>
<P>
   Then he whipped out a photograph of himself with his nephew,
Pavel Bure, the Russian-born hockey star and national celebrity, as
evidence of his own good character.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to crush me physically they know how to do it,''
he said ominously. ``They can make it look like I had a heart
attack or like I was hit by a car.''
</P>
<P>
   The No. 3 man in the region, Viktor Kondratov, laughs off
Tolstoshein's claim of persecution. A senior official in the
Federal Security Service, the heir to the old KGB, Kondratov
doubles as Yeltsin's anointed personal representative to this
region.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed impeccably in a suit and tie and carrying an unlighted
pipe, Kondratov looks like a suave character out of a John Le Carre
novel. He has staunchly opposed the governor, who he charges has
played fast and loose with the region's budget.
</P>
<P>
   But the security man is also not supporting Cherepkov. That has
raised speculation that the Kremlin favors the so-called ``zero
option'' in which Nazdratenko and Cherepkov are both ousted from
office and a new figure becomes the overlord of this eastern
outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Leading Moscow reformers, for their part, say that if the choice
boils down to Nazdratenko and Cherepkov, the eccentric former mayor
is the best bet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nazdratenko has been an absolute disaster and has created the
conditions for enormous corruption,'' said Yegor Gaidar, the former
prime minister. ``I do not overestimate Cherepkov's administrative
abilities, but he was elected and the actions the governor has
taken against him are clearly unlawful.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, most of the political gossip centers on
Nazdratenko's mysterious commendation for leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Critics quietly complain that the $1 million prize is simply a
device to transfer state money to Nazdratenko so he can in turn
hand it out to appreciative voters. Most of the cowed local media
have been careful not to ask too many questions.
</P>
<P>
   Nazdratenko's aides insist the award was arranged by a secretive
French baron, who has never been to Vladivostok and who learned
about the governor when one of his strongest supporters, Viktor
Fersht, visited the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Fersht says that both the New York City mayor, Rudolph Giuliani,
and the actress Demi Moore have been among the lucky winners.
Spokesmen for Giuliani and the actress said they had never heard of
the supposed donor and certainly never received $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   But that has not chastened Fersht. He insists that the New York
mayor is simply keeping mum about the prize to avoid U.S. taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Fersht also volunteered an explanation for Cherepkov's continued
popularity with many voters: a secret device that Fersht said
enables the former mayor to control voters' minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our region is simply a testing ground for the parliamentary
and presidential elections,'' Fersht said in a telephone interview.
``I have one of these devices and I will demonstrate it for you
sometime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
