<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH SCANDAL,   IN LIMELIGHT,   JEOPARDIZES   GOVERNMENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ An ebullient performance on national television by one
of Ireland's most prominent politicians has embarrassed the
20-month-old coalition government of Prime Minister Bertie Ahern
and raised the prospect that the government might collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Padraig Flynn, Ireland's member of the European
Commission in Brussels, the executive body of the European Union,
is a target of one of two government-established tribunals
investigating accusations that members of Ahern's party and other
politicians took large sums of money from businessmen in return for
official favors.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn, joking and lecturing the national television audience,
annoyed people and politicians of all parties by refusing to answer
directly an accusation that he took the equivalent of $75,000 from
a Dublin entrepreneur in 1989, three years before he moved to
Brussels. The public response refocused attention on the tribunals.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare act of public criticism of one of its own political
stars, members of Parliament from Ahern's Fianna Fail party
approved a resolution Wednesday night telling Flynn to explain the
affair immediately. Only Flynn's daughter, Beverly Cooper Flynn,
who succeeded him in the Parliament, defended his failure to
respond.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, leaders of the largest opposition party, Fine Gael,
said at their annual convention that the scandal would force a
national election in the next six months, three years earlier than
the constitutional deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Harney, the leader of the small, conservative Progressive
Democrats party and the deputy prime minister, has threatened to
withdraw from the government and bring down the coalition, and
force a new election if more damaging disclosures are made at the
two tribunals.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern has not been accused of taking any money improperly or
illegally himself, and the gifts were not necessarily illegal when
they were made, at least 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition political leaders say that as head of the largest
governing party, Fianna Fail, Ahern, a professional accountant,
should know about the payments and make his knowledge public. Ahern
asserts that he is an honest man and will testify before the
tribunals if summoned.
</P>
<P>
   To stay in power, Ahern needs the four votes held in the
166-member Parliament by members of the Progressive Democrats
party. The Progressive Democrats broke away from Ahern's party 14
years ago to combat what they saw as corruption in Fianna Fail.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn, according to the sworn testimony of one witness, accepted
about $75,000. The witness, Tom Gilmartin, an entrepreneur, said he
passed it to Flynn in 1989 for the Fianna Fail party, but that
Flynn kept it for himself. He said in interviews that Flynn begged
him to say that the money was intended for Flynn, not the party.
Gilmartin was looking for needed approval of a development in
downtown Dublin. Flynn was then the Environment Minister, and his
approval was needed for the project.
</P>
<P>
   The huge complex was never built.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern confirmed that the party never received the money and
called on Flynn to explain.
</P>
<P>
   After ignoring calls for him to comment, Flynn, in an appearance
two weeks ago on a national prime-time entertainment show, spoke of
how little money he earned ($150,000 after taxes) and how hard it
was to maintain his three houses, in Dublin, Brussels and
Castelbar, Ireland, on that kind of money.
</P>
<P>
   He brushed aside the question of the $75,000, saying only that
he had never taken money in return for favors. Critics in all
parties were quick to note that this begged the question of whether
he received and kept the money. He has since refused to elaborate,
saying only that he will cooperate with the investigating tribunal
if requested.
</P>
<P>
   The television performance stimulated widespread anger among
ordinary people and led directly to calls for Ahern to resign and
call a new parliamentary election.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmartin, who lives in England, said his anger at Flynn's
televised comments led him to disclose, two weeks ago, that he had
discussed the payment to Flynn in a meeting in 1989 with Ahern.
</P>
<P>
   This put Ahern at the center of the scandal. The prime minister
said at first that he had only a vague recollection of one meeting
with Gilmartin. Within 24 hours he changed his account, saying
there had been several meetings, but that he had never discussed
the gift money and that his party had never received it. He noted
that he has no power to remove Flynn. He said he thought Flynn
should say what he knows about the $75,000 gift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am an honest person, a credible person,'' the prime minister
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
