<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHAT'S GOING ON? 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The students at Bushwick Outreach, an alternative
high school in Brooklyn, were telling me about their encounters
with the police. Some were quietly emotional, but the prevailing
tone was resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Lani Soto, 18, recalled the night last July when two uniformed
officers approached her on a subway train in Bay Ridge. She had
just left work and was on her way to Williamsburg, where she lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about 11 o'clock,'' she said. ``I was just sitting
there and the cops came up and started asking me questions. One of
the cops said, `Get up.' I said I didn't want to get up. He grabbed
me by my hair and said, `You're going to get up.' He pulled me up
by my hair and pushed my face into the doors. Then he started
touching me sexually, claiming he was frisking me. He put his hands
between my legs and on my breasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the train stopped and the doors opened, I just stepped
out and they started laughing at me. I just started crying. The
cops can do what they want because they have a badge and a gun.
When it happened it made me feel low. I sat down on the bench and
waited for the next train.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Coram, 18, said he's been stopped and searched so many
times ``you almost become immune to it.'' He said the ``most
embarrassing incident'' occurred late on a Friday afternoon when he
and about eight friends were on their way to a party. ``An
undercover squad car pulled up on Liberty Avenue and these guys
jumped out real fast, screaming at us. My friend said, `Well, who
are you?' They didn't like that so they said, `All right, everybody
on your knees.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And they put us on our knees side by side and searched us one
by one. They cursed at us the whole time. The sun was out and
everybody was looking at us. When we got up we didn't even feel
like going to the party. We went home.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard said he and his friends feel there is nothing they can
do about the harassment, that it is just a routine part of life.
``If you resist, you will get the beating of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Angerosa, 19, said he and some friends were hanging out
on New Year's Eve when a group of police officers drove up and
ordered them to line up against a wall. Joseph's mother spotted
them from a window and ran outside. Joseph said that when she
demanded to know what was happening, a cop told her to ``shut the
(expletive) up and keep on walking.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph said, ``I asked the cop why he was talking to my mom like
that. He pulled out his gun, pointed it dead at me and told me to
get up against the wall. I did what he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are always being harassed by the police. I believe it is
because we are Hispanic. But what can you do about it?''
</P>
<P>
   The students related their stories in separate interviews, one
after another. Richard Wilcher told of the officer who, during a
search, grabbed his genitals and squeezed and yanked so hard he had
to go to a hospital for treatment. Omega Linton told of the officer
who, for no reason, demanded identification, including her name,
address, telephone number and Social Security number. When she
objected, he threatened to arrest her. She gave him the
information.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Cruz was stopped in a subway station by an officer who
demanded identification. She didn't have any. She said that when
she objected to the way she was being treated the officer grabbed
her, threw her against a wall and put her in handcuffs. Emily's
teacher, Ellie Weiss, happened to come by a few minutes later. She
persuaded the officers to remove the handcuffs and release her
student.
</P>
<P>
   The stories went on and on, too many for me to hear. Such is
life for young black and Hispanic residents of New York City. They
do not have the same rights as whites. The police treat them as
lesser beings, stopping them, demanding identification, and
searching their clothing and their bodies at will. They are fondled
and beaten and endlessly humiliated while the mayor, the police
commissioner and other top officials simply look the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've actually seen students break down, crying over what they
feel is serious harassment,'' said Adam Gerstein, the principal of
Bushwick Outreach. ``When you see that the students really are
traumatized, and when it happens so often, you've really got to
wonder what's going on out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
