<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABROAD, SHRUGGING SLIGHTLY AND CLAPPING POLITELY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-AFTERMATH, IMPEACH-STARR,
IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-POLITICIANS, IMPEACH-SOCIETY,
IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON, IMPEACH-LEGACY-REVIEW, EDIT-IMPEACH-AFTERMATH,
DOWD-COLUMN) 
(bl) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ President Clinton's acquittal on impeachment charges was
seen in most places around the world Saturday as a victory for
common sense.
</P>
<P>
   The good guys won, the influential French daily Le Monde told
its readers. ``The country recognized more of itself in Bill
Clinton than in Kenneth Starr, and so much the better,'' the
newspaper said in an editorial, referring to the independent
counsel whose findings led to the president's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The news itself did not even make the front page of Le Monde, or
that of popular British tabloid newspapers that normally thrive on
sex scandals.
</P>
<P>
   The slightly more sedate Times of London ran the banner
headline, ``Clinton: the great escape,'' but it did not get very
excited about the news. ``As an event it was rather like listening
to the football results when you already know who has won,'' the
article said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Britain, Clinton's impeachment on perjury and
obstruction of justice charges in the Monica Lewinsky affair has
always been seen as a matter of neither seamy sex nor high
principle, but rather as pure partisan politics.
</P>
<P>
   Never having really understood why the House of Representatives
and the Senate went through with the impeachment process, most
foreigners are glad it is over.
</P>
<P>
   South African President Nelson Mandela Africa congratulated both
the Senate and the White House on Friday's verdict and said he
hoped that the United States could turn its attention to more
urgent things.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, where Clinton planned to talk in Merida with
President Ernesto Zedillo on Sunday about immigration and drug
trafficking problems, political analyst Sergio Sarmiento told The
Associated Press: ``It's incomprehensible for the majority of
Mexicans that an intimate relationship would be converted into a
political persecution.''
</P>
<P>
   The head of Israel's opposition Labor Party, Ehud Barak, said he
had written to Clinton to express satisfaction with the Senate's
decision. Israeli radio reported that Barak hoped Clinton could now
turn to trying to restart the Middle East peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Deputy Prime Minister Tim Fischer hoped that the
United States could now focus on trade, The Associated Press said.
</P>
<P>
   In France, the conservative daily Le Figaro, which did put the
news of the acquittal on its front page, wondered whether Clinton's
popularity, soaring in all the months of the scandal inquiry, might
drop now.
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder, who visited Clinton in
Washington before the final Senate votes, said, ``The subject
doesn't interest me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, the chancellor told reporters, was to him ``one of the
great American presidents.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 1247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
