<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SOCIETY-2TAKE     02-13 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SOCIETY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A YEAR OF SCANDAL MAY ADD UP TO A BRIEF MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-AFTERMATH, IMPEACH-STARR,
IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-POLITICIANS, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON,
IMPEACH-REAX, IMPEACH-LEGACY-REVIEW, EDIT-IMPEACH-AFTERMATH,
DOWD-COLUMN) 
(bl) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After the tapes and the lies, the tears, the
betrayals and the trial, the impeachment drama that gripped, then
repelled and finally seemed to numb the nation for more than a year
is over at last. And in its wake, in the culture it both reflected
and so often seemed so disconnected from, it has left _ what?
</P>
<P>
   Deeper partisan dissension and a sharper moral divide? A renewed
respect for the instincts of democracy and the accuracy of public
opinion polls? A surfeit of sex jokes and a nation of children who
learned in the same breath about the birds and the bees and how a
bill becomes a law?
</P>
<P>
   Husbands and wives have been forced to face infidelity, perhaps
even their own, in new and public ways. Politicians and would-be
politicians have had skeletons in their own closets rattled. Much
of the press and popular culture has let slip all remaining
restraint on topics once taboo, because those topics arose in a
criminal investigation of the president and appeared in the Starr
report's footnotes.
</P>
<P>
   The reference points are pervasive. The night before the Senate
voted to acquit President Clinton, an episode of ``ER'' featured a
fetching young doctor in thong underwear, and the same ``Today''
program that broadcast the first televised interview with Linda
Tripp also included an interview with talk show host Jerry
Springer, who conducts his own daily brawls over infidelity, failed
friendship and the follies of lust and power.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to say that Watergate had the effect of making the
country more cynical,'' said Nelson George, the author of ``Hip Hop
America'' (Viking, 1998), a well received work on the pervasive
effects of hip-hop culture. ``This contributes in a different way.
Whereas there was a great suspicion of political leaders trying to
steal things or mislead the public, this feels like the presidency
and politics has become part of the Ricki Lake culture. This whole
thing is nothing more than another episode.''
</P>
<P>
   A highly arbitrary and unscientific sampling of writers,
historians and critical thinkers on both the left and right last
week revealed little certainty about the impact on the nation of
the investigation into the president's relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, beyond the foregone conclusion that the law allowing
appointment of independent counsels will be greatly modified or
allowed to lapse.
</P>
<P>
   But a rough consensus did emerge that the whole affair left the
transitory feeling of a nightmare or a movie, and that it amounted
more to an amplification of social and political trends already
well under way than a wholly new phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that there will be any lasting consequences
beyond the wretched Beltway,'' novelist Ward Just said from Berlin.
``The affair seems to me a kind of parenthesis in the national
narrative. It came out of nowhere and will end as it began, a
matter of tremendous consequence to Clinton and to Lewinsky, with
not much resonance for the rest of us. Anything momentous has a
mystery at its heart, and this episode has no mystery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moreover, it's been some time since Americans took moral
instruction from anyone in Washington. This story is like this
week's best-selling novel, remembered for as long as the plane
flight, forgotten almost at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Cass Sunstein, a professor at the University of Chicago Law
School who has argued that the independent-counsel law has created
``bizarre incentives'' for prosecutors with unlimited budgets and
undivided attention to pursue investigations beyond reasonable
bounds, said it was good that the Lewinsky case had apparently
doomed the law.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunstein added: ``There is also heightened risk of political
polarization among people for whom this is a defining event. Some
people will think that the impeachment shows the zealotry and
extremism of some elements, others that it shows that some
Democrats don't care about lawlessness. I tend to think that, by
itself, it's more blip than earthquake, but it may aggravate some
bad current tendencies toward political polarization, accusation,
even rage.''
</P>
<P>
   David Horowitz, a writer and president of the Center for the
Study of Popular Culture in Los Angeles and one of the more
prominent conservative voices here, said he thought ``people are
going to be less enthusiastic about probing questions and
investigations about candidates' private lives.'' By contrast,
Douglas Brinkley, a liberal historian at the University of New
Orleans, declared: ``We've learned that character does matter. It
is always going to be scrutinized in elections after this, because
people are going to want to know answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nora Ephron, the screenwriter and director, said that ``it's too
soon to tell'' what the impact of the past year's events would be
but added dryly: ``Will there ever be a husband anyone believes
again?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Debra Haffner, the president of the Sexuality Information and
Education Council of the United States, a nonprofit group that
advocates sex education, said the affair had forced painful
discussions between couples and between parents and children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this did either force some parents to talk perhaps
before they felt ready to do so, and I also think the adult silence
on this issue simply left many kids to their own devices,'' Ms.
Haffner said. ``In relationships I know where people had had
infidelity and moved on, and here it is again every night in your
bedroom on the 11 o'clock news, it has been very painful. No one's
talking about that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ms. Haffner said, she was surprised at the way
most Americans responded to the Starr report's more explicit
descriptions of sex in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected that America would not accept that and would turn
on the president,'' Ms. Haffner said, ``and yet America responded
with a maturity that said, `This is private, and these kinds of
details don't belong in the public sphere.'''
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Kalb, a longtime correspondent for CBS News who now heads
the Shorenstein Center for Press and Politics at the Kennedy School
of Government at Harvard, said the Lewinsky story, with its tabloid
details, and the all-news-all-the-time culture of cable and the
Internet inspired a level of sensationalist coverage that ``has
trumped old-fashioned mainstream journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Kalb said of the coverage, ``Years ago, it established a
beachhead on what could be called the island of journalism, and
gradually, it has extended that beachhead.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Kalb said, other stories, like the country's policy
toward weapons inspections in Iraq, had received less coverage than
usual ``because there is simply not enough space and time on
network news when there are so many pressures forcing editors and
producers to come in with more Monica or more ``news you can
use.''''
</P>
<P>
   Brinkley of New Orleans said he feared that one corollary of the
investigative and prosecutorial culture pervading Washington would
be ``a conscious effort not to leave historical footprints'' in the
form of tapes, notes and diaries, long the lifeblood of historians.
</P>
<P>
   But Brinkley was quick to say he did not believe the year's
events had left students particularly disillusioned, if only
because they had few illusions to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a society with a 40 to 50 percent divorce rate, and a
lot of these students come from broken homes,'' he said. ``The
perfect family is not a reality to them; they watch ``The Brady
Bunch'' and mock it.''
</P>
<P>
   Horowitz, the conservative writer, said the year was rife with
anomalies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our society works by a lot of unspoken rules and mores and
manners,'' he said. ``And that code was snapped by Clinton. He
doesn't seem to have the kind of conscience you'd expect in
somebody who has the responsibilities that he has.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Horowitz said, moderation won out. ``We're
not going to have, `Oh, God, the moralistic authoritarians telling
us what to do,''' he said, ``and it's not going to be anarchy,
sexual or otherwise, either. This is a very centrist country, knock
wood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 1251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-STARR-ART-775     02-13 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-STARR-ART-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT FOR STARR: SCRUTINY AND DECISIONS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-AFTERMATH, IMPEACH-TRIAL,
IMPEACH-POLITICIANS, IMPEACH-SOCIETY, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON,
IMPEACH-REAX, IMPEACH-LEGACY-REVIEW, EDIT-IMPEACH-AFTERMATH,
DOWD-COLUMN) 
(jw) 
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr has said he would
defer a decision on whether to indict President Clinton until his
impeachment trial was over. Decision time has now arrived.
</P>
<P>
   But it comes at a precarious moment for Starr and his office:
Never before in his 41/2-year tenure as independent counsel has
Starr been forced to fend off as many escalating inquiries and so
much mounting criticism from different quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department is launching an inquiry into alleged
misconduct by Starr's prosecutors. A special master is nearing
completion of a report on alleged leaks to the news media by
prosecutors in Starr's office. And the District of Columbia's
Office of Bar Counsel, which investigates accusations of wrongdoing
by lawyers, is conducting a separate inquiry into allegations of
misconduct made against several prosecutors in Starr's office.
</P>
<P>
   If that were not enough, the conduct of Starr's office will be
closely examined by the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee,
which will begin hearings on Feb. 24 to explore the strengths and
weaknesses of the independent counsel law. The controversial law,
enacted in 1978 after the Watergate inquiry, will expire on June 30
unless Congress reauthorizes it; the almost-certain demise of the
statute in its present form is likely to be one of Starr's
legacies.
</P>
<P>
   Although Starr has been relatively quiet in recent weeks, his
prosecutors watched the Senate trial very closely while preparing
for four pending criminal trials to be held later this year. Two
are scheduled to begin next month.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Starr must decide whether or not he
should seek the indictment of the president. Starr has told
associates that he believes he has the constitutional authority to
seek Clinton's indictment before his term expires in January 2001,
said several associates who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But Starr has not told his closest associates what he intends to
do, nor has he ``dropped any hints,'' one associate said.
</P>
<P>
   The associates said they believed that Starr was sensitive to
the fact that the indictment of a sitting president could cause the
nation to suffer a cataclysmic constitutional crisis after having
already endured a lengthy impeachment process. These associates
said they doubted whether Starr would ever be prepared to take such
a momentous step.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of Starr's cautiousness, one associate recalled
that Starr was especially sensitive about the timing of sending the
445-page impeachment referral to the House of Representatives last
September. The associate said Starr insisted that it not be sent
while the president was out of the country, or while Congress was
in recess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before he would decide to indict a sitting president, he would
consider many factors, including the impact of such a decision on
national security and the economy,'' said the associate who speaks
frequently with Starr. ``He is not reckless.''
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before the House Judiciary Committee last November,
Starr said he would wait until the end of the congressional
impeachment process to decide whether there was sufficient evidence
to seek the indictment of Clinton on charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice related to the Monica Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also testified that he had not reached a decision on the
question of whether there was sufficient evidence against Clinton
to persuade a ``fair-minded jury'' to ``convict based on these
facts.''
</P>
<P>
   But since the outcome of the Senate trial appeared certain for
weeks, Starr and members of his team have quietly confronted the
question. Several associates said last week that a sharp rift had
developed among Starr's prosecutors over what he should do and when
he should do it.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers inside the office and advisers outside the office
have quietly lobbied Starr to seek the indictment of the president
before he leaves office, associates of Starr said. Two senior
constitutional advisers, Ronald Rotunda and William Kelley, have
told Starr that they believe there is nothing in the Constitution
or recent legal authority that would prevent such an indictment.
Starr's office is aware that the president's lawyers would
challenge the constitutionality of an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   However, some lawyers in Starr's office and advisers outside the
office firmly believe that the office of the independent counsel
should not indict Clinton until after he leaves office in 23
months, if at all. Those lawyers said that a grand jury indictment
of the president while he was in office was unlikely, according to
associates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another issue facing Starr is that some of the most senior
lawyers in the office who played pivotal roles in the Lewinsky
inquiry will not be remaining in the office until Starr makes his
decision. Robert Bittman and Brett Kavanaugh, two of the office's
most important lawyers on the Lewinsky inquiry, have announced
their intentions to leave. And Jackie Bennett, Starr's deputy who
participated in the grand jury questioning of the president, is
also hunting for a job in Indiana, his native state, the associates
said.
</P>
<P>
   With those lawyers most familiar with the case leaving, The
Washington Post reported last week, it looks increasingly unlikely
that Starr intends to indict the president before he leaves office.
But one associate dismissed the speculation, saying, ``Those
lawyers don't know what Ken is thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, after the Senate's votes to acquit the president, the
leading prosecutor for the House impeachment managers said that it
would not be good for the country if Starr indicted the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think indicting and criminally trying him, after what
we have all been through, is going to be helpful to the country,''
said Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who heads the House Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   There has also been speculation about Starr's thoughts and plans
for his own professional fate, although he has been mum about his
future. Several associates have said they are convinced that Starr
may leave the office within the next several months.
</P>
<P>
   But another associate predicted that Starr would stay until the
important decisions were made and the clouds over his office had
lifted. ``I think he now feels a moral obligation not to drop this
thing,'' said the associate, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. ``He wants to see it through.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky grand jury's 18-month term expires next month. But
prosecutors could seek a six-month extension, which would allow the
current 23 members to continue hearing evidence about the Lewinsky
matter. Or, the associates said, Starr could seek a sealed
indictment against the president, or present the existing evidence
to a new grand jury for an indictment later.
</P>
<P>
   The statute of limitations on perjury and obstruction of justice
is five years, meaning that Starr could conceivably seek an
indictment as late as 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the matter of an indictment of Clinton, the office is
also actively investigating several issues relating to a former
White House volunteer, Kathleen Willey, who has testified that the
president made an unwanted sexual pass at her just outside the Oval
Office in November 1993. Starr's prosecutors are investigating
whether there were unlawful efforts to influence her testimony in
the Paula Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit against the president.
</P>
<P>
   In a related case, Julie Hiatt Steele, a friend of Ms. Willey's,
faces trial on charges that she made false statements under oath
that had cast doubt on Ms. Willey's claim. She is also charged with
trying to influence the testimony of others in the office.
</P>
<P>
   On March 8, Starr's prosecutors will begin Susan McDougal's
criminal contempt trial in Little Rock, Ark. Ms. McDougal is
charged with refusing to answer a grand jury's questions about
whether the president lied under oath when he testified in 1996
about the failed Whitewater land deal. If convicted, she faces a
10-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDougal is a former business partner of the Clintons in the
Whitewater real estate venture in Arkansas. She has already served
18 months in jail after a federal judge in Little Rock found her in
civil contempt for refusing to answer a grand jury's questions
about her dealings with the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, there will likely be two trials involving a
former Clinton Justice Department official, Webster Hubbell. In one
case, Hubbell is charged with fraud connected to a land development
deal in Arkansas. In the other case, which was recently reinstated
by an appeals court, he faces charges of tax evasion and mail
fraud. Hubbell has denied wrongdoing and is trying to quash the
indictment in the tax case.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's office must complete reports on his investigations into
the Whitewater land deal. He also must complete two other reports,
one on White House travel office dismissals, in which nepotism was
alleged, and another concerning an improper retrieval of hundreds
of FBI background inquiries of current and former government
employees, most of whom were Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   All three reports must be filed with the three-judge panel that
appointed Starr in August 1994. Associates said that those reports
would not likely be completed for some time.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
