<HEADER>
A4221 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-REDISTRICTING-     02-13 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-REDISTRICTING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG CENSUS ISSUE: USING SAMPLING IN REDISTRICTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (lb) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The two communities could hardly be more
different.
</P>
<P>
   One, in South Philadelphia just east of the Schuylkill River, is
largely black and poor, with people clustered in low-slung row
houses amid abandoned cars and trash-strewn lots.
</P>
<P>
   The other, Cheltenham Township, north of the city, is affluent
and racially integrated. Parked on the winding streets in front of
large fieldstone houses are Volvos and sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the method used in the next census count of the low-income
area south of the city's gleaming skyscrapers may determine which
district Cheltenham is in when new congressional maps are drawn in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   And statistical sampling may be the key.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Supreme Court ruled that the bureau could not
use sampling to help produce an official population figure that
will be used to determine the number of House seats each state will
be allocated.
</P>
<P>
   But the High Court did not explicitly rule on whether sampling
was permitted to establish precisely where inside a state people
live. Such information is used to draw boundaries for congressional
and state legislative districts.
</P>
<P>
   Though combatants often toss around terms like ``accuracy'' and
``fairness,'' the heart of the political battle over the 2000
census is whether sampling will be used in redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   Among Republicans and Democrats, political strategists and House
members, that far outweighs any questions on use of population
counts for distributing federal money or for determining the number
of House seats allocated to each state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Redistricting is the central issue,'' said Clark Bensen, a
Republican demographer who advises the Republican National
Committee on the issue. ``For most state legislators and House
members, the money is not the key issue that they care about.
Redistricting is what gets them excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Redistricting is the redrawing of every election district in
every state, for offices from city council to the House of
Representatives. The process is the masonry of American politics,
laying the foundation _ whether they have a politically safe
district or a competitive one _ upon which politicians base
virtually all their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Redistricting is carried out by state legislatures and
influenced by local and state politics. It is also affected by the
federal Voting Rights Act, which says the political power of
minorities cannot be seriously diluted in the process, and by the
``one-man, one-vote'' Supreme Court decisions requiring that all
congressional districts contain roughly the same number of people.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the next round of congressional redistricting will
not be felt until the 2002 elections. But with Republicans holding
a wafer-thin majority in the House, both parties are striving
mightily to gain whatever partisan advantage they can from the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that it's so close, I think people are seeing that any
little thing might have the potential of swinging control,'' said
Kimball Brace, president of Election Data Services, a political
demographics company. ``So now you're introducing this unknown
factor called sampling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau would like to use sampling to adjust the next
head count and avoid the errors of the last census. In the 1990
count, more than 8 million people were missed, many of them
minorities living in urban congressional districts that generally
vote Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau also estimated that 4 million people were counted
twice _ most of them affluent whites living in suburbs that tend to
vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Using sampling to correct those errors could have enormous
consequences on redistricting. ``Where you put these people,
whether by addition or subtraction, makes all the difference in the
world,'' said a Republican congressional aide who insisted on
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia is an example of the implications of sampling for
redistricting.
</P>
<P>
   The city has lost population since 1990, and will probably lose
one of its congressional seats after the next census.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent the 2nd Congressional District, which is about 62
percent black, from being broken up and its inhabitants scattered
into adjoining districts _ which may be a violation of the Voting
Rights Act _ local and state politicians are considering extending
its northern boundary across the city line into suburbs like
Cheltenham and Lower Merion.
</P>
<P>
   Such a change would not politically harm Rep. Chaka Fattah, the
district's Democratic incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have a slight majority in Cheltenham and Lower
Merion, but these communities have voted Democratic in the last few
elections. The two townships are now in the 13th District, and
though Republicans outnumber Democrats by 2-to-1, the 13th is a
true ``swing'' district.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton carried it in 1992 and 1996. Also in 1992,
voters elected Marjorie Margolies-Mezvinsky, a Democrat, to the
House. Two years later, she was defeated by a Republican, Jon Fox,
who was re-elected in 1996 by 84 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Joseph Hoeffel, a Democrat, beat Fox, largely on the
basis of a strong showing in places like Lower Merion and
Cheltenham. Losing those areas in redistricting would severely harm
Democratic prospects in the 13th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Hoeffel carried Lower Merion Township by about 5,000
votes, and Cheltenham by about 6,000 votes,'' said Marcel Groen,
chairman of the Montgomery County Democratic Party. ``He won the
election by 9,000 votes. Any questions?''
</P>
<P>
   But sampling might influence how much of Lower Merion and
Cheltenham are moved to the 2nd District. The 1990 census failed to
count nearly 15,000 people in the 2nd District, and counted more
than 4,300 in the 13th District twice, according to an analysis by
Democratic redistricting experts who used estimates from the Census
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Those missed tend to be renters, the poor, children, transient
people and those with low levels of education _ people who tend not
to vote.
</P>
<P>
   But whether they vote is irrelevant, redistricting experts say.
Every person added to Fattah's Democratic district through an
adjustment based on sampling reduces the need to move a person from
Lower Merion or Cheltenham Townships into the 2nd District. Without
sampling, those voters can be left in the 13th District, where they
improve Democratic prospects and harm Republican chances.
</P>
<P>
   Similar calculations are being made for congressional districts
all across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Republicans and Democrats fight over the use of sampling
for redistricting, experts in congressional map-making acknowledge
that they do not know the extent, if any, of sampling's effect on
the process. Other factors will influence redistricting as much as,
if not more than, sampling _ the makeup of state legislatures,
which party controls the governorships or whether the redistricting
plan faces a court challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Still, neither side is willing to ignore any impact sampling may
have, however small.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you do know is that if there is any impact that comes
about from sampling for redistricting, it's going to be bad if
you're a Republican,'' Bensen said. ``So as a Republican you don't
want it to take place, and as a Democrat you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, redistricting experts agree that to best understand the
debate over the next census, an issue replete with figures, the
best number to keep in mind is not the size of the undercount or
overcount, or the error rate in counting black or Hispanic people.
</P>
<P>
   The number to keep in mind is six. That is the size of the
Republicans' majority in the House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
