<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AMERICANS WILL GET TO SEE WHAT THEY MISSED IN '96 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If a wonderful sports event takes place but
nobody sees it on television, did it really happen? As a matter of
fact, yes, sometimes a game has validity even if it is shunned by
the big tube.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most glorious parts of the 1996 Summer Games was the
American women's gold medal in soccer before huge crowds in
collegiate Athens, Ga., far from the grubbiness of downtown
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, NBC was locked into its format of scripted
documentaries and jaded male basketball players, so the nation
hardly got to see Hamm and Akers and Overbeck doing what they do so
well.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, U.S. soccer officials raged at the injustice of
being ignored, but the tree that fell in the forest was heard,
ultimately. As a result, women will be seen playing soccer this
summer at the Women's World Cup, in front of large audiences, live
and on television.
</P>
<P>
   Does it matter that women will be playing the third of their
quadrennial World Cups at a time of year when basketball stages its
finals and baseball is in full gear? Maybe it will matter. Soccer
is already played by a huge swath of young American women, and some
of us who have seen compelling women's matches between the United
States and Norway or China think it could just be the ultimate team
sport for female athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Until that epic Olympic soccer tournament in 1996, the plans
were to limit the 1999 Women's World Cup to 16 teams, have them
play in modest stadiums in the Northeast, and allow teams and fans
to shuttle from game to game, on limited budgets. But Alan
Rothenberg, then the top U.S. official, huddled with Joseph (Sepp)
Blatter, who would soon take over FIFA, the world soccer body, and
they decided to think big and go national.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a crowd of 62,000 for the semifinals and over 70,000
for the finals, and our sense was that it was not just spillover
from Atlanta,'' said Marla Messing, the president of this 1999
Women's World Cup. ``We wanted to do justice to the World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of staging a regional event, they expanded to a
three-week jamboree in major stadiums in or near New York, Boston,
Washington, Chicago and the Bay Area, and culminating in the Rose
Bowl near Los Angeles, June 19-July 10.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night at 8 p.m. Eastern time, there will be a preview at
Spartan Stadium in nearby San Jose, with the Americans taking on a
world all-star team. At halftime, the draw for the World Cup will
be held, all of it televised on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance is not expected to be huge Sunday night, but Messing
says the crowds will come out this summer, and she should know. She
was responsible for filling the stadiums for the men's World Cup in
1994, and she remembered how pleased she was ``when we blew right
through our allotment'' a year ahead and had to scrounge for more
tickets to sell.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is not known as a soccer nation, but American
promoters do know how to sell a big event. The World Cup of 1994
sold 3.5 million tickets for 52 games, an average of 68,604 per
game, and Messing is not expecting to come close. However, she has
already sold 215,000 of the estimated 700,000 seats available in
the stadiums, some of which will be downsized, restricted only to
lower decks.
</P>
<P>
   Messing and staff have worked closely with girls' leagues
offering ticket packages and urging them to tailor their schedules
around the Cup. Messing has lined up corporate sponsorship and
television coverage and, while some dedicated promoters of men's
soccer chafe at perceived do-the-right-thing sentiment, for women's
soccer, Messing insists, she has not had to play a gender card _
``not once.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that ABC and ESPN will be televising all 32
games _ not just some heart-warming feature about Joy Fawcett's
being a mother of two, but Fawcett's booting a solid 20-yard pass
to a teammate; not just the stirring tale of Michelle Akers' battle
with Epstein-Barre syndrome, a neurological disorder, but Akers'
maneuvering herself into the atmosphere to head the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of these players will tell you they saw an image of
some other athlete when she was growing up,'' said Donna de Varona,
the Olympic swimming gold medalist and chairman of this Women's
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it was the ice hockey team in 1980,'' said Brandi
Chastain, referring to the Miracle on Ice by the United States team
at Lake Placid. ``I was impressed by the effort they gave.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the 1986 World Cup in Mexico,'' said Julie Foudy.
``I loved the enthusiasm and the passion in all the stadiums. It
was not just one country. It was the whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched the Olympics on television, gymnastics and soccer,''
Fawcett said. ``They made me want to be better, and now I want to
do that for young girls, to inspire them.''
</P>
<P>
   These athletes were shaped by established sports, male sports.
Now they will get a chance to play a World Cup in their own country
_ this time with the television cameras turned on. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 1309EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
