<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MORALISM OVERLOAD IN SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the righteous among us, the week spun into glorious
overload; you could sprain both wrists wagging I-told-you-so
fingers after Latrell Sprewell, the choking guard, was injured and
lost for a month; Eugene Robinson, the weak unsafety, announced he
would return his award for high moral character; Mike Tyson, the
people bender, went back to jail; Juan Samaranch and his merry band
were exposed as Olympian shakedown artists, and Dennis Lundy, the
Northwestern scholar-fixer, admitted to fumbling on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   But some history might temper the moralism. This season will
bring us the 80th anniversary of the Black Sox Scandal. Once
they've tampered with the World Series, can we crank up honest
outrage over anything else?
</P>
<P>
   Is that why there were no antisports demonstrations last week?
Were people numbed by the sheer critical mass of unsporting
conduct? Perhaps we are no longer looking for moral renewal in the
won-lost column, finding it instead in religion and politics.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early in the American sports century, the first major retailer
in the athletic mall, baseball, helped save its box office by
spinning an image of Shoeless Joe Jackson as a bucolic buffoon
caught in an urban web; this barefoot boy was no ungrateful farmer
striking back at greedy landowners. No, he was a sweet dummy
manipulated by teammates from the city and an evil genius, the
gambler Arnold Rothstein.
</P>
<P>
   At century's end, the major retailer, basketball, created the
athlete-model, Air Jordan, in a stunning display of marketing
synergy. Basketball sold shoes sold basketball sold shoes, as well
as other products. Because Michael's image was so carefully limited
to superior performance as a result of a passionate work ethic,
corporations were comfortable with him. The international audience,
which also responds well to action movies where language and
complex characterization don't intrude, loved Michael.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael is over now and Shoeless Joe will probably be
debunked as the Julius and Ethel Rosenbergs of sport, selling us
out to the enemy. It's time to get happy with what we've got. I was
disappointed that Sprewell was hurt just when I was appreciating
his game. Sprewell and Allen Iverson are the immediate future of
the National Basketball Association, as well as its most exciting
performers. Forgive their transgressions _ if indeed they got fair
shakes in the first place. If Sprewell had really done something
wrong, he would have been arrested for felonious assault, right?
Unless, of course, the NBA didn't want to risk exposing itself in
open court.
</P>
<P>
   There was guilty glee and empathy among male sportswriters when
they learned that Robinson had headed to vice-town after dropping
off his family the night before the Super Bowl. The Atlanta
Falcons' safety is a God Squadder, one of the growing number of
contemporary athletes who seem to be using higher powers as
performance-enhancing drugs. That very day he had received his
award from Athletes in Action. Shouldn't he have been above the
shabby rituals of traveling men playing by out-of-town rules? He
was a handsome, rich star, an All-Pro. Where were the swimsuit
models waiting to frolic in his suite?
</P>
<P>
   Was this just another Willie Loman story, filled with fear and
bravado? Just another little man caught in a plantation system?
Just another posturing football player who can't stand up and
organize against the National Football League owners' systemic
discrimination against black coaches?
</P>
<P>
   Fear and bravado, Mike Tyson was always champion of that
division. It's easy to understand the desire to punch out two guys
whose car just rear-ended yours. Jail? You should receive a high
moral character award. But Mike is marked for elimination; we used
his rage to entertain us and now he's more trouble than he's worth.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No sympathy for those Olympic devils. These are the same
hustlers who sue little Greek-American diners for using the sacred
name. (Now, the sponsors are busy scraping the five rings off their
corporate logos.)
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics have been frantically selling out since they
restarted as a sexist, classist, racist club in 1896. Forty years
later, under Samaranch's role model, Avery Brundage, the Olympics
lent its prestige to Adolf Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   The 1936 Berlin Games were a public-relations spectacular for
Nazism. Every city since has wanted the same cosmetic make over.
It's only too bad that some small-time chiselers from poorer
countries will take the fall on this.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Lundy's legal turnover. He pleaded guilty to perjury,
admitting he lied about fumbling at the goal line in 1994 to
protect the spread on a bet he had made on his own team. That
admission nullified Northwestern University's bet that the millions
it spent on a winning football team would pay off in national happy
news, increased enrollment and alumni donations.
</P>
<P>
   Results plus: Get-well cards to Sprewell, no more Robinson
jokes, therapy for Tyson, re-education camp for Lundy; dump the
Olympics and sell the franchise to Ted Turner's Goodwill Games.
</P>
<P>
   Historical redress: Dump Jordan and feature Shoeless Joe in a
Nike spot. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 1311EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
