u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-KOSOVO-710&AMP;ADD-N     02-13 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-KOSOVO-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES FORCE FOR KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Also moving in `w' category.) 
(lb) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton announced Saturday that he would
send nearly 4,000 troops to Kosovo to defend the ``national
interest'' as part of a NATO peacekeeping force, provided the
ethnic Albanians and Serbs who are warring there strike a peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``America has a national interest in achieving this peace,''
Clinton said. ``If the conflict persists, there likely will be a
tremendous loss of life and a massive refugee crisis in the middle
of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the parties have made little progress during peace talks
in France, despite pressure from NATO to reach a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   But in the event of an agreement, the Clinton administration and
its European allies want to have a force ready to move swiftly into
the area, a formerly autonomous enclave in southern Serbia, on the
border with Albania. Ethnic Albanian rebels in Kosovo are demanding
independence from Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the Senate found him not guilty on charges of
perjury and obstruction of justice, the president used what is
often a low-key forum for perfunctory policy ruminations _ his
weekly radio address _ to announce a decision that has been in the
works for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's announcement was timed to strengthen the hand of
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who flew on Saturday to
Paris to meet with representatives of the Serbs and Kosovo
Albanians, as well as with European foreign ministers who are
overseeing the peace negotiations under way in Rambouillet, France.
</P>
<P>
   But White House aides also expected Clinton's announcement to
draw concentrated news coverage and commentary to compete with
lingering musings over the trial.
</P>
<P>
   In his radio address, Clinton argued that the prospect of U.S.
participation in the NATO force would give ``both sides the
confidence to lay down their arms.''
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that the NATO mission, which is expected to include
28,000 troops in all, ``be well-defined, with a clear and realistic
strategy to allow us to bring our forces home when their work is
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration has been consulting with members of Congress
to secure their support for the mission, but it has taken the
position that it does not need formal congressional approval to
send troops. Clinton said Saturday that he would make his ``final
decision'' to send troops ``in close consultation'' with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Some prominent Republicans have voiced support for such a
mission, but others have raised concerns, some of which were echoed
by Pentagon officials until late last week. They worried that the
mission could drag on indefinitely, at high cost, and embroil U.S.
soldiers in what amounts to a civil war over ethnic grievances that
have roots dating back to the 14th century.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that he would not send troops unless the
Serbs and Kosovo Albanians agree to the force and demonstrate that
they will implement the peace agreement. That agreement, he said,
``must provide for an immediate cease-fire, rapid withdrawal of
most Serbian security forces, and demilitarization of the
insurgents.''
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for NATO peacekeepers on the ground in Kosovo to
enforce an armistice, the ethic Albanians are being asked to give
up demands for independence and accept autonomy, officials said. As
the president showed himself once again focused on his job on
Saturday, he also signaled that he is willing to put his robust
political approval ratings to the test on a potentially risky
military mission in a place unfamiliar to most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that he had learned from the conflict in Bosnia,
where a bloody conflict raged for years before the United States
brokered a still-fragile peace agreement and dispatched troops to
enforce it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bosnia taught us a lesson,'' the president said. ``In this
volatile region, violence we fail to oppose leads to even greater
violence we will have to oppose later, at greater cost.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned that in the case of Kosovo, the violence could spread
to Albania and Macedonia, and reignite the conflict in Bosnia. ``It
could even involve our NATO allies, Greece and Turkey,'' Clinton
said. ``If we wait until casualties mount and war spreads, any
effort to stop it will come at a higher price under more dangerous
conditions.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Under the current NATO plan, Kosovo would be divided into zones
overseen by a peacekeeping force that would be overwhelmingly
European. In Bosnia, by contrast, the NATO-led force is dominated
by Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1989, Kosovo was an autonomous region within the old
communist Yugoslavia, and ethnic rivalries there had been subsumed
for decades under the tough doctrine laid down by communist
Yugoslavia's founder, Josip Broz Tito.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also the cradle of Serbian nationalism, revered by
many Serbs as the site of their most holy Orthodox monuments and a
1389 battle that marked the start of their centuries-long struggle
to preserve that faith during rule by the Ottoman Turks.
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic used the cause of Kosovo to whip up
his campaign to carve a Greater Serbia from the collapse of
communist Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo's Albanians, who make up about 90 percent of the
province's estimated 2 million people, responded with a campaign of
nonviolent civil disobedience, creating a completely parallel
system of schools and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   As Yugoslavia disintegrated with a war, first in Slovenia and
then in Croatia and Bosnia, Kosovo was viewed by diplomats and
military specialists as the ultimate flashpoint.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, local police and special military units sent by the
Serbian government in Belgrade began a violent campaign to crack
down on the Kosovo Liberation Army, a rebel force that had
abandoned the Kosovo Albanians' previously peaceful tactics and
decided to fight for independence.
</P>
<P>
   A threat last fall of NATO air strikes has muted but not ended
the violence. On Saturday a bomb exploded outside a
government-owned bank in a southern Kosovo town, injuring nine
people, according to The Associated Press. No one immediately
claimed responsibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
