<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4247 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-NYT &LR;      02-13 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING FLAT: MANAGERS' AIRTIGHT CASE AGAINST PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Ill., Ala.)   (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-AFTERMATH, IMPEACH-STARR,
IMPEACH-TRIAL, IMPEACH-POLITICIANS, IMPEACH-SOCIETY,
IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON, IMPEACH-REAX, IMPEACH-LEGACY-REVIEW,
EDIT-IMPEACH-AFTERMATH, DOWD-COLUMN, IMPEACH-SAGES) 
(jw) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House managers working to convict President
Clinton fashioned their argument as a straightforward legal
proposition: They would prove he committed specific crimes and the
Senate would have to respond by evicting him from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, their legal case was far from airtight and was
no match for the undeniable political reality that the nation and
the Senate did not want to overturn an election. The public even
believed, and by significant majorities, according to polls, that
Clinton committed many of the very acts with which he was charged
by the managers.
</P>
<P>
   In arguing that he committed two crimes, perjury and obstruction
of justice, the managers found themselves stymied by
inconsistencies in testimony and ambiguous facts, as well as
confounded by White House lawyers who picked apart the elements of
the alleged crimes with care and precision.
</P>
<P>
   But for many senators, the measuring of Clinton's actions
against strict reading of the criminal code was almost beside the
point. Many of those who voted to acquit Clinton said flatly that
they believed he had committed some form of perjury and obstruction
of justice.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, who voted against both
articles of impeachment, said that ``the case presented by the
House managers proves to my satisfaction that the president did, in
fact, obstruct justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Collins said she believed the affidavit that Monica Lewinsky
filed in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct case and the efforts to
find Ms. Lewinsky a job in New York were all intended to conceal an
intimate sexual relationship with Clinton. Similarly, Ms. Collins
said she was convinced that Clinton's conversation with his
secretary, Betty Currie, in which he appeared to feed her innocent
explanations for his friendship with Ms. Lewinsky, was part of the
president's cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt in my mind that the frantic efforts to find
Ms. Lewinsky a job, the retrieval and concealment of gifts under
the bed of the president's secretary, and, most egregious, the
president's blatant coaching of Betty Currie _ not once, but twice
_ were clear attempts to tamper with witnesses and obstruct
justice,'' Ms. Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   But like many others, mostly Democrats, Ms. Collins said she
believed that the impeachment trial required a different approach
than an ordinary criminal trial. Even if he committed the offenses,
they said, it was not the kind of high crime and misdemeanor
required by the Constitution for removal.
</P>
<P>
   The managers fashioned the perjury article out of what some
might view as the most trivial issues in the impeachment drama.
</P>
<P>
   For example, they charged that Clinton should be convicted and
removed from office for such allegedly false statements as
asserting he was alone with Ms. Lewinsky on a limited number of
occasions when the actual number was 20. They also charged he
committed perjury when he read a statement to the grand jury saying
that ``what began as an innocent friendship'' evolved into a
regrettable intimate relationship. They say the relationship
actually began with flirting and Ms. Lewinsky's flaunting her
underwear.
</P>
<P>
   It became clear in the trial that the perjury charge was the
weaker of the two, and the managers spent most of their energy
prosecuting the second impeachment article, the one that charged a
widespread scheme to obstruct justice. But that effort was also
handicapped in legal terms by conflicting sworn accounts and an
inability to construct a coherent story in which they could prove
the president's role and motivations.
</P>
<P>
   For example, several of the ``seven pillars'' of obstruction, as
Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the chief manager, called them, involved
differing sworn testimony or interpretations of complicated events
like the effort to find Ms. Lewinsky a job.
</P>
<P>
   One of the issues was whether Clinton orchestrated the retrieval
of gifts he had given Ms. Lewinsky. Mrs. Currie said Ms. Lewinsky
had called her to initiate the retrieval. Ms. Lewinsky testified
that Mrs. Currie had called her and the House managers asserted
that meant the president had been behind the effort. The House
managers repeatedly portrayed Clinton as the master ``puppeteer''
behind many events.
</P>
<P>
   But as in the case of the gifts, they could never solidly
demonstrate his involvement. In addition, Mrs. Currie directly
contradicted Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Bucy, a criminal law professor at the University of
Alabama, said the managers' case may have been weakest in their
inability to show that Clinton intended to commit perjury or
obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if one resolved the factual discrepancies against the
president _ he was trying to get the gifts back, and he was trying
to coach her _ the weak part of the case is proving the intent to
violate the law,'' said Ms. Bucy, a former federal prosecutor.
``The reason is that he probably had multiple plausible intents,
like to hide this from his wife and daughter and everyone else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
