<HEADER>
A4277 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMR-PILOTS-ART-650(2T     02-13 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMR-PILOTS-ART-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILOTS UNION IN CONTEMPT, FINED $10 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ill., Minn., Fla., N.Y., Colo.)   (Eds: Also moving in `f' category.) 
(jw) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge in Dallas cited the union representing American
Airlines pilots for contempt Saturday and fined it $10 million for
ignoring his back-to-work order as the pilots' continued sickout
stranded tens of thousands of passengers on an especially busy
holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Joe Kendall of North Texas also imposed a
$10,000 fine on the president of the Allied Pilots Association and
likened the union's weeklong sickout to extortion by the Mafia.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, lawyers for American, the nation's second-largest
airline, asked Kendall to hold the pilots in contempt and to issue
``a coercive fine'' for failing to end the sickout despite his
Wednesday order directing them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilots association resembles one of the five families in
New York,'' Kendall said Saturday. ``It is the type of negotiation
one usually sees doing business with one of the five families in
New York. Pay us what we want or we will cost you more.''
</P>
<P>
   In a full-day hearing on Friday, the judge frequently scoffed at
the union's leaders when they insisted that they were doing
everything possible to persuade their members to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   American said about 2,100 of its pilots called in sick Saturday,
down slightly from Friday, but still enough to cause the airline to
cancel more than one-third of its 2,250 scheduled flights.
</P>
<P>
   But Larry Foster, a board member of the union, said only 1,300
had called in sick Saturday, insisting that many were unable to
signal their desire to return to work because of jammed American
switchboards.
</P>
<P>
   As the labor dispute dragged on, airline terminals grew even
more crowded and passengers' tempers grew shorter as their anger at
the pilots mounted. Over the last two days, passengers have erupted
into screaming at the American terminal at Kennedy International
Airport in New York, while passengers started a near-riot in Miami,
airline officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, American officials said, the sickout has affected more
than 450,000 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   At O'Hare International Airport outside Chicago Saturday
morning, Del Dooling, 43, a tired, unshaven salesman from
Riverside, Calif., was so angry about the cancellation of his
Friday flight to San Juan that he vowed never to fly American
Airlines again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The service has been wretched,'' he said. ``It's just
horrible. Everything is going wrong.'' Dooling added that in his
view the pilots should face a harsh penalty for defying the judge's
order. ``It should be prison and a big fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Norbert and Elaine Donay of Minneapolis were also stranded at
O'Hare because their Friday flight to San Juan was canceled,
disrupting their plans to vacation with their son. ``I was
furious,'' Mrs. Donay said.
</P>
<P>
   American officials had booked them on a Monday flight, but they
were so upset that their trip would be cut short that they made an
against-the-odds attempt to fly stand-by Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At Miami International Airport, Gertrudis Gonzalez, a
21-year-old student from Managua, Nicaragua, complained about being
stranded for more than a day because her Friday morning flight home
was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went hungry, they gave us nothing to eat,'' she said. ``We
were left wandering along the passageways.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute forced passengers, travel agents and American
service representatives to show a lot of resourcefulness. Standing
in the American terminal Saturday morning at Kennedy, Patrick Reed,
a plumbing wholesaler from Albany, N.Y., complained about the
cancellation of his flight to Vancouver. But he managed to make
alternative arrangements on a TWA flight to Chicago and then a
Cathay Pacific link from Chicago to Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   While relieved about his rerouting, Reed remained angry at
American's pilots, saying, ``I think the pilots have long since
made their point, and they're being very selfish.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the court hearing in Dallas on Friday, lawyers for the
airline asked Kendall to impose ``a coercive fine'' against the
union to punish the pilots for shunning his order and to pressure
the pilots to return to work as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Rich LaVoy, the union's president, told the judge that he was
doing his utmost to get the pilots to end their sickout.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Kendall had questioned the sincerity of the
union leaders' efforts to urge pilots to end their sickout. The
judge even mocked the union's protestations that it had urged
pilots to return to work after he learned that 12 of the union's 18
board members had called in sick on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, the union stepped up the urgency of its
messages calling on pilots to return to work. The union updated its
telephone message and its World Wide Web site on Friday night to
carry a statement by LaVoy, who said: ``I want to make a personal
plea to all of our pilots. The association's leadership needs your
help in complying with Judge Joe Kendall's order. We need to get
this airline back up and running at full capacity, and we need to
do so quickly. Please clear the sick list immediately and resume
your normal schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   The conflict between the union and the airline grew out of
American's purchase in December of Reno Air, a small carrier
serving the West. American has said that it intends to merge Reno
Air, which has 25 planes and 300 pilots, into American's much
larger network, but that it will take as long as 18 months to refit
Reno Air's planes and retrain pilots at both carriers.
</P>
<P>
   But the union contends that American is violating the most
fundamental clause in its contract, which requires that all flying
at the airline and any of its wholly owned subsidiaries be
performed by members of the pilots' union. The pilots say they are
concerned that American may want to transfer some of its flying to
pilots at Reno Air, who are paid about half as much as American
pilots. Many pilots have also voiced concerns that if the union
does not make a stand now, it will have set a dangerous precedent
if American buys an even larger airline.
</P>
<P>
   The union has demanded that the company speed up the integration
with Reno Air and immediately begin paying pilots at both carriers
as if the integration were already completed. Pilots at Reno Air,
who are members of a different pilots union, have expressed
reservations about the union's integration proposal because they
would lose seniority.
</P>
<P>
   American has said that the union's proposal would add $50
million to the $124 million it paid to buy Reno Air. The airline
said in court on Friday that it had already lost $40 million as a
result of the disruption caused by the sickout.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Buttrick, an airline industry analyst at Paine Webber in
New York, estimated that the airline could lose as much as $110
million in sales in the current quarter from the disruption alone
plus $50 million more from passengers' booking future tickets on
other airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But few analysts expect that American will suffer long-term
damage as a result of the job action, despite pledges by some angry
passengers never to fly the airline again. ``Consumers have the
attention spans of monkeys,'' said Mike Boyd, an aviation industry
consultant in Evergreen, Colo. ``They just forget real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Fare reductions and other incentives will draw passengers back
once a settlement is reached, he said. ``When American does fly,
they are really pretty good at it,'' he added. ``It is a
high-quality airline. They are going to get a pretty fast
response.''
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines was grounded for nearly three weeks in
September after its pilots went on strike. The carrier suffered
steep losses through the end of the year but has recently seen its
traffic return to normal levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long-term damage,'' Boyd said, referring to American, ``is
the continuing shattering of trust between the airline and its
pilots.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilots group, which is not part of the AFL-CIO, has received
little support from other unions or from its main rival, the Air
Line Pilots Association, from which it split three decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Mitchell, a spokeswoman for the AFL-CIO, said the
American pilots had neither kept other unions abreast of the
situation nor asked for help.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots' dispute has caused some inconveniences for other
union leaders because it has disrupted the plans of many labor
leaders to fly to Miami for the AFL-CIO's annual winter meeting,
which begins on Tuesday at the Fontainebleau Hotel in Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   The American pilots have received a message of solidarity from
an international pilots association, the Oneworld Flight Crew
Coalition, which includes 21,000 pilots from more than a dozen
airlines, including British Airways, Iberia, Japan Airlines and
Cathay Pacific.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
