<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4283 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT &LR;      02-13 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE MORE, BRAZILIANS TIGHTEN BELTS FOR A ROUGH RIDE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO _ Jose Oliveira has abandoned construction of the
addition to his house. Cleber Franca and his wife, Cristina, have
cut up their credit cards and decided not to replace their 1981
Volkswagen.
</P>
<P>
   When classes resume in late February, Wagner Gomes Carneiro's
two teen-agers will not return to the private school they attended
before Brazil plunged into economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Luiz Dominguez has canceled the vacation he and his family
planned to take and will go camping instead.
</P>
<P>
   For five years, the Brazilian middle class was the main
beneficiary of the burst of stability and growth enjoyed by Latin
America's largest economy. But in the last month, that entire
edifice has begun to wobble, along with the sense of financial
security that accompanied it. Families all across this country of
165 million people are now scrambling to protect themselves from
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anybody whose budget isn't being pinched and who
isn't cutting back in some way or another,'' said Luiz Henrique
Afonso, 55. He works for the state government here, which has
announced it does not have enough money to pay employees past
March. ``Everybody is working the maximum to spend the minimum,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The drastic devaluation of the nation's currency, the real, over
the last month has made that process as necessary as it is painful.
Prices of imported products, ranging from the wheat used in making
bread to medicine and car parts, have shot up, so much of the belt
tightening has begun with foreign-made goods.
</P>
<P>
   Although they seem convinced that the situation can only worsen,
most middle-class Brazilians have responded so far with
resignation, not panic. As veterans of decades of triple-digit
inflation and economic crises too numerous to count, they say they
know how and when to make the necessary adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 39, and this is probably _ what _ the 10th time that some
economic plan of the government has gone down the tubes?'' said
Franz Slama, a civil engineer who worries that a leaner government
budget, as demanded by Brazil's agreement with the International
Monetary Fund, will mean less work for him. ``As Brazilians, we're
accustomed to being in this sort of thing, and have learned how to
improvise.''
</P>
<P>
   Many families, in fact, began to economize even before foreign
reserves, a currency linked to the dollar and the stock market all
started to plunge precipitously in early January after a state
Governor threatened to default on $13.5 billion in loans his state
owed to the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easy to see this mess coming from a long way off,''
said Domingos da Silva, 68, a retired military officer and
architect. ``As soon as interest rates hit 50 percent back in
September, we started cutting back on all unnecessary expenditures
in our household.''
</P>
<P>
   Da Silva and his wife, Walkiria Sanches, 60, a retired civil
servant, said their income comes from pensions that now add up to
less than $1,500 a month. As a former army captain, he is exempt
from the increase in social security contributions that Congress
recently approved, ``at least for now,'' he said. But his wife is
not: under the new system, she calculates, her monthly check will
drop by $27.50 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's real money,'' she said. ``It represents a couple of
kilos of beans, a couple of kilos of butter and a couple of kilos
of meat every month. We've got to save more, and we're doing that
by not buying clothes and not going out at all to dinner, the
movies or the theater anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Oliveira, a 43-year-old father of two, worked lots of
overtime to make enough to expand his kitchen, a project now
mothballed because of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going to cost us at least $1,000 just in labor, not to
mention the raw materials,'' he said. ``So we told the contractor
to stop, and we canceled the order for the new curtains we were
going to install.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliveira, a supervisor in the repair department of the state
water utility, also has eliminated the bottle of beer he drank
every evening, and has withdrawn his daughter from the after-school
English course she was taking. ``As for shopping,'' said his wife,
Vera Costa, ``all we do now is look in the windows.''
</P>
<P>
   The major worry is care for Oliveira's mother. At 68, she
recently had a stroke and needs therapy, as well as medication that
costs almost double her $80 a month pension.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis hit Brazil at the peak of the Southern Hemisphere
summer vacation season; this runs from Christmas until Carnival,
which this year ends on Feb. 17. Many families were locked into
vacation packages for which they had paid in advance with Christmas
bonuses and could not cancel, and so they plan to tighten their
belts even more drastically as soon as they return to work or
school.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the recent crisis, Brazil's economy was expected to
contract by between 1 and 2 percent in 1999. But many forecasters
have now revised their calculations downward as a result of the
combination of high interest rates and a weakened currency, with
some even predicting a recession that may see the economy shrink by
as much as 5 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This crisis isn't our fault, but we're going to be the ones to
pay the price,'' da Silva said. ``That's the way it has always been
in Brazil, and that's the way it will always be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
