<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4287 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-WOHLERS14-COX     02-13 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-WOHLERS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers stays upbeat facing murky future
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Braves closer Mark Wohlers made some progress while
attending ``Camp Leo'' this week, but his comeback and major-league
future remain in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   In throwing sessions at Turner Field this week, Wohlers
continued to exhibit the same control problems that had him
pitching in AAA Richmond during the 1998 season. Some of his
pitches were short and in the dirt; others sailed to the backstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're keeping our fingers crossed,'' manager Bobby Cox said.
``We'll do whatever we can for him, because he'd be a huge plus for
us if he rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers' control problems were attributed, in part, to a
strained oblique muscle, his mother's health problems and his
divorce. The muscle has healed; his mother has recovered from a
heart attack and is in much better health now; and Wohlers has had
some time to work through his personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   He asked to work this offseason with Braves pitching instructor
Guy Hansen, who helped Wohlers last summer. Wohlers spent January
in Puerto Rico and California working with Hansen on his mechanics,
his grip and arm extension. But progress has been slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take it a day at a time,'' pitcher Tom Glavine
said. ``He's not going to get up one morning and throw every pitch
on the corner and throw every slider where he wants it. It'll be a
gradual progression. If anybody thinks he'll get there in the next
two or three days, they're crazy. It's not going to happen. That's
why you have to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers is hesitant to discuss the 1998 season, when he compiled
a 10.18 ERA and issued 33 walks in 20 1/3 innings in Atlanta,
followed by his 36 walks, 17 wild pitches and 21 hits allowed in 12
1/3 innings at Class AAA Richmond. He declined all interview
requests this week, saying that he might discuss his comeback
Wednesday when pitchers and catchers report for spring training in
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Braves pitching coach Leo Mazzone called Wednesday's session _
Wohlers' second of four that were scheduled this week _ a success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a good day (Wednesday),'' said Mazzone, who annually
runs a camp for his pitchers before spring training.
``Mechanically, he executed what he wanted to do about 60 percent
of the time, which is a big upgrade. He pulled a couple off, but he
knew what he was doing mechanically. . . . On a day like today you
go into the clubhouse feeling good.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves director of scouting and player development Paul Snyder
also watched the workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he had his extension, he was fine,'' Snyder said. ``When
he didn't, he was just like every other pitcher (without good
extension). . . . Sometimes he can be a little careless. He knows
that. But things are better now than they were last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports psychologist Jack Llewellyn has been working with Wohlers
throughout the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he ever considered for a minute he wouldn't be
able to pitch,'' Llewellyn said. ``That's a big part of it, his
attitude. And his attitude is tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Llewellyn said he works with Wohlers on visualizing success and
trying to recover from throwing bad pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every pitcher goes through adversity,'' Llewellyn said. ``The
question is: If he throws a bad pitch, how long does it take for
him to recover?''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers showed some resilience Wednesday, when three of his
first dozen or so pitches flew to the backstop and another four
landed in the dirt, one of which bounced over the fence. By the end
of his session of more than 30 pitches he was closing in on the
target.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take the good days and try to run with them,'' Llewellyn
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers did talk to Peter Gammons of ESPN and the Boston Globe
two weeks ago, saying: ``I'm just trying to put it all behind me
and move forward. I know what happened and where I've been. I just
have to use this experience to my advantage and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers also said: ``I really feel that dwelling on the past
will be counterproductive. What can it accomplish? This is 1999. I
plan to have a strong 1999. When I've re-established myself, maybe
sometime during the summer, I will open up. But for now, the best
thing I can do is concentrate on throwing and not talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine said watching Wohlers go through this process is hard on
everybody in the Braves clubhouse. He said he just tries to offer
his support and advice when Wohlers asks for it and stay out of his
way when he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things as a player you hear stories about
and hope it never happens,'' Glavine said. ``When you see it
happen, it's almost unbelievable. You don't want to watch it. You
don't want it to happen to you. It's a difficult situation for
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody in here wishes the best for him. For
personal and selfish reasons, we want to see him come back.''
</P>
<P>
   As for how or when, nobody knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it takes eight months, that'll be fine,'' Snyder said.
``Putting himself on a timetable _ that's the worst thing he can
do. That puts even more pressure on him.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, it's up to Wohlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly believe,'' Cox said, ``it can be worked out _ if
something can just snap one day, and there he goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
