<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4289 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-BIRTH14-CO     02-13 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-BIRTH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Birth of a race car
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORESVILLE, N.C. _ Things are hopping in the biggest little
race shop in NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   The Penske-Kranefuss Racing Team is about to give birth.
</P>
<P>
   Four just-about-completed stock cars are lined up, showroom new,
in the main building. Another car, half-finished, is in the
spraying booth getting a red interior. Welders are putting the
finishing touches on a surface that measures the car's balance and
weight.
</P>
<P>
   It's the week before the season-opening Daytona 500, and
everyone is concerned with finishing touches. It's a little like
looking at a newborn and counting fingers and toes.
</P>
<P>
   The mood is jovial. The Penske-Kranefuss team is 26 strong, and
like most other NASCAR teams, it will build some 12 cars this
season for drivers Rusty Wallace and Jeremy Mayfield. The $70,000
machines instantly become part of the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the cars have a little variance to them,'' shop foreman
Joe Don Bailey said. ``They're like kids. They might have the
parents' genes, but they've all got a little different
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Every part of the operation is gearing up for what it hopes will
be a run at a Winston Cup championship. In the chassis shop, Billy
Woodruff looks at a wall full of steel pipes and sees a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big ol' giant steel puzzle is all it is,'' Woodruff said.
``It's just that you've got to make your own pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the pieces fit better than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is our brand-new Daytona car,'' Bailey tells a visitor.
``When we tested it and wind-tunneled and digitized it, it showed
that the two previous cars we had were just a little bit better. So
it'll be a spare, ride the trailer down there. We won't even get it
out unless we crash before qualifying. If we crash before
qualifying, that'll be a better qualifying car. But if we crash
after qualifying, then we'll take the Busch Clash car because it's
a better race car. It's got low drag, but it's still got a little
bit more downforce.''
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the few Winston Cup teams that builds its cars
entirely within its own operation. Right down to its own nuts and
bolts. But don't ask machinist/programmer Dewayne Trammell how the
Computer Numerical Control machine works. It might be easier to
learn how to drive the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Z-minus-point-five, that would be a half-inch below
wherever you established Z-zero is,'' Trammell said, trying to
explain a formula for the manufacture of one of the 250 parts he
custom makes for the car. ``You have to establish that so the
program knows where to machine the piece.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easier to comprehend Bailey talking about one of the cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the car we built for Rusty (Wallace) to run at Indy
and Darlington,'' he said. ``He decided to go back to the Hopkins
cars because he won the race in Phoenix with a Hopkins car, so we
got it back from him. That car has two races on it. We'll take it,
strip it, cut the body off, get it to where we like our bodies at
and change it to what Jeremy likes in a car.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is just a sentimental bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just sent a car out to get sand-blasted; it was 01, the
very first of our own chassis,'' Bailey said. ``After Japan, it was
supposed to be sold to Jeremy's ARCA team. We got to looking at it,
and it was our oldest car, so we were going to delete out of the
stock. But every time Jeremy's run it, it's been a top-five car, in
position to win, just like it was in Japan. We ended up pulling it
back down here, cutting the body off of it. It's going back into
our stable. Sometimes it's hard to throw them out. When you've got
a good horse, you've got to ride it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in a new model year, some NASCAR teams recycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the old car is better than a new car,'' Bailey said.
``Kind of like an old shoe. Until you got that new shoe broke in,
you like to wear that old pair.''
</P>
<P>
   The team continuously looks for an edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race cars are always in evolution,'' Woodruff said. ``You're
always looking for that 2-10ths of a second advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   They might be found in the paint booth, where Terry Mayfield is
putting a darker blue on the No. 12 skin this season. Or in the 40
percent room, where a scale-model of the car, looking like a
beautiful toy, is manufactured with the same seriousness as a
full-size beast in hopes it will bring maximum results in a
mini-wind-tunnel test.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data that we get will be 98 percent of what the big cars
show you in the wind tunnel,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Or it might be something that visionary crew chief Paul Andrews
dreams up in a pre-building skull session with engineers. ``You
take what is working for you,'' he said, ``and tweak and refine
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All cars are not built the same,'' Bailey said. ``Like for
Daytona, we change frame-rail heights; for short-track cars we
prepare them for high-braking instances, different braking in them.
Our air program is doing some different things under the cars where
we're going to a different aero package. We have five full-time
engineers, so we change our chassis design to always make it
better.''
</P>
<P>
   All the while, staying within NASCAR's guidelines, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got it wrote to where you can't hardly do nothing,''
Woodruff said. ``There's been so many things tried, almost every
trick's been pulled.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
