<HEADER>
A4290 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-CHALLENGER     02-13 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-CHALLENGERS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ford drivers improving along with the Taurus
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dale Jarrett is healthy. Mark Martin isn't.
</P>
<P>
   But both drivers enter the 1999 Winston Cup series among a
handful of NASCAR teams trying to close the gap on two-time
defending champion Jeff Gordon and the No. 24 Chevrolet.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Gordon, who won last year's Cup title by a whopping
364 points, is a heavy favorite to win his third championship in a
row and fourth overall.
</P>
<P>
   But a handful of drivers could emerge and cut into Gordon's 13
victories of a year ago. Several Ford teams are optimistic after a
full season of driving the Taurus, which replaced the Thunderbird
before the 1998 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But the real challengers know they're going to have to improve
their operations, because Gordon probably isn't going to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way that dominance is going to go away is if they
self-destruct somehow,'' three-time Cup champion Darrell Waltrip
said.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the top five candidates looking to challenge Gordon:
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff Burton, No. 99 Ford. At age 31, Burton could be a rising
star on the circuit. He finished fourth and fifth in points the
past two seasons and in 1998 won two races with a career-high in
top-fives and top-10s.
</P>
<P>
   Burton finished in the top five in the final three races last
year, and he's looking to carry that momentum into this season. If
he improves his qualifying _ he started an average of about 10
positions farther back than those ahead of him in points _ Burton
should be improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point in your career, you have to get over that
potential label and start doing it,'' Burton said. ``You can't just
keep saying, 'It's time to learn; it's time to learn.' It's time to
apply everything you've learned, and now is that time.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Dale Jarrett, No. 88 Ford. In the last three seasons, Jarrett
finished second once _ 1997 _ and third twice in the points
standings. He says he feels physically better than he has in 20
years, thanks to offseason surgery to remove his gall stones.
Jarrett has gone to a low-fat diet and has lost nearly 15 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot better, better than I've felt in maybe 20 or 25
years,'' Jarrett said. ``I didn't realize how bad I felt until I
got everything taken care of. I'm much healthier, and I finally
have the energy and desire to get back on a good workout program.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett also should benefit from owner Robert Yates' decision to
move second-year driver Kenny Irwin out of the main facility so
Jarrett could concentrate on winning a championship. Irwin, last
year's rookie of the year, struggled to a 28th-place finish in
points, which might have been a distraction for the No. 88 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have one team that does well one week, and the other
one doesn't, it's kind of hard for those guys to enjoy their time
when they come in Monday morning,'' Jarrett said. ``They don't want
to hurt the feelings of the other guys. That's just very difficult.
Plus, we were running out of space.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark Martin, No. 6 Ford. Martin enjoyed the best season of his
16-year career in 1998, winning seven races and finishing with 22
top-fives and 26 top-10s. Yet, he still finished eons behind Gordon
in the points standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd take that season again any year I can get it,'' Martin
said. ``But those guys on (Gordon's) No. 24 team didn't miss a
beat. If they do that again, it doesn't matter what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's biggest concern remains the serious back pain he
suffered last season, a condition he says probably will bother him
the rest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Martin planned surgery after last season to improve a herniated
disc in his lower back. But doctors decided not to go through with
the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``My back is about the same status that it was in November _ not
better,'' Martin said. ``My hope was to have surgery in November
and come into the season with no back problems. I have back pain,
but I may have back pain the rest of my life. I can live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's back hasn't hindered him in preparing for the Daytona
500. He had the fifth-fastest speed in first-round qualifying, then
won the Bud Shootout, his first victory at Daytona International
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's team returns nearly intact after starting last season
with all but two new crew members. If Roush Racing improves its
restrictor-plate program _ Martin lost all but 43 of his 364-point
deficit to Gordon in the four restrictor-plate races _ Martin could
mount a serious threat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeremy Mayfield, No. 12 Ford. Mayfield and teammate Rusty
Wallace were the biggest surprises of last season, totaling 37
top-10s. If Mayfield continues to learn from Wallace, he could be
Ford's answer to Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield scored his first career victory 15 races into the 1998
season at Pocono and led the points race for four of the 33-week
schedule. The following week at Sears Point, however, Gordon
regained the lead, and he did not relinquish it. After Pocono,
Mayfield had finishes of 18th twice, 30th, 31st and 42nd, ending
any threat of a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rusty and I have talked about this before, but with any luck
at all, or if both of us had been a little bit better last year, we
would have won 10 or 12 races between the two of us, easy,''
Mayfield said. ``That's something we haven't forgotten, and we know
that we were that close last year. We feel we're going to be much
better this year.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rusty Wallace, No. 2 Ford. Wallace improved to fourth in
points last season, his best finish since placing third in 1994.
The resurgence comes from a couple of factors _ the dramatic
improvement of teammate Mayfield and the development of Penske's
engines after purchasing Larry Wallace's operation last year.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, who won at Phoenix last season to extend his streak to
13 consecutive years with at least one victory, didn't finish 11
events in 1997. In 1998, he had only two DNFs.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Wallace posted the fastest testing times at Daytona
and held the pole for the 500 for more than hour before being
bumped out of the front row by Gordon, rookie Tony Stewart and Mike
Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a brand-new car,'' Wallace said. ``We had a lot of
problems with some of last year's cars and that limited us to only
go so far with our suspension setup, so we went back and built a
new car. Man alive, it's so much better, it's unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   1998 STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   The final Winston Cup driver standings:
</P>
<P>
   Driver Points Money
</P>
<P>
   1. Jeff Gordon 5,328 $6,175,867
</P>
<P>
   2. Mark Martin 4,964 $3,279,370
</P>
<P>
   3. Dale Jarrett 4,619 $3,368,735
</P>
<P>
   4. Rusty Wallace 4,501 $2,133,345
</P>
<P>
   5. Jeff Burton 4,415 $2,114,597
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
