<HEADER>
A4291 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-GORDON14-C     02-13 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-GORDON14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Other drivers hoping for complacency from champ
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was more than six years ago that Jeff Gordon sat
behind the wheel of Rick Hendrick's third car and ran his first
Winston Cup race in the 1992 season-finale at Atlanta Motor
Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 200 races later, Gordon enters the '99 campaign still
looking at the competition in his rear-view mirror. ``The Kid'' _
Gordon doesn't turn 28 until August _ has 42 victories in 189
career starts, an average of one victory every 4.5 races.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon is coming off his best season, winning 13 races in 1998,
tying Richard Petty's modern-day record and posting 26 top-five
finishes and 28 top-10s. Gordon won more than $9 million in prize
money last year, increasing his career winnings to more than $26
million.
</P>
<P>
   In only six full seasons, Gordon already is 13th on the all-time
victory list, tied with Bill Elliott and the late Tim Flock. Among
active drivers, only veterans Darrell Waltrip (84 victories), Dale
Earnhardt (71) and Rusty Wallace (48) have won more races than
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With a third straight points title this year, Gordon would tie
Cale Yarborough as the only drivers to accomplish that feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of us will race for second if Gordon does that
again,'' said Dale Jarrett, who has finished second and third in
points to Gordon the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's set a big standard, and everybody is going to be out
there trying to make sure that it doesn't happen again,'' said Paul
Andrews, crew chief for Jeremy Mayfield and the No. 12 Ford.
``Everybody is going to step it up. Everybody is going to be
gunning for him, so he's going to have a tough road. Right now,
he's got a bull's-eye on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this the year someone finally catches Gordon and puts some
drama back in Winston Cup racing? Or will Gordon, who won the pole
for today's season-opening Daytona 500, simply move the bull's-eye
even faster?
</P>
<P>
   ``They have raised the bar and set a new standard,'' Rusty
Wallace said about Gordon and his Rainbow Warriors. ``Since it
doesn't seem like they're going to slow up any time soon, it's up
to us and the rest of the series to catch up to them. It doesn't
look like they're going to wait around for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Few NASCAR drivers believe that this is the year the No. 24
Chevrolet finally slows down. But it could be tough for Gordon's
dominance to continue, and his unprecedented success _ he has won
three points titles in his first six seasons, something no other
driver has accomplished _ could be a big reason why.
</P>
<P>
   Success can breed complacency, and some people think that Gordon
might not be as hungry. After Yarborough won 10 races and his third
straight points title in 1978, he had only four victories the next
season and finished fourth in points standings. Earnhardt, after
winning consecutive titles in '90 and '91, couldn't manage a top-10
finish in points in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be the team to beat than a team that doesn't do
anything,'' Gordon said. ``When we hear things like that, that
other teams are gunning for us, that's the best feeling you can
have. That's what you want to hear, because you want to be the team
to beat. I just hope we can live up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Gordon might have the distraction of his new Busch
Series venture with wife Brooke and crew chief Ray Evernham.
Gordon-Evernham Motorsports will compete in 10 races on the Grand
National Series in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon will drive in five of those events _ the two Charlotte
races, Michigan, Las Vegas and Texas. The last two are tracks where
Gordon has not won, as are Phoenix and the new Homestead, Fla.,
facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my job to make sure I don't get burned out and don't do
too much,'' Gordon said. ``The more successful we are as a race
team, the more I have to work. The more demands that are on me, I
just have to learn to deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people think that Gordon's new Busch team could be the
first step in the dismantling of the Hendrick juggernaut.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that is interesting to me is the Busch team
they are starting,'' Darrell Waltrip said. ``There is probably more
there than meets the eye. That could be the beginning of the end,
to some degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Or will it just be more of the same?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
