<HEADER>
A4292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAZZIE-RUSSELL14-COX     02-13 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAZZIE-RUSSELL14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Russell draws a winner
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ One of the offensive sets is called Picasso,
with a Pablo option. The press defense is Van Gogh.
</P>
<P>
   As a player, Cazzie Russell was an artist on the court. Now he
is teaching basketball to artists.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been surreal.
</P>
<P>
   With the three-time All-American and 12-year NBA standout as
coach, Savannah College of Art and Design is 17-8 and hopes to get
a bid to the NCAA Division III men's basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   If SCAD makes the field for the first time, Russell promises to
unveil a new play, one that is truly a work of art. ``We're saving
Rembrandt for the big dance,'' he said, breaking into a big laugh.
Russell, 54, obviously is enjoying himself, despite his unlikely
career path. You'd expect someone with Russell's basketball
pedigree to be coaching in the NBA or at a major college _ not
working at an art-and-design school of about 4,500 students located
amid the Spanish moss-draped streets of Savannah's historic
district.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I love coaching here,'' said Russell, who was an assistant
with the Atlanta Hawks for two years. ``Nobody expects anything
from us _ a team of graphic artists, cartoonists and fashion
designers. We come into another team's gym and they're going,
`Yummy, yummy.' But we fool 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Russell arrived three seasons ago, the only attention SCAD
had generated in basketball was for having a female on the men's
team _ an NCAA first. With Melissa Burden as a backup guard, the
Bees were 1-24 in 1992-93 after a winless first season of
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone laughed at us for having a girl,'' said Eddie
Concepcion, a former player who now is one of Russell's assistants.
``But she was as good as we had. We didn't have many players who
really belonged on a college team.''
</P>
<P>
   Tired of losing, SCAD president Richard Rowan, a former player
at Furman, decided to go after a big-name coach. He targeted
Russell after seeing a CNN feature on the all-time University of
Michigan scoring leader who was the No. 1 pick in the 1966 NBA
draft.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of life in the CBA, where he had coached for nine seasons,
Russell was associate pastor at Love Zion Baptist Church in
Columbus, Ohio, and coach at Centennial High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something I really had to pray about,'' said Russell,
who was ordained in 1989 and is now associate pastor of Happy Home
Missionary Baptist Church. ``I believe there is a divine purpose
for everything and I feel that Savannah is where the Lord wanted
me. I'm at peace. I feel really blessed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowan _ who hopes to move SCAD up to NCAA Division II and then
Division I _ is more convinced than ever he went after the right
person. And not just because the team is 51-23 in Russell's three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's concerned about the whole student, not just the
basketball player,'' Rowan said. ``There is no reason to think a
really good artist can't also be a really good athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   But academics come first at SCAD, despite Rowan's high-profile
hirings of Russell and baseball coach Luis Tiant.
</P>
<P>
   Trokon Nagbe, the team's second-leading scorer and top defender,
took last season off so he could take a year-long internship with
Marvel Comics in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never a question about it,'' Russell said. ``They're
here to prepare for the future. And at a Division III school,
that's not pro basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading scorer Chris Morris hopes to illustrate CD or magazine
covers. Backup guard Carroll Boomer is interested in designing
women's evening wear. Steven Stecina, the team's tallest player at
6 feet 9, came from Hungary to study computer art.
</P>
<P>
   SCAD's success has come despite a nightmare schedule that
requires almost as much travel as Russell endured in the NBA. The
school doesn't have a gym or a league affiliation, forcing a
25-game schedule with 20 road games. The Bees have been to New York
three times and to Maine and California once each.
</P>
<P>
   The long trips leave Nagbe and others plenty of time for their
artistic passions. ``I fill up a whole sketchbook,'' Nagbe said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the educational value of travel, Russell would prefer
more home games. But the Savannah Civic Center isn't available in
December, and that is when most teams play nonleague games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just pray that the NCAA will look at all our road games when
they pick teams for the tournament,'' Russell said. ``We deserve a
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell played in the NCAA Final Four twice at Michigan and won
an NBA title with the New York Knicks in 1970. But he insists that
reaching the postseason in Division III, where no athletic
scholarships are allowed, would be just as big a thrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm where I want to be,'' Russell said. ``Coaching is in my
blood, and so are these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   CAZZIE RUSSELL FILE
</P>
<P>
   _ Age: 54.
</P>
<P>
   _ Family: Wife Myrna, a former Alvin Ailey dancer, and three
grown sons.
</P>
<P>
   _ Update: Basketball coach at Savannah College of Art and
Design, where he is 51-23 in three seasons, and associate pastor of
Happy Home Missionary Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   _ Playing career: Three-time All-American at Michigan and No. 1
pick in the 1966 NBA draft. Played with Knicks, Warriors, Lakers
and Bulls in 12-year career, averaging 15 points. Won NBA title
with Knicks in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coaching career: Coached in the CBA nine seasons, winning
title first year with Lancaster, Pa. Assistant with Hawks under
Mike Fratello in 1988-89 and 1989-90.
</P>
