<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4293 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MENTALLY-DISABLED-JAI     02-13 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENTALLY-DISABLED-JAILED14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Advocates sputtering over mentally disabled boy's jailing
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ With an IQ of 58 and the functional
capability of a 5-year-old, Tony Laster cannot comprehend the legal
thinking that put him behind bars for seven weeks for stealing $2
from an eighth-grade classmate.
</P>
<P>
   Laster is not alone in this.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys and advocates for the mentally retarded say
they can't comprehend it either.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney Barry Krischer's ``zero tolerance'' policy for
school crimes is itself being judged by the treatment given Laster,
a hearing-impaired 15-year-old from Boynton Beach who is not able
to remember an address or phone number _ let alone sort out the
uproar his playground incident has ignited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's outrageous,'' said Lynn Whitfield, president of
the Palm Beach County Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers. ``To
have this child sitting in jail and not even being able to
understand why he's there is not fair, and it certainly is not
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Laird, executive director of The Association of Retarded
Citizens, said the Laster case is evidence of a prosecutor's
reckless disregard for the rights of the most vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is almost inhumane,'' Laird said. ``It is the height of
hypocrisy not to take disabilities into account when punishment is
administered.''
</P>
<P>
   Laster's attorney, public defender Toni Gilliam, believes the
state attorney's office is confusing get-tough politics for
justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to look at these on a case-by-case basis,''
she said. ``This is not the type of case even Barry Krischer
himself developed zero tolerance for. It should have been handled
as a juvenile matter or perhaps by the school itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Krischer has stood firm on his decision to treat Laster as an
adult and charge him with strong-arm robbery and extortion,
felonies that could send him back to jail for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids going to school must know they'll be safe there,''
Krischer said.
</P>
<P>
   He defends treating offenders as adults by saying it is the most
effective way to get their attention. Neither the dollar amount
stolen nor Laster's mental disability is reason to deviate from the
zero tolerance approach, prosecutors argue.
</P>
<P>
   ``A significant number of defendants in juvenile and adult
courts have low IQs or some form of retardation, or one of their
principal defenses is low IQ or mental retardation,'' said Mike
Edmondson, spokesman for the state attorney's office. ``What the
state has to establish is competence to prosecute. We regularly
prosecute offenses from murder to petty theft against defendants
with low IQs, physical addiction or alleged mental retardation.''
</P>
<P>
   Laster's unwitting challenge to prosecutorial policy began in
special-education art class at Congress Middle School in Boynton
Beach, where on Dec. 1 he pulled the two $1 bills out of the pocket
of a 14-year-old classmate, police say.
</P>
<P>
   Laster told them he was hungry and used the money to buy candy.
The victim said he felt physically threatened, and Laster was then
arrested by campus police.
</P>
<P>
   His sister Carolyn, 30, said her brother has had behavior
problems at school before, and that those worsened after his
grandfather, with whom he was very close, died of a heart attack in
May and his mother died of AIDS in November.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Laster said it is difficult for Tony to follow
instructions because of a hearing loss that forces him to wear aids
in both ears during classes. Quiet and withdrawn, Laster speaks in
sparse fragments of sentences and has struggled to advance in the
special education program.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Coleman, Palm Beach County school district associate
superintendent, said the school acted properly in arresting Laster
but would not discuss the case in detail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to say anything about it,'' Coleman said. ``We
dealt with it like we should. If anyone steals anything, the
student code of conducts says it's very appropriate for the schools
to contact police.''
</P>
<P>
   MOVE TO ADULT COURT
</P>
<P>
   Laster was transported by campus police from the school to the
Juvenile Assessment Center in West Palm Beach for evaluation.
Records show his disabilities were not recognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Youth acts in a normal manner,'' a caseworker wrote on an
evaluation form.
</P>
<P>
   Even had his handicaps been noted, Laster's fate likely still
would have been driven by the system's reaction to the serious
charges against him. A juvenile court judge by law had to score him
at 12 points on a risk assessment scale _ all of them coming from
the strong arm robbery count _and ordered him detained. A score of
11 or less would have allowed him to be released or monitored at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Though prosecutors could find no previous criminal record, the
allegations by Laster's classmate were enough to send him to the
Juvenile Detention Center.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 22, Krischer filed to have the case moved to adult court
and on Christmas Eve, Laster made his first appearance there.
County Judge Barry Cohen set his bond at $5,000, the statutory
minimum for the felony charges. Court records show the issue of
Laster's competence was raised at least briefly during the
appearance, which came during a mass hearing in which many other
defendants were called.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Laster said the family was telephoned by
juvenile-justice officials and told of her brother's arrest the day
after he was removed from the school. But it took weeks for the
family to fully realize the depth of the trouble Tony was in. By
then he was being held in the juvenile section of the Palm Beach
County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 20, Carolyn Laster paid $500 to bail her brother out. To
free him, she used the inheritance left him by his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody took a good close look at this kid or the family
situation,'' said John Walsh, an attorney with the Palm Beach
County Legal Aid Society who was assigned to the case Jan. 22 by
Circuit Judge Edward Garrison. ``What went drastically wrong was
the state attorney made a misinformed decision on this child.''
</P>
<P>
   Another case, same boy?
</P>
<P>
   This week, Krischer's office found juvenile records that may
indicate another incident involving Laster. They show a teen-ager
with a similar name (Lester), different birthday but same address
was charged with retail theft last summer. The boy was accused of
stealing a $60 crucifix from Burdines. The case never went to
court, and Laster's attorneys remain unconvinced the offender was
their client.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an attempt by the state attorney to retroactively
justify their actions,'' Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Laster said her brother has been traumatized by the
events of the past year. Four family members have died, and the
loss of his mother and grandfather have left him without adequate
supervision. Tony says he does not understand why he was put in
jail, or why he's being asked about the $2, or why reporters want
to talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He cried a lot and told people he wanted to go home when he
was in jail,'' Carolyn Laster said. ``He wants to be on TV, but he
doesn't understand how much trouble he's really in. He says he does
not want to go back to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance Block, an attorney who has been on the ARC's board of
directors for 12 years, said he hopes the state attorney's office
will reevaluate its position. He said ARC has been asked by
prosecutors, defense attorneys and judges to intercede in past
cases and work to rehabilitate offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole essence of criminal law is that there be intent and
an understanding of wrong,'' Block said. ``When you're dealing with
the mentally retarded, you have to step back and ask if they have
the same level of understanding. They are among the most vulnerable
in our society. This has been a gross overreaction and unjust all
the way around.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh and Gilliam will ask a judge at a March 8 hearing to
return the case to the juvenile courts. Laster is scheduled to be
tested by psychologists for competency before then, his IQ to be
measured once again. State attorney's office spokesman Edmondson
says his office's zero tolerance policy will remain in effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were truly a zero tolerance policy,'' Walsh said, ``they
wouldn't have enough state attorneys to prosecute every kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Oblivious to the legal arguments, Tony Laster is attending
classes again at Congress Middle School. His sister said he's
telling his friends to watch for him on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Post staff writers Lillian Weis and Stephanie Desmon
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
