<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4294 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QVC14-COX     02-13 2864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QVC14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Queen of Diamonique
 &HT;    WITH SIDEBARS at end of file
 &HT;    By Loretta Grantham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Kathy Levine recalls when a prankster
swiped the brass deer off the mantel of the original QVC set.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything to make it a little different,'' jokes Levine, the
first host to appear on QVC's inaugural broadcast Nov. 24, 1986.
``The mantra back then was to keep everything the same day after
day so viewers would get used to us and feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, deer or no deer, viewers got comfortable _ and fast. Less
than five years later, QVC racked up 125,000 phone orders in one
day totaling $10.4 million. In one day.
</P>
<P>
   And these days, the home-shopping behemoth boasts more than $2
billion in sales a year (twice that of St. Petersburg-based Home
Shopping Network).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was, in fact, set up for success,'' Levine says of the
cable network, created by Joseph Segel, founder of The Franklin
Mint. ``It had the proper backing financially, and timing was
perfect. If I hadn't been such a boob in the world, I'd have
thought about QVC's huge potential when I applied, but I wasn't
positioned that way mentally. I was just happy to have a job and be
on television for the first time in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Levine's mom, Pat, who lives in Palm Beach Gardens, was just as
joyous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was there the night she opened, cheering her on,'' Pat says.
``When she called and said, `I auditioned for this dumb thing,
mother, and they called me back,' well, I popped every button! It's
so right for her.''
</P>
<P>
   So right because, as her mom says, ``Personality and humor are
Kathy's long suits.''
</P>
<P>
   That and her ability to yak ad nauseam about most anything _
from a cubic zirconium ring to a holiday figurine _ as phone orders
roll in at a rate of three calls per second.
</P>
<P>
   The first ``products'' she ever hawked, handed to Levine during
her impromptu audition in 1986, were a phone and pencil. There was
no prep time, no quiet moment to gather thoughts. The items were
thrust forth, and she was commanded to ``sell!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pencils are incredible because you can erase your mistakes,''
she improvised in front of a camera, yellow No. 2 in hand. ``And if
you get angry, you can break a pencil in two. Then you can give the
extra piece to a friend, making you resourceful ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Levine, then in sales at a Philadelphia hotel (``and hours from
getting fired''), responded to QVC's Help Wanted ad in The
Philadelphia Inquirer thinking she'd be a phone operator. But once
in the company's then-modest headquarters in West Chester, Pa.,
Levine _ egged on by a friend _ requested an audition.
</P>
<P>
   Just six weeks later, she was on-camera extolling the virtues of
a wet-dry vac.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Sears product because we needed a brand name to lend
credibility,'' she explains. ``I loved it! You could pick up baby
food or sawdust.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, QVC sells items from a mile-long list of major brands, plus
products endorsed by celebrities galore. Joan Rivers and Nolan
Miller (jewelry). Victoria Principal, Tova Borgnine and George
Hamilton (skin care/cosmetics). Diane Von Furstenberg, Delta Burke
and Bob Mackie (fashion). Richard Simmons, Denise Austin and Susan
Powter (fitness equipment). And so on.
</P>
<P>
   Other categories include electronics; cookware; housewares;
books; videos; music; and memorabilia/collectibles. (Although
people guess jewelry is QVC's top seller, it's actually
housewares.)
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when a vast number of companies wouldn't be
caught dead associating their names with us,'' says Levine, who has
a bachelor's degree in Spanish education from C.W. Post College in
New York. ``The most sophisticated evolution has been in marketing.
Now people are lining up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lining up because QVC is the mall that never closes. The network
broadcasts 24 hours a day, seven days a week to 67 million homes.
There are 20 or so show hosts, who become loosely linked with the
products they sell most. For example, Levine and Diamonique, QVC's
cubic zirconium line that accounts for about $18 million in sales a
year. Jane Rudolph Treacy and sterling silver jewelry. Mary Beth
Roe and collectible dolls and teddy bears. Bob Bowersox and
anything in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   (Treacy, Bowersox and Levine, by the way, are the only remaining
original hosts out of 20.)
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Kauffman Levine _ who describes herself as a
``not-so-beautiful, not-so-brilliant, smart-ass Jewish girl from
Allentown, Pa.'' in her book, ``It's Better to Laugh'' _ is the
youngest of three kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had two boys, so I was thrilled to finally get my little
girl,'' recalls Kathy's mom, Pat, an aspiring actress who ran a
charm school back in Allentown. Kathy's dad, Arnold Kauffman, who
died about a year ago, was a dentist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you, her personality came through in a hurry.
Other mommies took their kids to Girl Scouts, but I had to keep
Kathy from eating the cookies. She was always popular but not
somebody's girlfriend. But she's developed into a stunning young
lady.''
</P>
<P>
   (Pat, by the way, is as chatty and quick to joke as a daughter.
When told the photos of her in Levine's book are gorgeous, she
replies, ``Oh my God, honey, everything's gone south since then!''
Pat and her second husband, Lee, once just seasonal residents of
Palm Beach County, came south for good in 1994.)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, young Kathy battled weight and what she considered to be
a big nose (which she had fixed at 27). Those insecurities, though,
are part of what make her so appealing to viewers. Real folks can
relate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to be in a business where people are
perfect,'' says Levine, now in her mid-40s and a size 10. ``The
pressure, I realize, comes mostly from me. I'm much nicer when I'm
thin. But it's very hard to stand next to Susan Lucci, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Soap diva Lucci is just one of many celebs Levine meets on the
job. The host works most often, however, with comic Joan Rivers,
who sells a line of ``fashion'' jewelry. (Not costume jewelry, mind
you. Sure, it's the same thing, but ``fashion'' sounds, well, less
cheap.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of Levine's most memorable on-air moments was with
Rivers _ who's known for her candor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was showing a ring and doing my spiel,'' Levine recalls,
``and I said something to the effect that the ring would be admired
even at a formal dinner party. I paused, and Joan said, `Have you
ever been at a formal dinner party when somebody farts?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it. And she just kept talking about it. I
doubled over in my chair laughing. I couldn't draw a breath. The
producer was screaming at me so loud the earpiece fell out.''
</P>
<P>
   (QVC hosts sport a little earpiece _ think Secret Service agent
_ so producers can feed them directions, product information and
updates. ``And you'll hear them order out for Chinese,'' Levine
jokes. ``You hear everything.'')
</P>
<P>
   There are no TelePrompTers in the studio; however, a caller's
name and hometown are displayed for the host. (``We were trained to
repeat names. People like that. We used to have to memorize
them.'')
</P>
<P>
   There's no makeup and hair team standing by (``we do our own'');
no dressing room with a star on the door (``are you kidding?''); no
car service like Katie Couric and Matt Lauer get each morning (``if
the weather's bad, they'll pick us up in the van''); and no free
clothes from publicity-seeking retailers (although they offer).
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd love for us to wear their clothes because I get mail
asking, `Where'd you get that jacket you wore last Thursday?'''
Levine says. ``But we get a wardrobe allowance and $10 a week for a
manicure. It amounts to about $3,000 a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hosts earn between $50,000 and $100,000, she says, with yearly
bonuses based on QVC's sales (``no big shakes, but you can take
your kid to EPCOT'').
</P>
<P>
   Levine, who's divorced, has no kids (unless you count her
miniature schnauzer, Chelsea). She lives and loves her job, pals
around with other hosts and is currently taking flying lessons. She
isn't mobbed at the grocery store (``people do look'') and isn't
the least bit stuck up, although she's considered to be a pioneer
in her industry _ an industry that has revolutionized American
shopping. And an industry that has gained overwhelming respect
because of sales results and savvy marketing.
</P>
<P>
   QVC's faux fireplace of yore _ once home to a brass deer (``we
loved to knock `Bambi' off the mantel''), the occasional plastic
plant and other tchotchkes _ was recently replaced by a $100
million state-of-the-art broadcasting facility with six different
stages, including a two-story house.
</P>
<P>
   All flash aside, though, QVC hosts still hang out in the lounge
with curlers in their hair. And they still nosh in the cafeteria
with everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``People forget that this is a retail operation,'' Levine says.
``What I do is really no different than working at
Bloomingdale's.''
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY OF QVC
</P>
<P>
   June 13, 1986 _ Joseph Segel, founder of The Franklin Mint,
creates QVC, which stands for ``Quality, Value and Convenience''
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 24, 1986 _ First live broadcast from West Chester, Pa.,
with hosts Kathy Levine and John Eastman
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 1, 1987 _ Programming expands to 24 hours a day, seven days
a week
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 3, 1988 _ QVC acquires manufacturing facilities, technology
and trade-name rights from MSB Industries for Diamonique, a line of
cubic zirconium jewelry
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 31, 1989 _ QVC buys rival shopping channel CVN
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 17, 1991 _ First $10 million day, during which 125,000
phone orders totaled $10.4 million in sales
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 26, 1994 _ The QVC Morning Show debuts with hosts Pat
James DeMentri and Dan Hughes, blending shopping and product
previews with news
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 29, 1994 _ ``The Quest for America's Best,'' QVC's
cross-country tour to discover 1,000 of the best new products from
American entrepreneurs, kicks off in Washington aboard The QVC
Local (a mobile TV studio emblazoned with the world's biggest road
map of the U.S.)
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 19, 1995 _ Comcast Corp. and TeleCommunications Inc.
acquire QVC
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 27, 1995 _ Launch of onQ Music, QVC's private music label
with A Vote for Love, a 30-song compilation chosen by viewers and
sung by Kenny Rogers
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 24, 1996 _ QVC's first $20 million day
</P>
<P>
   March 15, 1996 _ QVC ships 200 millionth package (that's one
package for every adult in America)
</P>
<P>
   July 9, 1996 _ QVC launches CV Directo in Mexico
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 13, 1996 _ QVC breaks ground for $100 million Studio Park
in West Chester
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 4, 1996 _ QVC hits the Web and debuts its new personal
shopping service, On Call
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 1, 1996 _ QVC launches QVC Deutschland GmbH in Germany
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 17, 1997 _ ``The Klondike Gold Rush'' becomes QVC's
highest-selling day ever with sales of $29,327,473
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 24, 1997 _ Studio Park opens, with a 165,000-square-foot
broadcast center and six different stages, including a two-story
house
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 29, 1997 _ QVC hits an industry revenue milestone with $2
billion in sales within a 12-month period
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 7, 1999 _ Jeb Bush, Florida's newly inaugurated governor,
calls QVC President Doug Briggs during a board meeting to persuade
the retailer to open a phone center in Port St. Lucie
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 27, 1999 _ QVC announces plan to open a 50,000-square-foot
phone center in Port St. Lucie, which will generate 1,641 jobs and
a $23 million payroll
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 3, 1999 _ 2,500 people join Gov. Bush and town officials at
a QVC bash in Port St. Lucie, which features free hot dogs,
balloons and a cake big enough to serve 750
</P>
<P>
   SO YOU WANT TO BE A QVC PHONE REP?
</P>
<P>
   On an average day, QVC receives about 233,000 calls (and you
thought your teen-ager tied up the line!). To help handle that
load, the retailer is opening a phone center in Port St. Lucie this
fall. Others are in San Antonio, Texas; Chesapeake, Va.; and West
Chester, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   John Hunter, QVC's senior vice president for customer services,
oversees phone reps, the company's vital link to viewers. He took a
moment while in Port St. Lucie recently to answer a few questions:
</P>
<P>
   1. How do you decide which calls go to which phone center? Is it
based on region?
</P>
<P>
   No, calls are distributed evenly to all three centers. For
example, the first might go to Texas, the next to Virginia, the
next to Pennsylvania, then back to Texas. There are people that
monitor this and route calls elsewhere if one center is
particularly busy. We have bilingual speakers in San Antonio, so we
route all bilingual calls there. We'll also be hiring bilingual
speakers in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   2. Do phone reps receive a discount on QVC merchandise?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, every employee _ whether full- or part-time _ gets a 30
percent discount on jewelry, 20 percent on electronics. Other
discounts range from 15 to 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   3. Are reps paid on number of calls answered or whether the
customer places an order?
</P>
<P>
   No, they're paid by the hour, and there are incentives but not
what you'd call commissions. Incentives are based on quality of
service. (Most full-time workers in Port St. Lucie will earn
starting salaries of between $7 and $8 an hour, plus benefits of
about $4.15 an hour.)
</P>
<P>
   4. Does it matter if a rep has a strong regional accent (i.e.,
``Thank y'all for callin'!'')?
</P>
<P>
   That used to be a big thing but not anymore. At one time, you
had to sound sort of neutral, but now we look for people who can
articulate well and who are service oriented.
</P>
<P>
   5. Do reps mingle with hosts and corporate bigwigs at the
headquarters in West Chester?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, everybody's family regardless of what job you do at QVC. We
all eat in the same cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   6. Say a customer wants to go on and on about her grandchildren.
Or about his golf score. How are reps trained to get the order and
move on?
</P>
<P>
   That's part of ``call control.'' Once you feel the call's
getting off track, you have to graciously steer the person back to
the business at hand. But we don't rush people. If they mention the
Bronx, the rep might say, ``Oh, gee, you're from New York?'' and
make some small talk. Reps are trained to mirror the caller's
manner and pace. If someone wants to chat, the rep chats _ within
reason, of course. If someone sounds impatient, they know to take
the order quickly.
</P>
<P>
   7. How do reps decide what callers to put on the air?
</P>
<P>
   It's actually kind of random. They ask questions, like if the
caller's tried a certain product before or is a first-time
customer. If a certain product is airing and the producer wants
callers on that item, a flag will go up on everyone's computer
screen. They also try to make sure there are no babies screaming or
dogs barking in the background, that the customer's account is paid
up and that the person hasn't been on the air in the past 30 days.
Then the call is sent to a coordinator who sits with the producer.
</P>
<P>
   8. How can phone reps make sure someone isn't going to scream
something ludicrous on the air?
</P>
<P>
   They can't. The coordinator talks to the person to make sure
they're not a crackpot, but you can't always be 100 percent sure.
The host doesn't have any sort of ``panic button'' to push, but the
producer can disconnect the call. When that happens, the host
handles it by saying something like, ``Well, folks, that's live TV
for you!''
</P>
<P>
   9. Have the computers ever crashed, making it impossible for
reps to take orders?
</P>
<P>
   Way back in the early days, yes, but not anymore. That's why we
have phone centers in different areas of the country, in case of
power outages and whatnot. We can manually take orders if we have
to.
</P>
<P>
   10. Are calls monitored?
</P>
<P>
   Randomly, yes, and reps like this because of the coaching and
feedback. For example, we might say, ``That was a great call, but
I'd recommend you do such-and-such next time.'' It helps them
improve and feel like part of a team. Being a phone rep is more of
a personality type than an age group or education level. We've
pretty much said you have to have a high school diploma, but beyond
that, we're open. You do, though, have to enjoy dealing with people
_ lots of people.
</P>
<P>
   QVC BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   67 million _ homes that receive QVC
</P>
<P>
   3 per second _ phone calls to QVC in 1997
</P>
<P>
   $2.1 billion _ QVC's sales in 1997
</P>
<P>
   $43,000 _ average income of QVC shopper
</P>
<P>
   35 to 54 _ age range of QVC shopper (3-to-1 female)
</P>
<P>
   53 million _ QVC packages shipped in 1997
</P>
<P>
   4,600 _ phone lines at QVC
</P>
<P>
   172,000 _ orders that QVC can pack and ship daily
</P>
<P>
   34 football fields _ combined size of QVC's four distribution
centers, in Suffolk, Va.; and Lancaster, Centerville and West
Chester, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   30 percent _ amount of airtime QVC devotes to selling jewelry
</P>
<P>
   1,680 _ number of products offered on QVC each week
</P>
<P>
   155,000 _ copies of In the Kitchen with Bob (a cookbook by QVC
host Bob Bowersox) ordered Sept. 25, 1994, more copies of a single
title ever sold in one day by any retailer
</P>
<P>
   16 minutes _ time it took for QVC to sell 35,000 caps from
Qualcomm Stadium in San Diego after the 1998 Super Bowl
</P>
