<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4295 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALTLAKE14-COX     02-13 1357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTLAKE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Salt Lake goal: Forget scandal, ignite spirit
 &HT;    By Glenn Hannigan
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Frank Zang misses the simple joy of flipping
through the morning paper and sipping a cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   His quiet ritual has turned into a daily test of nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to admit,'' says Zang, a media representative for the
Salt Lake Olympic Committee, ``I cringe each morning when I walk
out to get my newspaper, thinking about what might be greeting
me.''
</P>
<P>
   He has plenty of company. The bloodletting has persisted for
months in Salt Lake, draining the city's Olympic joy drop by drop.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the 2002 Winter Games face each day with
apprehension, dreading a new allegation that will open fresh
wounds. The ongoing scandal, which has taken more agonizing turns
than the giant slalom course at Park City, has been excruciating
for a city that has exemplified the virtues of hard work and clean
living.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of celebrating the three-year milestone to the start of
the Games this past week, Salt Lake had to face a jarring 300-page
report that accuses top officials of making covert payments to
International Olympic Committee members, providing extravagant
gifts and trips and concealing their actions.
</P>
<P>
   In a week when the organizers expected to be hosting parties,
they instead were reeling from the recent resignation of the SLOC's
two top officers. On Thursday, the SLOC hired Mitt Romney to take
over the beleaguered organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of humbling to deal with in Salt Lake,'' said
Margaret Adams, who manages the historic Beehive House, the former
residence of Brigham Young. ``We're very disappointed by the
activity of some of the Olympic leadership. We know it's going to
take a lot of work to restore our integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest Olympic scandal in history began in November, when
allegations arose of scholarship payments made by Salt Lake
organizers to family members of IOC officials. That rumor quickly
snowballed from a regional ripple into an international avalanche
as accusations surfaced that IOC members accepted large cash
payments, lavish gifts, college tuition, Super Bowl excursions,
European vacations and free medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Since the IOC launched an internal investigation, nine members
have resigned or been expelled, but that number is likely to
increase as investigators review allegations raised in the Salt
Lake report, and an additional report from Nagano, site of the 1998
Winter Games. Japanese officials have said that nine IOC members
might have broken rules during visits to Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney, which will host the 2000 Summer Games, also has come
under scrutiny, but was cleared by the IOC after an internal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, organizers of the '96 Summer Games have consistently
denied any wrongdoing in their bid efforts. But this past week,
Atlanta Olympic chief Billy Payne was confronted with a memo he
wrote to a top aide in 1990, suggesting they consider providing a
college scholarship, plane tickets and medical treatment for IOC
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was continually thinking out loud about things which might
have made a difference in our campaign,'' Payne explained. ``None
of these directives were ever seriously discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Salt Lake has graduated from the suspicion phase to a state
of full-blown scandal and disgrace _ and everyone here wants to
know when the hemorrhaging will stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the peak of this story a couple weeks ago, I was fielding
more than 100 calls a day from all over the world,'' Zang says.
``I'll be grateful when it slows down. Every day I just try to look
at it as though we're one step closer to the Games.''
</P>
<P>
   But what kind of Games? USOC officials have expressed concern
over the potential fallout if corporate and public confidence in
the Olympics is shaken. Last week, for example, David D'Alessandro,
president and chief operations officer of John Hancock insurance,
said his company was canceling negotiations with NBC for $20
million in ads to protest the IOC's failure to deal with the
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published in the Deseret News of Salt Lake City last week
found that 72 percent of respondents are worried about the SLOC's
ability to secure adequate funding because of concerns expressed by
corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   And Salt Lake City still must find a substantial number of
sponsors to meet its $1.45 billion budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have every confidence that people of Salt Lake will return
the reputation and dignity of the Olympics,'' says Payne, who was
successful in raising $1.7 billion to pay for the Atlanta Games.
``The power of the Olympic movement is far stronger than the
misdeeds of any small group of people. The goodwill and the spirit
of the people are 100 times more important than the leadership of
any organization.''
</P>
<P>
   It's Payne's belief that the same force that pulled the Atlanta
Games from its darkest hour _ the bombing at Centennial Olympic
Park _ has the power to do the same for Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our volunteers who rekindled the spirit of Atlanta,''
Payne says. ``After the tragedy of the park bombing, we weren't
sure what to do. I remember standing on my office balcony after the
bombing, privately grieving and not knowing whether we should
postpone the Games or not. It was the most difficult time of my
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``In just six hours, we had competition scheduled at the World
Congress Center. We knew if the volunteers didn't begin showing up
at 7 a.m., we couldn't continue the Games. We realized people were
going to be waking up, hear the news of the bombing, and possibly
get scared off.''
</P>
<P>
   That morning, with the future of the '96 Games on the line,
Payne walked toward the World Congress Center to thank whoever
showed up and try to rally them on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volunteers were scheduled to gather in the big Murphy
ballroom. I had no idea what to expect when I walked in at 7 a.m.
...'' Payne's voice breaks, recalling the scene. ``I still get
emotional when I think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were twice as many volunteers in that room as were
scheduled to show up. It was incredible. I've made speeches about
that moment _ the one time I was supposed to be a leader and I
ended up being inspired by them. The people took the bombing
personally. They decided they would not allow it to diminish their
Games. The people of Atlanta turned our greatest tragedy into our
biggest triumph.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the circumstances have little in common, Payne believes
the people of Salt Lake will ultimately decide the fate of their
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of folks in Utah feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can always weed out corrupt people from any
organization,'' says Curt Daems of Layton, Utah. ``That has nothing
to do with me or the people of Salt Lake. The challenge will be for
us to bring the enthusiasm back. I absolutely love Salt Lake City
and I'm committed to supporting this Olympic effort. Most of the
people I've talked with feel the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Daems is one of about 8,000 Olympic volunteers in and around
Salt Lake. The SLOC anticipates needing 15,000-18,000 volunteers
for the Games. At the peak of the 1996 Olympics, Atlanta needed
47,000 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Eynon, the SLOC's senior vice president for human resources,
says he's been ``surprised and thrilled'' by the response from
Utahns eager to volunteer. ``The magic of the Games is so powerful
it can blow through turmoil,'' Eynon says. ``Knock on wood, all
this negative news hasn't impacted the support we've been getting.
I think most people believe that after the scandal has run its
course, there will still be a spectacular Olympics to host.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne agrees: ``There's not a single day that someone doesn't
tell me how important the Olympic experience was for them. I have
received around 60,000 personal letters since the end of the Games
from people who wanted to share their stories. When you see how
everyone comes together for this event _ the miracle of people from
different cultures interacting _ it gives you hope for the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
