<HEADER>
A4296 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOKE-FUNDS14-COX     02-13 0267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKE-FUNDS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fla. study suggests funds from tobacco deal should target
elderly care, research
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Smokers go into nursing homes sooner and
die there younger than nonsmokers, but those who survive stay
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Those effects add up to more than $103 million a year in
smoking-related costs to Florida's Medicaid system, says a study by
a state and university research team.
</P>
<P>
   The study's principal author says it reinforces the need to
spend more of Florida's $12.7 billion tobacco lawsuit settlement
money on care for the elderly and research on preventive treatment
for smokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This clearly demonstrates they have needs that are
smoking-attriubtable and that are beyond the needs of nonsmokers,''
said economist Tim Lynch, director of Florida State University's
Center for Economic Forecasting and Analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch teamed with Dr. Richard Hopkins, chief of epidemiology at
the Florida Department of Health, to study nursing home residents
in 11 counties, the largest being Pinellas, Palm Beach and Broward.
They finished the two-year project in January, working under a
$100,000 grant from the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Lynch and Hopkins concluded that if the smokers had had the same
average length of stay as nonsmokers, it would have amounted to
10,781 fewer days for the year. That would have equaled more than
7.2 percent of the $1.4 billion in Medicaid spending on nursing
home care in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
