<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-WAR-SCHOOL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPEATING TO AD ART NOTE 
 LESSON IN CAUCASUS: WAR HAS RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locater map is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By STEVE LeVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TBILISI, Georgia _ Dato stood ramrod straight _ all four feet of
him _ discarded his considerable shyness, then defined proper
battlefield behavior: ``When we are defending our land, we should
not forget to remain just.''
</P>
<P>
   His classmate, Gyorgy, spoke up. ``If we ever appear in a war
zone,'' he declared, ``we know we should take care of people,
especially the wounded, and bring them to the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Tbilisi Public School 76, where 30 sixth grade
students are taking a course this year in the international rules
of war, with an emphasis on sparing the wounded, not executing
prisoners and respecting civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Devised by the International Committee of the Red Cross, it is
an emblem of the ferocity of the civil wars that have followed the
collapse of Communism and an experiment in preventing war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The course reflects the sober realization of humanitarian groups
that work day after day in the world's numerous war zones that
ethnic hostility has defied exhaustive mediation efforts. The
Geneva-based Red Cross, which has lost 12 of its own workers to the
murderous conflicts in the former Soviet Union, is addressing the
next generation with the message, ``This is if it does happen,''
said Guy Mellet, the Red Cross delegate in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to insure that ``the future elite of these countries
have knowledge that international humanitarian law exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia is an apt spot for the trial. Since the 1991 Soviet
breakup lifted the harsh rule that suppressed ethnic rivalries and
nationalism, it is one of many former Soviet battlegrounds _
Nagorno-Karabakh, Tajikistan, Chechnya _ rent by death and
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   As Georgian nationalism rose in this traditionally fractious
Caucasus republic, two of its regions _ Abkhazia and South Ossetia
_ tried to break away. By 1994, the toll of both wars was about
135,000 dead in a population of 5.5 million, more than one million
homeless, thousands of square miles of homes burned down to prevent
the return of rival ethnic groups and the virtual secession of
large chunks of Georgia's territory.
</P>
<P>
   The killing and bombardment of neighbor by neighbor tore at the
fabric of ethnic ties so violently that tradition would demand
blood revenge for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Now, from specially prepared booklets, 2.6 million 11- and
12-year-olds in Georgia, in neighboring Armenia and Azerbaijan, in
Uzbekistan and in Russia are taught the spirit of accords like the
Geneva Convention. While central to contemporary Western conduct of
war, few people in less peaceful parts of the world read or even
know about such accords.
</P>
<P>
   While mouthing the phrases about respecting certain conventions
in war, the pupils of Tbilisi School 76 are as robustly determined
as their parents, for example, that the breakaway region of
Abkhazia, a semitropical strip of resorts and mountains along the
Black Sea, belongs in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Abkhaz have long held otherwise, giving voice to
their discontent even in Soviet times. In 1993, fighting claimed
10,000 lives. Backed by Russian troops sent by hard-liners in
Moscow, the Abkhaz expelled Georgian forces and drove 260,000
civilians from home.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, mediation backed by the United Nations broke down when
the Abkhaz, asserting potential and actual terrorism, forced out
some 40,000 Georgians who had returned to homes abandoned in the
earlier war.
</P>
<P>
   In this Tbilisi school, traditional Georgian literature is used
as the vehicle to preach peace, or at least civil conduct during
war.
</P>
<P>
   On one recent day, the sixth graders discussed ``Mirandukht,'' a
story by a Georgian writer, Revaz Inanishvili. The main character
is a young girl who stands up for an elderly woman who is about to
be cheated by a rapacious butcher and who ends up befriending and
transforming him into an honest man.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, Khahuti Khvedelidze, uses the story to ask students
how they would solve the conflict with Abkhazia.
</P>
<P>
   A chorus of voices suggests approaches ranging from, ``We should
forgive them and become friends,'' to speaking a common language or
``Get back our land in a peaceful way.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news from the session was that no one suggested
resorting to violence. But there is no guarantee that these
children will grow up to find a peaceful way to settle undoubted
territorial disputes.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Khvedelidze suggested that the very absence of the
Communist clamps that suppressed and distorted national feelings
across the Soviet Union and its satellite states may give grounds
for hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very good children,'' she said. ``They are freer
than we were.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
