<HEADLINE>
REPEATING TO AD ART NOTE 
 BEHIND ERITREA-ETHIOPIA WAR, A `KNACK FOR STUBBORNNESS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locater map is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia _ On a continent of conflicts that often
make little sense to outsiders, the war that has reignited on the
Horn of Africa may make the least sense of them all.
</P>
<P>
   The two nations here, Ethiopia and Eritrea, know full well that
they are shambling into a confrontation nearly impossible for
either of them to win. The United States has praised both nations
for their bright leaders and promising economies. Yet people here
talk with resignation of how the war has an unusual potential for
destruction. Ethiopia and Eritrea, once brother nations, have spent
the last eight months since hostilities ceased buying as much
weaponry _ planes, tanks, artillery _ as possible. In manpower
alone, the war could become the biggest in Africa. Estimates of the
number of soldiers along the border range from 120,000 to 400,000.
</P>
<P>
   These troops are dug into trenches, hard to overtake. Each
nation is run by former guerrilla leaders, and neither side is
likely to back away now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are accustomed to war,'' Hambissa Ensermu, a 19-year-old
student at Addis Ababa University, said the other day. ``The only
choice we have now is to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
warned, ``We have got to accept the fact that this war is going to
produce tens of thousands of dead if it goes ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there has been a lull in hostilities over the last
several days, Eritrea already says it killed roughly 3,000
Ethiopian soldiers since fighting broke out Feb. 6. While Ethiopia
ridicules that claim as wildly inflated, it says more than 7,000
Eritreans have been killed or wounded.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the State Department advised American citizens to
leave both countries, citing worries that the fighting could spread
to either capital, as it did last spring, when Ethiopia launched
attacks against Asmara.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the weaponry and number of soldiers, there is another
element that may be driving the conflict to catastrophe, a quality
one observer called the two nations' ``knack for stubbornness.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute is nominally about a rocky piece of land along the
border, known as the Badme region, which is barely populated and
holds no special significance, as one merchant in the main market
here said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That area, I think, is desert,'' the merchant, Tilahun Wolde,
25, said. ``It's valueless.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he said he believed that Ethiopia should fight as
long as necessary to reclaim it from the Eritreans, who have held
it since May.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's territory, you know,'' he said. ``We'll die for our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders from around the world, including Kofi Annan, the U.N.
secretary-general, have called for a halt to the fighting. Last
week, President Clinton spoke out for the second time recently,
saying that ``a peaceful solution can and must be found without
delay.''
</P>
<P>
   His comments underscore that this, unlike most conflicts in
Africa, is one in which America has definable interests. Each
nation is a strong ally, and Eritrea sits astride the oil channels
of the Red Sea.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite their dispute, the two nations have been regarded as
being comparatively stable in a turbulent region. Their neighbor to
the west, Sudan, is a haven for both terrorists and Islamic
militants, U.S. officials contend. Their neighbor to the east,
Somalia, where 18 American lives were lost in 1993 in an effort to
alleviate famine, remains fractured among competing clans.
</P>
<P>
   More abstractly, the war would seem to sound death knells for
the notion of an ``African renaissance,'' pushed with special vigor
over the last few years by the United States and derided by many
less optimistic outsiders. Meles Zenawi, the prime minister of
Ethiopia, and Isaias Afwerki, president of Eritrea, were among the
``new breed'' of African leaders hailed by the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The roots of their conflict are tangled. Meles, from the
Ethiopian border province of Tigray, and Afwerki fought side by
side for years in the war to overthrow the brutal regime of
Mengistu Haile Mariam. They won in 1991, and two years later,
Eritrea, which had been the northernmost province of Ethiopia only
since 1962, separated peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   But the divorce of the two nations did not come without tension.
The most pronounced split came in 1997, when Eritrea introduced its
own currency over Ethiopia's objections. Ethiopia responded by
demanding that all trade with Eritrea be conducted in hard
currency.
</P>
<P>
   The two nations also never formally drew their 600-mile border.
Last May, the bad feelings erupted when Eritrean troops occupied
the Badme region, roughly 250 square miles. The Eritreans said that
old colonial maps showed that it belonged to them, but the
Ethiopians said it had always been theirs.
</P>
<P>
   After brief but fierce battles, the two sides agreed to a
cease-fire last June. Since then, they have worked toward both war
and peace.
</P>
<P>
   For war, each nation has bought hundreds of millions of dollars
in military hardware, mostly from Russia and Ukraine, several
diplomats said. Eritrea purchased half a dozen Russian MIG fighter
jets, essentially doubling the size of its small air force.
</P>
<P>
   For peace, the Organization of African Unity drafted a plan that
called for Eritrea to withdraw its troops and for Ethiopian
administration to be restored as international mediators decided
where, in fact, the border lay. Ethiopia accepted the plan. But
Eritrea has objected to a renewed Ethiopian administrative presence
and has demanded instead that impartial monitors be placed in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said Eritrea is willing to leave the disputed areas,''
said Yemane Ghevreab, an aide to Afwerki. ``We are saying that the
other side should also withdraw.''
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea also has called for any peace plan to address what it
calls the violations of the human rights of the 52,000 Eritreans
deported from Ethiopia since the first round of hostilities.
Ethiopia says that nearly 40,000 of its citizens have been ejected
from Eritrea. Human rights officials say both claims are inflated.
</P>
<P>
   Most foreign nations seem gingerly to blame Eritrea for not
accepting the OAU plan, the only peace proposal on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia has been using that refusal by Eritrea as its first
line of defense in the battle for public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not only an OAU exercise,'' Ethiopia's foreign
minister, Seyoum Mesfin, said in an interview. ``It's the voice of
the international community, which Ethiopia has accepted and
Eritrea has not.''
</P>
<P>
   There are currently no negotiations. Mesfin said that Eritrea
must be taught that ``acquiring territory by use of force is
unacceptable to civilized nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Ghevreab, of Eritrea, accused Ethiopia of resuming the
hostilities Feb. 6, in what he called ``an adventurist, very
reckless path.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad,'' he said. ``We shouldn't have come to this.''
</P>
<P>
   One Western defense official theorized that the fighting may in
fact have begun by accident.
</P>
<P>
   With so many troops in place along the border and clear
boundaries yet to be marked between them, there was, and remains,
ample room for miscalculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling is that this was not a planned offensive,'' the
official said. ``What you are seeing now is something we have
feared for months.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
