<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4316 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH-LEGACY14-COX     02-13 1630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-LEGACY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich legacy filled with irony
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Newt Gingrich was traveling and not available for
comment Friday when the Senate acquitted President Clinton of
offenses charged in two articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   His Marietta, Ga., office would not say where he was or what he
was doing when Congress closed the final installment of Gingrich's
four eventful years as Speaker of the House.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich has slipped away from Washington so quietly that it is
almost a surprise to enter the speaker's offices and not see the
familiar T. rex skull that so intrigued him.
</P>
<P>
   His demise as speaker was swift, followed by months of tumult
that made Gingrich's orderly exit quaint by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   But before he left, Gingrich cast his final votes in favor of
Clinton's impeachment. And the signature on the transmittal letter
that accompanied the articles of impeachment from the House to the
Senate belonged to Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   It was his final official act as speaker, a farewell to a
bedeviling adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Gingrich had been on the same political seesaw for
so long that their fortunes seemed inextricably and inversely
linked. Gingrich's rise came at Clinton's expense and his botched
legislative agenda in 1995 helped revive the president politically,
to cite just two examples.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Clinton survives as president, while Gingrich profitably
works the lecture circuit.
</P>
<P>
   There are those, mainly Democrats, who trace Gingrich's downfall
to his support for the president's impeachment. They remember the
speaker's vow to a meeting of GOPAC, his one-time political
organization, that he would mention Clinton's behavior in every
speech and a round of Republican television commercials late in the
1998 congressional campaigns that broached Clinton's sexual
relationship with Monica Lewinsky and the lies he told to conceal
it.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats picked up five seats in the House in the November
election, cutting the GOP edge in the House in half and spurring
frenzied efforts by Republicans to replace Gingrich as speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can joke and say it was Monica who brought Newt down.
But I think the whole thing did bring him down,'' said Rep. John
Lewis (D-Ga.), a Gingrich nemesis. ``If he had not been playing the
impeachment card, we would not have won the seats we won in
November and he'd still be around.''
</P>
<P>
   Randall Strahan, an Emory University political scientist who is
writing a book about Gingrich and other powerful speakers, said
that although Gingrich lay low during impeachment's final stages,
``Many people would agree he was its driving force.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans interviewed last week about Gingrich's role in
impeachment maintained that it ranged from minimal to nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Several pointed out that Democrats at one point accused Gingrich
of manipulating the process to inflict maximum embarrassment on
Clinton. A few weeks later, the same Democrats were pleading for
Gingrich to take command of a rudderless impeachment ship.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that in the spring of 1998, Gingrich provided a
crucial morale boost to Clinton's foes when he began raising the
Lewinsky affair in his speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.) recalled, ``We were
in a leadership meeting and he said it was time to start talking
about criminal activity, not personal activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The message was that Americans might recoil from a scandal about
consensual sex, but would take notice of accusations that the
president had broken the law.
</P>
<P>
   Still later, Gingrich suggested to a closed meeting of the
male-dominated House Republican membership that if Clinton had
groped Kathleen Willey, the one-time White House volunteer, and had
similar experiences with other women, then he could legitimately be
called a misogynist.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker, who frequently imposed his will on his GOP
colleagues, also allowed independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report
to Congress to be posted on the Internet, with no excisions of its
explicit sexual references.
</P>
<P>
   Yet once Starr's report was in Congress's hands, and the House
Judiciary Committee began its investigation, Gingrich said ``not
one word to us,'' said Rep. George Gekas (R-Pa.), a committee
member and one of 13 prosecutors in the Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans portrayed Gingrich as, at best, a reluctant
impeachment warrior, uncomfortable with the subject matter, but
unable to resist calls to move ahead because of his own political
problems with social conservatives and his fear of alienating a
crucial component of the Republican constituency.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was of two minds about impeachment and both showed
themselves,'' said Jack Pitney, a political science professor at
Claremont McKenna College in suburban Los Angeles. ``I think he
realized impeachment is a powerful weapon, but that it could
backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich also was aware that Democrats would use his $300,000
penalty and reprimand for violating House ethics rules in their
counterattack, Pitney said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ironies Pitney identified is that Democrats used
Gingrich's real or perceived involvement in impeachment to raise
money for their own campaigns. ``Newt Gingrich 's unique place in
history is that he was a powerfully effective fund-raiser for both
parties at the same time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Linder, who served as chairman of the House Republican campaign
committee, seconded the notion that Gingrich said little about
impeachment in the waning stages of the campaign. He has denied
repeatedly, for instance, that Gingrich had anything to do with the
controversial campaign ads that mentioned the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Linder believes that Gingrich allies _ including GOPAC executive
director Rich Galen and political consultant Joe Gaylord _ feared
that the speaker would not receive proper credit for widely
anticipated Republican gains in last year's election. They spread
the story that Gingrich approved the ads, Linder said.
</P>
<P>
   Galen has denied any involvement and Gaylord has not returned
telephone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Linder is among many Republicans who discount impeachment's
impact on the election and instead blame the GOP's lack of a clear
agenda for turning off conservative Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In this view, the congressional leadership's decision to agree
with Clinton on a $500 billion catch-all spending bill, which
contained money for a range of social programs and projects that
critics derided as pork, doomed the GOP at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not convinced that the base of the Republican party
stayed home because of impeachment. They stayed home because of the
budget deal,'' former Rep. Bob Walker (R-Pa.), a Gingrich
confidant, said. ``It was a strategic mistake that was not Newt's
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's undoing was in his being party to an agreement that
blurred the lines between Republicans and Democrats, several
Republicans said.
</P>
<P>
   The new speaker, Rep. Dennis Hastert (R-Ill.), is in many ways
the antithesis of Gingrich. Not a polished orator, the former
wrestling coach has pledged to focus on the nuts and bolts of
running the House and leave the visionary thinking to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's what we need now, a plodder,'' Rep. Saxby Chambliss
(R-Ga.) said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, to make sure that he was clear that the palace intrigue
that was often a part of the Gingrich years had passed, Chambliss
added, ``That's P-L-O-D-D-E-R.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's supporters also have sought to ensure that their man,
Time's Man of the Year in 1995, would be remembered for something
other than the controveries that marked his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Galen, in an e-mail file he regularly sends to reporters and
political junkies, got in a plug for his one-time boss Friday in a
comment on the legacy Clinton hopes to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``His legacy is having LOST the House in 1994, having prevented
the Democrats from winning it back in 1996 because of the way he
conducted his campaign, and being unable to take it back in 1998
despite it being all but placed in his hands,'' Galen wrote.
``Looked at another way, Clinton couldn't beat Gingrich in three
tries.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before Gingrich resigned his seat last month, his staff
produced a 21-page report on Gingrich's legacy that goes well
beyond the Contract with America, a balanced budget and welfare
reform. In florid tones, the report credits Gingrich for the rise
in the stock market, a drop in interest rates, creation of 7.5
million new jobs and Americans' ``renewed sense of optimism about
themselves, their families and their future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be little doubt that with the benefit of sober
reflection, Gingrich's name will rank with handful of speakers
whose strong hand, particularly in a time of weakened presidential
leadership, changed the course of the country for the better,'' the
report concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Pitney, the California political scientist, and Emory's Strahan,
took a more nuanced approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest part of his legacy came the day he took the gavel
because he played a huge role in ending 40 years of Democratic
control,'' Pitney said.
</P>
<P>
   Strahan said, ``His actual impact on public policy is pretty
hard to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he has removed himself from political life, many of
Gingrich's friends are certain that his hiatus is temporary.
Gingrich continues to raise money assiduously. His new political
action committee took in more than $200,000 in the last 45 days of
1998, an envious pace for any politician.
</P>
<P>
   And, in case there was any doubt that Gingrich has future
political designs, his staff's report on his legacy should make
clear that he does.
</P>
<P>
   It was titled ``an interim report, the Speaker of the House
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
