<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBYA-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBYA CLOSER TO HANDING OVER SUSPECTS IN PAN AM BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said early Saturday
that ``important progress'' has been made toward persuading Libya
to turn over two suspects wanted in the 1988 bombing of a Pan
American flight over Lockerbie, Scotland, which killed 270 people.
</P>
<P>
   Annan's office issued the cautiously optimistic statement after
Saudi Arabia and South Africa said in separate announcements that
what South Africa called a ``common understanding'' had been
reached by their envoys with Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi.
</P>
<P>
   Annan is now looking forward to the ``speedy conclusion of this
matter,'' according to the statement issued by his office.
</P>
<P>
   Though the diplomatic impasse has appeared to be on the brink of
solution several times before, Gadhafi has always balked. Hence,
the statements issued from Pretoria, Riyadh and the U.N.
headquarters in New York were hopeful but restrained.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials in Washington declined comment
Saturday , saying they were waiting for more information. But White
House officials remained skeptical, noting that Gadhafi had always
found reasons to pull back from a deal before.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the statement issued by the United Nations
suggested that a breakthrough had been achieved. It was released
after separate statements from Johannesburg and Riyadh and after a
meeting late Friday between Annan and Rihad Massoud, the deputy
chief of mission of the Saudi Embassy in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi and South African diplomats had asked Annan's help in
securing Libya's agreement to turn over the two Libyans for a trial
at The Hague, in the Netherlands, before a court of Scottish
judges. On Dec. 5, Annan had traveled to Libya and met in a desert
tent with Gadhafi to discuss the Libyan leader's reservations about
the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said that Gadhafi had expressed concern about whether
the two Libyans would be treated and tried fairly, and whether the
United States would permit the lifting of sanctions against Libya
that have been imposed since 1992 in part for its failure to hand
over the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomats said that the secretary-general assured the Libyan
leader that U.N. resolutions would be followed.
</P>
<P>
   According to a resolution adopted by the Security Council last
August, as soon as the Security Council is informed that the two
suspects have safely arrived in the Netherlands, sanctions against
Libya are to be ``suspended immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Ninety days after that, the sanctions are to be formally lifted
when and if the Security Council is assured by the
secretary-general that Libya is no longer supporting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   A U. N. official said that United Nations lawyers are now
attempting to draw up a legal document describing the agreement and
understandings reached by the South African and Saudi envoys who
have met several times with the Libyan leader.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Prince Bandar bin Sultan, the Saudi
ambassador to Washington, and professor Jakes Gerwel, director
general of the office of the South African president, Nelson
Mandela, warned Gadhafi in Libya that the United States and Britain
were committed to stiffening the sanctions if Libya failed to turn
over the suspects.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, American officials had said that the United
States and Britain would press for an oil embargo and other stiffer
sanctions against Libya if Gadhafi did not comply with U.N.
resolutions calling upon Libya to turn over the suspects, Abdel
Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah.
</P>
<P>
   Gadhafi was reported to be concerned about where the two men
would serve their sentences if convicted. Britain and the United
States insist that the men be jailed in Scotland, but Gadhafi had
expressed concerns about whether they would be safely treated in
Western jails.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, American officials said, some of the assurances
sought by Gadhafi had to do with placing U.N. monitors in the
prison where the men would be held in the event of a conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Libya has reacted harshly to American threats to expand or
stiffen sanctions if Libya fails to turn over the suspects. In a
statement issued by JANA, the Libyan news agency monitored by the
British Broadcasting Corp., the government in Tripoli said, ``Libya
will never accept any solution under the threat of sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 at the urging of the United States and Britain, the
United Nations imposed sanctions against Libya banning air travel
to and from the country and limiting the sale of oil equipment. The
sanctions have left the oil-rich desert country diplomatically and
physically isolated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
