<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Feb. 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mainly tranquil and dry conditions are expected across the
nation on Sunday. No significant precipitation will fall east of
the Rockies, and sunshine will dominate the southern two-thirds of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   The jet stream will retreat from the eastern states, and in its
place, high pressure will build along the Atlantic seaboard. The
morning will be very chilly in the Southeast and Florida with
freezing temperatures as far south as Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   A brisk wind will diminish in New England, but some clouds and
scattered flurries will remain. A storm developing well offshore
may bring clouds and flurries to Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   A rapid warming will occur from the Mississippi Valley to the
eastern Rockies. Strengthening winds from the southwest will
transport warm, dry air from northern Mexico toward the central
Plains. Record readings are possible in eastern Colorado, Kansas
and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and isolated showers will accompany a complex cold front
crossing the upper Middle West. A chilled Pacific air mass will
flow into the northern Rockies behind a cool front. Patches of
light snow will fall across Montana and along the west slopes of
the Wasatch and Uintas. Several inches of snow are possible.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure over Washington and Oregon will promote dry and
rather cool weather. Sunshine will be sparse along the northwest
coast. A disturbance approaching California will bring clouds in
the afternoon and perhaps a shower Sunday night. The Southwest
should stay bright and become warmer.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Quick Change
</P>
<P>
   It felt like early summer for half of Thursday night in Erie,
Pa. A balmy wind from the south boosted readings to near 70 degrees
until 3 a.m. on Friday. By 8:30 a.m., snow was falling and bursts
of heavy snow accumulated 2.1 inches during the day. This scenario
was repeated at many other locations in the Northeast on Friday as
a powerful cold front pushed to the coast. However, the chill
following this front was typical for the season. A century ago on
Feb. 13, readings fell below zero all across Alabama, perhaps the
greatest cold outbreak in the South's history.
</P>
</TEXT>
