<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4320 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-CIRCUIT14-     02-13 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-CIRCUIT14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pulling away from image of 'Triple-A'
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If money can buy status, NASCAR has a million reasons
to believe it can change the perception of the Busch Grand National
racing series from Triple-A to major league.
</P>
<P>
   The Busch, NASCAR's ``other'' racing series considered the
stepping stone to Winston Cup, is getting a big marketing push in
1999 as the No. 2 racing circuit in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   That's Busch league, not bush league.
</P>
<P>
   The series has enjoyed tremendous growth in popularity,
attendance and prize money.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance has increased 286 percent during the past 10 years.
Sponsor Anheuser-Busch's contribution to the points fund has
increased from $150,000 in 1992 to $650,000 in 1998 to $1.5 million
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we developed plans for the Busch series, we knew we had a
valuable property that is much more than a feeder system to the
NASCAR Winston Cup series,'' said Brian France, senior vice
president of NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   While showcasing future Winston Cup stars, the Busch series has
offered something the Cup has not: close competition.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen different drivers won in the 31-race series last year.
Nineteen different drivers won the pole in the last 19 races.
Fifty-two drivers led at least one lap. The fastest qualifier and
the slowest qualifier have been separated by an average of .536
seconds, and the average margin of victory was 1.432 seconds from
first to second.
</P>
<P>
   The series had a huge range in experience and age: 17-year-old
Casey Atwood became the series youngest-ever pole-winner, and at
the age of 56 years and 10 months, Dick Trickle became the oldest
driver to win a Busch race with his victory at Hickory, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   But there's this second-banana position that NASCAR is trying to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to position the series as the proving ground for the
Winston Cup series while emphasizing that in no way is the NASCAR
Busch series a minor league,'' said Kevin Triplett, a NASCAR
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because so many people are familiar with baseball, we refer to
Busch as a Triple-A series,'' Triplett said. ``In no way do we feel
that the Busch series is minor league. We've felt that way for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, a number of Winston Cup drivers feel the same way.
Mark Martin, Ken Schrader and Jimmy Spencer regularly run Busch
races, and this year defending Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon
will drive five races for a team he is starting with his wife,
Brooke, and his Cup crew chief, Ray Evernham.
</P>
<P>
   Randy LaJoie, a two-time Busch champion who has made brief runs
in Winston Cup, has seen first-hand the growth of the Busch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more money than there used to be,'' said LaJoie,
who won the Busch title in 1996 and 1997. ``I think that's what's
bringing Gordon back. Also it's a good series, otherwise people
wouldn't want to come here and race. And maybe these guys are using
it as a test for Sunday. With NASCAR's testing procedures now, any
track time you get is a bonus. The cars are getting very similar.
There are things you can do in a Busch car that can help you on
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   But LaJoie knows the series needs an image makeover.
</P>
<P>
   He has run several races in Winston Cup. ``I got recognized more
for running the Budweiser car than I did for winning two
championships,'' LaJoie said. ``The fans, I think, have followed
the Busch series the last couple of years, but they still ask you
'when are you going to drive NASCAR?' We do drive NASCAR. But the
fans really put your name with Winston Cup because that's the
elite, that is the upper echelon. But there's nothing wrong with
the Busch series.''
</P>
<P>
   While other drivers are leaving Busch for the upper echelon _
Buckshot Jones, Elliott Sadler, Kevin Lepage and Tony Stewart are
moving up to Winston Cup this year _ LaJoie, for one, has been
content to remain in Busch.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the involvement and the money Busch is putting in,
there's no reason you can't make a good living in the Busch
series,'' he said. ``I'm going to take my piece of that cake and
run with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Trickle, the veteran, isn't shy about referring to Busch as the
proving ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty hard for a guy to go right to Winston Cup without
schooling himself,'' Trickle said. ``In order to run Winston Cup
some day you have to get a lot of seat time in cars that are close
to them. Busch is the closest thing to them. It's really a major
stepping stone for what is Winston Cup. It's the next notch under
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a place for drivers to compete, but more
importantly to marketing-savvy NASCAR, it's another vehicle for
sponsor involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start a Winston Cup race on Sunday, 43 cars,'' Trickle
said. ``Does that mean there's only 43 sponsors in this country,
only 43 drivers in this country? No, there's a lot of great drivers
out there, and you can't put them all into 43. This gives a second
43 drivers a chance to race. They need a place to race, and the
fans want to watch more than just Winston Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
