   &UR; TOP: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lead story: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-KOSOVO (Washington) _ President Clinton announced Saturday
that he would send nearly 4,000 troops to Kosovo to defend the
``national interest'' as part of a NATO peacekeeping force,
provided the ethnic Albanians and Serbs who are warring there
strike a peace agreement. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in `i' and `w' news files.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Top center: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AMR-PILOTS (Undated) _ A federal judge in Dallas cited the union
representing American Airlines pilots for contempt Saturday and
fined it at least $10 million for ignoring his back-to-work order
as the pilots' continued sickout stranded tens of thousands of
passengers on a especially busy holiday weekend. By Steven
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in `a' and `f' news files.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Off-lead: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-AFTERMATH (Washington) _ The official word from
President Clinton and congressional leaders in the aftermath of
Friday's impeachment vote was that the time had come to bury the
hatchet and work together on important policy issues. But out of
camera range, many in the White House and the Capitol said the bad
blood was so pervasive, the ideological divisions so vast and the
political interests so disparate that they doubted productive
bridges could be built between the president and the Republican
Congress. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in `w' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOLD: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-SUSPECT-AFRICANS (New York) _ For Africans, particularly West
Africans, the police shooting of Amadou Diallo, an immigrant from
Guinea, has only reinforced the vulnerability they feel in New York
City. They left a continent where they were a racial majority _
where divisions were based on class or politics or tribe but rarely
on skin color _ for a country where they are a minority and where,
they say, race matters all too much. By Amy Waldman.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in `a' news category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TRIAL (Washington) _ A look at the political maneuvering
behind the scenes during the Senate trial among the three sets of
actors: the president, the Senate and the House Republican
managers. By Lizette Alvarez, John M. Broder and Katharine Q.
Seelye. -column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 3:15 p.m. ET in `w' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-VLADIVOSTOK (Vladivostok, Russia) _ These days, this
rough-and-tumble port city is the daffiest place in Russia. The
former mayor claims to have extrasensory powers. Local elections
have been invalidated 15 times. The mental hospital even released
some of its patients after squabbling officials allowed its budget
to run dry. So the news that the autocratic governor has received a
mysterious $1 million prize for his work as one of the world's
great leaders seemed par for the course. Michael R. Gordon. With
map.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-DRUGS (Washington) _ While U.S. officials admit privately
that by most statistical measures, the Mexican record on fighting
drugs looks especially bad this year, aides to President Clinton
say Mexican officials have been cooperating more closely with the
U.S. than ever before. By Tim Golden and Christopher S. Wren. With
map.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in `i' news category.)
</P>
<P>
   LIBYA-LOCKERBIE (Undated) _ U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
said Saturday that ``important progress'' has been made toward
persuading Libya to turn over two suspects wanted in the 1988
bombing of a Pan American flight over Lockerbie, Scotland, that
killed 270 people. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in `i' news category.)
