<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds have good shot at vying in Central
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since being eliminated by Atlanta in the 1995 NLCS,
the Cincinnati Reds are an aggregate 18 games below .500, have
finished a combined 40 games out of first place and suffered the
ignominy of every Marge Schott punchline that Jay Leno has dished
out. The Big Dead Machine.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in a spring that finds Schott finally on her way out, the
Reds open camp this week with a lighter step. The arrivals of Greg
Vaughn and Denny Neagle have given the Reds a chance to improve
immediately. And in the tepid NL Central, a little improvement can
go a long way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry Larkin called me right away,'' Vaughn said after
arriving from San Diego, ``and said he was trying to get out of
there until he found out I was coming. Now, he's happy.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, an infield with Pokey Reese at second and Aaron Boone
at third is no knee-buckler to the rest of the league. And the Reds
are already shamelessly milking 1999 prospects for more than
they're worth. During the news conference welcoming Vaughn, general
manager Jim Bowden four times held up a placard for the TV cameras
with a phone number for ticket orders.
</P>
<P>
   But those seeking a darkhorse for postseason could do far worse.
Vaughn gives Cincinnati the cleanup hitter it has long lacked: No
Red has had a 100-RBI season in nine years. Neagle teams with Pete
Harnisch (14-7 last year) to anchor an improved rotation that
includes Brett Tomko and Steve Avery.
</P>
<P>
   And competition is strong enough in the field that four
positions are unsettled: Hal Morris and Sean Casey vying for first
base, Jeffrey Hammonds and Mike Cameron in center, Michael Tucker
and Dmitri Young in right and Brian Johnson and Eddie Taubensee at
catcher. Depth does not necessarily equal strength, but there is
more talent here than there has been in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   WELCOME TO SUDS CITY
</P>
<P>
   Bill Campbell, just hired on as Milwaukee's new pitching coach,
thought he had a problem with ear-wax buildup when told how many
complete games the Brewers threw in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two complete games? For the whole season?'' he asked. ``That
can't be right.''
</P>
<P>
   Those two games were the lowest total in National League
history. Campbell should also know that Brewer starters made it
through the seventh inning just 42 times and nine of those games
belonged to Jeff Juden, who was dumped in early August. What of
one-time ace Cal Eldred? He is coming off his second surgery in
four years and does not figure to break camp with the club.
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado right-hander Kevin Ritz, recovering from rotator-cuff
surgery performed last June 23, threw from a mound for the first
time last week but cannot predict if he will be able to pitch this
season. ... Trevor Hoffman, put off by the player exodus in San
Diego, has upped his contract demands. After nearly agreeing to a
three-year, $15 million offer after the season, he is now seeking
four years at $32 million, saying, ``If they can trade a 50-homer
guy (in Greg Vaughn), they can trade a 50-save guy.'' ... Former
Brave Paul Byrd opens Philadelphia's camp as a member of the
rotation, after a superb 5-2 record and 2.29 ERA in eight starts as
a Phillie. But suspicions abound. ``You don't pick up 20-game
winners off the waiver wire,'' manager Terry Francona said. . . .
Pittsburgh again asks Bill Mazeroski to come to spring training to
show the Pirates what a glove is for. The Pirates committed 95
infield errors last year, including 45 at shortstop. Mazeroski led
the NL in assists nine years and turned more double plays than
anyone in history, 1,706.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
