<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to build an NBA champ
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The moves that could determine the viable championship
contenders were not necessarily the ones that brought the big
names. Talent wins in the NBA, but the clubs that understood the
value of acquiring complementary help are the ones that bear
watching.
</P>
<P>
   Cases in point: For all Michael Jordan did in carrying the Bulls
to six titles in eight years, there was a Horace Grant or a Dennis
Rodman to solidify things. With Magic Johnson's Lakers, he had Kurt
Rambis or A.C. Green. Larry Bird had Dennis Johnson with the
Celtics. Isiah Thomas' Pistons had Vinnie Johnson. When Houston and
Hakeem Olajuwon captured successive titles (1994, '95), there was
Robert Horry or Sam Cassell.
</P>
<P>
   This year, many teams added complementary help. But four clubs
picked up a star and the kind of unsung help that makes champions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Atlanta. The Hawks filled a need at small forward by signing
free agent LaPhonso Ellis. But the acquisition of backup power
forward Grant Long also was significant. Long's allow-no-layups
mentality and hustle give the Hawks a physical edge it has not had
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   He's a player who flourishes without needing the ball. He simply
goes and gets loose balls and rebounds. No doubt he pushes starter
Alan Henderson in practice and at times will challenge him for
minutes in games.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important is Long's tough-guy attitude, which
permeates the club. It is an incalculable intangible.
</P>
<P>
   _ Houston. Trading for Scottie Pippen elevated the Rockets to
bona fide challengers, but signing Antoine Carr away from Utah
could keep them there. When he gets healthy, Carr's playoff
experience, low-post scoring, rebounding and shot-blocking will be
big.
</P>
<P>
   With Utah, Carr helped drive the Jazz to successive NBA Finals
by relieving and playing alongside Karl Malone. At 6-foot-9, 260
pounds, Carr plays center and power forward. He's the kind of
veteran help greatly needed to back up Hakeem Olajuwon and Charles
Barkley _ both still capable, but both aging.
</P>
<P>
   _ Phoenix. It'll reveal itself one day that losing Antonio
McDyess to Denver was the best thing that could have happened to
the Suns, because they replaced him with free-agent Tom Gugliotta,
who is a better, more consistent all-around player.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet for run-and-gun Phoenix was inking former Chicago
Bull center Luc Longley. At times, he looked awkward and in the way
in the Bulls' rhythmic triangle offense. But he was the big banger
in the middle that was desperately needed.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have been a doughnut team for a long time. Longley
fills that void. Plus, if he was paying attention while riding
Jordan's coattails, he brings championship know-how.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sacramento. The Kings have the potential finally to rid
themselves of the perpetual-loser tag hung on them over the years.
That's the magnitude of power forward Chris Webber, who was traded
there from Washington for, in essence, guard Mitch Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   But the reason Webber stands to return to all-star form, and
Sacramento has playoff aspirations, is the signing of free-agent
center Vlade Divac. Webber seldom has played with a center who can
pass or who can play on the perimeter as Divac can. That gives the
skilled Webber inside room to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Divac has vast playoff experience, including the 1992 NBA
Finals with the Lakers. His skill, experience and unselfishness
will not make Sacramento the kings of the West, but he'll help them
rise.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
