<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kings' Williams shining early at the point
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's early, yes, probably too early, to even get into
assessing the league's top rookie talent. But Sacramento point
guard Jason Williams has been so solid and so spectacular in his
first NBA week that he's hard to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   In four games going into the weekend, Williams outplayed No. 2
pick Mike Bibby of Vancouver and Phoenix all-star Jason Kidd,
scoring more than 20 points twice _ all the while doing so in
fashion that sparked memories of Isiah Thomas, Nate Archibald and
other ``small'' playmakers.
</P>
<P>
   That he is a flashy white player from West Virginia with an
inner-city game adds to the intrigue. And so, he has the nickname
``White Chocolate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Williams) is just so creative,'' Kings coach Rick Adelman
said. ``He's quick as a cat, tough as nails, and he's not cocky but
extremely confident.''
</P>
<P>
   He has another distinction. Williams is the only player in the
NBA to have thrown a touchdown pass to Minnesota Pro Bowl receiver
Randy Moss. Williams and Moss attended DuPont Junior High School in
Belle, W.Va., with Williams serving as quarterback and captain in
the eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moss was the best everything I've ever seen,'' Williams said.
``He could do everything.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems that the same could be said for Williams, who committed
to basketball only in high school. In college, he ended up getting
kicked off the Florida team for violating team rules, which later
was learned to be for smoking marijuana. So, it's a scary prospect
that Vernon ``Mad Max'' Maxwell plans to be a mentor of sorts for
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay away from all the B.S. because it's easy to get into in
the NBA,'' Maxwell said he told Williams, 23. ``I'm not going to
let him get into anything, because I've been there and done that.''
</P>
<P>
   And then some.
</P>
<P>
   CAN'T BEAT 'EM? BUY 'EM
</P>
<P>
   After the Charlotte Hornets cut rapper/producer Percy Miller _
better known as Master P one of his NBA clients made it clear that
his agent had other options. Not playing for other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, he could go straight to the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a year or so,'' Boston's Ron Mercer said, ``he might just
buy a team. I wouldn't put it past him.''
</P>
<P>
   With another profitiable yea, Miller could add to the $56
million he made last year with the release of his final CD and
producing several groups. But he loves the NBA and plans to stay
close to it through clients Mercer and Derek Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   Here's a list of the top salaries that players will make after
losing three months of the season to the lockout. Seems that some
guys aren't hurting too much.
</P>
<P>
   1. Patrick Ewing, Knicks: $11.1 million
</P>
<P>
   2. Shaquille O'Neal, Lakers: $9 million
</P>
<P>
   3. David Robinson, Spurs: $8.9 million
</P>
<P>
   4. Kevin Garnett, Timberwolves: $8.4 million
</P>
<P>
   5. Alonzo Mourning, Heat: $7.88 million
</P>
<P>
   6. Juwan Howard, Wizards: $7.88 million
</P>
<P>
   7. Hakeem Olajuwon, Rockets: $7.77 million
</P>
<P>
   8. Scottie Pippen, Rockets: $6.6 million
</P>
<P>
   9. Larry Johnson, Knicks: $6.1 million
</P>
<P>
   10. Chris Webber, Kings: $6 million
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee guard Ray Allen. The rising star saved more than $3
million by negotiating his own six-year, $71-million contract
extension with the Bucks. Why use an agent when the system in place
dictates the maximum a player can receive?
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Charles Barkley. It took Sir Sap exactly two games to
berate a fan with expletives. In an otherwise successful campaign
to win back the fans, Barkley _ as usual _ comes off as vulgar.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTABLE
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I had Charlotte or the Dairy Queen in Sheboygan Falls.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Joe Wolf on his employment options when he signed with the
Hornets
</P>
<P>
   ``If losing means that we saved the season, traded off on a few
issues, protected free agency and most of the ``Larry Bird''
exception, then I can live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ NBA Players Association head Billy Hunter on whether his side
lost in the protracted lockout
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told myself that I was going to go work out hard, do it
and then see the scale and not see progress. Then I get low again
and feel like I'm wasting my time.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sacramento's 303-pound Oliver Miller on his weight struggles
</P>
