<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUBURN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Controversy over football dogs Auburn
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. _ To its loyal followers, Auburn _ both the town
and the university _ is not a location on a map but a place in the
heart. That is why the students, faculty, alumni and townspeople
who share this beloved space are often referred to as ``the Auburn
family.''
</P>
<P>
   But today the heart of Auburn is heavy and the family, to put it
charitably, is dysfunctional.
</P>
<P>
   When the school announced on Feb. 5 that it would pay $500,000
rather than play a football game with Florida State on Sept. 2, the
criticism of Auburn came quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The ACC called Auburn's actions ``reprehensible'' and suggested
that its members might not play the school in any sport in the
future. Newspaper columnists from New York to Los Angeles
challenged Auburn's institutional integrity. Talk shows questioned
the school's courage, suggesting that its battle cry of ``War
Eagle'' be replaced with ``War Chicken.'' Even the Wall Street
Journal weighed in negatively on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the nation this controversy will quickly disappear.
But for Auburn and its people, the Florida State flap is just the
latest in a string of embarrassing episodes brought about by its
football program.
</P>
<P>
   From the arrest last spring of wide receiver Robert Baker on a
cocaine possession charge, to the sudden and controversial
resignation of football coach Terry Bowden in October, to this
latest controversy, the students and supporters of this university
have been hammered with a litany of bad headlines over the past 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I talk to and the e-mail I receive basically ask
one thing,'' Lee Davidson, the editor of the Auburn Plainsman, the
student newspaper said. ``People just want to know when all this is
finally going to end.''
</P>
<P>
   On campus, there is resentment that the bad news created by the
football team continues to overshadow an impressive year in Auburn
athletics. The men's basketball team was 23-1 and ranked No. 3
going into Saturday's game with Alabama. The baseball team is
ranked in the top five. The women's basketball team is 18-5 and
headed to another NCAA Tournament. The swimming program is among
the best in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But around the state, the conversation about Auburn continues to
focus on a football program in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come to Auburn, you understand what the situation
is,'' said Casey Dunn, a senior catcher on the baseball team.
``They (football) put 85,000 people in the seats. We don't. I can't
complain about the way we are treated.''
</P>
<P>
   Other students are not as forgiving when they see the kind of
money being shelled out to fix football's self-imposed problems.
The $500,000 Auburn paid to Florida State could grow to $1.8
million if the ACC sues to recover lost television revenues.
Bowden's settlement with Auburn will pay him $620,000 in cash plus
other benefits. Two other former coaches, Pat Dye and Wayne Hall,
remain on the payroll (at over $100,000 each) for duties that are
vague at best.
</P>
<P>
   ``They spend money for football, for cleaning up football
messes, and we can't even get help for new wrestling mats,'' said
Chad Weaver, a sophomore on Auburn's club-level wrestling team.''
</P>
<P>
   This latest controversial episode also reopens an ongoing
discussion over who, exactly, is in charge of the Auburn athletics
department.
</P>
<P>
   David Housel, Auburn's highly-respected athletics director, has
been taking the lion's share of the heat over what he called ``an
institutional decision'' not to play the game with Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Auburn University President William Muse stepped
forward and said he supported Housel's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done the right thing because he's weighed all the factors
involved,'' said Muse. ``I have a great deal of respect for David.
I feel very strongly about him as a person and an administrator.''
</P>
<P>
   While Housel is the point man and receives strong support from
alumni, there is growing concern that the major decisions
concerning the school's athletics department are being made an hour
south of here, in the Montgomery offices of Bobby Lowder.
</P>
<P>
   Lowder, a multimillionaire banker, is without question the most
powerful man on the Auburn board of trustees and, say his critics,
is not bashful about using that power. He was the driving force
that brought Pat Dye to Auburn as head coach in 1981. He was
instrumental in hiring Bowden in 1993 and, if you believe his
critics, he was the man who told Bowden he would not be back in
1999, prompting the mid-season resignation. Lowder, contacted at
his office Friday, still denies he forced Bowden out.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that without Lowder's backing, both financial
and personal, Auburn would not have been able to lure Tommy
Tuberville away from Ole Miss to be its new coach. There has been
strong speculation on campus and around the SEC that Lowder
promised Tuberville last November that if he came to Auburn, he
would not have to play the Florida State game. Then Lowder left it
to Housel to do the dirty work.
</P>
<P>
   Lowder strongly denies that he had any hand in Auburn's decision
to pull out of the Florida State game.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the decision was basically made when Terry (Bowden)
resigned,'' said Lowder. ``Bobby Bowden (the Florida State coach)
said then he didn't want to play the game. In retrospect, maybe
that's when we should have done it. But David Housel's a nice guy
and he attempted to work through channels and get them (Florida
State) another opponent. But I agreed with it then and I agree with
it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowder denies that he is micromanaging the Auburn athletics
department and says his critics are a handful of academics who
don't like his management style, which he admits can be abrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a business worth about $10 billion,'' said Lowder. ``I
don't have time to manage the athletic department.''
</P>
<P>
   Some alumni, however, are growing increasingly uneasy with the
soap-opera that continues to surround this athletics program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an Auburn loyalist but I'm not a blind loyalist,'' said
Toby Propst of Atlanta, Auburn class of '57. ``I'm going to
withhold my judgement until I get all the truth and I haven't heard
it yet. But there are a lot of us who really wonder who's running
the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for nine months in the newspaper business, Housel has
spent the last 33 years on the Auburn campus. After graduating from
Auburn 1969, he worked his way from the athletic ticket office, to
sports information director, to athletics director in 1994. He is
the definitive ``Auburn man'' whose love of the university has
never been questioned, even by his critics.
</P>
<P>
   Housel's supporters feel he has been left out on a limb to take
the heat on issues like the Florida State decision and others that
are beyond his control. Given all the sins of the football program
over the past 12 months, they are afraid that Housel is going to be
offered up as a sacrificial lamb to calm the alumni.
</P>
<P>
   Both Lowder and Muse said Friday that they support Housel.
</P>
<P>
   Housel understands the concerns of the Auburn faithful and asks
for patience. He is convinced there are better days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand (why people are upset) because I want
something nice to happen to Auburn and the Auburn people deserve
it,'' said Housel. ``Obviously, we've taken some PR hits. We intend
to survive and carry on and go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning heals a lot of wounds and with Tuberville, Auburn should
win. The opening game of the 1999 season, now with I-AA Appalachian
State, is 201 days away. For Housel and others who love Auburn, it
can't come soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Auburn people are very passionate about their school and
they want to see the athletic program and the football team do what
they should,'' said Housel. ``That's one of the things that makes
this place special.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
