<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Karl, Bucks try razzle-dazzle
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Don't bet against George Karl leading the Bucks into
the playoffs this abbreviated season. Karl's innovative style and
combustible personality always give his teams a chance for success.
</P>
<P>
   Karl's latest gimmick? In a victory over Charlotte, he played
Glenn Robinson at center against Derrick Coleman. Karl's
justification: ``It worked, didn't it?
</P>
<P>
   They're calling it the micro brew in Milwaukee and Robinson is
happy. ``It's given me a chance to work on a bigger guy, drive him
to the hole, maybe make my jump shot easier. It gives me a chance
to mix up my game offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   More good news for the Bucks was Ray Allen's decision to extend
his contract with them and the apparent agreement of point guard
Terrell Brandon to do the same, saying ``I'll take care of my
contract at the end of the year. The starting five other than
myself are under contract for three or four years. That's a plus
for the franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bucks now look a little better after the flip-flop draft
deal from 1996 when they gave up Stephon Marbury, but traded him
for the rights to Allen and Andrew Lang.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, Allen paid Johnnie Cochrane $500 an hour to
negotiate his $70 million deal with owner Herb Kohl, the U.S.
senator.
</P>
<P>
   YOU HAVE THE TIME?
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Anderson likes young Paul Pierce so much he's willing to
give him the watch off his wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him early in camp that if he wins Rookie of the Year,
I'll give him my Rolex watch,'' Anderson said. ``He's all revved up
about it. And every game I see him, it looks more and more like I'm
about to give it up, right?'' ... The Celtics not only beat Miami
108-101, they made an enemy of Pat Riley. After Terry Porter made
two free throws to get Miami within 104-99 with 10.8 seconds left,
Rick Pitino called a time out. As he and the Celtics were in their
huddle, Riley stood apart from his team and stared at them. Tim
Hardaway told Celtic players he and the Heat are going to remember
that time out. ... Boston's Dwayne Schintzius missed two games with
a broken nose, then re-broke it in warmups in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   PROBLEM SOLVED
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell's injury may give Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy
the opportunity to use him as the club's six man. Van Gundy was
considering that in pre-season. When Sprewell comes back from a
stress fracture in his right heel, he will need to play his way
back into the rotation, anyway. ... There was some outrage in New
York when the NBA rescinded Alonzo Mourning's opening-game
suspension stemming from a fight in the playoffs.
Mourning-antagonist Larry Johnson couldn't complain, though. The
league refunded about $80,000 it took from him after the incident.
... When the Nets' Jayson Williams shot 3-for-6 Thursday in a loss
to the Bucks, it ended two straight games without a hoop from the
center who broke his nose in Atlanta. He was 0-for-12 in that span.
</P>
<P>
   A DEARTH AT CENTER
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards are using a center-by-committee with three
offensively challenged players _ Terry Davis, Ben Wallace and Otis
Thorpe. That puts a lot of pressure on guards Rod Strickland and
Mitch Richmond. Washington wants to bring up Gheorghe Muresan, but
must wait at least two more weeks to see if Muresan is healthy
enough to even run down the court. Muresan had back surgery in the
offseason to relieve pressure from his spine. A fourth center,
Lorenzo Williams, is out for the season with stress fractures in
both feet.
</P>
<P>
   LAYUPS
</P>
<P>
   Life's a lot quieter on the road for the new Bulls, said
assistant coach Bill Cartwright: ``It was great. You just come in
and walk right to your room.'' ... After the Pistons beat the
Pacers, Detroit's Jerry Stackhouse was defiant. ``They haven't won
anything yet. The Pacers are just like us. Everybody acts like they
won it last year because Chicago is no longer in the fold.'' ...
Larry Bird also is unhappy with the Pacers. ``It's not good ...
when you start out like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
