<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barkley will delay surgery
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Make no mistake, Charles Barkley is hurting, but he
says he can deal with it. Swelling in his left knee convinced him
to get an MRI that revealed a partial tear of his medial meniscus.
Anti-inflammatory medication and some treatment should allow him to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the injury, Barkley has proceeded with business as
usual. Diagnosed on Tuesday, he went through the full shoot-around
Wednesday morning and played 36 minutes against the Kings, scoring
16 points with 16 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``My knee is going to be sore,'' Barkley said. ``That's just
something I can't worry about anymore. It affects me, obviously. I
missed some shots I normally wouldn't miss because I can't explode
like I wanted to. But we made a decision to delay the surgery so I
can't complain about it. I just have to play through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said Dr. James Andrews of Hughston Clinic is among those
telling him to hold off on surgery. ``I'm going to try to play for
the next couple weeks and hopefully, I won't need surgery,''
Barkley said. ``I think I can play with the pain. I just want to
make sure it's not going to get worse. Pain I can
</P>
<P>
   deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   AW, POOR SHAQ
</P>
<P>
   Through Thursday, the Lakers are 33-21 with Shaquille O'Neal out
of the lineup, a .611 winning mark. With him in the lineup, they
are 87-28, .756. ``Nobody's going to feel sorry for us, not our
enemies, not our fans,'' Coach Del Harris said after O'Neal
suffered his latest injury in the second quarter of the Lakers'
victory over Denver on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's lower-stomach muscle pull is similar to common injuries
suffered by hockey players. Hawks assistant trainer Pete Radulovic,
who worked in that capacity for the L.A. Kings, says the only sure
fix is surgery.
</P>
<P>
   WARRIOR DISSENSION
</P>
<P>
   Warriors coach P.J. Carlesimo had said before the season that he
thought depth would be the team's greatest strength. Instead, it's
a source of dissension.
</P>
<P>
   Center Erick Dampier, perhaps the least-vocal player on the
team, played only 20 minutes in a double-overtime loss to Dallas
and then played 21 against Seattle, then complained, ``I can't get
going by myself. The game is just starting. I've got to get in
there and break a sweat. In and out in five minutes, I don't think
you can get into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Delk, the team's most explosive scorer, played seven
minutes against Seattle. Jason Caffey, signed to a seven-year, $35
million contract, played 17 minutes. Donyell Marshall, last year's
starter at small forward, played six minutes, none in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   BETTYE FALK?
</P>
<P>
   Corliss Williamson lists Elbert Crawford as his agent. But every
decision goes through the Williamson &AMP; Son Janitorial Service in
Russellville, Ark. That's where Bettye Williamson presides as vice
president of the family-owned business. ``Mom is my real agent,''
Williamson says ``She's mom-slash-agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Mom won't deny it. ``The paperwork still goes through me,'' she
said. ``My husband teases me all the time. He says, 'When are you
going to let him grow up?' I say, 'Never.'''
</P>
<P>
   A TRUE JAIL BLAZER
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers have a young forward named Art Long on the injured
list who fits with the team's Jail Blazer image. Long, 26, is a CBA
veteran with time in France, Argentina and Portugal. Last summer,
he served 27 days in an Ohio jail for violating probation after
reaching a plea bargain in a domestic-violence incident involving
his girlfriend while he was on academic suspension from
U-Cincinnati. He had also been on three years' probation for
selling marijuana to an undercover cop. But wait, Long and Danny
Fortson were arrested as disorderly and intoxicated and punching a
police horse. They were acquitted. Maybe the horse had it coming.
</P>
<P>
   LAYUPS
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Buss, on making Del Harris a lame duck by not giving him
an extension on his contract, which runs out this season: ``It's
not a problem with me.''
</P>
