<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons focus on re-signing Bradford, Burrough
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like most NFL teams, the Falcons are moving
deliberately into the free-agent market, focusing first on
re-signing some of their own 11 unrestricted free-agent players.
</P>
<P>
   The first priority appears to be cornerback Ronnie Bradford, who
is considering a contract proposal by the Falcons after starting 10
regular-season games and the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Bradford came to Atlanta before the 1997 season having starting
just 15 of 41 games in three years with Denver and one with
Arizona, and has proved to be perhaps the team's greatest bargain
of the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries to his ribs, left knee and shoulder caused him to miss
10 of 35 starts in two seasons. But despite modest athletic
abilities, he has surpassed expectations playing opposite Pro Bowl
cornerback Ray Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   In two seasons, Bradford has 91 total tackles, 25 passes
defensed and seven interceptions in 30 regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   His base salary was $300,000 in 1997 and $450,000 last season.
</P>
<P>
   In talks early in the season, the Falcons were willing to nearly
double his salary but only wanted to sign him through 2000.
Bradford and his agent, Peter Schaffer of Denver, are believed to
be seeking a three-year deal that averages at least $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Schaffer wants to know how the Falcons will use Bradford, but
the team is having a tough time saying. Meanwhile, several teams,
including Cincinnati, have inquired about his client.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronnie has an interest in returning to the Falcons,'' Schaffer
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons also want to re-sign four-year reserve defensive end
John Burrough, who played last season on a one-year, $397,000
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Despite modest career numbers of 102 total tackles and 1.5
sacks, Burrough is drawing interest from several teams.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta also has shown interest in re-signing starting strong
safety William White, who will be 33 next season. His age works
against him, especially considering free safety Eugene Robinson
will be 36, and White is somewhat one-dimensional, as the team
replaced him in passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and Omar Brown, who played in just two of 16 games, are
the only safeties under contract.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve safety Devin Bush, the team's 1995 first-round draft
choice, has scheduled visits to St. Louis, Pittsburgh and the Jets,
and agreed to visit Washington, Chicago and Cincinnati. He started
most of his first three seasons before serving as a backup in
Atlanta last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Falcons) told us (Friday) they want him back,'' Bush's
agent, David Levine, said. ``It's been a sizzling market for Devin.
He would return if (the circumstances) were right, but I think it's
a longshot.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta officials have not yet inquired about quarterback Mark
Rypien.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons allowed Rypien, 36, to keep half the $400,000
signing bonus they gave him last season before he decided to sit
out the season because of family illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves said last week the team could be interested in
a quarterback like Rypien.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
