</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FREEAGENTS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL's '99 free agent crop thin
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For most of the first six years of free agency in the
NFL, too many personnel directors approached spring signing period
like those daredevil cliff divers of Acapulco: Jump first and deal
with the consequences later.
</P>
<P>
   However, as the market opened for business Friday, those general
managers were surveying the 1999 free-agent waters with
deliberation. Even franchises that would have been performing
free-agency half-gainers in other years were reluctant to stick
their toes in the surf this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this talent pool, there is no deep end,'' Green Bay general
manager Ron Wolf said. ``In the last couple years, most teams have
gotten smarter and concluded you're better off retaining your own
best players. You don't win with free agents. The teams that regard
it as a panacea get into trouble year after year.''
</P>
<P>
   Most personnel directors spent the days before Friday trying to
re-sign their potential defectors. On Thursday alone, clubs either
re-signed or applied ``franchise'' designations to seven players
who otherwise would have been included in the
Journal-Constitution's annual rating of the top 30 unrestricted
free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Several general managers noted that 61 percent of the 84 players
originally selected for the Pro Bowl game are still with the team
that drafted them. Only 28 Pro Bowl players, or 33 percent, came to
their current teams as free agents. Miami coach Jimmy Johnson
emphasized that only four Pro Bowl players changed teams in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos, who are an exception,
include 12 former free agents and two players acquired in trades
among their 22 starters. The standard in free-agency often has been
set by teams such as Carolina, which spent a record $27 million on
free agents in '98 and won only four games, and Washington, which
paid $16.4 million for defensive tackles Dana Stubblefield and Dan
Wilkinson but still rated only No. 28 against the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how few players perform as well with their new
teams as they did with their old ones,'' Cincinnati coach Bruce
Coslet said.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis general manager Bill Polian said, ``First off, the
cost of signing a player is prohibitive. And second, you are
severely punished if you make a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   One team that won't have to worry about salary-cap implications
is the expansion Cleveland Browns. The club spent just $18.06
million to acquire 37 players in Tuesday's allocation draft. Even
accounting for a rookie pool that probably will be in the $6
million range, the Browns are more than $30 million under the 1999
cap limit of $57.288 million.
</P>
<P>
   Team president Carmen Policy, whose cap manipulation with the
San Francisco 49ers was legendary, and director of football
operations Dwight Clark have made no pretense about their
intentions to corner the market. The Browns are hot on the trails
of such highly regarded players as defensive ends Chad Bratzke
(N.Y. Giants) and Derrick Alexander (Minnesota) and center Wally
Williams (Baltimore).
</P>
<P>
   ``They can go as high as they want to on a guy, blow everyone
else right out of the water,'' Giants general manager Ernie Accorsi
said.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans general manager Bill Kuharich said, ``The Browns can
drain the pool.''
</P>
<P>
   The Browns' bounty represents about one-fourth of the cap room
available in the league. The anticipated spending spree by a team
that some GMs joke should be called the ``Greens'' will further
deplete the pool already thinned by re-signings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every agent you talk to thinks he's taking his guys to
Cleveland, and every player you talk to has you believing he's on a
flight there tomorrow,'' Pittsburgh director of football operations
Tom Donahoe said. ``But they can't sign 400 players, you know?
Sooner or later, they run out of roster space or cap room.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Browns take five or six of the high-profile players out
of the market the effect might be an upgrading of lesser-talented
veterans. A quick survey on Friday indicated that some of the
players who were drawing the most early attention were veterans who
never have gone to a Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh strong safety and former Georgia Tech standout Lethon
Flowers already had six visits scheduled and turned down $2 million
a year to stay with the Steelers. The Falcons' Devin Bush, a former
starter used primarily as a nickel safety in '98, had at least five
teams inquire about him. Journeyman backup Rich Gannon of the
Chiefs, who has just 56 starts in 10 seasons, is the most ardently
pursued quarterback before signing with Oakland Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Teams will look at San Francisco wide receiver J.J. Stokes,
recall the colossal flop of former Dallas wide receiver Alvin
Harper a few years ago and back off. The 49ers vet has never been a
lead receiver and a team might be able to land just as good a
player, such as Washington wideout Leslie Shepherd, for a cheaper
price.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're seeing so far,'' agent Eric Metz said. ``The
midlevel players are the ones getting the early action.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
