<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL's `Jackie Robinson'
 &HT;    By Jeff Schutlz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NHL's march to the 20th century continues.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 13 blacks among the NHL's some-700 players this
season, including 10 currently on rosters. Folks, that represents a
record high.
</P>
<P>
   Racism? No. Although Willie O'Ree, the NHL's first black player,
in 1958, said he encountered racist remarks from fans and opposing
players on the ice, he never got the feeling from teammates he
wasn't wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call me the Jackie Robinson of hockey,'' said O'Ree, now
63, ``but I didn't have to put up with the racism Jackie put up
with when he was playing in the Southern states. Sure, some things
were said by some fans. But I was prepared for it. I was a black
boy living in a white area. Ninety-seven percent of my friends were
white. I was the only black on a number of the athletic teams I
played on. But hockey was my love.''
</P>
<P>
   Those last few words are seldom spoken by blacks in North
America, but O'Ree believes the situation is changing. He was in
Atlanta last week to help start the Atlanta Thrashers'
street-hockey program. Two dozen African-American youths held
hockey sticks and slapped around a ball at the Warren Boys &AMP; Girls
clubs, getting instruction from team officials and O'Ree, who is
the director of youth development for the NHL's diversity task
force.
</P>
<P>
   O'Ree was hired last year by commissioner Gary Bettman. Bryant
McBride, the NHL's vice president of business development, avoided
taking a shot at past league executives, such as former
commissioner John Ziegler, but he said, ``Gary Bettman wanted to
grow the league in all areas, at all levels. We saw Willie as an
important piece of that puzzle. The reason we're doing things like
this is to give kids the opportunity. If, as a byproduct, the Tiger
Woods of hockey comes along, wonderful. It would be the ultimate if
an inline skater from our program put on ice skates one day and
made it to the NHL. Imagine what would happen if we had that one
breakthrough player, a 6-3, 210-pound linebacker type who decided
hockey was on his radar. That would change the game.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Ree played with 11 teams in six leagues before retiring in
1980. Only 45 games in parts of two seasons (two in 1958, 43 in
1960-61) came in the NHL with Boston, who integrated before the Red
Sox did with shortstop Pumpsie Green in 1959. After his final game
with the Bruins in '61, 30 years passed before he heard from an NHL
official.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you believe that?'' O'Ree said. ``Thirty years after I left
the league, I get a call from a gentleman in the NHL in 1991, and
he invites me to the All-Star game in Chicago. I said, `Why do you
want me?' and he started talking about how I was a pioneer and all
that. So my wife and I went, and we had a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the NHL created a diversity task force, in part
to help at-risk kids get access to ice hockey. McBride felt the
program needed ``a culminating event,'' so he called O'Ree in La
Mesa, Calif., and asked if he would lend his name to an annual
All-Star game for 10- to 12-year-old boys and girls. The fourth
Willie O'Ree All-Star weekend will be held Feb. 27-28 in
Washington. The next step was up to Bettman, who hired O'Ree as a
league employee last February.
</P>
<P>
   There was a 17-year lapse between the first black NHL player
(O'Ree) and the second (Mike Marson with Washington). But O'Ree
sees promise, pointing to long-time goalie Grant Fuhr of St. Louis,
as well as young players like Boston's Anson Carter and Edmonton's
Mike Grier.
</P>
<P>
   None of them had to overcome the obstacles O'Ree did. The New
Brunswick native lost vision in his right eye at the age of 18 when
he was hit by a puck in the juniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor told me I'd never play hockey again,'' O'Ree said.
``But that doctor didn't know what my dream was.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
