<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tampay Bay's Williams ready to bolt
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The pronouncement from former Georgia high school
football coach and insurance executive Art Williams that he will
sell the Tampa Bay Lightning if he can't bring in a partner soon
should not come as a great surprise. Aside from the Bolts'
projected financial losses of $20 million this season, Williams has
not dealt with the losing well. He fired general manager Phil
Esposito only two games into the season and has been bouncing off
the walls while Esposito's replacement, GM-coach Jacques Demers,
has preached patience with young players. Williams, who is used to
having total control and expecting quick results, increased the
Lightning's payroll and improved travel conditions, but the result
has been a seven-game losing streak and league-worst record of
11-37-4 going into Saturday's game against San Jose. The
near-20,000 seat Ice Palace is half empty for most home games.
Williams says he will keep the team if he can find an investor by
this summer. What he didn't say was that he hired an investment
firm in mid-December _ only seven months after purchasing the team
and Ice Palace for $117 million _ and didn't get a nibble for six
weeks. Many people think he already has decided to sell the team
and arena outright, even if at a loss. Williams admits he has
stayed away from home games, saying, ``I haven't been coming to
games recently for a simple reason _ this team broke my heart. ...
I couldn't have been happier the first month of the season _ then
the bottom fell out. I've been more upset with the constant losing
than all the money coming out of my wallet.'' But that has not sat
well with fans, one of whom told the Tampa Tribune: ``How does he
expect people to come out and support his team when he can't come
out and support it himself? Does he think he's the only one whose
heart is broken?'' Demers and assistant coach Rick Paterson blew up
at radio announcer Larry Hirsch in a staff meeting the other day
when Hirsch called the team ``a car with four dead tires'' and
suggested a return to two-a-day practices. No wonder Williams wants
out.
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina, still struggling at the gate, has hired Richard Petty
to do advertising spots going into next season. One commercial
depicts him driving a hot-rod Zamboni with forward Keith Primeau as
a passenger. ``I can't sell 'em on hockey, '' Petty said, ``but I
think I can slow 'em down enough so that, if they take a look at
hockey, they'll like it.'' . . . . Petr Nedved had 21 points in his
first 16 games as a Ranger but had only six points in the next 16.
... The potential sixth season in Pavel Bure's five-year, $47.5
million deal is at Florida's option. But there are incentives
within the deal that could switch it to Bure's option. He would
make $11 million in the 2004-05 season. ... Mario Lemieux made his
strongest statement yet about possibly heading a group to
purchasing the bankrupt Penguins, saying, ``We've been working
pretty hard the last couple of months to put some investors
together, not only to buy the team but to make sure it stays in
Pittsburgh.'' ... For what it's worth, Wayne Gretzky has the worst
plus-minus rating _ minus-14 _ on the Rangers' roster.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
