<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers close to sealing rink contract
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Contracts are still ``about a week away'' from being
signed, but Ice Forum president and founder Jack Burton
acknowledges that a deal to build the Thrashers their permanent
practice facility is close to completion. ``We're very glad to have
the Thrashers associated with us,'' Burton said. ``It's a great
match.'' The Thrashers will practice at the Ice Forum in Duluth,
one of four rinks owned by Burton. The facility currently has only
one sheet of ice, but Burton estimates that he will spend $3.2
million to build another rink and a 15,000-square-foot addition
that will house a locker room, training equipment and offices for
the team's coaches and general manager Don Waddell. The team's top
executives will keep their offices at CNN Center. Burton is
confident that the training facility and offices will be completed
by early August _ training opens Sept. 4 _ and the additional sheet
of ice possibly soon after. ``In the event the second sheet of ice
is not ready in time, they'll use the existing rink,'' Burton said.
Burton will recoup some of his investment with a long-term lease
with the Thrashers. He also said the deal will include ``some
promotional perks that are quite substantial,'' such as players
making personal appearances. ... Hoping to milk as much publicity
as possible out of the release of the team's jersey, the Thrashers
will unveil their togs at an event in March. Details have not been
completed. ... Before the start of a news conference the other day
to announce the team's street-hockey program at the Warren Boys and
Girls Club, an NHL official covered the ``Pro Player'' logo on
Willie O'Ree's polo shirt with black tape, so as not to upset
officials at Nike, the program's sponsors. ... Waddell is wearing
his new diamond-stuffed Stanley Cup ring, which is valued at
approximately $13,000. Waddell, who spent only one year with
Detroit, did not go to the White House with the Red Wings recently.
But he did go last year, when the team was honored for the title
the year before.RED LIGHT DISTRICT
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's attempts to market its scoring ``stars'' could be
hampered by a lack thereof. At the current pace, there will be only
two 50-goal scorers this season, the fewest in a full season since
1969-70, when no one scored that many in a 76-game season. The
current leaders and paces (through Feb. 10).
</P>
