<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLWEST14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Honeymoon (continued) in Nashville
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For a team that entered the weekend 11 games under
.500, things could be a lot worse in Nashville. The first of at
least three sellout crowds in a row watched the Predators lose to
Detroit the other night. Former Flames forward Curt Bennett said,
``I was at the game, and it was unbelievably loud, even though they
were losing.'' It doesn't hurt at the box office when consecutive
home games are scheduled against the Red Wings, the two-time
defending Stanley Cup champions; Pittsburgh, with Jaromir Jagr; and
the New York Rangers, with Wayne Gretzky. Just to add to the
goodwill with fans, the Predators announced they would not increase
ticket prices next season, although a price increase in a season or
two could end the honeymoon quickly. Nashville might be one of only
seven teams in the league to show a profit this season. On the ice,
the team sits near the bottom of the Western Conference standings
but remains within reach of a playoff berth. Forward Patrick Cote
said, ``I really can't imagine what that would be like. I know our
place would be absolutely rocking.''
</P>
<P>
   WILY COYOTES
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix officials are considering a plan to accept $10 million
in renovations at America West Arena rather than pursue a new home.
The arena, designed as a basketball-only facility, has
approximately 4,500 obstructed seats in a hockey setup. The
Coyotes' situation has become a source of irritation for Suns owner
and arena operator Jerry Colangelo, who lured the hockey team to
Phoenix from Winnipeg. Richard Burke has complained about lost
revenue and the poor ice quality at America West, putting more
pressure on Colangelo and the community to get something done.
Taxpayers have footed the bill for a new baseball stadium, and the
Arizona Cardinals have asked for a new stadium, so it might not be
the right political climate for the Coyotes to get a new venue
approved.
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago general manager Bob Murray is mum on rumors that have
him dealing forward Doug Gilmour to Buffalo. The Blackhawks signed
Gilmour as a free agent for $18 million over three years, but
Gilmour is struggling, and the team is in last place in the Central
Division. ``Trade rumors are part of the game,'' Gilmour said.
``But if you're asking me, 'Did I ask for a trade?' _ no.'' ... San
Jose's Mike Ricci on the team's 10-game, 17-day road trip: ``We
started (the season with two games) in Japan, and now we have this.
Maybe our last five games should be in Russia.'' ... After going
0-59-10 in games they trailed after two periods, St. Louis won
consecutive games with third-period comebacks over Florida (5-4)
and Tampa Bay (5-4). ... Detroit is in the middle of five games
against teams with losing records. Good thing: The Wings are 6-16-1
against opponents that are .500 or better. ... From Edmonton center
Doug Weight: ``My first full year, I had 74 stitches in my face,
one for every point I had. I went home for Christmas and had (sets
of) seven, seven and eight stitches in my face. My mom looked at me
and said, 'I don't think you should go back.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
