<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MARTIN-DAYTONA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SEASON HAS MARTIN GUNNING FOR DAYTONA 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Most years, seven victories and 22
top-five finishes would have earned a Nascar Winston Cup
championship for Mark Martin. But it wasn't enough in 1998, when
despite having the best season of his career, he was the runner-up
to Jeff Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Compare Martin's finishes with Gordon's last year, and one
statistic jumps off the page. On the circuit's restrictor-plate
races (the high-banked oval tracks at Daytona and Talladega) Martin
saw his championship hopes snagged by poor finishes.
</P>
<P>
   In the races at Daytona, Martin lost valuable points, placing
38th and 16th; at two races at Talladega, he finished 23d and 34th.
Gordon, on the other hand, had top-five finishes in three of the
four races at those tracks on the way to winning his third title in
four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a brand new car, a brand new team last year and that
showed,'' said Martin, who was also the Winston Cup runner-up in
1990 and 1994. ``It wasn't our fault on the big tracks. We got
caught up in a few wrecks and broke a valve spring one time. But
we've made great gains on the car this winter. Every year is a
learning experience, an evolution.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the green flag waves over the 41st running of the
Daytona 500, stock car racing's biggest event, and Martin, driver
of the Valvoline Ford Taurus, can get his season on track by
finishing up front on the 2.5-mile oval. He will roll off the
starting grid ninth while Gordon has the pole.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's 1999 season got off to a promising start last Sunday
when he drove down victory lane at Daytona for the first time in a
stock car after winning the Bud Shootout, a non-points race.
Martin's team owner, Jack Roush, hopes the recent breakthrough
victory is a sign of things to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark Martin deserved to win that championship'' Gordon said,
referring to last year's points race. ``He had a great season. He's
done everything he has ever been asked to do. Maybe it's his
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But he added that you still don't want Martin to beat
you.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to getting his car in tune during the off season,
Martin's mind is more at ease now and so is his heart. Last August,
his father, Julian Martin, whom he was very close to, his
stepmother and half-sister were killed when their private plane
crashed. The accident occurred in the middle of a heated Nascar
season, and Martin didn't miss a race. He soldiered on, won races
and managed to be the only car to challenge Gordon late in the
season. ``It was a tough year in a lot of ways,'' Martin said,
lowering his head. ``It was hard on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he wonders how he was able to continue on with the
season after plane crash. But anyone who has spent much time around
Martin knows that he is unflappable, his focus intensifies when he
is faced with adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the curse of my personality,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who is 5-foot-6-inches tall and weighs 150 pounds, is
not your typical stock car driver. He is most different when it
comes to his physical fitness. Martin is one of, if not the,
fittest drivers in Nascar. No barbecue for him, he prefers bagels.
His days often begin with a strenuous workout. His regimented
routine calls for him to wake up a 5:30 a.m. and to be in bed by 9
p.m. That's why, even at 40 years old, Martin does not think twice
about driving in a Busch series race the night before he climbs
into his Winston Cup ride.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's strategy for winning his first Daytona 500 is to drive
hard, drive smart and pray that nothing breaks. Daytona is one of
two tracks where Nascar requires carburetor restrictor plates to
slow the cars to protect drivers and fans. But the devices rob the
engine of almost half of its horsepower and makes the field
unnaturally even, keeping the cars close, which means that wrecks
are a virtual certainty.
</P>
<P>
   The situation makes patience a necessity. If a driver steps out
of one of the drafts at Daytona without another car to help, he
might drop 15 positions instead of advancing.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt, who won last year's Daytona 500, will start
Sunday's race from the fourth spot, the same place he started last
year. Once again, he showed why he is one of the favorites by
dominating his 125-mile qualifying race on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The other favorites: Gordon, who starts his bid for a third
straight title and fourth in five years; Bobby Labonte, who
dominated the restrictor-plate races last season and was the
pole-winner and second-place finisher in the Daytona 500 last year
and won the other 125-miler on Thursday; Rusty Wallace, who was
strong last week; Dale Jarrett, who is a two-time winner here;
Earnhardt's teammate Mike Skinner; Gordon's teammate Terry Labonte,
Bobby's older brother; and Tony Stewart, who will make his first
career start from the front row.
</P>
<P>
   There is a $1 million bonus that can be won by Jarrett, Gordon,
Terry Labonte, Spencer or Mayfield, the top-five finishers in last
fall's Winston 500 at Talladega. If any of those five win the race,
they will collect the bonus plus the $1.1 million winner's share of
the record purse, which exceeds $8 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget Martin, whose car was fifth fastest in
qualifying last weekend. But not everyone is convinced that Martin
has the car to win. When listing who he thought should be favored
for Sunday's race, Jeremy Mayfield, Wallace's teammate, omitted
Martin. ``I'm not sure about Mark,'' he said. ``He's been fast this
week, but there are a lot of cars faster than him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All you can do is give your very best,'' Martin said. ``In
racing, the result is uncontrollable. But the effort is
controllable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do it last year,'' Martin, shrugging his shoulders.
``I just hope we can be as blessed again and have the kind of
season we had in 1998.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
