<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4362 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-ART-4TA     02-13 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT BATTLE DEALT MEAGER SPOILS TO ALL SIDES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Ark., Texas, Ill., Miss., S.D., Conn., Wash., Ky.,
Utah, Mass., La., N.J., Iowa, Del., Ariz., Pa., Ohio, Calif.,
W.Va.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-AFTERMATH, IMPEACH-STARR,
IMPEACH-POLITICIANS, IMPEACH-SOCIETY, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON,
IMPEACH-REAX, IMPEACH-LEGACY-REVIEW, EDIT-IMPEACH-AFTERMATH,
DOWD-COLUMN, IMPEACH-LEGAL, IMPEACH-SAGES) 
(Eds: Note language in quoted material in 17th paragraph of 2nd
take, `We were shocked...'.) 
(jw) 
 This article was reported by Lizette Alvarez, John M. Broder and
Katharine Q. Seelye, and was written by Broder.  
  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, watched the Dec. 19
House vote to impeach President Clinton, and the vicious partisan
brawling that preceded it, with a sense of foreboding. Christmas
was still six days away, but the holiday season ended for her as
she followed the House proceedings from the living room of her home
in the coastal town of Falmouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that Christmas was over that day,'' Ms. Snowe, a
moderate, recalled on Friday after the Senate found Clinton not
guilty of the charges of perjury and obstruction of justice brought
by the House. She voted against both articles.
</P>
<P>
   Like other members of the Senate, she knew that Clinton's
conviction and removal from office were unlikely. With other
members of the Senate, she began immediately searching for a way to
avoid the political horrors of the House while carrying out their
constitutional duty.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the House voted to impeach Clinton, Ms. Snowe sat
down to sketch out her goals for the impending trial in the Senate:
bipartisanship, dignity, adherence to historical precedent and a
quick and fair conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers and advisers wanted much the same thing
as the Senate leadership and moderates like Ms. Snowe _ plus, of
course, acquittal by the widest possible margin. They also were
determined to demolish the charges brought by the House and to
portray the entire exercise as illegitimate and nakedly political.
</P>
<P>
   In a Senate that cherished bipartisanship far more than did the
fractious House, the White House lawyers and political strategists
knew that they faced uncertain terrain. It was unclear going into
the trial whether the president could depend on the support of all
the Democrats, some of whom had harshly criticized his behavior,
but it was also more possible to fashion a defense that would
appeal to independent-minded Republicans like Ms. Snowe.
</P>
<P>
   But White House expectations in late December and early January
were low. One senior White House official said at the time that he
expected the president would ultimately be found not guilty, but
not until after a long and gruesome trial lasting as long as six
months.
</P>
<P>
   The third set of actors in the Senate drama _ the House
prosecutors _ had a wholly different agenda. They wanted a full and
extended trial, with testimony from dozens of witnesses, ending in
the removal of the president. But they, too, had little hope of
getting their way in the notoriously self-important Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were entering alien territory,'' said Rep. Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., who led the 13 Republican House ``managers'' who
presented the case against the president.
</P>
<P>
   All three of the major players achieved some of their goals. The
Senate as an institution emerged less bloodied by the process than
the House, and fewer nerve endings were left raw from the political
conflict. The trial ended on Friday with handshakes across the
aisle and promises to work together on issues of policy from Social
Security to military spending.
</P>
<P>
   The president was found not guilty but hardly vindicated. Even
his most effective advocate before the Senate, former Sen. Dale
Bumpers, D-Ark., had described Clinton's behavior as
``indefensible, outrageous, unforgivable, shameless'' as the
president watched on a small television in his private study off
the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecution team walked away with the fewest spoils.
Their wish list of witnesses was whittled down to three _ Monica
Lewinsky, Vernon Jordan and Sidney Blumenthal _ and they appeared
on the Senate floor only as ephemeral two-dimensional figures on
television screens. The prosecutors managed to win only 45 votes to
convict the president on the first of two articles of impeachment
and 50 votes on the second. And they did little to repair the image
of the House Republicans as a group hellbent on embarrassing and
ejecting a popular president.
</P>
<P>
   None of the actors could claim victory after 13 months of
revelation and public revulsion. But the Constitution bore up well
under the strain, and the president and congressional leaders vowed
to try to forget the agony and the anger of the journey just ended.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a brief Rose Garden statement on Friday, called for
a time of ``reconciliation and renewal for America'' and indicated
he was prepared to forgive those who tried to get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, members traded congratulations on the floor and
said the trial might even have strengthened the institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we preserved the dignity of the Senate,'' said Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who voted to convict Clinton on both
impeachment charges. ``It ended as the founders intended it to.''
</P>
<P>
   Gathered with his prosecution team in the House Judiciary
Committee hearing room where the impeachment proceedings began last
fall, Hyde was bowed but not resentful. ``I have no regrets,'' he
said quietly.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone calls from jittery senators, haunted by the House
impeachment proceedings, followed Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the
majority leader, everywhere during the Christmas break. His cell
phone rang in the middle of the Cotton Bowl, where he sat with Sen.
Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, at his side. It rang as he bounced
his baby granddaughter on his knee at his son's house. It rang in
the car, in the office and at home in Pascagoula, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Lott spoke so often to Sen. Thomas Daschle, D-S.D., the minority
leader, that the two practically had a hot line.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators insisted to Lott that they wanted a short trial
with no witnesses. Others wanted a full trial with live testimony.
All of them fretted about the impact on the Senate, and they
wondered if they could trust each other _ Republicans and Democrats
_ to keep it civilized.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., called an old friend, Sen. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash., and one of Lott's confidants, who was heading to
Hawaii with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before you say anything, I know why you called,'' Lieberman
remembers Gorton saying. ``I was about to call you for the same
reason. We have got to start talking about how the Senate handles
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The conversation was the genesis of a plan that would set the
tone of cooperation that Lott and Daschle hoped to establish.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The details were in flux, but almost everyone agreed on the
goal: preserving the dignity of the Senate. Sen. Mitch McConnell,
R-Ky., said, ``Having a sense that the outcome was not in doubt, it
fell in two categories: Honor the Constitution and do as little
damage to the institution as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lieberman-Gorton dialogue had the quiet assent of Republican
and Democratic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The two, who talked five times a day over the holidays,
fashioned a plan that could perhaps avert a final vote on the
articles of impeachment by taking a test vote on the charges and
the evidence. The idea appealed to Lott, who found the idea of a
long trial with a slew of witnesses distasteful. ``He is a
realist,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate conservatives furiously rejected the proposal, and by
the time the new Senate reconvened the first week in January, the
plan was nearly doomed.
</P>
<P>
   At the first Republican caucus, conservatives refused to curtail
the trial in any way. ``People wanted a final vote on the articles,
even if it was a losing vote,'' said Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The trial would proceed, but first the two sides had to agree on
a framework.
</P>
<P>
   On. Jan. 7, a Thursday, Lott, Daschle and their lawyers tried to
work out a plan, but it foundered on the question of witnesses.
Republicans wanted the right to summon witnesses; Democrats wanted
none, or at most a sharply limited number.
</P>
<P>
   The next day 100 Democrats and Republican gathered in a
bipartisan caucus behind the closed doors of the ornate Old Senate
Chamber to salvage the process. Republicans were hoping the meeting
would soften Democrats, especially Daschle. Democrats were hoping
the conservative hard-liners would be moved by the history of the
moment and agree to their plan.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not until the very end of the caucus that a
breakthrough occurred.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing the two sides discuss their proposals for the
trial, Gramm stood up and called the two plans identical except for
the differences over witnesses. ``I rise today not as Massachusetts
man, or as a New Englander, but as American,'' Gramm said, quoting
Daniel Webster. He suggested that the Senate proceed with the
trial, postponing the question of which witnesses to call and how
many.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., agreed.
</P>
<P>
   With the liberal and the conservative in agreement, Lott seized
the moment. ``Let's put it in writing,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, in effect, put off the difficult question of witnesses
and began the historic proceeding with a unanimous 100-0 vote on
procedure. It was to be the last unanimous vote of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers and top political advisers were in a
grim mood on the morning of Dec. 19 as they gathered in the office
of John Podesta, the White House chief of staff. They knew that
later that day the House would approve two articles of impeachment
against the president, marking Clinton forever as only the second
American president to be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   But they were not prepared for the announcement that morning
from Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., who was the Speaker-designate,
before the first vote was tallied. He was quitting his post and
leaving the House because of reports of marital infidelities,
Livingston said, and he urged the president to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   The group in Podesta's office fell silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were shocked,'' said one senior member of the president's
legal team who was present. ``I felt, Jesus, we're at a point where
we're eating our own. It genuinely scared me. I was shaking. The
whole thing seemed to me to be very, very mean and very unstable.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's men decided that something had to be done, and
quickly, to stop what they feared might become an avalanche of
calls for Clinton to follow Livingston's lead and resign, as
Livingston had himself suggested in his stunning remarks on the
House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, White House press secretary, bolted into the Oval
Office and asked the president what he wanted to say. According to
Lockhart's handwritten notes of the conversation, Clinton wanted
his spokesman to immediately issue a statement urging Livingston to
reconsider. ``He's a decent guy and doesn't deserve it,'' Lockhart
remembers the president's saying to him about Livingston. ``The
politics of personal destruction has to stop here,'' the president
added.
</P>
<P>
   The shock waves of the Livingston resignation spread far beyond
the West Wing of the White House and had a sobering effect on
members of Congress of both parties who might have been
contemplating calling for Clinton to step down in the aftermath of
the impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of the entire government unraveling, very few members of
Congress joined a clamor for Clinton's resignation. The president
had dodged one of the most potentially hazardous moments of the
entire impeachment battle.
</P>
<P>
   But still the trial lay ahead. Clinton's lawyers regrouped after
the impeachment vote and began to plot a strategy for defeating the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   There was agreement within both the legal and political councils
of the White House that they had botched the handling of the House
debate, underestimating the resolve of House Republicans and giving
insufficient attention to answering the legal charges raised by
Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   They vowed not to make that mistake again before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we thought going into the trial was that we had to
aggressively make the case that the charges brought by the House
managers were a house of cards, and that's exactly what we did,''
said one senior White House official.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Just before New Year's, the 13 House managers sat in the
Judiciary Committee conference room, which they had labeled ``the
War Room,'' with doughnuts and coffee spread across the oversized
table. They were almost giddy about their new role as prosecutors,
picturing an expansive courtroom drama, a full trial with witnesses
galore and fiery cross-examinations.
</P>
<P>
   Although almost everyone in Washington was predicting that it
would be impossible to garner a two-thirds majority to convict the
president in the Senate, Hyde and his colleagues had confidence in
their case. They were less certain of the Senate terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate did not want salacious testimony brought to its
hallowed chamber, the managers well knew. While the article of
impeachment charging the president with perjury was mired in the
lurid details of who touched whom and where, the managers, led by
Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., saw greater promise in the obstruction
case, the impeachment article that had drawn a weaker vote from
their House colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   They hoped to call 15 to 18 witnesses, a roster that included
the stars as well as the bit players: The videographer who had
taped the president's deposition in the Paula Jones lawsuit, an
expert on sexual harassment, Secret Service agents, a judge and
even Dick Morris, the sometime presidential adviser. ``We were
being very generous in those days,'' Rep. Ed Bryant, R-Tenn.,
recalled wistfully in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   But word came, indirectly and almost immediately, that Lott was
unenthusiastic about witnesses. He was even considering ending the
trial before a vote on the final articles, something being floated
in his caucus.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first sign of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, Daschle kept the White House informed of
his strategy for handling the proceeding and keeping Democrats
united, but did not seek advice from the president or his advisers.
</P>
<P>
   He made it clear to Clinton that he should keep his distance
because any heavy-handed efforts to lobby senators would be seen as
tampering with the jury and would surely backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made mention of the fact at some point that I didn't want
calls made to senators,'' Daschle said on Friday. ``I just felt
there had to be some separation here and that lobbying in this case
would be unseemly, and they respected that. I don't know of one
call that the White House made to one senator.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said they took Daschle's advice and
deliberately avoided inserting themselves into Senate
deliberations. But there was a constant stream of contacts between
top White House political aides under the direction of Steve
Ricchetti, the deputy chief of staff, and Daschle and his aides.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also spoke frequently with a handful of Democratic
senators to ``take their pulse,'' as one aide put it. Clinton's
closest contacts were with Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey,
Sen. Christopher Dodd of Connecticut, Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa and
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president wasn't disengaged or oblivious,'' said a senior
White House staffer who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
``Everyone knew what he thought and wanted. This wasn't a blind
date. But everyone knew this was out of our control. We were at
best in the back seat with someone else driving.''
</P>
<P>
   For the trial to be legitimate, the House managers insisted,
there had to be witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Arguing the managers' case for witnesses at a bipartisan meeting
in one of Lott's suites, Hyde offered numbers from ``15 to 18.''
Sen. Joseph Biden, a D-Del., remembers feeling his jaw drop,
especially when the managers mentioned that they were thinking of
calling the five Jane Does _ women linked to the president whose
uncorroborated stories were not part of the public impeachment
record.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us in private thought it was even remotely possible to
do this,'' Biden said. His Republican colleagues agreed, for the
most part, and sent word to Lott.
</P>
<P>
   A second meeting followed, this time exclusively Republican, to
hammer home the point. Sen. Jon Kyl of Arizona, Sen. Arlen Specter
of Pennsylvania and Sen. Mike DeWine of Ohio subtly suggested a
pared-back list.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson, one of the House managers, said the senators had a
firm position: ``You can ask for whatever witnesses that you want
to, but you are going to lose votes with some of the moderates if
you have an expanded list,'' Hutchinson recalls being told by
Senate colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The magic figure, Hyde said, boiled down to the famous ``pitiful
three.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Rogan, D-Calif., angrily suggested a protest.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't they just walk out of the Senate chamber, their legal
pads and files under their arms? He was talked out of it. Other
members were upset, briefly, with Hyde, believing he had acquiesced
too easily to the Senate's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   But as the managers debated who should make the final cut,
Senate Republicans privately worried whether any of the witnesses,
all of them presidential allies, would serve the House well.
</P>
<P>
   The first interview with Ms. Lewinsky was a success of a sort,
said Bryant, who had been chosen to preview her testimony because
he ``could be her father.'' Bryan found her chatty, open and blunt.
The prosecutors decided to depose her.
</P>
<P>
   But she was not nearly as open the second time around. She
measured her words carefully. Her lawyers nudged her when they
wanted her to clam up, Hyde said. ``I realized very quickly in the
deposition that it wasn't going to happen,'' he said. ``She didn't
tell her story like she could have.''
</P>
<P>
   After the constrained and careful testimony of Jordan and
Blumenthal, any hope for live witnesses vanished. The Senate had
seen the videotapes. They did not want to see anymore.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers saw their task was not simply to plant
reasonable doubt in the minds of the Senate jury, but to undermine
what one White House official called the ``unreasonable certitude''
of the House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   And the lawyers did so, in excruciating and sometimes tedious
detail, pointing out the House managers' mischaracterization of
testimony or logical fallacies. David Kendall, the president's lead
private lawyer, obliterated one of the prosecutors' assertions when
he demonstrated that Jordan could not have taken steps to further
Ms. Lewinsky's job search after learning of his appearance on the
witness list for the Jones suit against the president. As Kendall
informed the Senate with delight, `` Jordan was high over the
Atlantic in an airplane on his way to Amsterdam'' when a federal
judge entered an order allowing Ms. Lewinsky to be called as a
witness and could therefore not have been aware of her status.
</P>
<P>
   But the impeachment trial was never solely about facts and dates
and inconsistent memories. It was a supremely political event as
well, and the White House had to manage that aspect of the case
while not appearing to be tampering with the president's jury.
</P>
<P>
   A pivotal moment came on Friday, Jan. 22. Lanny Breuer, a lawyer
in the White House counsel's office who has been one of the central
figures in the president's defense, was seated at the defense table
on the floor of the Senate when Lawrence Stein, the White House's
chief legislative lobbyist, slipped into the chamber and handed him
a note.
</P>
<P>
   The news was almost too good to be believed: Sen. Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., the influential custodian of Senate history and no friend
of Clinton's, was going to sponsor a motion to dismiss the
impeachment charges. Byrd had not earlier indicated how he would
vote on the charges. Byrd's defection would be a disaster for
Clinton; with his support for dropping the charges, the Democratic
front against conviction would remain solid.
</P>
<P>
   Breuer passed on the note to his colleagues at the defense table
_ Charles F.C. Ruff, Kendall, Greg Craig, Nicole Seligman and
Cheryl Mills. There were smiles of silent satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the beginning of the end,'' a senior White House
official said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it was. Although the Byrd motion failed 54-46 on Jan. 27,
only one Democrat voted with the Republicans. It was certain from
that point forward that the Republicans would never amass the 67
votes necessary to convict Clinton and remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   To greater and lesser degrees, the three sides in this historic
impeachment trial _ the Senate, the House prosecutors and the White
House _ accomplished their missions.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, which never wanted an impeachment trial, was not
riven by bitter partisanship, like the House, thanks largely to
Lott's and Daschle's willingness to talk and compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that on occasions, I did some things that I
thought were fair to help him,'' Lott said, ``and I tell you that
he did some things for me that he didn't have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who held a last news conference in the Judiciary Committee
hearing room dominated by his oil portrait, said the House managers
had carried out their constitutional duty, even as most of America
wished they would go away.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, the White House got what it wanted, a clean verdict
of not guilty. The president's lawyers had once feared that the
three witnesses would lead to their darkest nightmare, a
months-long trial. But Daschle's ability two weeks ago to secure an
agreement with Lott that calling any new witnesses would require
bipartisan support had virtually assured the witness list would end
at three.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lott-Daschle compromise showed that there wouldn't be any
new witnesses,'' a White House lawyer said. ``That was a huge
moment for us, a major turning point.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott, announcing the agreement on witnesses, said that the trial
would conclude no later than Friday, Feb. 12, ``barring some
bolt-of-lightning discovery that we don't now see.'' Lightning did
not strike. The depositions were taken, portions of the tapes were
shown, the Senate spent three days in secret deliberations, and on
Friday at 12:39 p.m. the last senator cast his vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The End,'' said Rahm Emanuel, the former White House senior
adviser.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
