<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-THORNE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNE REPLACES MCCARVER 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although Tim McCarver will not call Mets games on
Channel 11 this season, Gary Thorne, his former Channel 9 partner,
will. Thorne will work with Tom Seaver, who is replacing McCarver,
and Ralph Kiner, who is expected to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working with Tim was a treasure,'' Thorne said during a
conference call to announce his four-year contract. He said that
McCarver's dismissal, believed to be partly over the criticism he
delivered from the booth, ``won't change how I approach games.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My obligation is to tell the truth,'' Thorne added. ``I have
to be honest. If it gets me in trouble, that's the cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this a warning to me? Maybe it is, but it won't have any
impact on me. I wish Timmy was back. He is a joy in my life. And
maybe when I'm finished working with Tom Seaver, I'll say the same
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Thorne said that he never saw Mets management chastise McCarver
for being critical, but he said that he had engaged Mark Bingham, a
team executive, in ``philosophical discussions'' about his
play-by-play role. ``I'm a journalist,'' Thorne said.
</P>
<P>
   McCarver is expected to join Channel 5's Yankee announcing team
on Tuesday. He will call about 42 of the station's 50 games.
</P>
</TEXT>
