<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOAT-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ZEALANDERS OMITTED AMERICA ONE SKIPPER ON THEIR REGATTA `A'
LIST  
 A BOAT SHOW WEEKEND IN MIAMI  
 ROLEX YACHTSWOMAN OF THE YEAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla., R.I., Ga .,  Australia, France, Switzerland)   By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At this time last year, Paul Cayard was being doused with
torrents of water _ fire hoses, he called it then _ that poured
over the decks of his round-the-world ocean racer, EF Language.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is in New Zealand, buoy-racing on his America One
training yacht. He has put to rest the dangers of sailing in the
Whitbread Round the World Race, which he won. But in its place, he
says he is confronted with the political backwash of racing for the
America's Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That fifth leg of the Whitbread was one of the most satisfying
times of my career,'' Cayard said during a recent telephone
interview from New Zealand. ``The Whitbread was a new challenge,
but our team of sailors managed to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're in Auckland for the America's Cup. We're here trying
to figure out the new race course, and the other competitors. But
it is sometimes frustrating, and a less glamorous job than what the
public sees.''
</P>
<P>
   Cayard is feeling the pressure of being one of the front-runners
in the America's Cup challenger trials, which begin in Auckland,
New Zealand, in October. But it is the Kiwis who are making sure
the tension does not abate any time soon. As the winner of
yachting's oldest trophy in a competition held off San Diego in
1995, New Zealand sailors have the hometown advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The New Zealanders have invited 4 of the 15 cup challengers _
and not Cayard _ to Auckland on March 1 for a week of unofficial
racing against the Kiwi defense team in two yachts used in the 1992
cup by New Zealand. It is the third rendition of a spring regatta
that is a test of sailing skills as opposed to new technology that
the New Zealanders have dubbed ``Road to the America's Cup.'' But
Cayard's team has never raced in it. Perhaps it was planned that
way, he says now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of political,'' he added. ``The first year, I really
wanted to do it, but they said they wanted to give new teams a
chance for the exposure. The second year, in 1998, I was invited,
but I was in the Whitbread and couldn't go. This year, I wasn't
invited.''
</P>
<P>
   Four other challengers have accepted this season: Prada, the
Italian team; Yaka France, one of two French cup teams; America
True, the San Francisco syndicate led by Dawn Riley, and Swiss FAST
2000, the first Swiss team in America's Cup history.
</P>
<P>
   As for Cayard, he will return to San Francisco on Feb. 28 with
two months of cup practice on One Australia, a yacht that competed
in the 1995 America's Cup trials. ``It's been good to be out
sailing and racing here,'' he said. ``We're seeing all the bits and
pieces coming together.'' Anchor's Aweigh in Four Days
</P>
<P>
   A Boat Show Weekend in Miami
</P>
<P>
   The annual extravaganza that has become the Miami International
Boat Show has four days left in an exhibition that began on
Thursday at the Miami Beach Convention Center. The show, which
includes Strictly Sail, the sailing arm of a mostly powerboat
display, ends on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,000 boats are being shown at three sites in the
Miami area, including the Biscayne Bay Yachting Center and the
Miamarina at Bayside Marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the attractions are a high-dive show, a casting pond
for fly fishermen and seminars on everything from solar power for
boats to buying a multihull.
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen new boat designs are on exhibit, as well as
new gear, such as a rotary-power marine engine by Rotary Power
Marine Corp., and a new fiberglass skiff by Porta-Bote
International. It folds flat to four inches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to broaden the base of people we talk to,'' Cathy
Johnston, the boat-show manager, said last week. ``We know what
regular boat buyers want. Now we have a campaign to show other
people how they can own a boat too.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolex Yachtswoman of the Year
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Alison, a 38-year-old sailor from Newport, R.I., received
her fifth Rolex Yachtswoman of the Year title in a ceremony on Feb.
5 at the New York Yacht Club. It is the highest national award in
the sport of yacht racing. Alison was honored for her 1998
victories in match racing and her status as a world keelboat
champion.
</P>
<P>
   Named as Rolex Yachtsman of the Year was Paul Cayard, who
received the honor for the first time. He was selected in large
part, said nominating officials, ``for becoming the first American
to win the Whitbread Round the World Race.''
</P>
<P>
   In winning her fifth title, Alison topped Ted Turner, the
cable-news entrepreneur and former America's Cup helmsman, who won
the Yachtsman of the Year title four times.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
