<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMR-WORK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILOTS' SICKOUT BEGINS TO HAVE RIPPLE EFFECT
</HEADLINE>
   (See also AMR-PILOTS; Also moving in `a' news file.) 
(jw) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Workers at American Airlines who belong to other unions appear
to generally support the pilots' union in its dispute with the
airline. But some say the flight cancellations are cutting into
their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Other workers worry that if the dispute continues much longer,
the airline may begin to lay people off. There have been no layoffs
so far.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots' sickout has led the airline to cancel as many as
half its scheduled flights for eight days. Some flight attendants,
who get a minimum paycheck each week but make more by putting more
hours in the air, say the cancellations have already begun to
reduce their wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't work a flight, I don't get the hours and I don't
get the higher pay,'' said one flight attendant at La Guardia
Airport in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first couple of days I supported them,'' she said.
But, she added: ``They have made their point. It's time for them to
go back. It's hurting me.''
</P>
<P>
   Like others interviewed, the flight attendant would speak only
on the condition that she not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Hedges, the president of the Association of Professional
Flight Attendants, said in a message on the union's telephone line
that its members had lost thousands of flight hours because of
cancellations. The union represents 20,000 flight attendants at
American.
</P>
<P>
   ``As painful as it is, it is out of our control,'' she said.
``We cannot and will not interfere in this dispute.''
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants' union is in negotiations for a new
contract. Some flight attendants said the issues involved in the
pilots' dispute would affect their contract.
</P>
<P>
   One flight attendant said that if American was allowed to bring
in workers from its newly acquired Reno Air at wages lower than
those paid to workers at American, it would erode other unions'
contracts. And he said the outcome of the pilots' dispute would set
a precedent for those contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilots have the strength to do what they are doing,'' he
said. ``We don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Another worker, who performs maintenance on American's planes
and is represented by the Transport Workers Union, said his fellow
workers were worried that if the pilots' sickout continued, the
airline might begin laying off workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
