<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-OYSTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: WHEN OYSTERS ARE MOST OF YOUR WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It offended my New England frugality, but earlier this winter I
paid $18 for a car tire inner tube that is used to help me gather
oysters.
</P>
<P>
   The tube floats the wire basket that is tethered to me as,
wearing chest waders, I rake the oysters from the bottom of a salt
pond. For decades I made do with battered, discarded inner tubes
scrounged from the local gas station. With my own patches added to
the many that already existed, I would get a season or two out of
them before they failed. On my first oystering expedition this
winter, the tube I was using lost most of its air in half an hour
and flipped upside down in three feet of water, returning its
precious cargo to the pond. That afternoon I bought the new tube,
telling myself that my next oystering foray would more than pay for
such unseemly profligacy.
</P>
<P>
   Winter is the time of the oyster for food gatherers in the
Northeast. Most hunting and fishing is over and the oysters are fat
and tasty having recovered from the rigors of spawning.
</P>
<P>
   On Tisbury Great Pond on Martha's Vineyard, where I do my
oystering, there is also a commercial fishery for them. The
commercial harvesters use dredges dragged behind outboard-powered
skiffs. The individual after a mess of them for family consumption
can use a potato fork or some rake-like tool designed especially
for the task.
</P>
<P>
   Although the wading oyster harvester can eventually fill his
basket on a dark and windy day, high noon, clear skies and smooth
water make the task much easier, enabling you to spot the quarry on
the bottom; otherwise you are simply probing blind, waiting to feel
the grating of shells against your rake. Good visibility also
enables you to pick out individual specimens rather than clusters.
On any natural oyster bed, there are many of the bivalves that have
perished for one reason or another. Some, their shells tightly
closed, look enticing but hold nothing but sand and mud. As you
become adept at oystering, you will be able to identify such
specimens on the bottom. Their shells tend to be several shades
lighter than those of their living counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Clustered oysters have to be separated when you bring them
ashore. A short board _ on which to rest the clusters _ and a
little billy club, perhaps the broken wooden handle of a hammer,
are needed for this. In our family, my partner, Ruth Kirchmeier,
accompanies me on my oyster forays, wandering along the pond shore,
watching birds and finding occasional animal tracks, including
those of deer, otters and muskrats. When I come ashore with my
first load of oysters, she sets about breaking up the clumps,
discarding those that are dead or too small, while I return to my
raking.
</P>
<P>
   With a little practice, you become adept at separating these
clusters, but every once in a while an oyster is broken. Ruth deals
with these broken oysters on the spot. Using her penknife, she
separates the meat from the shell and devours the critter and its
juices. In years past, we used to bring a bottle of
ketchup-horseradish sauce with us, but we finally decided that the
aroma of the salt pond and the moaning of the distant surf was
condiment enough.
</P>
<P>
   When the culling operation is complete, we return all the
discarded shells, including the diminutive live specimens, to the
water because future generations of oyster larvae need rough,
slime-free surfaces on which to fasten themselves. The shells of
their forebears are, under natural conditions, the usual anchoring
spots.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, one of my jobs was to smash the shells of oysters
that we gathered into small pieces to feed them to our chickens.
Now, sans chickens, we scatter the shells in our dirt driveway to
firm up the earth.
</P>
<P>
   We carefully place our culled oysters, deep side down, in a
separate container. They must be stored in that position so that
their life-sustaining liquid will not drain away. Packed in that
manner, covered with a damp cloth or an old towel that is
occasionally wetted, they will last for weeks if stored in a cool
spot. A root cellar would be ideal for this, but not many of us
have root cellars. An unheated room is good, and outside storage in
the shade works well unless the temperature is consistently below
freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Oysters will survive occasional below-freezing dips in
temperature, but if you have them outside and a protracted period
of bitter cold is forecast, you will have to take them inside. If
you keep them inside, you will, after a week or so, begin to detect
the odor of decay. Don't panic. It's not the oysters that are
dying, but the reddish-brown clam worms that _ at least in my
locality _ live in the outer portions of the oysters' shells.
</P>
<P>
   Much is made of the difficulty of shucking oysters, but any
reasonably dexterous person will be able to handle the needs of his
or her family after a few hours' practice. Hold the bivalve deep
side down and hinge away from you in your gloved left hand and
insert the oyster knife's thin, tapered, two-edged and blunt-nosed
blade between the bivalve's two shells about a third of the way up
from the hinge. Keep the thumb and forefinger of your right hand
close to the knife's point to minimize the chance of slipping and
stabbing yourself. Push and wiggle the blade a little and you'll
find a place where the blade will enter. Then, all you have to do
is shove the blade deeper and swing it back and forth to sever the
oyster's adductor muscle which is between the shells on the
opposite side. Slide the knife back toward the hinge and twist it
to free the upper shell from the lower.
</P>
<P>
   According to A.J. McLane's ``The Encyclopedia of Fish Cookery''
(Holt, Rinehart and Winston, 1977), champion oyster shuckers can
for short periods of time open oysters at the rate of one every
three or four seconds. Such dexterity is beyond ordinary mortals.
I've been opening them for more than 60 years and I find that one
every 10 or 15 seconds is all that I can manage. There's no hurry.
Those that you don't open today will be good tomorrow, or even next
month. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
