<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-CROSS-COUNTRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALASKAN TRIES TO OUTSKI EUROPEANS AT THEIR GAME  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Austria, Poland, Norway, Maine)   By JACK BELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he was a child growing up in Anchorage, Rob Whitney's
parents used to take him cross-country skiing. Kicking and
screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents would have to drag me out of the house,'' he said.
``I hated it with a passion.''
</P>
<P>
   No more.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney, now 19 and the top American male junior skier,
practically lives on the frozen trails of North America and Europe.
Late last month against older and more experienced competition at
the Chevy Truck U.S. Championships in Rumford, Maine, he finished
seventh in the 10-kilometer classic race and sixth in the 30K
freestyle. His strong performance at the nationals earned Whitney
an invitation to the World Championships, Feb. 18-28, in Ramsau,
Austria, as part of the five-man American senior team.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Whitney has just finished competing in Saalfelden,
Austria, in the World Junior Championships, which ended last
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm capable of making the podium at the juniors,'' the
eternally confident Whitney had said. That, however, did not happen
last week in Saalfelden. Whitney's best performance was in his
first race, the 10K classic, in which he finished seventh. He was
part of the 4 X 10K relay team that was a distant 15th last
Saturday. Then in his final attempt at ``making the podium,''
Whitney slumped to 20th in the 30K freestyle event, 2 minutes 41
seconds behind the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney (6 feet 2 inches, 195 pounds), who has taken a leave of
absence from the University of Alaska, Anchorage, to train
exclusively with his Polish coach, Zenon Babraj, finished eighth in
the 30K race at last year's junior championships in Switzerland. As
he has heard countless times since that race, it was the best
showing in cross-country skiing by an American male in the juniors
since Bill Koch finished third in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Koch went on to win an Olympic silver medal for the United
States in the 30K classical at the Innsbruck Games in 1976. He is
also credited with revolutionizing the sport when he developed and
popularized the skating style (now called freestyle).
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear that so much that it's beginning to get old,'' Whitney
said, referring to the inevitable comparisons with Koch. ``Sure
it's flattering, but it's also a lot of hype. You can't let it go
to your head.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a danger that a young skier with as much promise as
Whitney could be harboring hopes of challenging the likes of
Norway's Olympic dynamo Bjorn Daehlie in the world championships
while underestimating his peer group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is that he will be looking past the juniors to the
seniors,'' said the U.S. Ski Team's cross-country manager, Luke
Bodensteiner, a past American Olympian and the author of the book
``Endless Winter.'' It was a concern that was confirmed by
Whitney's less-than stellar performance at the junior
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob is one of the best juniors in the world right now,'' said
Bodensteiner, ``and we hope that he shows it. Right now I believe
that any 19-year-old is too young to do well in the World Cup.
Simply for him to get into it and get used to competing against a
higher caliber of competition is useful. We expect some great
results from him heading to the 2002 Olympics, but really, I think
he needs to use that as a springboard to the 2006 Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Whitney's comments ooze with a refreshing innocence, a
sense that he has many years of success awaiting him on the world
stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe there's a perception that we stink,'' Whitney said.
``That bothers me, but all I can do is show up and race. I
understand that cross-country skiing is not America's sport. Ninety
percent of the races and best racers are in Europe. It's a European
sport and we're pretty isolated. But to race fast you need to race
against the fastest racers. You need to get passed, get passed a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitney realizes that he is unlikely to make much of an impact
internationally, perhaps for years to come. That he has got to pay
his dues.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at least, he is no longer a reluctant skier. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
