<HEADLINE>
MERGER NEAR, 2 JEWISH PHILANTHROPY GROUPS PICK A LEADER
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: Canada, Israel) 
 (jw) 
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As two powerhouses of Jewish philanthropy, the United Jewish
Appeal and the Council of Jewish Federations, prepare to merge
within the next few months, the new entity said that it had chosen
Charles Bronfman, a Canadian billionaire, to be its volunteer
chairman. Bronfman, co-chairman of Seagram Co. and a prominent
Jewish philanthropist, will oversee the strategic direction for the
new group.
</P>
<P>
   The UJA and the Jewish federations, once viewed as a mainstay of
Jewish philanthropy, have come under sharp criticism in recent
years as being unresponsive to donors and uncreative in their
giving. While they still raise more than $1 billion a year, they
have struggled to convince Jews in the United States and Canada
that they are as relevant today as they were during the Holocaust
or the early days of Israel. Many large donors have chosen to
emphasize other causes or contribute through their own foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed to address these criticisms, the groups agreed last year
to combine forces. While the merger has not received final
approval, the reorganization appears to have the backing of the
United Jewish Appeal and the United Israel Appeal, which oversees
the money raised by the UJA for Israel, as well as the 189
federations that make up the council. The new entity will shift
decision-making power to the federations, which will select roughly
two-thirds of the new group's 120-member board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Donors in local communities will have more say over where the
dollars sent to Israel should be spent and whether a bigger share
of money should go to Jewish community-building at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Bronfman, a soft-spoken 67-year-old who has done
much of his own giving through his foundations, seems to be an
effort to reach out to both disaffected givers and loyal
supporters. Describing himself as an ``an encourager of change,''
Bronfman has been active in the groups without being a member of
the old leadership. ``I think there is a great opportunity for
rebirth, rethinking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The culture change has to happen because they are sitting in a
sea that is very unsettled,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bronfman was chosen by a 25-member nominating committee. ``
Bronfman is dedicated to Jewish affairs all over the world,'' said
Charles Goodman, chairman of the committee. ``It was a unanimous
and enthusiastic nomination.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Noting the difficulty of leading the board of a new nonprofit
organization, Goodman said that the committee was ``very grateful''
to Bronfman ``for his willingness to accept his role in the new
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his better-known brother, Edgar Bronfman Sr., 69, the
other co-chairman of Seagram, Charles Bronfman has not been among
the most vocal critics of the UJA and the Jewish federations. Edgar
Bronfman, president of the World Jewish Congress, has publicly
questioned the groups' agenda. He has argued that money raised
would be better spent on efforts to encourage a sense of Jewish
identity, through support of day schools or other means.
</P>
<P>
   The new group, which has yet to be named, has adopted a broad
mission statement. In addition to its traditional role in
supporting projects in Israel and overseas, the group states that
it will also try to help strengthen the Jewish people through
programs that foster Jewish renaissance and renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bronfman has strong ties to Israel as both an investor
and a philanthropist. He is chairman of three Israeli businesses:
Koor Industries, a diversified holding company; Claridge Israel, a
private investment company, and The Jerusalem Report, a biweekly
magazine. Last year, he teamed with another prominent Jewish
philanthropist, Michael Steinhardt, to establish Birthright Israel,
a program to help young Jews from anywhere in the world visit
Israel. Bronfman and Steinhardt each have contributed $5 million to
the program, which will also receive financing from the Israeli
government, local North American federations and other donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel has as much to offer us in our quest to be a Jewish
people as we have to offer them,'' Bronfman said. He also
emphasized the importance of the groups' historical work in
supporting the exodus of Jews from other countries to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Approached informally about a year ago, Bronfman said that he
only recently became interested in the position. Over the last six
months, Jeffrey Solomon, president of the Andrea and Charles
Bronfman Philanthropies, has been acting as a consultant to the new
group. Solomon had been a top executive with the UJA-Federation of
New York before he was recruited by the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   While Bronfman acknowledged that the new group faced a
significant challenge in proving its value and reaching out to more
Jews, especially younger ones, he was quick to emphasize the
positive. ``We are one of the most blessed generations of the
Jewish people,'' he said. ``Let's do something wonderful, and let's
do it together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
