<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANSAS-CITY-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 REJUVENATING THE HEART OF KANSAS CITY  (bl) 
 By JILIAN MINCER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Since 1984, the Ewing Marion Kauffman
Foundation has been providing funds for projects that support
early-childhood education, fight child and drug abuse and promote
entrepreneurship.
</P>
<P>
   In January, it moved to its new midtown headquarters on a
37-acre campus bounded by Troost Avenue, Brush Creek Boulevard,
Rockhill Road and 48th Street. Its construction, along with
improvements on the four-mile Brush Creek corridor, have helped
spur development of a four-square-mile area.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the north-south thoroughfare has been a dividing
line between the mostly white, affluent neighborhoods to the west
and the predominantly poor, minority neighborhoods to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently little private investment has occurred east of
Troost Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   But as its 180 employees move into the foundation's new
headquarters, Kauffman Legacy Park, a dozen projects costing an
estimated total of $500 million are under way or about to move off
the drawing board on the east-west Brush Creek corridor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the best potential urban development sites in the
city,'' said Vicki Noteis, the city's director of planning and
development. ``Thinking east-west in Kansas City is breaking with
tradition,'' she added, noting that all the major arteries run
north-south.
</P>
<P>
   Residents, businesses and institutions in the area hope that as
projects like the Kauffman campus are completed, they will attract
other development to the area, which already includes most of the
city's major cultural, education and research institutions.
</P>
<P>
   These include the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, the Kemper Museum
of Contemporary Art, the University of Missouri-Kansas City and the
Midwest Research Institute. About 60,000 people live in the
adjacent neighborhoods that range from some of the city's most
upscale historic homes to low-income housing projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision is for a world-class cultural and research district
that is surrounded by healthy communities,'' said Robert B. Rogers,
chairman of the Kauffman Foundation. ``We chose this location
because we wanted to be as close to our client base as possible.
This is the heart of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the new development along the corridor can be attributed
to infrastructure improvements in the area, such as realingnment of
streets for better traffic flow and reconstruction of bridges.
</P>
<P>
   But by far the most significant improvement has been flood
control and beautification of the property abutting Brush Creek.
The city began this work more than 20 years ago after a flash flood
along Brush Creek and elsewhere in the city killed 25 people.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan was for flood protection only. However, in
1983 voters approved two half-cent sales tax increases to provide
funds for infrastructure projects in the city. The tax was renewed
in 1988 and now it generates about $30 million a year. The tax
expires Dec. 31, 2000, but city officials said that it was expected
to be renewed.
</P>
<P>
   About $90 million of the fund has been spent on transforming the
once muddy Brush Creek into a pastoral setting with bike trails,
fountains and parks. Roads along the creek have been realigned to
better accommodate traffic and bridges rebuilt with the area's
natural limestone.
</P>
<P>
   The public improvements are now helping to attract private
investment to the area. Among others, H &AMP; R Block, the
tax-preparation firm, is planning to open a service center in
September with about 120 full-time employees and 600 temporary
employees during the tax season. The 83,500-square-foot center
represents the first significant for-profit investment east of
Troost Avenue in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most significant project is the $125-million
Stowers Institute for Medical Research, which is across the creek
from the Kauffman Foundation. James and Virginia Stowers, who made
their fortune through their mutual-fund business, American Century
Cos., have created a $336-million endowment to run the nonprofit
Stowers biomedical research facility. The 600,000-square-foot
project is expected to open next year on the site of a former
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The builder of the new 37-acre campus on the other side of the
creek from the Stowers Institute, the Kauffman Foundation, was
established by Ewing M. Kauffman, founder of Marion Laboratories,
now Hoechst Marion Roussell, a pharmaceutical company. Kauffman was
also the original owner of the Kansas City Royals baseball team.
From the start, the foundation's emphasis has been on helping
adults and children gain greater self-sufficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Today the foundation, which has assets of about $1.5 billion,
provides funds totaling more than $60 million a year, primarily for
youth development and entrepreneurship programs. The Youth
Development Division provides funds for programs such as
child-abuse prevention and the training of early-childhood
educators, especially in inner cities. And the Kauffman Center for
Entrepreneurial Leadership was established to educate both children
and adults about business skills.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons the foundation decided to build a new
headquarters was because much of its work involves holding
conferences and training sessions, and it regularly had to rent
space for these events.
</P>
<P>
   One of the many unusual features of the new 135,000-square-foot
facility is that about one-third of its space is a conference
center. The various rooms can accommodate as many as 200
participants. The conference center will be used for events
sponsored by the foundation as well as by the programs it finances.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston architectural firm of Kalmann, McKinnell and Wood,
which in 1961 won a national competition to design Boston's City
Hall, designed the foundation's new headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Kauffman Foundation sought neighborhood input in the design
of the two-story building because it is surrounded on the north by
historic homes. The architects blended it in with the natural
environment, using maple and stone in its structure.
</P>
<P>
   The building will also house the Muriel McBrien Kauffman
Foundation, named for the late wife of Ewing Kauffman. The
foundation supports organizations that make the arts more
accessible in the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most unusual feature of the campus is that it is
designed to draw visitors to the area. The Ewing and Muriel
Kauffman Memorial Gardens, which are still under construction, will
include walking paths that lead from the Kauffman site to an
already existing landscaped mall to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Another unusual feature of the campus is that the state's
Department of Conservation plans to build on the northeast corner
an educational nature preserve that will include a pond, plantings
and hands-on learning centers for families and schoolchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
