<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4375 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONN-COL-SCHOOLS-NYT &LR;      02-13 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-COL-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PUTTING TWO EDUCATIONAL RIVALS TO THE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERBURY, Conn. _ It's not that Waterbury hasn't tried to fix
its schools. It has mandatory summer school for students who fail.
It has a charter school. In three weeks, it will start Saturday
classes for failing students, with only 10 students per class. Next
year, it will create a magnet school. It even requires uniforms in
grade school and has a dress code _ no jeans or slouchy shirts _
for high schoolers.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing has worked. In an annual ranking of state school
districts based on student test scores, Waterbury was 161st out of
164. Only 47 percent of the city's 15,500 students scored at grade
level in reading, math and science.
</P>
<P>
   The school superintendent, Roger Damerow, said that such scores
had been explained away too easily and too often by blaming social
conditions in this old factory town: abundant poverty, many
immigrants who speak little or no English, little parental
involvement in schools and high student turnover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been using socioeconomic status as an excuse for years
but the politicians say it is not sufficient,'' Damerow said.
``Politicians say: `All kids are equal, so have at it. Get to
work.'''
</P>
<P>
   So in a gesture that is part desperation, part renewed
determination, the city has given an unlikely pair the chance to
run two new schools in what is probably the United States' first
teach-off.
</P>
<P>
   The expectation is that the groups, fierce enemies in the
education world, will try to outdo each other in a competition
whose only winners will be students.
</P>
<P>
   The first new school will open in the fall and be run by the
Edison Project, the private, for-profit company that runs 51
schools around the country, mostly in struggling school districts
like Waterbury. In 2000, another school will be handed over to the
very group that many critics love to hate as the embodiment of
sullen resistance to school reform: the teachers union.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came to us and said they wanted to bring Edison in
here,'' said Jack Cronan, president of the Waterbury Teachers
Association. ``And we said: `OK, give us parity. Let us show you
what we can do at our school.'''
</P>
<P>
   Each school will operate for five years. After that, the city
will try to figure out what worked, what didn't and what to do
next.
</P>
<P>
   Each school will have about 500 students, in kindergarten
through eighth grade. At the Edison school, students will get their
own computers and a longer school year. The union does not yet know
what it will do differently. It will not lengthen the school year,
Cronan said, but it might have a longer school day _ this from a
union that once filed a grievance over a plan to lengthen the day
by five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the Waterbury Teachers Association tries, Cronan said,
it will show that for all Waterbury's school problems, the union is
not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   But everyone knows what the problems are. Hang around the Tinker
Elementary School on Highland Avenue at 2 p.m., when parents come
to fetch their children, and you will hear the voices of people who
are at wit's end about their schools. Like the city officials, they
care less about pinning blame than finding answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to the point where they feel they just don't have
the talent to do it themselves, and they have to go to the
outside,'' said Joe Ciccomascolo, a retired accountant, as he
waited for his granddaughter, Olivia Ann, a first-grader. ``It's so
hard to understand why we can't measure up on a state basis or on a
national basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Damerow said one answer might lie with the very gritty,
street-smart kids who are having so much trouble with school.
</P>
<P>
   ``My theory is that any dummy can make it in the suburbs,'' he
said. ``Mom drives you to school in the station wagon, she picks
you up and drives you home, she makes you do your homework. Our
kids come out of places you wouldn't want to walk past at night,
and they face incredible difficulties just getting to school. They
have skills, and I'd like to find a way to apply them in the
classroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Waterbury school officials toyed with the idea of bringing in a
private school operation five years ago, but the union howled and
the school board shelved the idea. Now the sense of urgency has
forced the city and its teachers into a truce. Even Cronan concedes
that the time has probably come to give the privateers at Edison a
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, maybe we do need them,'' he said. ``Something to knock
down that first domino.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
