</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKE-OGRADY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'GRADY YEARNS FOR MORE DAYS IN YELLOW  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia, Ireland, France ,  Great Britain )  By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The good times keep rolling for Stuart O'Grady, who,
with the same enthusiasm that briefly lit up the somber Tour de
France last July, merrily rolls along with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing your name painted on peoples' faces and chests gives
you good motivation,'' O'Grady, a 25-year-old Australian, said with
his standard-equipment grin at the recent presentation of his
Credit Agricole bicycle team in Paris. The body art was on display
during the Tour Down Under, a four-day race last month in his
native Adelaide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a wicked atmosphere,'' he continued. ``The first
day we had 40,000 people at the race, with thousands along the road
every day. The hills were like the Tour de France, people eight
deep.''
</P>
<P>
   It helped, of course, that a hometown boy was wearing the yellow
jersey of the leader of the inaugural Tour Down Under, a race he
went on to win. ``In Adelaide, the last day, there were 60,000
people cheering me in the yellow jersey,'' he said. ``People in
Australia are really starting to take to cycling big time.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the credit goes to O'Grady, who spent three days last
summer in the authentic yellow jersey _ the one donned by the Tour
de France's leader _ and later won a daily stage in the race. His
reactions ranged from explosions of joy (``I've gone to
Disneyland!'') to indecipherable Australianisms ending in ``mate.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Tour floundered under the weight of a doping scandal,
O'Grady's exuberance reminded everybody how pure, how much fun, the
race could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that was heavily publicized back home,'' he said. ``Now
it's like being a pop star: You go to a restaurant or cafe and
people don't want to let you pay. You walk out and everyone starts
cheering. And it all started with the yellow jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most overnight sensations, O'Grady spent a long time
preparing for his big moment. ``At least three years, the first
three after I turned professional,'' he said. ``Last year, the
fourth year, everything just seemed to fall into place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before that, I had the Olympic medals and things like that,
but you don't get the same recognition. The Olympics are every four
years and people tend to forget about it after a year.''
</P>
<P>
   He was part of the pursuit team that won a bronze medal at the
Olympic Games in Atlanta in 1996 and gold medals at the world
championships in 1993 and 1995; as an individual rider, he took a
bronze in the points race in Atlanta and another bronze in pursuit
at the 1995 world championships.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, O'Grady said he ``played soccer, athletics, squash,
everything'' before turning definitively to the bicycle at 13. He
comes from a cycling family, he explained, with a father who raced
on the road and track and uncles _ his mother's brothers _ whom he
described as competitive in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Moving from the track to the road himself, he turned
professional in 1995 with the Gan team, based in France, which has
changed sponsors and become Credit Agricole. For his first three
years, O'Grady said, he was ``allowed to ease my way into the
program. If you come over and want to do everything in every race,
you'll just kill yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, before he headed into the three-week Tour de France,
he won the nine-day Prutour in Britain in early June. It was a
small stage race but a big boost. ``It was extremely important for
my confidence and maturing,'' O'Grady said. ``I had the pressure
on.''
</P>
<P>
   A month later, in the Tour, everything fell into place. After he
finished a fine 24th in the 189-man field in the prologue in
Dublin, he was part of an eight-man breakaway on the fourth stage
and wound up third over all, a few seconds behind the leader.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, after he won two bonus sprints and finished third
in another, he received the yellow jersey, which he wore until Jan
Ullrich took it away half a week later in the first time trial. A
week after that, O'Grady won the stage into Grenoble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's your dream when you take up a sport to get to the
pinnacle,'' O'Grady said. ``I know it's going to be hard to please
everyone by doing it again. But it's like in the Tour: If you do a
good prologue and you're an attacking kind of rider and you try to
get in the breaks, things can happen. And last year they did
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   What about this year? ``In '99 things have really kicked off on
the right foot,'' he replied, referring to the Tour Down Under.
``I'd be happy to do what I did last year for the rest of my life.
But now I'm going to look more seriously at some of the classic
races and some small stage races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every race I'll start may not be Alpe d'Huez,'' he said,
referring to the fearsome Tour de France climb. ``I'll rate myself
a chance and try to be competitive.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 1549EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
