<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SOUTHBRONX-REAL-3T     02-13 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SOUTHBRONX-REAL-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOUTH BRONX VERY DIFFERENT FROM THE CLICHE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Few urban areas have ever had a worse image than the
South Bronx in the 1970s, with hundreds of buildings abandoned,
stripped, burned and rotting. The neighborhood became a synonym for
disaster _ a warning, perhaps, of where cities might be heading.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't very long ago, but in parts of the South Bronx it
seems like another century. Where surreal decals of flower boxes
and window shades once adorned burned-out buildings, those derelict
structures have been renovated and real people with real
furnishings have moved in. The population is growing, not falling.
Artists, antique stores and other businesses, symbols of growth
rather than decay, are arriving.
</P>
<P>
   South of 169th Street, in the part of the South Bronx closest to
Manhattan, lie neighborhoods like Hunts Point, Mott Haven and Port
Morris, areas that were particularly stricken by abandonment and
crime. Now, many streets are unrecognizable.
</P>
<P>
   Crime rates are significantly lower, and like many other urban
areas, parts of the Bronx are beginning to be transformed. In the
last 11 years, 57,000 units of housing have been built or
rehabilitated in the borough as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   While none of the residents would argue that no more
improvements are needed, the ascent of these neighborhoods is all
the more astonishing in the light of where they began. But the
area's image has still not recovered, and people who work and live
there say that visitors are still shocked at the extent of the
revival.
</P>
<P>
   On a two-block stretch of Bruckner Boulevard, a street
infamously immortalized by Tom Wolfe in his novel ``The Bonfire of
the Vanities'' as a threatening place, charming antique stores have
been popping up, and above them, renovated apartments rent for
$1,000 a month. The antique district also fills two blocks on
adjoining Alexander Street, and with a zoning change last year
allowing mixed commercial and residential uses, the value of the
buildings, available just a few years ago for less than $50,000,
has tripled.
</P>
<P>
   Over in Hunts Point, new houses and apartment buildings have
replaced the weeds that thrived in abandoned shells. On Manida
Street, where two-story, century-old town houses with rounded
facades survived the difficult years, a group of artists are living
and working to create a vital cultural life, through the Point
Community Development Corp., at Manida and Garrison Streets.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few months, the Point plans to take over 9,000
square feet of space in the nearby American Bank Note Building, a
windowed structure on Garrison Street with large, open interior
spaces and panoramic views of Manhattan. The space will be home to
the dance troupe founded by Arthur Aviles, a modern dancer who
performed for some years with Bill T. Jones. The Point also plans
to begin renting studio space in the building to artists.
</P>
<P>
   Within walking distance, a huge outpost of ABC Carpet and Home,
one of the most stylish stores in Manhattan, doubled its space
three months ago at 1055 Bronx River Ave. and began offering the
same kind of merchandise sold at its other stores, luxurious
sheets, antiques, and oriental rugs, but marked down between 30 and
90 percent. Some customers come from the South Bronx, but the vast
majority drive in from Westchester, Connecticut and New Jersey,
lured by easy access from the Bruckner Expressway, the Bronx River
Parkway or the Cross Bronx Expressway, and free parking.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the South Bronx, residential and commercial projects
are being built; loan rates are more affordable in the economy as a
whole, but even more important, banks are making loans at rates
comparable to those in other regions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a risk penalty applied to people buying buildings in
the Bronx,'' said Harvey Rottenberg, a partner in NYMC Capital
Corp. in Manhattan, which lends money to businesses. Experienced
investors in commercial properties and multifamily buildings could
get money at competitive rates, he said, but many borrowers less
experienced and less able to demonstrate stable cash flow were
paying between one and five percentage points more on their loans.
</P>
<P>
   More private money began flowing to the Bronx about two years
ago, he said, when big national lenders looked at the borough
without prejudice and realized it had strong occupancy, retail and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we're surprised by the amount of business we're
seeing out of the Bronx,'' he said. In just one year, from 1997 to
1998, he said, his company's loans for investments in the Bronx
rose by 400 percent. The flourishing of the South Bronx, he said,
is part of the borough's overall economic improvement. In the South
Bronx, he estimated, his company lent almost $10 million last year,
for projects that included a live chicken market and a beverage
distributorship.
</P>
<P>
   There is so much activity that ``it is hard to walk two blocks
in either direction without seeing construction,'' said Neil
Pariser, senior vice president of the South Bronx Overall Economic
Development Corp., known as Sobro. Groups that have renovated
buildings taken over by the city for nonpayment of taxes are
running out of opportunities for that kind of renewal, Pariser
said. ``It is now difficult to find a space to convert,'' he said.
``You can't find a city-owned building that's vacant for rehab. We
don't have tons of buildings anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   With new housing established or under construction, the focus is
shifting to development of real estate for commercial and
industrial purposes. Opportunities offered by the Bronx will be
examined in a three-session seminar sponsored by the Steven L.
Newman Real Estate Institute of Baruch College beginning March 16
at the college.
</P>
<P>
   But many problems still remain in the South Bronx, including a
higher than average unemployment rate and a lower than average
income in most households. It is not in immediate danger of
becoming a chic area. Bronx Borough President Fernando Ferrer, who
grew up in Hunts Point, jokes about the criticism from those who
fear gentrification in any guise.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The people who have moved into the new buildings of the South
Bronx, Ferrer said, ``are not folks that can even remotely be
described as the gentry.'' They are working people with household
incomes of about $55,000, with one member employed as, perhaps, a
secretary, and the other perhaps as a corrections officer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the vitality in the South Bronx is so unmistakable, and the
improvements so profound, that even though there is much to be
done, people who never expected to return have been lured back.
</P>
<P>
   People like Majora Carter, who is in the process of acquiring
the house on Manida Street where she now lives. Ms. Carter returned
to the neighborhood where she grew up in 1995, when she was getting
a master's degree in creative writing at New York University and
found there wasn't enough money for rent in Manhattan and tuition.
Because of the compatible people she found in the neighborhood,
artists, writers and others with a lot of energy and optimism, she
has decided to stay.
</P>
<P>
   It was, she said, something she could never have anticipated.
``The Bronx was burning,'' she said. ``I didn't want to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Also back is F. Maximo Soba, who works as a salesman in the
furniture section at ABC while he studies historic preservation at
Mechanics Institute in Manhattan. He never intended to return to a
place with such unhappy memories, he said, a place where his mother
suffered from drug addiction, contracted AIDS and died.
</P>
<P>
   He fled as soon as he could, he said, moving to Manhattan, to
Brooklyn, and eventually to Puerto Rico, where he ran a gallery and
store selling antique Spanish furniture. When the roof literally
caved in on the operation, he went back to his grandmother's home
in the South Bronx three years ago, to regroup.
</P>
<P>
   Like Ms. Carter, he found the area so changed he decided to
stay, and last year moved into a town house floor-through on Manida
Street with three bedrooms that rents for $750 a month _ a price,
he said, that wouldn't even get him a studio in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some sections of Brooklyn, the South Bronx is not
overflowing with elegant old brownstones awaiting upwardly mobile
bargain hunters. Much of the housing originally constructed in the
South Bronx consisted of five-story walkups. A lot of the new
housing has been built with subsidies and is restricted to tenants
with relatively low family incomes.
</P>
<P>
   The vacancy rate in the South Bronx is very low. Apartments of
any kind are hard to find and tend to be passed around by word of
mouth, not advertising. But when they can be found, there are great
bargains, such as floor-through apartments in charming old town
houses, like Soba's, that on average rent for $750 a month.
</P>
<P>
   There are hundreds of town houses, for instance, in Mott Haven
between 134th and 144th Street, as well as on Alexander Avenue
between 138th Street and 141st Street, many of them architecturally
charming and just one subway stop north of Manhattan. But they are
not frequently available for sale. Sid Miller, director of the
Haven Heights Group, a real-estate brokerage on East 138th Street
in Mott Haven, said that many town-house residents show no interest
in moving even though their properties are rising in value. This
week, for instance, he closed on a deal for a brownstone on East
138th Street that sold for $155,000, a typical price for a house in
relatively good condition with architectural details.
</P>
<P>
   Miller began selling real-estate in the South Bronx 10 years
ago, he said, thinking it would be the next hot area. The influx he
anticipated did not happen, in part because homeowners do not seem
interested in leaving, despite the ``scent of money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is a comment often made about people who didn't flee the
South Bronx in the 1970s: They have hung on, and they don't plan to
go even if they have the means to do so. The Bronx is being
restored primarily by the people who lived through the grim time
when landlords were torching their own buildings for the insurance
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bronx at one point was ashes,'' said Delmas Vernon Cole,
the assistant director of Nos Quedamos, which in Spanish means ``We
are staying.'' His group, which is building housing for
middle-income people in the South Bronx, was created by residents
who successfully fought a city plan in the early 1990s to bulldoze
35 blocks east of Yankee Stadium. ``People stood up and created an
organization,'' he said. ``They decided to stay. That spirit alone
is pulling up the South Bronx,'' The changes in the neighborhood
are ``incredible,'' Cole said, but they are not yet reflected in
public perception. ``I think it is starting to change,'' he said,
``but when you say the South Bronx, it's still a very negative
image.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cole, a lifelong South Bronx resident who received a
bachelor's degree from New York University and a master's in urban
planning from Harvard, it isn't just a place that nearly burned to
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember another Bronx,'' he said, ``before the Cross Bronx
Expressway. I remember beautiful neighborhoods where people knew
everybody. It was an ethnically mixed and diverse neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   But then the massive highway construction that broke established
communities apart helped spark a process of urban decay, Cole said,
followed by a middle-class exodus to places like Co-op City, in the
north Bronx, and the suburbs beyond. ``By the end of the '70s you
could walk six blocks in any direction and you wouldn't see a
light. It was like being in a ghost town,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that housing has been built, and filled, he said, the place
needs the services that attract and keep the middle class, such as
good garbage collection, good schools, good parks and good air.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A small but appealing commercial strip lies around Bruckner and
Alexander, in the southernmost part of the South Bronx, where
antique dealers and artists have moved in. The first ones arrived
about seven years ago, but more are coming all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny Tillery, who opened Tigris &AMP; Euphrates at 79 Alexander St.
last June, said that business in her antiques store has been
``fantastic.'' She imagines the area eventually being like
Greenwich Village, or Soho. ``It has that potential and flavor,''
she said. To speed it along, she said, she hopes to open an Italian
restaurant in her building. ``People are looking for things to eat
when they come over,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the development in the area has been pushed by Sobro,
which plans to work next on the revitalization of the south side of
Bruckner so it resembles the restored blocks on the north side.
Annual commercial rents vary, but the average in that area is
probably between $15 and $20 a square foot, Pariser said. ``We need
food,'' he said. ``We need cafes. And I think we're going to have
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it doesn't have any of the amenities of the Village or
SoHo, the antique district does have a key advantage: It is
incredibly geographically convenient. Although the expressways that
were cut through the Bronx may have destabilized neighborhoods,
they now make it easy for people to shop there. Denise Cruz,
co-owner of the Custom Design Studio, an upholsterer that has been
at 47 Bruckner Boulevard for four years, said that customers come
from Westchester and Connecticut as well as Manhattan because
transportation is so easy.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Chapman, the senior executive vice president of ABC Carpet
and Home, said that customers come to his store from everywhere in
the region and that the South Bronx's central location could make
it a fertile area for development by big outlet stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picture a Secaucus here,'' with its outlet stores, he said.
Chapman, a native of the South Bronx, said that security is good in
the area, and he is dismissive of those who fear crime there.
``I've had more cars stolen in my New York location,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As in other parts of the city, businesses benefit from a general
drop in crime. Detective Robert Butler, a community affairs officer
for the 41st Precinct, which includes Hunts Point and Longwood,
said that both drugs and prostitution still exist, but less so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot better now than it used to be,'' Butler said,
better even than just two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The different feeling about crime shows up in all kinds of ways.
Josephine Infante, executive director of the Hunts Point Economic
Development Corp., said that businesses in the area's industrial
park never used to put signs out because they figured they would be
stolen. Now, she said, ``everyone puts out signs.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the area around Bruckner and Alexander stands out as a
retailing oasis, the enclave over at Hunt's Point is one of
artistic ferment. It is drawing people who grew up in the
neighborhood as well as people from outside.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Trattner, who teaches metal sculpture at the School of
Visual Arts in Manhattan and lives on the Lower East Side, was
working on a sculpture at the Socrates Sculpture Park in Queens
when she heard that the people at the Point were looking for
artists to work on a sculpture garden at the Hunts Point Avenue
subway stop on the No. 6 line. She built ``Pipe Dreams'' for them
in a space at the Point, and after it was erected she decided to
stay on, renting an outdoor studio space from the Point and
offering blacksmithing workshops to children in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   She finds the place supportive and invigorating. ``I have this
automatic community here of people who have an interest in my work
and are encouraging,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She has talked to her artist friends about her work, but when
she says she is working in the Bronx, she said, ``they say, `Oh,
that's so far.''' It takes her about 50 minutes to get there from
the Lower East Side, she said, but somehow, to people in Manhattan,
the area is psychologically much farther away.
</P>
<P>
   And in one way, she said, it is very different _ a way that is
beneficial. ``I feel like I've found a haven here,'' she said.
``Partly, it is the actual cityscape up here. Things are more
spread out. You have a sense of the sky. And there's so much
excitement up here. People are hungry for invention.''
</P>
<P>
   The Point recently bought its building from Max Blauner, who
also owns the old American Bank Note Company building on Garrison
Street between Tiffany and Barretto, which covers 365,000 square
feet and is six stories at its tallest point. It is only half
occupied, mainly by companies in the textile business. The Point
and Blauner have nearly reached agreement for the Point to rent the
9,000 square feet, partly for Aviles' dance company and partly to
be sublet to artists in increments of 400 square feet for $375 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lipson, executive director of the Point, said he had also
just received $12,000 in grants to develop a business plan to open
a Latin jazz cafe and club at the corner of Garrison and Hunts
Point Avenue, in a lovely building with a semicircular facade
typical of the area. Since it began five years ago, the Point has
nourished a number of business and artistic enterprises, including
a theater, hip-hop classes and a partnership with the International
Center of Photography that offers classes to local children and
adults.
</P>
<P>
   Still, progress in the amenities that make a neighborhood more
than just housing can be tough, and is uneven.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Torres is the director of the visual arts program at the
Longwood Art Project at 965 Longwood Avenue, between Beck and Kelly
Streets, an area distinguished by a number of historic homes as
well as a new Police Athletic League building. The center has been
offering free working space to artists, and organizing shows, but
financing has become too difficult to obtain, and people have been
reluctant to travel to shows in the South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The center's last exhibition in the space will start Feb. 27.
Beginning in June, it will become a cyber gallery and will provide
computers so local artists can make and show work on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Rivera, a Bronx native and a real-estate lawyer with an
office in the Throgs Neck section, said that young, upwardly mobile
black and Hispanic residents, like their counterparts with other
ethnic backgrounds, still gravitate to Manhattan, to neighborhoods
like Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   The next step, Rivera said, is to make the South Bronx, so close
to Manhattan, more appealing to a large range of people. The area's
renewal, he said, has been mostly of the ``meat and potatoes
kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, ``lifestyle and social opportunities have to catch
up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
