<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4383 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-MARKETING-2TAKES-     02-13 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-MARKETING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IOC NEEDS REFORMS TO SURVIVE  
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Note at end provides author identification.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID F. D'ALESSANDRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It seems to be the way the world works: Every
government that forgets about the people who give it power and,
instead, concentrates on keeping its secrets, keeping its perks,
maintaining its rituals and preserving its own hide, eventually
implodes.
</P>
<P>
   It happened to Louis XVI, and it happened to the Soviet
Communist Party. Now, it's happening to the International Olympic
Committee. Day by day, the IOC proves itself to be more and more
incapable of rising above the corruption scandal surrounding it and
further and further from the honesty and openness that the Olympic
Games represent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, our concern at John Hancock is so profound that, if the
IOC cannot or will not clean up the mess in which it finds itself,
we will refuse to run any of the $20 million in advertising we had
budgeted for the televised broadcasts of the 2000 Games in Sydney,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the company plans to remove the Olympic rings from its
stationery and billboards if the situation is not resolved. John
Hancock pays about $40 million every four years to sponsor the
Games. Perhaps the IOC will only do the right thing when it
understands that its revenues as well as its reputation are in
peril.
</P>
<P>
   When the news broke in December that the Salt Lake City bid
committee allegedly bribed IOC members during the bidding process
for the 2002 Games, many of us involved with the Olympics were
initially heartened by the IOC's response.
</P>
<P>
   One of its most respected members, Dick Pound, investigated the
IOC's conduct in Salt Lake City, and he produced a thorough and
creditable report. Releasing Pound's findings on Jan. 24, Juan
Antonio Samaranch, the president of the IOC, said exactly what
needed to be said: ``We are resolute in our determination to root
out the improprieties and to ensure that this never happens
again.''
</P>
<P>
   That resolve wound up being tested almost immediately. On Jan.
22, the Australian Olympic Committee president John Coates revealed
that he had promised payments of $35,000 each to two IOC members
from Kenya and Uganda for their national sports federations just
hours before the critical vote for the host city of the 2000 Games
was cast.
</P>
<P>
   Although allegations were coming out of the woodwork about other
cities' efforts to win the Games, Sydney's case was especially
clear-cut. There was a definite intent to influence the outcome of
the selection process: Coates said he decided ``I wasn't going to
die wondering why we didn't win.'' Coates also revealed that the
payments were made contingent on Sydney's winning. And Sydney did
indeed win by just two votes.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 2, one day after the Australian Olympic Committee
admitted it could not account for $10,000 given to the Kenyan IOC
member's personal foundation, the IOC abruptly cleared Sydney of
any wrongdoing, calling the eleventh-hour payments ``perfectly
correct.''
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible not to wonder what the IOC means by the word
``correct.'' Over in Lausanne, Switzerland, the IOC also seems to
be confused about the word bribery. According to the dictionary, it
is ``the act of influencing the action of another by corrupt
inducement,'' and the behavior of the Sydney bid committee appears
to fit this definition pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   The press may be right when it compares the IOC to royalty. The
IOC is like a royal family, one in which the cousins have been
marrying each other so long it's no wonder that their ideas of what
means what are a little daft.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the really interesting part: the IOC came to the
conclusion that all was well in Sydney weeks before a fact-finding
mission Samaranch had promised even took place, without even an
attempt at a formal investigation, without making Sydney's bid
documents public, and without talking with sports officials in
either Kenya or Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC also closed the books in the wake of mounting evidence
that the payments in question were nowhere near the wildest example
of Sydney's generosity. According to published reports, in order to
curry favor with another IOC member, the Australians spent $160,000
transporting seven horses to Mongolia. Guess the horses refused to
fly coach.
</P>
<P>
   The fig leaf the IOC is hiding behind in its refusal to
investigate the Sydney case is fooling no one. It has sent a letter
to all bid committees for the 1996 to 2006 Games, asking them if
they are aware of any corruption.
</P>
<P>
   This is like sending a letter to the proverbial fox in the hen
house asking, ``Would you mind telling us how many chickens you
have eaten?'' Then, if the fox sends back a polite note, ``None,
thank you,'' you issue a public statement exonerating the fox.
Incredible.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What we have here is not the zealous pursuit of corruption that
the IOC promised, but a classic cover-up. Here was the perfect
opportunity for the IOC to prove that it sincerely intended to
reform. Instead, it looked its own transgressions in the eye and
then retreated, shamelessly. This retreat lacks courage, lacks
leadership, lacks integrity, and falls well beneath the Olympic
ideals.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC's cravenness became even more embarrassing last week,
when Sydney itself took the high road. Michael Knight, president of
the Sydney Olympic Organizing committee, called in the former
auditor-general of South Australia for an independent review of its
bid.
</P>
<P>
   The current leadership of the IOC is running out of chances. The
IOC has called a special session in March, and if it does not adopt
radical reforms, it will have lost any remaining shred of
credibility. If it is to survive, the IOC's reforms had better
include the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ First, an admission that it is incapable of investigating
itself. Samaranch calls the Olympic movement a ``family.'' If this
is so, let's stop pretending that a family can investigate family
and, instead, bring in some impartial professional auditors to do
the work. The IOC should immediately call on the governments of bid
countries or the United Nations to investigate Olympic bidding
practices and other alleged improprieties. It should cooperate
fully with these investigations, rid itself of anyone who has
abused the Olympic ideals and replace those who attempt to
rationalize or disguise impropriety.
</P>
<P>
   _ Second, it's time to create an IOC membership that will make
the IOC accountable to the world community, one made up of
representatives appointed by every member country of the United
Nations. This is considerably different from the IOC's idea of
worldwide representation _ every member nominated by Samaranch and
appointed until age 80.
</P>
<P>
   _ Third, the host city selection process must be permanently
changed so that the IOC membership at large never again has the
opportunity to visit, vote on and shake down the cities vying for
the Games. And Olympic athletes must become far more involved in
the host-selection process. On Friday, The Times reported that the
IOC may scrap its plans to reform this process because of
objections from the membership. Hopefully, the IOC leadership will
not be so weak because retreat on this point would be unforgivable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fourth, the IOC should demand that its members disclose all
gifts received in their capacity as delegates, including plane
tickets, free hotel accommodations and meals, as well as any income
they or their families derive, directly or indirectly, from any
association with the Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fifth, an immediate search should begin for Samaranch's
successor, even though his term extends to 2001. We are not calling
for Samaranch's resignation at this time; we're simply recognizing
that it will take time to find the best possible candidate to
replace him whenever he leaves. Athletes, sponsors, news media and
national sports federations should participate in this search.
</P>
<P>
   If the IOC is incapable of making these changes, it is time for
the Olympic movement to look for new leadership, within the IOC or
outside the organization. More is at stake here than the pride and
arrogance of a few people in Lausanne.
</P>
<P>
   Let's remember that there is a major difference between the IOC
and a monarchy. In a monarchy, the little people serve the pleasure
of the royals; Olympic athletes, on the other hand, do not train
and sacrifice their whole lives to serve the self-appointed
sovereigns of the IOC Indeed, the IOC's only reason for being is to
serve the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   To its credit, the current leadership of the IOC has turned the
Olympics into an enormous popular success that has allowed the
Games to command billions of dollars from corporate sponsors and
broadcasters. And the IOC has used these tremendous resources to
support sports at the grass roots level around the world.
</P>
<P>
   However, the lethargic pace of the IOC in rooting out corruption
and its abrupt about-faces as to what constitutes corruption are
hurting every constituency it serves _ the corporate sponsors who
write the big checks, the broadcasters who write even bigger
checks, and the athletes in places so poor they cannot even afford
a team uniform or a pair of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   All of us depend on a public that believes the Olympic Games are
higher, purer, and more noble than any other sporting event in the
world. Though it doesn't happen very often, the interests of the
poorest athlete and the richest corporation are exactly the same
here: we all want the Olympic Games to stand for an integrity that
can't be bought. They have no value to any of us if they don't.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: David F. D'Alessandro is president and chief operations
officer of John Hancock Financial Services. A noted expert on
sports marketing, he is the architect of the company's Olympics
strategy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 1558EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4385 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT &LR;      02-13 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT HOME: PAYING OFF CO-OP SHARE LOANS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Co-op shareholders, like home buyers, usually borrow
money to purchase their apartments. And just like homeowners, they
must also make sure to tie up any loose ends that may remain when
they pay off their loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a whole series of things to watch out for when you
pay off a share loan,'' said Arthur Weinstein, vice president of
the Council of New York Cooperatives and Condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case with mortgages, he said, share loans are usually
``secured loans'' _ meaning that in addition to giving the lender a
promissory note for the amount of the loan, a borrower also
provides the lender with a lien against the borrower's property.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of the lien are specified in a document known as the
security agreement. Unlike homeowners, who pledge real estate as
security for their loans, co-op shareholders instead pledge stock
certificates showing the number of shares allotted to their units
as well as their proprietary leases.
</P>
<P>
   As with home mortgages, Weinstein said, co-op security
agreements are filed in the public records to inform prospective
purchasers of the presence of the outstanding loan and the lien it
imposes on the property. Rather than being ``recorded'' like a
mortgage, however, the lien created by a share loan is evidenced
instead by filing with the county clerk a legal document known as a
UCC-1 Financing Statement.
</P>
<P>
   The UCC-1, Weinstein explained, is a form promulgated under the
provisions of the Uniform Commercial Code, a federal law that
governs certain commercial transactions. Like a recorded mortgage,
he said, a filed UCC-1 form provides public notice of the lender's
security interest in the borrower's property.
</P>
<P>
   The requirements of many lenders, however, go beyond having only
the filed UCC-1 form as security for a share loan. In fact,
Weinstein said, lenders typically demand actual, physical
possession of both the original stock certificate and a duplicate
of the borrower's proprietary lease bearing original signatures.
Moreover, he said, lenders will also insist upon receiving what is
known as a ``recognition agreement'' from the co-op itself.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Greenstein, another Manhattan co-op lawyer, said that the
recognition agreement, which is signed by the borrower, the lender
and the co-op corporation, commits the co-op not to cancel the
stock or the lease or to allow additional financing without the
consent of the lender.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also requires the co-op to notify the lender if
the borrower fails to make monthly maintenance payments. That
provision is significant for co-op lenders, Greenstein said,
because a co-op lien for unpaid maintenance charges takes
precedence over the lien of the lender. The recognition agreement,
he explained, gives the lender the opportunity to make payments on
behalf of a defaulted borrower to prevent the co-op from
foreclosing.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Greenstein said, co-op lenders will typically require
two other documents _ a signed stock power and a signed assignment
of the proprietary lease, which give the lender the right to
transfer the shares and lease into its own name or the name of a
third party. Both documents become operative only if the borrower
defaults on the loan and the bank forecloses under the security
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Greenstein said, with most co-op share loans there
will be at least eight separate loan documents required and held by
the lender: the promissory note, the security agreement, the UCC-1,
the original stock certificate, a duplicate proprietary lease with
original signatures, a stock power and assignment of proprietary
lease, and the recognition agreement. Most of them, he said, should
be accounted for when the loan is paid in full.
</P>
<P>
   As with a mortgage, Greenstein said, a share loan can be
satisfied in a number of ways _ it may be paid in full over the
full term of the loan, paid early in a lump sum from the borrower's
own funds, or paid early in a lump sum out of the proceeds of a
sale of the apartment or a refinancing of the loan.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how or when the loan is satisfied, Greenstein said,
the borrower should insure that the lender returns at the very
least the promissory note, the stock certificate, the proprietary
lease and the stock power and assignment of lease. The lender
should also provide the borrower with what is known as a UCC-3
Termination Statement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The UCC-3 terminates the UCC-1,'' Greenstein said, adding that
for that to happen the UCC-3 form must be filed in the same
government office that the UCC-1 was originally filed. Moreover, he
said, borrowers should make sure that all of the information on the
UCC-3 matches exactly the information contained on the original
UCC-1.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Racht, a Manhattan co-op lawyer, said that it was not
unusual for borrowers who pay off their share loans to receive a
UCC-3 form from their lender and then fail to file it. It is also
possible that the UCC-3 form prepared by the lender contains
incorrect information and cannot be used to terminate the UCC-1.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, Ms. Racht said, that could create problems when
the shareholder wants to sell the apartment because the original
lien will still be reflected on the records. Such problems can be
magnified significantly, she said _ with accompanying time spent by
lawyers dealing with the situation _ if the original UCC-3 form is
lost by the shareholder or if the original lender has gone out of
business or cannot be located.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Ms. Racht said, it is for that reason that it is
imperative for a borrower who has paid off a share loan to receive
and safely file the original promissory note, the stock
certificates and the proprietary lease. It is also useful, she
said, to request the return of the original security agreement _
marked ``canceled'' _ and the original ``recognition agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   The note and security agreement, she said, can be used to prove
that the loan has been paid. The stock certificates and proprietary
lease, she said, will be required at the time of sale. And the
recognition agreement, Ms. Racht said, could be useful if the co-op
has not reflected the payment of the loan on its books.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Ms. Racht said, shareholders who take out home equity
loans or lines of credit need to be particularly vigilant with
regard to UCC-1 liens. In most cases, she said, home equity lenders
will file UCC-1 Financing Statements when a loan or line of credit
is established. As a result, she said, it is necessary for
borrowers who pay off their equity loans or cancel their lines of
credit to insure that the lender provides them with a UCC-3
Termination Statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can really be a big problem,'' Ms. Racht said. ``Because
you can end up with a UCC-1 lien sitting out there for an equity
line of credit you haven't even tapped.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
