<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUSPECT-INQUIRY-2T     02-13 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUSPECT-INQUIRY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISITING A KILLING: MANY DETAILS, BUT A MYSTERY REMAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-SUSPECT-AFRICANS, NY-SUSPECT-BULLETS) 
 (bl)  
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When four plainclothes police officers arrived for
work in the Bronx at 9:30 p.m. 11 days ago, the mission of their
late-night tour was as clear as the evening sky.
</P>
<P>
   They were members of the Street Crime Unit, assigned to patrol
the 43rd Precinct in an unmarked car, keeping a wary eye out for
crimes in progress, people with illegal guns and a rapist who had
terrorized 44 women.
</P>
<P>
   But less than three hours later, the officers' lives would be
capsized, an unarmed West African immigrant would be dead at their
feet and the often strained relationship between the Police
Department and the city's many minority groups would again be as
tense as a trigger finger.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of perhaps no more than 10 seconds, investigators
believe, the officers fired a fusillade of 41 shots at Amadou
Diallo, a 22-year-old street peddler, killing him and raising a
series of questions about how an unarmed man with a spotless record
came to be gunned down in the doorway of his apartment building in
the Soundview section.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many of those questions remain unanswered because the
officers have yet to speak to investigators and detectives have yet
to find anyone else who witnessed their initial encounter with
Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   The largest of those questions _ and one that even police union
officials have been unable to answer _ is what could explain the
explosive barrage of bullets unleashed against what many neighbors
have described as a thoroughly mild-mannered man.
</P>
<P>
   But through a review of official police documents and interviews
with law enforcement officials, lawyers for the officers, and
neighbors of Diallo, the broad outlines of what occurred on Wheeler
Avenue in the early morning hours of Feb. 4 can be discerned.
</P>
<P>
   That night, less than two hours after driving their maroon Ford
Taurus off Randalls Island, where their unit's headquarters are,
the officers responded with several other patrol cars to a report
of an officer needing assistance, just blocks from the shooting
scene. In that incident, an officer had been injured around 11 p.m.
when he fell down the stairs of a building at 1261 Boynton Avenue
while trying to arrest two youths on assault and drug possession
charges.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they arrived, however, their lawyer said, the
suspects had been arrested, so Officers Kenneth Boss, Sean Carroll,
Edward McMellon and Richard Murphy resumed patrol. Although as
white men, the officers did not blend in with the largely minority
community they were in, they were dressed unobtrusively in gray and
black sweatshirts, blue jeans and sneakers. McMellon also had on a
baseball hat.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, which remains unclear, at 12:40 a.m. the
officers drove down Wheeler Avenue, a one-way street of two-story,
red-brick homes where Diallo lived. A witness has told the Bronx
district attorney's office, which is leading the investigation,
that while parking his car before the shooting he spotted Diallo in
the vestibule of Diallo's building at 1157 Wheeler Ave. and saw
Diallo peering up and down the street, as if he was waiting for
somebody.
</P>
<P>
   That witness was not there when the shooting started, police
officials said, so it remains unclear just what about Diallo caught
the officers' attention. The officers' union lawyer, Stephen Worth,
has said the officers believed that Diallo fit the generic
description of the rapist for whom they were looking.
</P>
<P>
   The officers double-parked and McMellon and Carroll started up
the stairs to Diallo's building, while Murphy and Boss trailed
behind. All had their badges out, Worth said, and all identified
themselves as police officers.
</P>
<P>
   But Worth said Diallo appeared to have a problem understanding
and responding to the officers' shouted commands. Diallo's friends
have disputed the notion that he had a problem understanding
English. At some point in the encounter, according to Worth's
account, the officers believed that Diallo was reaching for a gun
and, believing their lives were in jeopardy, opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo was hit by 19 of the 41 bullets fired at him; 11 of them
struck his legs, and one hit his right arm. The other seven struck
his torso. His body fell back against the wall of the vestibule and
slid to the floor, where it was found, propped up at the waist in a
slouched sitting position, investigators said. Near his body
investigators found a beeper and his wallet, police officials said,
which are perhaps the items he was reaching for when the police
fired. In his pants pocket were his house keys.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear which of the officers shot first, although a
person who has heard the officers' account of the events that night
said there is no disagreement among them over which of them first
began shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators estimate that the closest officers, McMellon and
Carroll, fired at Diallo from the building's stoop, perhaps at a
distance of 5 to 12 feet. One spent shell casing was found inside
the vestibule near Diallo's body, but investigators believe it may
have been kicked there in the shooting's chaotic aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   The city medical examiner's office has declined to say whether
any powder burns were found on Diallo's body, which would indicate
that he was shot at very close range.
</P>
<P>
   Police have traced at least three of the bullets that hit Diallo
to the guns of McMellon, Carol and Boss. They have yet to trace a
bullet that struck him to Murphy's gun, although the ballistic
tests are still being conducted.
</P>
<P>
   The most puzzling question to be answered is whether any factor,
aside from panic, prompted the officers to fire so many times. So
far, three possible theories have emerged.
</P>
<P>
   The first theory is that the officers may have mistakenly
believed they were being fired on because some of their own bullets
appear to have ricocheted off the wall. One of the officers, Sean
Carroll, has turned in a pair of pants that he says he was wearing
that night which have a small hole in one leg, possibly created by
a wayward bullet, a person close to the officer said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A second theory being advanced is that Diallo did not fall down
immediately upon being shot because the bullets passed so quickly
and cleanly through his body, leading officers to continue firing.
</P>
<P>
   A third theory holds that the other officers may have become
confused when McMellon fell back on the stairs during the shooting,
and believed he had been hit. The officer suffered a fractured
tailbone in the incident. His colleague, Carroll, also said after
the shooting that he had hurt his right knee, left foot and neck,
although it is not clear how.
</P>
<P>
   When the shooting ceased, several witnesses have reported that
the officers appeared distraught, apparently after realizing that
Diallo had no gun. One police supervisor said Boss appeared ``dazed
and teary-eyed'' as he sat in the back of a police car after the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could not speak and just indicated with a hand gesture that
he was OK,'' a police official said, speaking on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials have said that none of the officers made
statements about what occurred at the scene and they have not been
questioned since. Barry Scheck, a lawyer for the Diallo family,
said Saturday that he found it discomforting that New York
officials do not do more to question officers immediately after
fatal shootings, before they have a chance to coordinate their
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every other city in America, when a shooting like this goes
down, the officers are asked, `What happened, man?''' Scheck said.
</P>
<P>
   But Worth said officers in shootings that are investigated as
criminal matters are never questioned here because no officer under
scrutiny would be careless enough to disregard his constitutional
right to avoid self-incrimination or agree to be interviewed
without his lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``To suggest that police officers should be brought into the
stationhouse and somehow attempted to be questioned is ludicrous,''
he said. ``These are police officers who advise people of their
constitutional rights on a daily basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the officers were taken to the emergency room at
Westchester Square Hospital in the Bronx, where they waited for
approximately four hours to be treated, according to members of the
hospital staff. In addition to the orthopedic injuries reported by
McMellon and Carroll, some of the officers were suffering from
trauma, police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the officers became upset that they were being
forced to wait so long to be seen by a doctor and lodged a
complaint with the hospital's administrators. A spokesman for the
hospital, vice president Lisa Nenner, declined comment on the
incident.
</P>
</TEXT>
