<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-OAKLEY-ART-2TAKES     02-13 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-OAKLEY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAKLEY IS COMING HOME, BUT DON'T EXPECT HUGS AND KISSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Canada)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Corine Oakley kept fussing with the satellite dish
outside her Cleveland home last week, turning and twisting to no
avail. She went back inside and tried the remote again. Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 10 years, she could not watch her son's
games on television. On the screen and in spirit, Charles Oakley
had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to change my dish around, go to the cable company or
do something,'' she said. ``Some days, I hate to talk to Charles,''
she added. ``He sounds so low. He just stays in his hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley still receives the pro-rated balance of his $10 million
salary and gets to play basketball for a living. But he never
dreamed the final years of his career would involve high-fiving a
Raptors' mascot and watching his 20-something teammates fold in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The power forward who never wanted to leave Madison Square
Garden returns to New York on Tuesday night. He brings not only the
tenacity and grit that endeared him to Knick fans the past decade,
but also the resentment that comes with being traded from a
contender to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't leave on bad terms, I didn't trade myself,'' Oakley
said. ``Maybe they should announce my name and then call Ernie out
there and ask him if he has anything to say,'' he said, referring
to Ernie Grunfeld, the Knicks' team president and general manager
who made the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Seven months after he was dealt to Toronto for Marcus Camby, the
subject remains an open wound for Oakley. In reflecting on it and
his career in New York, he was candid about his feelings about his
former teammates, management, the future of the Knicks and his
gradual adjustment to playing for an expansion franchise. From
Grunfeld to Patrick Ewing, no one was spared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the talent around him gets better,'' Oakley said
of Ewing. ``I don't know if he needs to take less shots or what.
But something in his game needs to change for them to be a better
team. Over the years, he's always been the main focus. Can he
accept somebody else getting the spotlight? The more he can accept,
the better off the team will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Knicks' new acquisitions, he added: ``When a lot of guys
need the ball, it's hard to gel. Larry trying to sacrifice, Allan
need the ball, Sprewell need it, Patrick need it. Then you get a
Dennis Scott. All he does is shoot 3's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many of those new guys have playoff
experience. You got to look at that, too. I know Dennis Scott went
to the finals. He didn't hit a shot, I think.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley, who will be a free agent after this season, is still
undecided about his future, so much so that he isn't sure whether
to buy or rent. For now, he occupies a corner suite of a posh,
Victorian-style hotel near the Raptors' new arena in downtown
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   An open box of Frosted Flakes rested on the television console.
A pair of briefs hung over the TV. Eighteen pairs of dress shoes _
from Mauri to Pablo De Marco _ were strewn around the front room.
Always the fashion plate, Oakley had two clothing racks brought in
to hold 70 or so of his designer suits. More overburdened than
anything being wheeled around the Garment District, the two racks
stand on opposite sides of his bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Miniature speakers connected to his compact disc player anchor
both ends of an ornate fireplace mantle. A crystal chandelier and a
mahogany china cabinet occupy the room, too. It's an odd fit, as if
the National Basketball Association's king of grunt work was
awkwardly thrust into a Merchant and Ivory screenplay, alongside
Emma Thompson and Anthony Hopkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different,'' Oakley said. ``All they talk about is
hockey, hockey, hockey. The money is different. They say Toronto is
like New York, but I haven't been out.''
</P>
<P>
   In Manhattan, Oakley was the consummate socialite. One night
after a game, he would stop by Cafe 31 next to the Garden. Other
nights, he would hold court at the Shark Bar on the Upper West
Side. In Toronto, he watches CNN, checks his stocks and telephones
his friends to take the pulse of New York and reminisce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great time my 10 years,'' Oakley said of his tenure in
New York. ``I know I had ups and downs and people might not always
like the way you do things. But deep down inside, I gave my best
every night. That's all I could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't go out there and try to shortcut it. Some nights, I
didn't get double-figure rebounds, but I'd try to do something
else. You always got to work. It's all about work. You ain't doing
one thing, do something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Along those lines, Oakley already has made his mark with the
Raptors. In four games, he's averaging 9 points and 8 rebounds. He
bought his teammates T-shirts that read ``Strictly Business'' the
first few days of training camp. To make sure he was not acquired
to babysit, Oakley and the veteran center Kevin Willis met with
Coach Butch Carter before the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were about the business of basketball and not about the
business of taking care of young guys and letting them run the
place,'' Carter said. ``I assured them that there would be a dress
code on the airplane and no extra people allowed in the locker
room.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley said, ``It's a job, not a day-care center.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, he's the same old Oak. Beyond the banging inside,
he still tries to get away with a few behind-the-back passes and an
ill-advised shot or two during the course of a game. He humors his
teammates by knocking rookies down and telling them in very abrupt
terms to get back up.
</P>
<P>
   But the trade has made the calluses pile up faster than the
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to be respected,'' he said. ``I had a run-in
with Ernie and Checketts,'' he said of Grunfeld and Dave Checketts,
the Garden president. ``It wasn't a respectful conversation, so
that gave me some hints and views about life and issues, about,
`Don't let anyone ever know your hole card.'''
</P>
<P>
   He compared the Garden's corporate structure to a seedy
back-room card game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like playing poker,'' he said. ``You see somebody
standing around a table, and you never know why he's standing
around. Sometimes, he's trying to look at your hand. You're
watching a Western movie and they're playing cards, and people
standing around. You never knew who's playing together.''
</P>
<P>
   His brutally honest comments, he said, did not always mesh well
with an image-consumed franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, all I tried to do was show them my respect,
this and that,'' he said. ``We sat down at midseason. Sometimes,
they didn't want to hear the truth. They'd be like, `We know this,
but we don't want anyone else to know.' They always try to control
what you say in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Never fully elaborating, he said: ``Some things were said in a
conversation with us that I thought wasn't the proper thing that
should have been said. Even though I didn't let it stop my
performance on the court, I always knew that anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Corine Oakley drove five hours north from Cleveland to be with
Oakley's sister, Saralene, last Tuesday night to see her son play.
Sitting in her seat at Maple Leaf Gardens, she recalled the
Grunfeld family visiting her Cleveland home during the All-Star
Game in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him, `Would you ever trade Charles?' while he was
eating the food I cooked for him and his family. Ernie said, `Oh,
no, we'll never trade Charles.'''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley was in Virginia on draft day last June, having a good
time with friends. He had heard rumors, but had not received the
call from Grunfeld until about 12:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `What?' He said, `We wanted to get younger,' and I
said, `You ain't gotta say nothing to me. Bye.'''
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld tried to further explain the trade, but Oakley
interrupted, recalling that he said: ``If I'm traded, I'm traded.
I'm no longer your commodity.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley said their next exchange came during a face-to-face
encounter at John Starks' annual golf outing in September. When
Grunfeld approached Oakley and his friends at a table, Oakley
refused to shake his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you want to shake my hand?'' Oakley asked. ``You just
traded me. You shouldn't even want to deal with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers said Grunfeld left shaken and disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld said he does not remember the specific conversation
with Oakley's mother and added: ``We had tremendous respect for Oak
and what he did for the franchise. It's never easy to trade a
player, especially a player you have a long history with. But
that's part of the business. There may be a handful of guys that
have never been traded in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing said: ``He's a great player. I miss him and I wish he was
still here.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Corine Oakley. While she concedes that her son was lucky
to play for the same team for 10 years, Corine, like a lot of
people at the Garden, misses seeing Charles in a Knicks uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will be missing Oakley in other ways, too. For the
last decade, Oakley brought his teammates home at least once a year
to eat his mother's cooking. Corine would even alter the menu,
making string beans with turkey because Ewing did not like pork.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard one of the Knicks players ask, `Is Mrs. Oakley going
to cook for us when we go to Cleveland?''' Corine Oakley said.
</P>
<P>
   She smiled ruefully and shook her head. ``I don't think so.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
