<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4390 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SUSPECT-BULLETS-57     02-13 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUSPECT-BULLETS-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR SAYS OFFICERS' NEW AMMUNITION WILL BE SAFER
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-SUSPECT-AFRICANS, NY-SUSPECT-INQUIRY) 
(jw) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Saturday that the Police
Department would issue hollow-point bullets to officers in the
coming months, adding that the decision was based on a concern for
public safety.
</P>
<P>
   These bullets, which differ from regular ball ammunition in
their ability to expand greatly on impact, cause greater injury to
people they strike but are less likely to pass through a body and
hit bystanders. In July, the department first announced that its
40,000-member force would be issued the new ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to the conclusion a few months ago after studying it
very carefully that hollow-point bullets would actually be safer
than the bullets that were being used,'' said Giuliani, joined by
Police Commissioner Howard Safir at a City Hall news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether it was prudent to issue officers bullets that
cause more serious injury, Safir said studies comparing the two
types of ammunition had found that fatalities were about the same.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came as reporters peppered Giuliani and Safir
with questions about the Feb. 4 killing of Amadou Diallo, an
unarmed street peddler who was shot by four officers from a street
crimes unit who were patrolling in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials have long complained that ball
ammunition, like that used by New York City police officers, has
less stopping power than hollow-point ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Most municipal and federal law enforcement agencies have already
switched to hollow-point ammunition, and the New York City Police
Department began testing several different brands last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't happy with the performance of the first brand, then
we tried another,'' said Marilyn Mode, a department spokeswoman.
``We expect to have delivery within the month and everything should
be fully implemented within six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of getting the officers to the shooting
range to get qualified to shoot the new ammunition,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who favor replacing ball ammunition point out that with
conventional bullets, an officer must fire more bullets to bring a
suspect down and that the ball ammunition can pass through a
suspect or ricochet, sometimes hitting unintended targets. The
officers who killed Diallo fired 41 times, leaving several holes in
the wall of his apartment building vestibule before he slumped to
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the department's plans to switch to hollow-point
bullets said the mayor's announcement was merely an attempt to
defuse criticism of the officers' use of extraordinary firepower in
the Diallo case.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the overriding criticisms coming from the Diallo
shooting was the number of shots fired,'' said Norman Siegel,
executive director of the New York Civil Liberties Union. ``With
the change to hollow-point bullets, they are attempting to make the
argument that you won't have to fire 41 shots any longer. You will
have to fire less times to take a person down.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel added that the mayor and police commissioner should be
concentrating on the weapons training that officers received and
how they were taught to interact with people on the streets. ``Cops
should not see every young African-American man they pass as a
profile for a criminal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said he and representatives of the NAACP Legal Defense
and Educational Fund had asked state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer
to create a special police misconduct legal unit within his office.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The office would monitor complaints of police brutality,
maintain a database that tracked patterns of reported and confirmed
acts of police misconduct, and would develop a team of
investigators that could help district attorneys when prosecuting
police misconduct cases, Siegel said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, Diallo's family joined the Rev. Al Sharpton at
the headquarters of his National Action Network in Harlem for his
weekly radio broadcast and a rally.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton reiterated his call for Giuliani to suspend or arrest
the four officers who shot Diallo, and he announced a series of
gatherings and protests in the coming weeks, starting with a
motorcade to Newark International Airport in New Jersey on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo's body is being flown home to Guinea in West Africa for
burial.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton also announced that the Diallo family would set up a
foundation to finance scholarships for African students studying in
America and to support families victimized by police brutality. He
said he would make the first donation, of $500.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo's parents, uncle and cousin spoke briefly at the rally.
``I miss my cousin, I miss my friend,'' Neneh Kallay, 24, said.
``All I ask is justice.'' As Diallo's mother nodded, Ms. Kallay
said, ``I know wherever he is, he's smiling down on us _ he's
saying, `Thank you, thank you very much.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The mother of Patrick Baily, who was shot and killed by Officer
Kenneth Boss in Brooklyn in October 1997, spoke at the rally. Boss
is one of the four officers who shot Diallo; the shooting of Baily
is still under investigation by the Brooklyn district attorney's
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had done something when my son was killed,'' Evadine
Baily said, ``this kid would still be alive today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
