<SLUG> BC-NY-NJ-PORT-SHIPPERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORT AUTHORITY STRUGGLES TO KEEP 2 SHIPPERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Md.)  (bl) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Executives of the Port Authority of New York and New
Jersey are scrambling to prevent two shipping lines that transport
billions of dollars' worth of cargo through the harbor from moving
to Baltimore, even as New York and New Jersey are locked in a
bitter struggle over subsidies intended to keep them here.
</P>
<P>
   Sea-Land Service and Maersk Line, whose sprawling operations at
the Elizabeth Marine Terminal in New Jersey handle a quarter of all
the container cargo moving through the port, have threatened to
move to Baltimore, which has a harbor with deeper channels and has
offered subsidies that would cut their costs by tens of millions of
dollars. The two carriers, which together have about 1,000
employees and a $100 million payroll, rejected the Port Authority's
last offer in September.
</P>
<P>
   Top commissioners at the Port Authority, Lewis Eisenberg of New
Jersey and Charles Gargano of New York, are to review a new
proposal from the carriers on Tuesday; that may lead to talks that
will narrow the gap between New York and Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations have taken on increasing urgency because
Sea-Land's long-term lease in Elizabeth expires at the end of the
month and Maersk's leases expire over the next 16 months. The two
companies, which have an operating alliance, say they will make a
final decision in March on whether to build a hub port for North
American trade in Baltimore or greatly expand the one at the
Elizabeth Marine Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains unclear whether New York and New Jersey can forge
a united front to deal with Sea-Land and Maersk. The leases have
become entwined in the disputes between the two states about the
Port Authority. New York, which has taken a tougher stance with the
companies, contends that New Jersey has long received too much of
the agency's revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has emerged as the port is poised to invest billions
of dollars in new construction and deeper channels to accommodate
the huge hulls of a new generation of container vessels. The
changes are aimed at tripling the port's cargo volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an absolutely crucial issue,'' said H. Claude Shostal,
president of the Regional Plan Association, a private planning
group for the two states. ``We risk losing a significant portion of
the shipping industry to Baltimore and Halifax, Nova Scotia. We'd
better get serious about retaining this business or we're going to
see a serious economic engine weakened.''
</P>
<P>
   New York and New Jersey diverge in their approaches to the
negotiations. Fearing that the departure of Sea-Land, a unit of the
CSX Corporation of Richmond, and Maersk, owned by the Danish
conglomerate A.P. Moller, could prompt other defections, New Jersey
Gov. Christie Whitman and her representatives at the Port Authority
have been more willing to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Given the fierce competition in the industry, Sea-Land has said
it cannot afford the rent proposed by the Port Authority, which
would jump immediately from about $19,000 an acre annually to
$36,000 and rise to $106,000 over the life of a 29-year agreement.
Governor Whitman is now assembling a package of tax breaks and
other incentives to sweeten the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Gargano has taken a harder line with the companies, which his
supporters say are unlikely to relocate because much of their cargo
is destined for the New York metropolitan region. According to one
Port Authority official, the rent proposal rejected by Sea-Land and
Maersk already had a hefty subsidy built into it, because the Port
Authority would be spending $456 million more on dredging and
bulkhead improvements than it would get back in rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those companies are bluffing,'' the official said. ``This is
supposed to be a negotiation. But New Jersey has practically
written them a blank check.''
</P>
<P>
   Port Authority officials say that Hanjin, the giant Korean
shipper, has signed an agreement with the authority to build its
own terminal in Elizabeth and at a higher rent than is now being
proposed for Sea-Land.
</P>
<P>
   David Shuman, a transportation consultant with R.L. Banks &AMP;
Associates who has worked with Baltimore, shares some of Gargano's
skepticism about the companies' true intentions, particularly after
Vice President Al Gore announced in January that the federal
government would provide 75 percent of the costs of a five-year,
$733 million dredging project in New York Harbor. The announcement
addressed the most important demand by Maersk, which is building a
fleet of deep-hulled ships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore's announcement was devastating news for us,'' Shuman
said. ``Our sense was that it's New York's to lose and the other
ports were being strung along.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tommy Tomsen, president of Maersk, insisted that his company
was not using Baltimore as a bargaining ploy. ``We're not
bluffing,'' he said. ``Baltimore has developed a real alternative.
This decision could go either way.''
</P>
<P>
   James White, executive director of the Maryland Port
Administration, acknowledged that every port on the Eastern
Seaboard that competed for Sea-Land and Maersk ``wondered whether
they were serious.'' But, he said, their proposal to build a
335-acre facility at the Dundalk Marine Terminal has won the
attention of the company's executives.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   New York's stand has alarmed some politicians.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to New York Gov. George Pataki, Assemblywoman
Elizabeth Connelly of Staten Island complained that New York's
``take it or leave it'' approach with the carriers was threatening
jobs at the Howland Hook container port on Staten Island, as well
as in Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   Gargano, vice chairman of the Port Authority, said he was
concerned about the loss of jobs. ``We're making every effort
possible to accommodate Sea-Land and Maersk,'' he said. ``But there
are limits.''
</P>
<P>
   James Devine, general manager for Sea-Land in Elizabeth, said
the Port Authority was unfairly seeking to recover the cost of
dredging the harbor from the carriers. Instead, he said, those
costs should be borne by both states. ``They're coming at us for
the historic pollution and siltation of the New York harbor,'' he
said. ``That's what's driving the costs to untenable levels.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that the negotiations did not get off to an
auspicious start in the spring of 1997 with an incident that was
either a misunderstanding or a signal that both sides should be
ready to play hardball. During an outing at the Fiddler's Elbow
golf course in New Jersey, a Sea-Land executive, Nick Taro,
welcomed the new executive director of the Port Authority, Robert
Boyle, saying the two men would be seeing a lot of each other at
the upcoming lease negotiations. According to shipping industry
executives, Boyle responded: ``There won't be any negotiations.
We'll give you a price and you'll sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Port Authority executives do not dispute the remarks, but they
now say that Boyle thought Taro was referring to another, unrelated
maritime issue.
</P>
<P>
   After months of fruitless talks, Sea-Land and Maersk issued an
invitation to other East Coast ports to bid for their business.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Maersk highlighted the need for dredging in New York
Harbor by bringing into Elizabeth the Regina Maersk, the largest
ship ever to steam into the harbor. Maersk explained that much of
the massive ship's cargo had to be unloaded in Halifax before it
could navigate the relatively shallow channels in New York. The
message was clear: if New York and New Jersey wanted the carriers
to stay put it had better find the money to dredge the harbor for a
new generation of super ships.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the lease has become a bargaining chip between
New York and New Jersey. If New Jersey wants help for the maritime
industry, New York wants additional funds for new airline terminals
at Kennedy International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to satisfy New Jersey,'' said a senior New York
official, ``then we need something, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Verplanck, president of the New Jersey Chamber of Commerce,
took a dim view of the disputes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' she said, ``is that while they're duking it
out on minor issues, we may see a major shipping industry literally
go south.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
