<HEADER>
A4400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENNELLY-PROFILE-NYT &LR;      02-13 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNELLY-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CONGRESSWOMAN WILL BECOME SOCIAL SECURITY COUNSEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (bl) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Barbara Kennelly, the newly retired U.S.
congresswoman, found running for governor last fall a grim chore
but always beamed when congressional votes took her back to her
beloved Washington. Tuesday, she starts a new job there promoting
the passage of President Clinton's plan to insure the solvency of
Social Security, and the glow is back.
</P>
<P>
   Chatting this week in her home here just four blocks from the
governor's mansion, which nevertheless remained far out of reach as
she struggled to evict Gov. John G. Rowland, Mrs. Kennelly, a
Democrat, said the offer from the White House came as a surprise,
but the position seems suited to her fervor for legislation and her
16 years of friendships on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Already, she is talking about her new job in the argot of
legislative ``sausage-making'' and invoking the longtime former
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, where for eight
years she was the only woman. ``That's what it's all about _ to get
enough votes,'' she said. ``I learned it under Danny Rostenkowski:
it doesn't matter how good your legislation is if you can't get it
out of committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly had been courted by several corporate boards, and
was offered a teaching position at one of her alma maters, Trinity
College in Hartford. ``It would have been a nice life, but I'm not
ready for that yet,'' she said. ``You just can't go as fast as I
was going and work as hard as I worked, and then drop it. So now
I've got to go back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Her landslide defeat in November seemed an unfitting final
career entry for Mrs. Kennelly, who has spent most of her 62 years
feasting on politics, first as the daughter of John Bailey, who was
chairman of both the Connecticut and national Democratic parties,
and later as the wife of James Kennelly, who was speaker of the
Connecticut House of Representatives. Then she took up the family
business, as a Hartford councilwoman and later as secretary of
state. It all ended so fast.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of a recent phone conversation, when asked whether
she was on another line, she replied bluntly, ``I only have one
line these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, her title will be counselor at the Social Security
Administration, and she will make $125,900, a bit less than a
member of Congress but more than the governor. She has taken the
job for a year and thinks it should be clear by then whether the
president's plan will pass. ``If things are moving still, of course
I'll stay for a second year,'' she said. ``But if it's not going to
happen, why?''
</P>
<P>
   Word of Mrs. Kennelly's awkward campaign style, which was
typified by the afternoon when a rally about health care flopped
and she kept telling puzzled reporters it was ``a honey of a day,''
were a mystery to people who knew her in Washington, where she was
a respected and skilled back-room operator. ``The last couple of
months were rough, just keeping going,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after the election, Mrs. Kennelly has achieved such
a clinical distance from her 28-point loss to Rowland that she is
almost eager to offer an armchair autopsy, and said she would do
the same in private sessions with Democrats who are thinking of
running statewide. ``I'll be happy to tell them about all the
mistakes I made,'' she said cheerily.
</P>
<P>
   The main lesson, she said, is that people get most of their
political information from television commercials and polls. ``If
you don't have the money lined up, don't bother,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly had never had a tough congressional race, and
admits she was utterly unprepared to challenge a popular incumbent.
She said she had thought that if she were willing to run, the
Connecticut Democratic Party would rush to help her. Instead, she
said, she found herself struggling alone to hire staff members and
raise money. ``The naivete, really, is stunning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the election, she retreated to a childhood friend's island
home off Vero Beach, Fla. She played golf every day, then returned
to Hartford, her lifelong home, to close her campaign office. She
had finished shuttering her Capitol Hill office by the time she was
called back for the Dec. 18 debate and the Dec. 19 vote on
impeaching the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was good for me,'' she said. ``It let me go back, and I
saw everybody, so it's over. You say your good-byes _ closure,
really.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kennelly was still the vice chairwoman of the House
Democratic Caucus and helped run the impeachment strategy meetings,
but she was one of the few Democrats who did not go to the White
House after the House voted to impeach Clinton. ``They acted like
it was over,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was her final vote. She thought she was gone for good. She
said she was honored when the University of Connecticut, in Storrs,
asked to house her papers, and she shipped 82 boxes. A freight
service filled the basement of her home here with the photographs,
awards and statuettes from her suite in the Cannon House Office
Building. On Wednesday, her desk arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Heading back to Washington, one of her first chores will be
house hunting: she passed along her longtime apartment to her 1st
District successor, Rep. John Larson. ``I'll be all right,'' she
said. ``I've got friends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
