u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-NY-SUBURBS-NYT &LR;      02-13 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-NY-SUBURBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBURBS TAKE PRECAUTIONS AGAINST 2000 COMPUTER FLAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALLEY STREAM, N.Y. _ In the millisecond that 1999 turns into
2000, the heat in the village hall will stay on and the lawn
sprinkler system will stay off.
</P>
<P>
   Both are governed by newly installed computerized timers, and
will not be affected by the so-called millennium bug, said Vincent
Ang, the clerk of this Long Island village. Officials also replaced
the village's 15-year-old mainframe computer. Total cost of
compliance: $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Across Long Island, municipalities and businesses are checking
their computers for date-related problems. Nassau County government
alone is expected to spend millions to make sure welfare checks go
out and traffic lights keep working.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how fearful some people are about the approach of
the new millennium,'' Ang said of the Year 2000 problem. ``But
every night on the news we get bombarded with some possible new
tragedy, like the crash of the stock market. It's like the world's
going to come to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But whatever happens, at least I know we're ready,'' he said
about his village of 30,000. ``We've got our new computer system up
and running, and we've installed some new gears in our official
clocks for stamping village records. The gears weren't anything
high tech, but it was still a part of becoming Y2K compliant.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the shorthand for making sure computers will work
properly next year. To save space and memory, many older computers
and programs were designed to specify dates using only the last two
digits of a year. That could cause them to confuse 2000 with 1900.
</P>
<P>
   ``This oversight may even force a computer system to shut down
entirely,'' said Murray Schwartz, a lawyer with Meyer, Suozzi,
English &AMP; Klein who addressed the legal and insurance issues raised
by the problem at a recent seminar in Melville.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possible ramifications have been linked to everything from
commercial Armageddon to the muffled bang of a wet firecracker,''
he told the group. ``And while the answer may lie somewhere in
between, its scope and effect may depend importantly upon measures
taken over the next 11 months.''
</P>
<P>
   While the federal government has so far spent more than $50
billion upgrading its computers, Nassau County government has spent
about $40 million, said County Legislator John Canning, who is
chairman of the Committee on government Service and Operations.
</P>
<P>
   Canning said the county began planning for the changeover in
1994, but still had much to do, especially in the Department of
Social Services, with its many cases involving welfare, Medicaid,
and child support payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're already tracking payments into the next century,'' he
said. ``But since they are not yet entirely Y2K compliant, they've
gone back to pen and paper.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also some lingering concern about the county's 680
computer-operated traffic lights. ``They're running tests on them
now,'' Canning said. ``All we need is countywide gridlock on the
first day of the new millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Nassau and Suffolk County report that their emergency 911
telephone systems are ready. However, Detective Lt. Kevin Caslin,
spokesman for the Nassau County Police Department, said that 300 of
the department's 600 personal computers were still under review.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're already at least five years old, long past the three
to four years they were expected to last, so we're hoping for new
replacements,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Small businesses, some with only one personal computer and very
limited budgets, are also taking precautions. Paul Forchelli, a
partner in a Goodyear tire and auto service shop in Oyster Bay,
said that even though Goodyear had provided him with a computer
that keeps track of his customers and inventory, he will not be
taking any chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come December, I'm making printouts of everything,'' he said.
``For years, I used to put everything down on cards and file them
away by hand. I may go back to the old system for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the precautions being taken, Forchelli, Canning,
Schwartz and Ang all said they planned to spend New Year's Eve at
home with close friends when 2000 arrives. They do not plan to
travel, especially in planes or elevators.
</P>
<P>
   But they attach no cosmic significance to the change in the date
and do not fear a physical end to the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about it,'' said Ang, ``it's pretty presumptive
of us to think that just because we put a time and date on
something, we've got it right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
