<HEADER>
A4404 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHRISTIAN-SCHOOL-2     02-13 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHRISTIAN-SCHOOL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A RELIGIOUS MODEL, SEEDS FOR A CHARTER SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the Rev. Floyd Flake walks into Allen Christian
School, which he founded 17 years ago, the reception he gets is not
exactly divine, but it is a bit better than that accorded most mere
mortals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning, Reverend Flake,'' a class of first graders
eagerly chants, jumping from their seats, instantly recognizing the
tall man with the mustache whose formal portrait hangs next to his
wife's in the school lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning,'' Flake replies, pausing midstride just long
enough to ask, ``Did you do your homework?''
</P>
<P>
   Allen Christian School, a stone's throw from Kennedy
International Airport, is the model for the charter school that
Flake, the former congressman from Queens, wants to create in the
same corner of southeast Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Flake, the senior pastor of the Allen African Methodist
Episcopal Church, is the best known of a handful of inner-city
ministers in New York City who hope to get charters from the state
under the law approved in December, and to create a new model for
secular public education inspired by the values of the neighborhood
church.
</P>
<P>
   The Allen school is unapologetically Methodist, with children
participating in daily sessions of ``praise and worship.'' But
those who believe that his larger agenda is religious, Flake said,
misunderstand his leadership and the role of many black churches in
New York City and across America. The role, he said, is building
community, saving lives and giving children hope for the future as
much as any religious creed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easy to diminish me,'' Flake said. ``Why reduce me to
just a preacher?''
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of a charter school is that it is public, financed by
the taxpayers, yet independent of the Board of Education, Flake
said. So it would bridge the gap between those who can pay the
$3,500-a-year tuition charged by Allen Christian School and those
who cannot.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ministers are not the only ones who want to start
charter schools. Wall Street businessmen, teachers, parents and
civic groups have also expressed an interest, and so has New York
City Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew. Of Flake, Crew said last week,
``I will meet him in the marketplace of ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepping into the Allen school is like stepping into a quaint
photograph from the 1950s. Every classroom features a long list of
homework scribbled in white chalk on a green board. Teachers sit
behind wooden desks at the head of the class, and most students
have been neatly arranged in rows rather than in the small groups
common in many schools today. Posters of historic figures, looking
stiff and distant _ Rosa Parks, the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King
Jr., George Washington, George Washington Carver, John F. Kennedy,
President Clinton _ have been tacked to the walls of hallways and
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to tell who is rich and who is poor at Allen
Christian School. The 480 boys and girls, from prekindergarten to
eighth grade, have surrendered fashion to uniforms: yellow shirts,
blue slacks, ties or neckerchiefs and plaid jumpers. And race is
irrelevant; there are no white students, although Flake said there
are some of mixed race. There are no white teachers or
administrators either, although there is a Filipino, a Cambodian
and a Honduran on the teaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Some charter schools _ notably in North Carolina _ have been
accused of resegregating the schools. Flake scoffs at the notion
that any school he started would resegregate New York City's
schools. ``You cannot be more segregated than the public school
system,'' he said dryly. In the New York City school system, just
16 percent of students over all, and 2.4 percent in his corner of
Queens, are white.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no rationale for fighting a fight about something you
can't change,'' Flake said. ``The best integration, quite frankly,
is a good quality education.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The school has a computer lab, connected to the Internet. In
third grade, all children begin studying Spanish. They learn to
play the recorder. There are two music teachers, a performance band
and a jazz ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of lowering expectations out of fear that some children
will not be able to meet them, the school keeps up a steady
drumbeat of pressure and encouragement _ letters home to parents
and tutoring after school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mrs. R.,'' one letter from a teacher to a parent begins.
``Jordan needs to come to school with his pencils sharpened. He
spent 20 minutes this morning sharpening them. He did not do his
journal work, and he was late copying his homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Corey Harewood, a 13-year-old eighth grader, goes to a teacher's
house with four other students after school to be tutored in math
so he can keep up his 85 average. ``She feeds us,'' he adds
enthusiastically, talking about milk and cookies, not math
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get free Spanish tutoring,'' pipes up his friend Raymond
McGill.
</P>
<P>
   These are teachers, Flake said, who earn $17,500 to $28,000 a
year. The public financing for charter schools, he said, would
allow him to compete with the $45,000 average of public school
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In the second grade, 7-year-old Darnique ticks off a few pithy
observations about learning at Allen Christian: ``If we talk, we
get a lot of homework. We learn to carry the one. We get hard
words. If we get bad grades, we have to do it all over.''
</P>
<P>
   A big blue banner in the lobby blares, ``In the Pursuit of
Excellence.'' But slogans are common in public schools, too. Almost
unheard-of are the lists, posted behind glass, of students who have
met the challenge, scoring high enough on tests to make the
principal's list, the honor roll or the merit roll, in descending
order.
</P>
<P>
   The school, Flake said, has not tried to reinvent its curriculum
or to substitute Bible studies for reading, writing and arithmetic.
Rather, it uses the state curriculum that many public schools
simply ignore, he said. In the fifth grade, children are reading
``The Prince and the Pauper,'' in the sixth grade, ``Animal Farm.''
One day last month, the third grade took a weekly spelling test,
while Faith Mack's second-grade students reviewed what they had
learned about Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it mean, `overthrow'?'' asked Ms. Mack, a tall,
thin, stern teacher with a smile she tries to suppress, passing out
oversize dictionaries to three of the children. ``Why did Mandela
feel that there was such unfairness?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to have a passbook to travel to where you want to
get,'' said Kenneth, a solid, serious-faced boy.
</P>
<P>
   Free-associating, Andrena, the clear beads in her ponytail
rattling, wondered, ``Why didn't Martin Luther King become
president?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to his life?'' Ms. Mack replied tactfully. ``He
had a short life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be president,'' Andrena insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Test scores tell a provocative story. When they are very young,
the children at Allen score the same on average as those in the
surrounding public schools: about 76 percent of third graders score
at minimum competency on the state reading test. But by sixth
grade, a gap has opened, with 89 to 95 percent of Allen students
scoring at minimum competency over the last four years, compared
with 65 to 79 percent of students in the nearby public schools in
Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't spend eight hours a day proselytizing,'' Flake said.
``We teach everything the public schools are teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Allen Christian School does offer its share of religion.
Most of the students do not belong to his church, Flake said, but
they all join in ``praise and worship'' when the bell rings every
day at 8:40 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   One Tuesday last month, Ms. Mack picked three children to lead
the session. Taking their places on a well-worn burgundy rug, they
stood facing the rest of the class of 17. Darnique thrust a black
Bible high into the air with all the strength in her spindly arms
and led the class in the first of several pledges, this one to the
Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pledge allegiance to the Bible, God's holy word,'' the
children began.
</P>
<P>
   Next came the familiar pledge to the United States flag, hanging
over Darnique's right shoulder. Then the pledge to the Christian
flag, hanging over her left shoulder: ``I pledge allegiance to the
Christian flag, and to the Saviour for whose kingdom it stands. One
Saviour, crucified, risen and coming again, with life and liberty
to all who believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they recited the pledge to their school, beginning, ``I
am a unique and gifted individual, made in the image of God,'' and
ending, ``I will let nothing keep me from my destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   The pledges over, the children clapped, danced and sang a medley
of songs, from ``Lift Every Voice'' to ``Kumbaya.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a session lively enough to shake the morning cobwebs out
of any second grader's eyes, and if transferred to a public school,
to alarm more than a few civil libertarians.
</P>
<P>
   Flake said that, if allowed to start a charter school, he could
relegate religion to before or after school and meet the
constitutional requirements of separating church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Founding a public school, said Flake, who just turned 54, is the
logical next step in a 23-year career as a minister, whose church
has grown to 10,000 people from 1,400, and as a congressman. Before
resigning from Congress in 1997, he brought millions of dollars in
state and federal money into his district, developing, owning,
managing or controlling 26 blocks of housing, health services, a
charter bus company and strip malls.
</P>
<P>
   Just as his church has taken over underperforming retail strips,
chasing out the drug dealers, so he wants to reinvent failing
public schools in the image of Allen Christian.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a hustle,'' Flake said. ``School is part of what
we do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
