<SLUG> BC-VETERAN-ENEMIES-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ up the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There I was, kneeling to cut the grass over the graves of my
men, and all around me my former enemies were helping me do it.
That really solidified my feelings of reconciliation.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after he returned to the United States that year, Donlon
was named executive director of the Westmoreland Scholar
Foundation, an organization dedicated to ``rebuilding bridges of
understanding between the people of Vietnam and the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation provides scholarships for Vietnamese-American
students at three Kansas City area colleges. It also recently
sponsored two ``scholar-interns'' who spent a summer working at a
hospital in Danang.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next phase, we'll start bringing Vietnamese students
here,'' said Donlon, who is donating all the proceeds from his
privately sold autobiography to the scholarship fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see,'' said Norma Donlon, ``the true warrior spirit is not
just about war and killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A real hero is a person who does the right thing every day,
not because someone is watching, but simply because it's the right
way to live.''
</P>
<P>
   For information about Roger Donlon's autobiography, call (913)
772-5480 or send e-mail to Donlon2wsf &LR; aol.com
</P>
</TEXT>
