<HEADER>
A4407 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUTURE-COOPERATION-2N     02-13 0217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-COOPERATION-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ rights all stalled.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Democrats may be more inclined to stall than pass a
lot of bills. The party needs to pick up seven seats in the House
to regain the majority it lost in 1994. With the polls now in their
favor, they may not want to give GOP leaders much to crow about
heading into the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to fight the interests of the minority in
not wanting us to get anything done,'' Blunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Democrats will be tempted to pass bills if Republicans
meet them more than halfway, said Thomas Mann, a congressional
scholar with the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, he said, will be pulled between their agenda and
the need to improve their image by showing that they can work with
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a complex set of motivations out there,'' Mann said,
``and what emerges from that is anybody's guess.''
</P>
<P>
   The clock is ticking. With the 2000 presidential race already
heating up, most experts suggest that Congress will soon be tied up
in political maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a window until July or August,'' said freshman Rep.
Dennis Moore of Kansas, a Democrat. ``After that, it's finished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 1624EST &QL; 
