<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOCK-BANKER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
H&AMP;R BLOCK TO BUY NEW ENGLAND MORTGAGE BANKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ H&AMP;R Block Inc. said Friday it is buying
Assurance Mortgage Corp. of America, New England's largest
independent mortgage banker, for $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, which is expected to be completed before
Block's fiscal year ends April 30, will increase Block's nationwide
mortgage lending strength by about one-third and significantly
expand the company's ability to make conventional and
government-backed mortgage loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``At any given time, more than a million of Block's 15 million
customers are looking for a mortgage, and our goal is to be able to
respond to that need,'' said Frank L. Salizzoni, Block's president
and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Assurance Mortgage, which last year closed $1.3
billion in mortgages nationwide, is the second mortgage lender
acquired by Block, of Kansas City. The other lender, Option One
Mortgage Corp., of Santa Ana, Calif., originates about $1.9 billion
in loans annually. Block bought Option One in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But Option One specializes in non-conforming mortgages, which is
what the lending industry calls loans to borrowers whose credit
histories or financial circumstances prevent them from qualifying
for traditional mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held Assurance Mortgage deals primarily in
conventional loans, which are traditional mortgages that Fannie
Mae, Freddie Mac and other institutional investors repackage as
mortgage-backed securities for sale on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   These conventional mortgages also are sometimes called
conforming loans because they meet Federal Housing Administration
or Veterans Administration standards for federally backed insurance
against defaults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providing conventional and government mortgages is one more
piece of the financial program we are building at Block to become a
financial partner to our customers,'' Salizzoni said.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 60 percent of the potential borrowers who might turn
to Block for mortgages would qualify for conventional loans, which
generally feature lower interest rates and monthly payments than
unconventional loans, estimated Herbert Buchbinder, a senior vice
president and analyst at George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The company must use brokers to make those conventional loans
now, but won't need to after the transaction is completed,
Buchbinder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a good strategic accretive acquisition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Block's bid to become a financial services partner for clients
has led Block during the past several months to buy a financial
planning firm as part of a drive to eventually offer those
services, along with mortgages, at its approximately 9,000 U.S. tax
services offices.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, the company also began buying regionally dominant
traditional accounting and consulting firms around the U.S. to
expand into that financial services realm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
