r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUTURE-COOPERATION-2T     02-13 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUTURE-COOPERATION-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS TO STRIVE TO PUT ASIDE HARD FEELINGS, CONFRONT ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite the inevitable bitterness and bad blood
left over from the impeachment battle, members of Congress now are
pledging to get down to the business of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Expect some cooperation and an initial burst of legislative
activity, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am optimistic,'' said Republican Rep. Roy Blunt of Missouri,
the House's chief deputy whip. ``I think the desire to move on with
a post-impeachment agenda is going to be strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at the issues that will loom large and how they
might fare in the upcoming year:
</P>
<P>
   - Social Security: This may be too huge and complex to solve in
a year, but headway could be made before 2000 elections interfere.
</P>
<P>
   - Taxes: Conservative Republicans earlier called for a sweeping
10 percent cut in income taxes. President Clinton and Democrats
want smaller changes, such as focused tax credits or tightened
business loopholes. Moderate Republicans and Democrats may hold the
key, asking for elimination of the code's built-in marriage tax.
</P>
<P>
   - Medicare: This is the other entitlement program, one that
needs budgetary infusions or reform quickly.
</P>
<P>
   - Military preparedness: This is an easy winner for both sides.
The only questions are how much fresh cash, and for what? Missile
defense, pay raises and improved benefits for the troops,
recruitment incentives and new jet fighters, for starters.
</P>
<P>
   - Education: This was a big number in Clinton's State of the
Union laundry list. Republicans may be ready to approve school
improvements, but will work to eliminate big government
interference.
</P>
<P>
   - Managed health care: Democrats thought they had a hot issue in
a ``patient's bill of rights'' measure last year. Look for them to
try again, while the GOP will work to limit government oversight.
</P>
<P>
   But one might ask, how can they work together after all the
impeachment bitterness?
</P>
<P>
   Behind the upbeat talk are two overarching political factors.
Republicans, who continue to fight deteriorating poll numbers, will
want to prove that they can do more than obsess over the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meantime, will want to upgrade a badly tarnished
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can be and this must be a time of reconciliation and
renewal for America,'' he said Friday after his acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. Sam Brownback of Kansas said the impeachment
ordeal had ``really intensified the willingness of both sides to
work together.''
</P>
<P>
   That hopeful outlook isn't shared by all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans want to retain Congress, and Democrats want to
take it away in 2000,'' said Marshall Wittmann, director of
congressional relations with the Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put it in movie terms, we'll have a short period of
Shakespearean love followed by the thin red line.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Republican lawmakers in particular have begun
churning out press releases on topics ranging from Social Security
to taxes to Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   The president himself has stimulated much of the
anything-but-impeachment talk, showing interest in a range of
poll-tested issues, including Social Security, one of thorniest
topics around.
</P>
<P>
   His Jan. 19 State of the Union message may have launched the
issues parade. Criticized by some Republicans for discussing 77
issues in 77 minutes, the president announced initiatives on health
care, education, crime, trade, the environment and campaign-finance
reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very good chance that Congress will have a very
productive next year or 18 months,'' said former Democratic Rep.
Jim Slattery of Kansas, now a Washington lobbyist. ``I think he'll
be bending over backward to find a bipartisan coalition in the
Congress that he can work with.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked on NBC whether he could work with Clinton, House Speaker
Dennis Hastert responded: ``Absolutely. He's the president of the
United States. And, you know, the Congress, if they want to get
anything done, has to work with the president.''
</P>
<P>
   But others expect Clinton to struggle. Complicating the picture
is Clinton's reported vow to seek revenge on GOP House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Jack Danforth, a Missouri Republican, said the
scandal had forever undermined Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that for the next two years we will have a weak
president,'' Danforth said. ``Weak presidents don't accomplish
much.''
</P>
<P>
   But aiding Congress will be one of the cardinal rules of Capitol
Hill: Holding a grudge is a big mistake. A lawmaker who is an enemy
on one issue could become a badly needed ally on another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Congress has an ability to compartmentalize second only to
the president,'' said former Democratic Rep. Alan Wheat of
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Will that translate into major accomplishments?
</P>
<P>
   Although Social Security grabbed the most headlines after the
president's State of the Union speech, lawmakers acknowledge that
reaching a consensus on such a divisive issue is tricky. The
president's call to invest part of Social Security funds in the
stock market was met with GOP criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a program of such magnitude and personal importance that
just working through the differences takes more than can be done in
one short session of Congress,'' said Wheat, now a Washington
government relations consultant.
</P>
<P>
   With big budget surpluses coming, Republicans are insisting on a
large tax cut. Democrats, though, bridle at that notion. They
suggest that tax-cut money won't be there once Social Security,
Medicare and other issues are addressed.
</P>
<P>
   Other divisive topics: A patient's bill of rights, an increase
in the minimum wage, the size of the defense budget and an increase
in the deduction for health insurance for the self-employed.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, traditional differences between the parties might
prove to be as big a roadblock as any bad blood over impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, those differences led to gridlock. A series of
high-profile bills on taxes, campaign finance and patients' rights
all stalled. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
