<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOPTION-RACE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TO DECIDE ADOPTION DISPUTE INVOLVING MIXED-RACE CHILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Just weeks after Maya's birth, her mother
decided that the mixed-race infant should be adopted by a white
professional couple in Columbia, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Maya, now 3, calls the couple Mom and Dad. But whether she stays
with them is a matter for the courts to decide.
</P>
<P>
   The little girl's African-American aunt in Maryland won custody
rights in October, a decision by a Jackson County judge in Kansas
City. Last week the Columbia couple asked a state appeals court in
Kansas City to allow them to keep the girl.
</P>
<P>
   The case has implications beyond a custody dispute. The fight
for Maya's future raises questions about whether birth parents can
choose adoptive parents, what rights relatives have, and what role
race plays.
</P>
<P>
   Maya's case stands apart from other disputes involving white
adoptive parents and black family members. Those almost always
involve adoptions through state agencies and courts, which choose
the adoptive parents. But Maya's adoption was arranged through a
private agency, and her mother chose the adoptive parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is very unusual _ it embodies questions we're
struggling with across the board,'' said Madelyn Freundlich,
director of the Evan Donaldson Adoption Institute in New York, an
adoption advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   It is almost unheard of for a judge to allow a relative to adopt
a child after the biological parents have selected someone else,
Freundlich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It raises questions about the finality of adoption,'' she
said. ``It raises questions about whether any decision holds at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Maya, she remains with the Columbia couple as they await
the legal outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Maya's biological mother is white and her father black. She went
to live with the Columbia couple when she was 8 weeks old.
</P>
<P>
   Facts about her adoption dispute came to light Wednesday in
arguments before the appeals court in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel reported that Bill Clark and Marta Nolin
are psychologists for the state and have been married for more than
a decade. They also have an adopted 6-year-old boy who is
African-American and American Indian, and Maya is closely attached
to him. Clark and Nolin strive to make the children aware of their
racial and ethnic heritage.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of dispute is Denise Adams-Hill, a single,
divorced attorney from Potomac, Md. She is the sister of Maya's
biological father and has been estranged from her brother for
years.
</P>
<P>
   She filed for adoption on July 30, 1997, and Jackson County
Family Court Commissioner John F. Payne agreed. Later, a Family
Court judge approved the decision.
</P>
<P>
   At the appeals court hearing this week, Adams-Hill's attorney,
Gerald McGonagle, read his client's plea: ``I am her family, and I
understand what she will be faced with when she is growing up. I
understand who this child is.''
</P>
<P>
   McGonagle read a statement by Clark in which Clark said he and
his wife would raise Maya like she was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   An appeals judge asked McGonagle if race was the main issue.
</P>
<P>
   McGonagle replied, ``The issue is what is best for this child.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanford P. Krigel, attorney for the Columbia couple, said race
clearly was a big part of the case.
</P>
<P>
   An appeals judge asked if any Missouri law required judges to
approve private adoptions in which the mother chooses who will
adopt. Krigel said judges routinely side with the mother's decision
but could cite no law requiring judges to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Krigel also argued that it's wrong to ignore the three-year bond
Maya developed with Clark and Nolin. ``My clients are the only
parents Maya has ever known.''
</P>
<P>
   He asked the judges to allow his clients to adopt Maya, or
return the case for retrial before a different commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Krigel argued that Payne erred by not allowing the testimony of
Kris Probasco, a social worker expert on child attachment, and of
Rod Adams, Maya's father.
</P>
<P>
   Probasco, who also operates an Overland Park, Kan., private
adoption service, said in an interview that removing Maya now could
cause her lifelong problems with trust and relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, Maya's father, said in an interview that Maya belongs in
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and Nolin declined to comment after the hearing.
Adams-Hill did not return repeated telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Both Missouri and federal law forbid denying an adoption solely
on the basis of race. Yet race can be considered in deciding what
is best for a child, and experts differ on that point.
</P>
<P>
   At trial last year, each side in Maya's case called a national
expert on transracial adoption. Though neither testified, they
granted interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Rita J. Simon, of American University in Washington,
is a professor of law, justice and society who supports transracial
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's data says transracial adoption served the child's
best interest,'' she said. Children in such adoption cases grow up
healthy and well adjusted, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Simon said numbers alone show why white parents are needed to
free black or biracial children from state foster care.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 percent of 100,000 children cleared for state
adoption in the United States are African-American, but
African-Americans make up only 12 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Ruth McRoy, of the University of Texas at Austin,
argues that transracial adoption can leave children with an
identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't place white children with black families, and there's
a reason for that,'' she said. ``To be raised by a biological
relative is a good alternative if at all possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Greater efforts in recent years have resulted in more
African-American children being placed in homes of the same race,
McRoy said.
</P>
<P>
   In Maya's case, the appeals court promises a quick decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
