<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERAN-ENEMIES-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIETNAM WAR VETERAN MAKES PEACE WITH FORMER ADVERSARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In 1964, Roger H.C. Donlon, then a captain
with the Army's Special Forces, went to war in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   He led a 12-man Special Forces team assigned to advise several
hundred South Vietnamese troops at a remote base camp near the
village of Nam Dong.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 2 a.m. on July 6, a Viet Cong battalion reinforced
by North Vietnamese Army regulars attacked the outpost. It was the
first such combined assault on an American base.
</P>
<P>
   Within moments the camp's mess hall, command post and dispensary
were in flames. The incoming fire was constant, the mortar barrage
deafening.
</P>
<P>
   Hour after hour, the guerrillas emerged from the darkness to
charge the barbed-wire perimeter of the camp.
</P>
<P>
   As the camp exploded around him, Donlon, wounded in the stomach
and the shoulder, crawled from position to position, firing
constantly while encouraging and deploying his men.
</P>
<P>
   And then, he wrote later, ``a tremendous blast went off in my
face. I could hear myself screaming as I sailed through the
air....Strangely, I didn't want (my scream) to end. When it ended,
I was certain I'd be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   When he regained consciousness moments later, he was doubled
over in pain. Still, he dragged himself through the camp, carrying
ammunition, bandaging the wounded and directing fire at the
attacking troops.
</P>
<P>
   The battle ended when American reinforcements arrived at dawn.
Two members of Donlon's team were dead, along with an Australian
adviser, 55 South Vietnamese soldiers and 250 Viet Cong.
</P>
<P>
   In December, still recuperating from his wounds, Donlon went to
the White House to receive the Medal of Honor. He was the first
soldier fighting in Vietnam to win the award. His men won two
Distinguished Service Crosses (posthumously), four Silver Stars,
five Bronze Stars and nine Purple Hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, when the United States withdrew from the war,
Donlon was among those who mourned deeply and never expected to
return to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1993 he did return, unarmed and on a very different
mission. He was, in fact, one of the first American veterans to
return. He was among a delegation sponsored by People to People
International, a cultural and education exchange program based in
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways,'' Donlon said recently, ``my life has shifted
from being a warrior to seeking reconciliation with a former
adversary.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps without knowing it at the time, Donlon outlined the
later course of his life at a luncheon in the late 1980s. Asked
what he would do if he met the man who led the attack at Nam Dong,
Donlon responded:
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I guess I would commend him for the courage his men
displayed and offer my sympathies for those he lost. And then I
would shift the conversation to the future and ask about his
current dreams and aspirations.''
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from the Army in 1989 _ he's now 65 _ he settled
in Leavenworth, Kan., and joined the board of People to People
International. And members of that organization eventually
suggested that he could play a vital role on a path-breaking
journey to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a lot of soul-searching over that one,'' Donlon said
last week. ``And I finally decided it was something I wanted to do.
It was time to start a healing process.''
</P>
<P>
   In his recently published autobiography, Beyond Nam Dong, Donlon
described the anxiety he felt on the day he returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the plane began its descent into Hanoi,'' he wrote, ``the
hair on the back of my neck started to prickle...most of us felt we
would not be welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   But his fears ebbed as a coterie of Vietnamese officials warmly
greeted the delegation and presented Donlon's wife, Norma, with a
dozen roses.
</P>
<P>
   At a reception in Hanoi, Donlon spoke of his desire to visit a
rural cemetery where many of the South Vietnamese soldiers he once
led are buried.
</P>
<P>
   His hosts shook their heads. There is no such place, they said.
</P>
<P>
   But Donlon's tour guide, a former Viet Cong officer, said
privately that he would see what he could do.
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, on a visit to Hue, Vietnam's old imperial
capital, the guide went to Donlon's hotel and said he would drive
him to the isolated graveyard near Nam Dong.
</P>
<P>
   They left early the next morning and drove for three hours
through the mountains. When they arrived at the abandoned cemetery,
Donlon walked across a grassy field picking wildflowers to lay on
the weed-choked graves of his men.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of villagers gathered around him, and he explained that
in America people sometimes joined hands when they prayed. He then
bowed his head and reached out, not knowing what would happen. In a
moment he felt a hand grip his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up,'' he wrote, ``and the entire group was linked
together. The seed of reconciliation had been planted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What a remarkable thing,'' said Bob Ulin, a retired Army
colonel and longtime friend of Donlon's. ``I have friends who say
they could never go back. But Roger did, because he believes that
the men we fought were soldiers like us, serving their country like
us. That's something many veterans have not come to grips with.''
</P>
<P>
   Ulin's perception is shared by other Vietnam veterans in this
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger Donlon has set an important example for us,'' said Henry
Laurent, a retired Special Forces sergeant who lives in Tonganoxie,
Kan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting older now, and time is running out for us to
make peace with what happened there.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Donlon went again to Vietnam. On that visit he met a
former officer who had helped plan the Nam Dong attack. Together
the two men returned to the old battle site.
</P>
<P>
   ``He even helped me tote in a big wreath,'' Donlon said. ``And
he arranged to have some of his men (former troops) clean up the
cemetery. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
