<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE NEEDS BALANCE TO SUCCEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: If Medicare benefits are ever extended to cover
prescription drugs, it will prove disastrous unless accompanied by
complementary reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever those reforms may be, they must abandon Medicare's
one-size-fits-all coverage. The escalating proliferation of
treatment alternatives demands that Medicare keep pace with medical
science. Therefore, the most basic reform of all must give
beneficiaries autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   As the system now exists, it tilts unfairly toward beneficiaries
needing surgery and care-intensive hospital stays. For those whose
ills are manageable with prescription palliatives, Medicare falls
woefully short.
</P>
<P>
   Given the medicinal and scientific discoveries that have led to
increasing supplies of miracle drugs, Medicare has become an
economically irrational arrangement. Although drugs might sometimes
be preferable options from both financial and medical standpoints,
the rational choice often dictates going with more heroic, risky
and expensive treatment because it is covered by Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is to find a way to cover all reasonable treatment
regimens without accelerating the bankruptcy of a system already in
serious financial trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Any such solution demands limits. Medicare isn't exactly
open-ended as far as benefits are concerned, but neither is it
subject to traditional budget restraints. Medicare's budget is
whatever a year's worth of valid bills amount to. The stewards of
its finances try to keep income and outlays in balance, but if
claims exceed revenue, they must be honored if made in good faith.
</P>
<P>
   The necessity of limits is what makes autonomy imperative.
Autonomy gives senior citizens the opportunity to assess their own
situations and choose coverage plans fitting their particular
needs. We know this is possible because it's the cornerstone of
private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   How would the concepts of autonomy and limits complement each
other? That would be for the insurers to figure out. Government as
insurer hasn't done a very good job of creating disciplines that
restrain demand for a good for which the demand is theoretically
infinite.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, corporate insurers have been relatively
successful at balancing the interests of those who pay the
insurance bills, the insured and the care providers.
</P>
<P>
   The administration seems to want to cover prescriptions by
tapping the anticipated revenue surpluses of the next 15 years.
Under this plan, though, drug coverage would be just one more
expensive demand appended to an already overburdened system.
Meantime, the surpluses may prove illusory.
</P>
<P>
   A federal advisory commission, on the other hand, also wants
prescriptions covered but would reorganize Medicare to put the
insurance function into the hands of private companies. The
commission proposes a fixed annual payment from government that
Medicare enrollees could use to shop for their own coverage. This
approach marries the concepts of beneficiary autonomy and financial
limits, which are critical to Medicare's future salvation.
</P>
<P>
   This is not something many seniors will be comfortable with, but
any other approach risks a status quo that is unsatisfactory and
unfair to many and becoming more so all the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 1630EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
