<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4413 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWIM-RECRUIT-NYT &LR;      02-13 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIM-RECRUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT KENYON COLLEGE, THE DYNASTY THRIVES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Guam, Calif.)   (jw) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAMBIER, Ohio _ Jim Steen, the swimming coach here at Kenyon
College, faces the usual recruiting obstacles of remote private
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you say, `Come to Gambier, pay $30,000 and let me beat
the bejesus out of you for four years and you'll be good'?'' he
mused before a recent practice. ``We say that all we're looking for
is someone smart, rich and talented, or smart, poor and talented,
or smart, middle class and idealistic and talented.''
</P>
<P>
   Steen has found them all in staggering abundance. If they did
not arrive accomplished, they likely were once they had been
coached by the 49-year-old Steen, the small-college composite of
John Wooden and Doc Counsilman.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon is tucked away on a one-mile wooded strip of Gothic
buildings about 40 miles north of Columbus. It is known for
nurturing the talents of the actor Paul Newman and the writer E.L.
Doctorow, but it also has earned a reputation as a swimming
dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   Under Steen, the men's team has won 19 consecutive Division III
national championships and the women's team has won 15 in a row.
Both are records for all National Collegiate Athletic Association
competition. Not bad for a liberal arts haven.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like winning,'' Athletic Director Robert Bunnell said.
``We're not embarrassed by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon occasionally loses regular-season meets, some to Division
I teams. The men even failed to win the conference meet two years
ago. What sets the Kenyon teams apart from other teams is what they
do when the competition is at its keenest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that amazes me is how fast his kids swim at the end
of the year,'' said Matt Liddy, the head coach of Wright State, a
Division I school in Dayton, Ohio, that lost to Kenyon in a recent
meet.
</P>
<P>
   Steen treats the dual meet season as the preseason, saying his
swimmers have only so much psychic energy. They produce ordinary
times during most of the year and blossom in time for the
conference meet.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, he cajoles and commands in a dry soprano voice that
cuts through the splashing. In an interview, he is a swirl of
energy, rising and sitting, pacing and pointing.
</P>
<P>
   The swimmers said he was the consummate motivator, pushing
buttons and playing father-confessor. Katie Varda, a senior who is
a six-time NCAA event champion and one of 60 athletes under Steen,
was struggling with career concerns recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day he pulled me out of the water,'' she said, ``and asked
me, `What's going on?' I ended up totally bawling my eyes out.''
</P>
<P>
   Steen's daughter, Sarah, a sophomore distance freestyler who was
coached by her mother at the local high school, admitted that she
sometimes joins the complaints about her dad's methods.
</P>
<P>
   And Lloyd Baron, a sophomore freestyle sprinter, said: ``Every
once in a while there are situations where you kind of roll your
eyes and you go, `Oh, this again' or `This drill again.' But when
you get results at the end of the season, you think, `I guess he
was right.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the men and women won 11 of 20 events at the NCAA
meet, and the men broke four Division III records. The Lords'
200-yard freestyle relay recorded the seventh-fastest time in all
divisions. The school has an Olympian, Darrick Bollinger, a junior
from Guam, and the reigning Division III female swimmer of the
year, Marisha Stawiski, a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Through a phone network and word of mouth from swimming alumni,
the school is able to recruit good athletes who are great students.
</P>
<P>
   Even by those standards, though, Baron has unusual credentials.
A high school all-American, he is a chiseled 6 feet 6 inches and
200 pounds and has a condor-like wingspan.
</P>
<P>
   He said ignoring Division I scholarship offers was no sacrifice,
considering the improvement he would make under Steen.
</P>
<P>
   The coach validated his faith. By the end of last season, Baron
was swimming faster than all but four of the 14 sprinters who were
faster than he was in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon has been so dominant that Steen took a sabbatical in 1995
and '96 to evaluate his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to explain my success,'' he said. ``Is it luck or
what?''
</P>
<P>
   Visits to the Olympic training center and the University of
Southern California inspired a revelation of sorts. Steen witnessed
coaches with different styles simply coaxing the most out of their
athletes _ just as he had done.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches who visit Kenyon are often left scratching their heads.
The five-lane pool is no better than a parks-and-recreation
complex. The workload, though demanding, is not revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   But a look into the agenda of the full-time assistant coach,
Arthur Albiero, reveals a program that thrives on details. Albiero,
with clicker in hand, counts the strokes of each swimmer during
races and logs all the results into a computer so he and Steen can
figure out the best balance between a swimmer's stroke length and
frequency. Coaches also record every training session from the day
a swimmer arrives on campus.
</P>
<P>
   If a swimmer is showing excessive fatigue, coaches sometimes
draw a blood sample to measure lactic acid buildup. Steen also
invented a pulley contraption called a Power Rack that builds
stroke-specific muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon, which has a $100 million endowment, has a bargain in
Steen. The swim team's operating budget is $34,658, according to
school records. Many swimmers pay their way at an annual
semester-break training session in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Although by its very nature the winning streaks have created
pressure, Baron said he would not be devastated if Kenyon did not
win the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Steen even said one of his goals was to have a team lose the
national championship and bounce back to win it again the following
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a team than can swim better than us,'' Stawiski
said, ``I give them all the credit in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
