<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4417 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-CONN-SETONHALL-NY     02-13 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-CONN-SETONHALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT PUSHED TO THE LIMIT BY SETON HALL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn.)   (jw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It was not supposed to be this much of a
skirmish for Connecticut. Not like this. The second-ranked team in
the country, Connecticut expected to cruise into Continental Arena
on Saturday, solve Seton Hall's slowdown tactics and continue to
dream the bigger dreams the Huskies have for March. But the Pirates
got in their way in a big way. Well, for 36 minutes they did.
</P>
<P>
   Playing without Shaheen Holloway, its starting point guard and
best player, Seton Hall made the Huskies sweat, helped force them
into their worst shooting performance of the season and almost
shocked Connecticut. The Huskies averted a major upset, but only
with a late rally that secured the 53-48 victory. Then Connecticut
exhaled.
</P>
<P>
   On a day the Huskies missed on all 14 shots they attempted from
3-point range and shot a brutal 33.3 percent, they displayed just
enough fortitude and veteran grit to beat an undermanned team. The
Huskies played poorly, and even missed six of their eight free
throws to keep the game tense in the final minute, but they did
survive.
</P>
<P>
   With all five of their starters scoring at least one basket, the
Huskies outscored the Pirates by 15-4 to finish the game and sneak
away with the victory. The Huskies (22-1 over all, 13-1 in the Big
East) could not wait to complete this game, a sloppy contest in
which Seton Hall (12-12, 6-9) stayed feisty and stayed in the game.
Kevin Freeman had 13 points to top the Huskies, while Richard
Hamilton added 12 and Khalid El-Amin, 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to defeat a team like Connecticut this late in the
season, a team like ours has to play a perfect basketball game,''
Seton Hall Coach Tommy Amaker said. ``I thought we came close, but
it wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Pirates, one of the plays they will
vividly remember involved Ty Shine, the freshman point guard who
was filling in for Holloway. With the score even at 44 and less
than four minutes left, Shine inexplicably tripped over his own
feet as he tried to bring the ball across halfcourt. Ricky Moore
scooped up the free ball, raced in for a layup and was fouled. He
completed the 3-point play to put the Huskies in front, 47-44. The
Pirates never regained the lead.
</P>
<P>
   That did not mean Seton Hall lacked opportunities. Rimas
Kaukenas (21 points) rimmed two 3-point shots, which would have
tied the score at 51, and Chuck Moore missed the front end of a
one-and-one seconds later to give Connecticut possession with the
51-48 edge. After Ricky Moore missed two free throws to give Seton
Hall another life, Shine's runner in the lane rolled out.
</P>
<P>
   The deliberate pace that Seton Hall enforced for a good portion
of the first half was successful at the outset of the second half.
The Huskies, who entered the game averaging 80.6 points, wanted to
run the ball and use the advantage they had in athleticism, but the
Pirates played aggressive defense and were methodical on offense.
The Huskies were so flustered, they missed their first 10 shots of
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   While Connecticut is assured of being in the National Collegiate
Athletic Association tournament and is fighting for one of the four
prestigious and critical No. 1 seedings, Seton Hall is trying to
stay on the post-season radar screen. The Pirates are a long shot
to reach the tournament and need to keep their record above .500 to
at least have a chance at qualifying for the National Invitation
Tournament. So while both teams had motivation Saturday, the
Pirates might have been more desperate.
</P>
<P>
   With less than 10 seconds left in the first half, El-Amin was
bottled up near the free-throw line by Chuck Moore. El-Amin finally
tossed up an off-balance jumper that touched the front of the rim,
hit the back and dropped through the basket as time expired to trim
Seton Hall's lead to 28-27. But El-Amin still banged his fist on
the press table because it had been a frustrating 20 minutes for
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin's last-second struggles epitomized the struggles the
Huskies endured after it looked as if they had buried the Pirates
early. With just over eight minutes left in the first half, Amaker
called a timeout after a 16-2 run by the Huskies gave them a
seemingly comfortable 22-12 lead.
</P>
<P>
   During the sluggish stretch, the Pirates went 12 straight
possessions in which they made seven turnovers, sank one of five
shots and scored a mere 2 points. If the Huskies had not been so
frigid from the field (0 for 8 from behind the 3-point arc and 13
for 34 over all in the half), they could probably have sent Seton
Hall's fans home early. Even with Hamilton starting for the second
straight game, Connecticut could not make shots consistently.
</P>
<P>
   But Connecticut's failure to put Seton Hall away and,
presumably, Amaker's timely lecture helped the Pirates resuscitate
themselves and play like a different team. They weathered
Connecticut's trapping defense as both Chuck Moore (7 points) and
Kaukenas (5 points) nailed 3-pointers, and the Pirates unleashed a
14-1 run of their own to make the score 26-23. Surprisingly, the
Pirates led by 1 at the half and were alive until the last minute
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
