<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN GRETZKY GETS THE BLUES   WHEN THE TEAM STRUGGLES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Mich., Tenn. Pa, Mo., Ill., Canada)  By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It finally sounded as if the Rangers' struggles were
getting to Wayne Gretzky on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about it and prepare for it,'' an obviously miffed
Gretzky said after the Rangers' 3-1 loss to the Carolina Hurricanes
at Madison Square Garden. ``It's not one guy, it's not two guys.
It's the whole team. And it's always the same way. We take three or
four penalties in the first period, fall behind by a goal, and then
spend the rest of the night fighting for our lives. It's not good
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   With the defeat, the Rangers (20-25-7) fell to 12th place in the
Eastern Conference. They remained just 6 points out of the eighth
and final playoff spot, but trailed four teams for a post-season
berth with 30 games to go.
</P>
<P>
   Six of those games come in the next nine days, beginning Sunday
afternoon at the Garden against the two-time defending Stanley Cup
champion Detroit Red Wings _ a tough assignment for any team,
especially one that is now a season-low five games under .500.
</P>
<P>
   It should be even tougher for the Rangers, who are 3-8-0 in
their last 11 games and who have lost five of their last six games
at the Garden, where they are now a game below .500 for the season.
They are now 45-64-25 over the last two seasons _ since Mark
Messier was pushed aside by team management and departed for
Vancouver, leaving Gretzky as the Rangers' marquee star.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gretzky and Messier, who is currently out four to six weeks
with an injured knee, have seen better days; Vancouver is in 12th
place, too, in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky's comments Friday night were delivered, as usual, in
muffled tones. But regardless of the volume, the tone might have
been Gretzky's strongest all season. The message was one of
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just keep giving games away,'' Gretzky said.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is that the Rangers cannot score with any regularity.
Brian Leetch tallied the team's only goal on Friday night, to
extend his goal-scoring streak to 3 games after he had gone a
career-high 23 without one. And Todd Harvey, who was playing for
the first time in 11 games, assisted on the early third-period
goal.
</P>
<P>
   But that was it. Gretzky had a disgusted look on his face for
most of the evening. Rangers Coach John Muckler double-shifted the
38-year-old center for much of the second period, to no avail. With
five minutes left in the period and the Rangers only trailing by a
goal, Gretzky was reduced to lifting one arm in premature
celebration on a shot of his that Carolina goalie Arturs Irbe sat
on before it could reach the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible,'' Gretzky would later say of the Rangers' play
at the Garden. ``I think we should all be extremely embarrassed by
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' fans certainly were. They booed the home team off
the ice after the second and third periods. But the Rangers'
struggles are not reserved for home-ice alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been no advantage wherever we've been,'' Leetch, the
team's captain, said. ``Obviously, we haven't had any advantage,
anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Now come games against Detroit at the Garden, and then in
Nashville, on successive nights. Then it's back to the Garden for
contests against Montreal on Wednesday and Pittsburgh on Friday,
before a two-game swing to Edmonton and Calgary next Sunday and
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   By the time that stretch is over, the Rangers could find
themselves out of the post-season chase for the second time year in
a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuses, losses, we can't have them now,'' said Leetch. ``We
need a win.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be a start.
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Beukeboom is doubtful for Sunday's game. He suffered a
minor concussion when he was kneed in the back of the head by
Martin Gelinas in the second period of Friday night's loss. The
Rangers have listed Beukeboom as day to day. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers need scoring. On Friday, they acquired some grit
instead. That is what Neil Smith, the Rangers president, obtained
in Eric Lacroix, whom he obtained from Los Angeles for Sean Pronger
in an exchange of forwards who are still looking for their first
goals of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the Rangers sent a pair of defensemen, Jeff Finley and
Geoff Smith, to the St. Louis Blues for future considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling was that we had a number of players like Sean and
that is why Sean was not getting into our lineup,'' Smith said of
Pronger, who had been acquired by the Rangers earlier this season
in the deal that sent Aleksei Kovalev to Pittsburgh for Petr
Nedved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already have Brent Fedyk, Manyy Malhotra and a couple of
other guys, sort of our good, checking forwards. One of the things
we don't have in our lineup are more people like Todd Harvey and
Adam Graves, players that crash and use the physical part of the
game. With Lacroix, I thought I could add a physical player and a
better scorer.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacroix, said Smith, had requested a trade. Earlier this season,
he had been traded from Colorado by his father, Pierre. In 34 games
this season with the Avalanche and Kings, Lacroix had one assist.
Last season, though, he did notch 16 goals.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers Coach John Muckler said that Lacroix would likely skate
on a line centered by the rookie, Malhotra. As for a more
established scorer, the Rangers are thought to be interested in
Doug Gilmour, should the Blackhawks move the veteran center before
the trading deadline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
