<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RETURN OF SEIKALY BOLSTERS NETS' HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Next to Kerry Kittles, he was the most
impressive player at the New Jersey Nets' training camp. He ran the
court like a small forward, scored in the post over the gifted shot
blocker Jim McIlvaine, and made Jayson Williams work extra hard for
rebounds. According to his coaches and teammates, Rony Seikaly was
playing great, giving the Nets their first scoring center since
Derrick Coleman was traded three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then, during an evening practice Jan. 24, Seikaly and the
excitement he had generated came tumbling down on Chris Gatling's
foot. Hours later, the 6-foot-11-inch Seikaly was found to have a
sprained left ankle. Now, after three weeks of inactivity, he is
back, expected to play in Monday's game at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   With the Nets reeling after losing three of their first four
games, Seikaly will be looked to for a much-needed scoring boost
off the bench. A 15-point scorer throughout his 10-year career, he
should help the Nets improve on their woeful scoring average of
85.3 points per game, a figure nearly 12 points lower than last
year's Eastern Conference-leading average of 99.6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rony is something else on that post,'' Williams had said
before Seikaly was injured. ``He's out here killing people.
McIlvaine is supposed to be one of the top two or three best shot
blockers in the league, and they're going at it pretty good and
he's getting his shot over McIlvaine.''
</P>
<P>
   Seikaly, who rehabilitated his ankle by sitting in a hyperbaric
chamber, was in uniform for Thursday's sobering 95-75 defeat at
Milwaukee, but Coach John Calipari chose not to use him. Seikaly
had not yet completed a full practice with the club, and Calipari
wanted to make sure he was ready before throwing him into the
raging fire that is National Basketball Association post play. ``I
got dressed to play, so if he would've called my number I would've
played,'' Seikaly said after the game, noting that his ankle was
fine. ``But I guess it'll be a lot better now that I'll have three
practices.''
</P>
<P>
   After workouts Friday, Saturday and Sunday, Seikaly should be
there to spell Williams, or play alongside him, in the battle with
Miami's Alonzo Mourning. Before the injury, Calipari had been
experimenting with a lineup that included Williams, Seikaly and the
6-10 Keith Van Horn.
</P>
<P>
   With a starting five that is among the smallest in the league,
Calipari knows the importance of having a big unit available when
necessary. Without Seikaly, the only way for the Nets to go big was
by playing Williams and McIlvaine together. But neither player is
much of a scorer from the low block.
</P>
<P>
   Seikaly's return will give the Nets an alternative look, one
that Calipari and Williams had raved about during camp. Seikaly's
scoring ability should draw attention and enable Williams to roam
for offensive rebounds and put-backs. Defensively, Williams, who is
more than an inch shorter than Seikaly, will still guard the
centers, since Seikaly's mobility allows him to cover most power
forwards.
</P>
<P>
   And since both Williams and Seikaly run the court well, the
bigger lineup will not hinder the Nets' running game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you say big team, it's not really a slow team,'' Seikaly
said. ``We're a quick big team because Jayson and I can beat any
centers down the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that he is back, the Nets are hoping Seikaly, who averaged
16 points and 11 rebounds as Miami's starting center from 1988 to
1994, will remain healthy. Since joining the club in a trade with
Orlando on Feb. 19, 1998, he has been more recognizable in street
clothes than in shorts and sneakers _ a bone contusion in his right
foot limited him to nine games with the Nets last season.
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   The Nets are hoping that their starting point guard, SAM
CASSELL, who sprained his right ankle during a 36-point, 9-assist
performance in the season opener, will be able to play Monday.
Without him, the Nets' offense has been horrible, shooting just 38
percent from the field and averaging 78 points per game. Both
Cassell and his backup, ERIC MURDOCK, who has a strained left
groin, are listed as questionable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
