<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 2/13/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Feb. 13, 1999 -- NY-AIRPORTS-RUNWAYS, 2-13
-- As an aircraft lands, others taxi along the runways at LaGuardia
Airport. For 30 years, the Federal Aviation Administration has
rationed landing and takeoff slots to keep La Guardia and Kennedy
airports from being overwhelmed by airplanes. But last week the
Transportation Department, its parent agency, proposed phasing out
the limits over five years. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Feb. 13, 1999 -- NY-SUSPECT-AFRICANS, 2-13
-- The Farafina Coffee Shop in Harlem offers Africans and Americans
the food and the talk of the old country. From left, Ben Aziz, from
Mali, Buddy Muhammed, also from Mali, and Richard Stone, an
American. For Africans here, particularly West Africans, the fatal
shooting of Guinean immigrant Amadou Diallo by police has only
reinforced the vulnerability they feel as black immigrants in this
city. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) SAO JOSE DOS CAMPOS, Brazil -- Feb. 13, 1999 --
BRAZIL-ECON, 2-13 -- Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
speaks to reporters as his Argentine counterpart, President Carlos
Menem looks on during a news conferece at the Aerospace
Technological Center on Friday. Menem was touring the facility
during his state visit. In the last month, following the drastic
devaluation of the nation's currency, that entire edifice of the
economy has begun to wobble, along with the sense of financial
security that accompanied it. (Presidencia Argentina/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) TORONTO -- Feb. 13, 1999 -- BKN-OAKLEY, 2-13 -- Charles
Oakly during a news conference in Tornoto after being traded to the
Raptors by the Knicks in 1998. The power forward who never wanted
to leave Madison Square Garden returns to New York on Tuesday
night. He brings not only the tenacity and grit that endeared him
to Knick fans the past decade, but also the resentment that comes
with being traded from a contender to Canada. (Edward Keating/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) CHICAGO -- Feb. 13, 1999 -- AMR-PILOTS-2, 2-13 -- An
American Airlines employee hears complaints from passengers at
O'Hare Airport on Friday. A federal judge in Dallas cited the union
representing American Airlines pilots for contempt Saturday and
fined it $10 million for ignoring his back-to-work order. (Todd
Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 13, 1999 --U.S.-KOSOVO, 2-13 --
President Clinton completes his weekly radio address on Saturday in
the Oval Office. Clinton announced Saturday that he would send
nearly 4,000 troops to Kosovo to defend the ``national interest''
as part of a NATO peacekeeping force, provided the ethnic Albanians
and Serbs who are warring there strike a peace agreement. (Shana
Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MEXICO CITY -- Feb. 13, 1999 -- MEXICO-POLLUTE-REVIEW,
2-13 -- On the fringes of the Mexican capital, livestock like these
sheep are adding to the pollution problem. This winter the
residents of Mexico City, who are long accustomed to breathing
toxic concentrations of industrial and vehicle exhaust, are also
breathing poisonous amounts of what the authorities refer to with
scientific detachment as fecal matter. (Keith Dannemiller/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) TBILISI, Georgia -- Feb. 13, 1999 -- GEORGIA-WAR-SCHOOL ,
2-13 -- Sixth grade students read a Red Cross booklet that teaches
about the ethics of combat. As an experiment in preventing war
crimes, The Red Cross has devised a curriculum on humanitarian
rules of war for children in conflict zones. (James Hill/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) MANCHESTER, N.H. -- Feb. 13, 1999 -- IMPEACH-POLITICIANS,
2-13 -- Steve Forbes, left, signs a Bible for Greg Salts at the New
Hampshire Christian Coalition dinner earlier this month. The
aftershocks of impeachment are already being felt by politicians
who fear the nation is entering an era in which their private lives
will draw more intense scrutiny and embarrassing disclosures than
ever before. Forbes, the millionaire publisher who sought the
Presidency in 1996 and will try again in 2000, said: There's going
to be a lot of muck thrown at those who run. (Kirsten Elstner/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 13, 1999 -- IMPEACH-TRIAL, 2-13 --
House managers sought a full Senate impeachment trial, but that did
not happen. On Friday, Reps Bob Barr, R-Ga., and lead impeachment
manager Henry J. Hyde, R-Ill., walked back to their chamber
following the Senate's acquittal of President Clinton. (Carol T.
Powers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) AMMAN, Jordan -- Feb. 13, 1999 -- JORDAN-AID, 2-13 --
King Abdullah II of Jordan awaits the arrival of a delegation
paying their respects on the death of his father on Thursday at the
Royal Palace. After a week that brought the death of King Hussein
and the crowning of his son as successor, Jordanians are hoping
that the overwhelming solidarity shown in response to their trauma
will prove to be more than passing. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CHICAGO -- Feb. 13, 1999 -- AMR-PILOTS, 2-13 -- Diane
Dawson lets out a sigh while waiting on a long line at the American
Airlines counter at O'Hare Airport on Friday. Dawson was trying to
get to Dallas to see her son who is being deployed to Bosnia to
take part in the NATO peace-keeping operations. A federal judge in
Dallas cited the union representing American Airlines pilots for
contempt Saturday and fined it $10 million for ignoring his
back-to-work order. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) VLADIVOSTOCK, Russia -- Feb. 13, 1999 --
RUSSIA-VLADIVOSTOK-2, 2-13 -- View of the port of Vladivostok,
Russia's main Pacific port. Local elections have been invalidated
15 times. The mental hospital even released some of its patients
after squabbling officials allowed its budget to run dry. So the
news that the autocratic governor has received a mysterious $1
million prize for his work as one of the world's great leaders
seemed par for the course. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) VLADIVOSTOCK, Russia -- Feb. 13, 1999 --
RUSSIA-VLADIVOSTOK-1, 2-13 -- An ice-fisher on the frozen bay,
Russia's main Pacific port, with the city in the background. Local
elections have been invalidated 15 times. The mental hospital even
released some of its patients after squabbling officials allowed
its budget to run dry. So the news that the autocratic governor has
received a mysterious $1 million prize for his work as one of the
world's great leaders seemed par for the course. (James Hill/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
