</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4443 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKWHITE-JASPER14-C     02-13 3338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKWHITE-JASPER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pain and prejudice: Black teen's death shows how accusations of
racism can twist lives
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER _ Cecil Peacock felt the stir of an old heartache last
summer, and the familiar pain nudged him out of the house and down
the highway to a little church that was not his own.
</P>
<P>
   On that sun-flamed afternoon in June, Peacock slipped into the
overflow crowd outside the Jasper church and mourned twice over.
</P>
<P>
   He joined in the collective grief for James Byrd Jr., a black
man dragged to an unthinkable death a few days earlier, allegedly
by three white men. He also ached for his own son.
</P>
<P>
   Peacock, a sad-eyed, stooped woodsman of 67, had a son who also
died on a lonesome stretch of road in the Piney Woods near Jasper.
The body of the black teen-ager was found in a ditch on Nov. 5,
1977, just eight miles from where Byrd's body was left last June.
Police say Ray Peacock, 18, was killed when a white teen-ager named
Rocky Phelps accidentally hit him with his pickup; the Peacocks say
it was murder motivated by race.
</P>
<P>
   The teen's death shows how accusations of racism, proven or not,
can poison relationships and twist lives. For 21 years, the Peacock
and Phelps families have been haunted by the death. And whether
Peacock's death was planned or accidental, it is, like Byrd's, a
part of the legacy of racial division in Deep East Texas, a
pine-covered section of the state where the Ku Klux Klan still
maintains a presence.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Peacock's late-night death has come to symbolize the racial
mistrust that can fester when a black person is killed under
unusual circumstances. After Byrd's slaying last summer, local
blacks began to talk openly about Ray Peacock's death and others
they said had been ``swept under the rug'' over the years.
</P>
<P>
   This week, a Jasper jury will begin to hear testimony in the
first trial of a suspect in Byrd's gruesome dragging death. Many
people will be watching for signs of how race relations have
changed in the years since the Peacock family was left with hearts
full of racial mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   CROSSING OVER
</P>
<P>
   Ray Peacock got noticed a lot.
</P>
<P>
   He wore a dazzling hot-pink suit to his prom at Burkeville High
School in Newton County. He had a red Mustang when no other black
male student had a car. He was senior class president and vice
president of the student council in an integrated class where
blacks were the majority. He had a black girlfriend, but white
girls slipped him covert love letters that he hid in a bedroom
drawer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am white as day, and you, black as night. ... This is why
our secret must be kept on highest star,'' one girl wrote. ``The
world's just not ready, so we deny going steady.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Peacock graduated in 1977, when racial segregation was
outlawed yet persistent enough to divide a simple ritual such as
voting on the most popular couple for the school yearbook. One
white couple and one black couple were always chosen _ and
photographed _ separately.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed dating _ known locally as ``crossing over'' _ was not
accepted in Deep East Texas then, and Cecil and Theresa Peacock
believed their children would be in danger if they crossed
courtship's color barrier. They warned their six children away from
interracial romance.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, Ray Peacock left home for college in Beaumont.
He returned every weekend to the family's small wooden house in
Shankleville, a rural community in Newton County founded in 1867 by
two ex-slaves named Jim and Winnie Shankle. Ray Peacock was a
descendant of the Shankles, who are honored on a state historical
marker for the powerful love that inspired Jim to walk 400 miles
and cross the Mississippi River to find Winnie after she was sold
to a Texan.
</P>
<P>
   On one of Ray Peacock's visits home, someone phoned the Peacock
home to say the family's cows were wandering loose on a nearby
two-lane highway, Texas 87. Ray Peacock volunteered to round up the
cows and drove off in his Mustang. It was sometime before 10:30
p.m. on Nov. 5, 1977.
</P>
<P>
   About 11:30 p.m., his car was found on the grassy shoulder. The
headlights were on, the emergency lights blinked, the driver's door
stood open, and music played from the tape deck. A deputy found Ray
Peacock's body about 225 feet from the car, face down with no
apparent wounds, according to a sheriff's report.
</P>
<P>
   That night, two white youths came forward to say their pickup
had hit somebody in the foggy darkness. The 18-year-old driver,
Rocky Phelps, said he and his younger brother had turned around and
looked for a body along the road but didn't see anyone. Scared,
they drove to their uncle's house.
</P>
<P>
   Racial tension flared immediately after Peacock's body was
discovered. The first call Newton County Sheriff Wayne Powell got
was from an unidentified woman who demanded to know what the
sheriff planned to do about the white man who had killed a black
man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there was no doubt going to be a problem over it
because of the way it happened,'' said Powell, who is white.
</P>
<P>
   He said Peacock had pulled off the road and parked his car on
the shoulder facing oncoming traffic, a dangerous position. Phelps
was startled to see the headlights of Peacock's car pointing toward
him through the fog. Anticipating a collision, Phelps swerved. But
he veered toward the headlights, passing in front of Peacock's
parked car and avoiding the Mustang's open door. As he came around
the Mustang, the pickup hit Peacock.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a bad freak accident,'' Powell said. ``The family
was upset about it, but there was no (criminal) offense committed.
The boys were just as innocent as they could be.''
</P>
<P>
   That explanation was too outlandish for the Peacock family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so far-fetched that even a child would wonder why, or
have questions about it,'' said Theresa Peacock. ``Why would you go
to where the lights are instead of staying on the highway?''
</P>
<P>
   The Peacocks say there are other discrepancies in the official
account of Ray Peacock's death. None of the family's cows was found
loose that night. The sheriff's department report says no wounds
were found on the body, but the autopsy report says the teen-ager
had a broken back and multiple abrasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was foul play,'' said Jasper NAACP founder Booker T.
Hunter, who helped the Peacock family comb through mud and grass
the morning after Ray Peacock died to look for clues to his death.
``He was killed. That's all there was to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dorie Coleman, a black mortician in Jasper who handled the
funeral, also rejects the official account of the death.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no scars, bruises, contusions or anything on (his)
face, on his arms or elbows _ which is inconsistent with being hit
by an automobile,'' Coleman said. ``I've picked up numerous victims
hit by automobiles. Once a car hits a body, that body is going to
land, and there will be some cuts and bruises.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have been scarred up, bruised and cut up.''
</P>
<P>
   To this day, many people in the area believe Ray Peacock was
castrated. That question was settled when Theresa Peacock went to
the funeral home and said she wasn't leaving until she saw her
son's body.
</P>
<P>
   ``People came and told us they cut his private parts out, but
they didn't,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pulled the sheet to check because that was something I
wanted to know personally,'' she said. ``I went from the top of his
head to the bottom of his feet. I knew he didn't have any scratches
on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Powell said he insisted on a county-financed autopsy,
which concluded that Ray Peacock died of a severed aorta and a
broken back ``due to massive blow from behind, typical of being
struck by motor vehicle with a high front, such as pickup truck.''
</P>
<P>
   But the county autopsy raised more questions for the Peacocks
than it answered because they insist they saw no wounds on the
teen-ager's body. And the cranium was not examined, said Coleman,
the funeral home director. The family and Coleman tried in vain to
obtain a second autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People and the Peacock family to protest the death fizzled
because few people were willing to publicly challenge the official
ruling that it was accidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a racial thing, and we didn't have enough people,''
Cecil Peacock said. ``They said, `We got to live here.' There's one
thing I've learned about crime. You've got to have someone in your
corner.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes his son was lured out of his house that Saturday
night by white youths angered by his friendships with white girls.
``A lot of people said he met a white girl down there, and these
white males were already down there waiting. They mobbed him,''
Cecil Peacock said.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Rice, a political science professor who is director of
the Race and Ethnic Studies Institute at Texas A&AMP;M University, said
discrepancies can fuel charges of racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kinds of things are sort of brushed aside,'' he said of
the family's questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You end up having two camps (one black, one white), and no one
is able to prove beyond a shadow of doubt exactly what happened,''
said Rice, who is black. ``So, since proof is hard to come by,
there will always be doubt as to really what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   A FAMILY'S TRAUMA
</P>
<P>
   The death of Ray Peacock turned his family upside down.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very life-changing event for all of us,'' said his
sister Venetia, who was1 when he died. ``It affected us deeply. It
changed our whole entire family.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotional stress hit Cecil Peacock the hardest. He had a
history of anxiety problems, but the trauma of his favorite son's
death in a racially charged atmosphere overwhelmed his ability to
cope in the everyday world, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He stopped working. He woke at odd hours and roamed his
property. Sometimes he took to chopping wood and wouldn't stop
until all the hedges were cut down.
</P>
<P>
   He carted junk home and left it all over the yard. Trucks, cars,
scrap metal, clothes, boxes, appliances, car parts, tires and more.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Peacock tried in vain to move the junk away from the
front yard. ``I just had to throw up my hands,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her voice cracks and catches even today as she remembers how her
three young daughters were teased to tears because they lived in a
junkyard.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was rough,'' she said. ``Children would tease them and call
their father a junkyard dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Cecil Peacock says he had a nervous breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought every white man in Newton County was my friend until
that happened'' to his son, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Cecil Peacock was unable to work, Theresa Peacock's
earnings as a janitor became the family's only income.
</P>
<P>
   Now 64, Theresa Peacock still sweeps schoolroom floors, cleans
blackboards, empties trash cans and scrubs bathrooms. In many ways,
the job gave her a respite from the unpredictable quirks of her
tormented husband.
</P>
<P>
   Church gave Theresa Peacock the emotional strength to go on
after her son was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the only thing I could really rely on,'' she said.
``I really didn't have any trust in the whites after it happened.
It just made me more frightened around them. The only thing that
really kept me going was reading my Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was completely afraid to go anywhere,'' she said. ``I didn't
go anywhere by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Her two oldest sons already had left home when Ray Peacock was
killed, leaving the girls, ages 11, 8 and 6, at home to absorb the
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a childlike feeling that things were coming apart, that
nothing was right and everything was just wrong,'' said Venetia
Peacock, the eldest daughter, now 32.
</P>
<P>
   The world got smaller and smaller for the growing Peacock
sisters. Their parents allowed them to leave home for few places
except school and church. Friends were scrutinized by their
parents, and dating boys was difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother basically picked my junior prom date,'' said Venetia
Peacock, who lives in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   She has worked for several nonprofit groups that provide social
services to low-income families because of a personal ``need to
stick up for the underdog,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At night, she studies for a master's degree in business. She
hopes it will help her gain a management position so she can be a
more powerful voice for people unable to help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   She has never given up questioning what happened to the brother
whom she adored.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a thread that you weave through fabric,'' she said.
``It's stuck on my life in every way,'' she said. ``It's probably
affected all of us in how we think about fairness.
</P>
<P>
   ``When something like this happens, you really have to work
twice as hard not to blame a whole race of people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   THE DRIVER'S PAIN
</P>
<P>
   The white man who drove the pickup that authorities say killed
Ray Peacock is now a traveling oil well driller with an 18-year-old
child of his own. He is uncomfortable speaking about that night 21
years ago and says he is still haunted by his actions behind the
wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell Mr. Cecil (Peacock) that I'm still about as upset
about it as he is,'' Phelps said. ``Not a day goes by that I don't
think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Phelps said he was trying to avoid a head-on collision on a
foggy roadway, and didn't realize he had hit a person until his
younger brother told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me that we'd hit a person, and we turned around, and
we couldn't see nobody. So, naturally, we were scared to death, so
we went back to my uncle's house and then called in (to the
sheriff's office),'' Phelps said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing racial about it,'' he said. ``The blacks are
what made it controversial. The first thing they done was call in
the NAACP, and it was a racial thing and everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Phelps said his life, too, was changed forever by Ray Peacock's
death. The uproar was so overwhelming that Phelps stayed out of
school at the request of school officials, who also instructed his
brothers and cousin to stay home. Phelps never went back to school.
He dropped out and moved in with his grandmother in New Iberia,
La., and began working in the oil fields. He didn't move back to
Newton for seven years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Phelps says times have changed and blacks and whites
coexist peacefully in Deep East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there are any racial deals, either way,'' he
said. ``I mean, I see these white girls going with these black boys
in school, and the same vice versa, and there ain't nobody doing
nothing or saying nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't approve of it, but it's not my business,'' he said.
``But I don't approve of a white girl going with a Spanish guy
neither. That's me. I just don't believe in mixing races.''
</P>
<P>
   A TOLL OF RACISM
</P>
<P>
   Experts on race are not surprised that the Peacock family and
Phelps still feel like victims of their circumstances more than two
decades later. The emotional toll of such racially tinged incidents
can be debilitating, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that's really the untold story of the impact of
racism, particularly on those who suffer from racism,'' said Rice,
the A&AMP;M race institute director. ``The psychological long-term
impact is tremendous and quite intense, and one never forgets the
kind of treatment, the kind of behavior that they were exposed
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if racism is only perceived, he said, the effect would be
the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you have experienced really traumatic effects of racism,
it becomes embedded within you,'' Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Lingering doubts and resentments about deaths like Ray Peacock's
make efforts to change the dynamics of race in Deep East Texas all
the more difficult after a shocking incident like Byrd's death.
Even before then, blacks and whites in Deep East Texas had settled
into a subtle, unspoken code of behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is smooth ``as long as the black man stays in his
place and doesn't buck the system,'' said Coleman, the Jasper
mortician. ``Every small town has a system.''
</P>
<P>
   Blacks who gain political and economic power learn not to
challenge the unspoken code of subordination, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're singing the songs that the good ol' boys want to hear.
`Yes.' `OK,''' he said. ``It will probably always be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   But a task force created by Jasper's black mayor, R.C. Horn, has
taken the lead in trying to bring change. At meetings over the past
few months, local blacks came forward to tell personal stories of
racist slights, and white residents apologized for using slurs or
being dismissive toward blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, the mayor's task force agreed to tear down one
of Jasper's oldest symbols of segregation. A 163-year-old fence in
the city cemetery that divided white graves from black graves,
including the plot where Byrd is buried, was removed during a
ceremony of reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things need to go much further than that,'' Rice said. ``That
was just symbolic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have people in that part of Texas who are making an effort
to try to promote positive race relations,'' said Bill Hale,
executive director of the Texas Human Rights Commission, which
combats employment and housing discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   But, ``You still have a significant number of people who want to
keep blacks in a white-defined role, said Hale, who is white.
``That means they want blacks to stay in their place. So it's a
very mixed kind of situation. It switches back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Diggles, who as director of the Deep East Texas Council
of Governments is one of the most prominent blacks in the area,
argues that the Byrd slaying should not be considered a symbol of
local racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``That murder could have happened in other parts of the
country,'' Diggles said.
</P>
<P>
   Diggles' Council of Governments is working to alleviate poverty
by trying to obtain economic development grants and to attract
business to the area, which has been hit in recent years by the
closing of lumber mills, hospitals, and furniture and door
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   The unemployment rate of blacks is more than double that of
whites in the region, but Diggles says racism is not the reason.
``The average wage and salary disparities are probably a reflection
upon starting from behind and trying to catch up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he sees less segregation and more social mingling of
races, especially among the young. Lots of interracial children are
growing up in the area, and he said there is ``an enormous amount''
of mixed dating.
</P>
<P>
   But just because mixed dating is more prevalent, that doesn't
mean it's accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Diggles said some local school officials have asked him to
conduct sensitivity workshops on interracial dating ``for those
people who don't know how to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   MEMORIES OF A SON
</P>
<P>
   Theresa Peacock didn't display any photographs of Ray Peacock
for nearly -- decade because her husband couldn't bear to see them.
</P>
<P>
   But today, the most striking picture in their living room is a
large painting of Ray Peacock modeled after his high school class
photo. Photographs of all six Peacock children fill the walls of
the small room, where a wood stove and an Army blanket nailed over
the door keep out the winter dampness.
</P>
<P>
   The Peacocks cherish their son's high school yearbook and memory
scrapbook, where the secret love letters from white girls were
found tucked among the pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only wish things could be different, you know?'' one letter
says. ``I mean, oh man, everything could be so neat! And we
wouldn't have to hide what we feel inside.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter is not signed, but Theresa Peacock learned that a
white girl wrote it after she painstakingly matched the handwriting
to a good-luck tribute inside her son's yearbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I was the last to know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And she might be the last ever to be convinced that her son's
death was a simple roadway accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``God in heaven would have to come down from heaven and tell me
that,'' Theresa Peacock said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
