<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BLACKWHITE-JASPER _ On a lonely stretch of road outside the
EastTexas town of Jasper, a black man dies a mysterious death late
one night. His broken body is found in a ditch. The suspects are a
couple of young white men in a pick-up. The black man's family
believes the white men lured him to the fog-shrouded road so they
could castrate him and beat him. Jasper, Texas 1998? No, it all
happened in 1977, a bigoted time when a black teen in East Texas
could lose his life for dating a white girl and no one would be
punished. We trace the modern history of East Texas race relations
through the Peacock family, a mother, father and five surviving
children who are still emotionally wounded by the death of
18-year-old Anthony Peacock on an isolated road near Jasper.
Through their personal experiences, we document the moral shadow
dance between whites and blacks in a part of Texas that still
carries vestiges of the Old South. Advances beginning of trial
testimony, scheduled to begin Tuesday. (Gamino, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-IMPEACH _ AUSTIN _ The impeachment is over. Bill Clinton is
still in office, to the chagrin of many Republicans. Yet, a
Republican with possible designs on the office, Gov. George W.
Bush, has stayed way out of the fray. Why? How has that helped/hurt
him? How has the impeachment affected the timing of his
announcement for the office? Will the GOP experience with Clinton
inoculate Bush against prying into his ``young and irresponsible''
days? Or will it redouble efforts to dig up dirt on him? A look at
how impeachment politics intersects with presidential politics in
2000. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SALTLAKE _ SALT LAKE CITY _ Frank Zang misses the simple joy of
flipping through the morning paper and sipping a cup of coffee. His
quiet ritual has turned into a daily test of nerves. ``I have to
admit,'' says Zang, a media representative for the Salt Lake
Olympic Committee, ``I cringe each morning when I walk out to get
my newspaper, thinking about what might be greeting me.'' Zang has
plenty of company. The bloodletting has persisted for months in
Salt Lake, threatening to sap the color from city's Olympic facade,
drip by drip. The ongoing Olympic scandal has been excruciating for
a city that has historically extolled the virtues of hard work and
clean living. Instead of celebrating the three-year milestone to
the start of the Games this week, Salt Lake has had to face a
jarring 300-page report that accuses top officials of making covert
payments to IOC members, providing extravagant gifts and trips,
then concealing their actions. (Hannigan, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BLACKHISTORY-VOICES _ Overview of the importance of oral
traditions in the African American community. (Keilman, Dayton
Daily News). 30.
</P>
<P>
   w/BLACKHISTORY-DIALOGUE _ A dialogue with four octogenarians on
the early years of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   MISSINGCHILD _ KETTERING, Ohio _ Sunday story on the missing
girl from Kettering, Ohio. Many possible angles, depending on
developments, but will possibly be an ``anatomy of a search''
story. (Beyerlein, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   MENTALLY-DISABLED-JAILED _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ With an IQ of
58 and the functional capability of a 5-year-old, Tony Laster
cannot comprehend the legal thinking that put him behind bars for
seven weeks for stealing $2 from an eighth-grade classmate. Laster
is not alone in this. Defense attorneys and advocates for the
mentally retarded say they can't comprehend it either. State
Attorney Barry Krischer's ``zero tolerance'' policy for school
crimes is itself being judged by the treatment given Laster, a
hearing-impaired 15-year-old who is not able to remember an address
or phone number _ let alone sort out the uproar his playground
incident has ignited. (Moffett, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SMOKE-FUNDS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Smokers go into nursing
homes sooner and die there younger than nonsmokers, but those who
survive stay longer. Those effects add up to more than $103 million
a year in smoking-related costs to Florida's Medicaid system, says
a study by a state and university research team. The study's
principal author says it reinforces the need to spend more of
Florida's $12.7 billion tobacco lawsuit settlement money on care
for the elderly and research on preventive treatment for smokers.
(McLachlin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   STATE LEGISLATURES
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-LEGE _ Texas border counties have long come to Austin
with hat in hand, only to be neglected by legislators and pushed
around in the political trenches by more powerful regions. They
haven't helped themselves, they admit, by bickering among
themselves. But now border leaders say their infighting is over,
they are working together for the first time, and they are ready to
crank up their new unified voice in this year's legislative session
as they push for a Border Marshall Plan. (Harmon/Davis, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Well, now, wasn't that fun! We got to talk dirty
in public for more than a year. We learned the names of lots of
members of Congress. We discovered it's a toss-up whether it is
more dangerous to be a friend of Bill or a friend of Linda. And it
all ended just about where it began. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ I was out of my mind to even think we ever
would hear the last of Monica Lewinsky _ or of Ken Starr, even Bill
Clinton. While America might want closure, it's not going to get
it.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.) MOVED
THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ Four days a week, Joel Klein, the
Justice Department's antitrust chief, walks over to the federal
courtroom where the Microsoft trial has unfolded for the past 16
weeks. There Klein sits on a wooden bench, watching David Boies,
his top gun, pick Microsoft's defenses apart. Microsoft has made
Boies' task easier by concocting a legal strategy that has
occasionally left the judge shaking his head in disbelief at what
he has heard. (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox News Service in
the Washington bureau.)
</P>
<P>
   MOVED Thursday in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   QVC _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Interview with QVC host Kathy
Levine, and a discussion of the company's success. With sidebars on
becoming a sales rep, QVC by the numbers, and a timeline.
(Grantham, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NOFUN _ It's an odd contradiction. Isn't this supposed to be,
after all, the country where the fun never sets? Aren't booming,
multi-billion dollar industries _ TV, movies, sports, the Internet,
Hollywood, video games, theme parks, casinos _ built on amusing us
silly? Yet, beneath all this packaged jollity, about half the
nation's population, according to Yankelovich, suspects that life
is passing them by. (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WWII-MERCHANTMARINE _ BRUNSWICK, Ga. _ It was the middle of the
night of April 8, 1942 when a gigantic explosion shook this port
town and lit up the black Atlantic sky like the Fourth of July.
John Henderson, then 11 and now a physician, remembers it well. A
German submarine had just torpedoed the USS Oklahoma, killing 22
men. All of the bodies were identified, except four that were
burned beyond recognition. Now, a Brunswick group made up of former
Merchant Marine sailors has finally identified the four, and is
raising money for a bigger monument to mark their common grave.
Rep. Jack Kingston is trying to have the four awarded the
Distinguished Service Medal, and helping the Brunswick group track
down relatives of the long-dead sailors. It's a little known fact
about World War II that the Merchant Marine suffered more
casualties, per capita, than any other branch of service. It's
little known for a reason - Washington didn't want the public to
know that 10 times the number of ships sunk at Pearl Harbor went
down within sight of East Coast cities - several near Brunswick.
We'll tell the story of these men, what happened to them, talk to
people who remember hearing the explosion, and others, to Merchant
Marine vets who are now demanding their due. Illustrate with photo
of a small marker, headlines from the Brunswick papers, photos of
the site where this ship went down, etc. Hopefully we will have
mugs of the four men, now that they have been identified. And we'll
try to talk to members of their families who were simply told their
loved ones had been lost at sea. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 50. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/WWII-ORGS _ If you want to help/contact organizations.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WWII-SUBCMDR _ Interview with Reinhard Hardegan,now 85, who was
commander of a German sub that sank several ships off the coast of
St. Simons. He became somewhat of a hero in America years later for
his efforts to avoid killing tourists who flocked to the beach
after one shipwreck. (Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 23.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   BILLYRAY-CYRUS _ NASHVILLE _ With his tight jeans, muscle shirts
and goofy haircut, Billy Ray Cyrus was on top of the country music
world in 1991 when he broke out of Eastern Kentucky obscurity with
the monster novelty hit, ``Achy Breaky Heart.'' But the ride didn't
last long. Within two years, he was the joke of Music Row as radio
programmers and label execs turned their back on him. As he watched
his records (and his manager) die, Cyrus also soared into
depression, retreated into his teepee on his farm, and did some
soul searching. This year, he emerged from the isolation with a
comeback hit (``Busy Man''), a new haircut, and newfound respect
within the industry. (MLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
MOVED
</P>
