<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4447 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMR-PILOTS-1STLD-WRIT     02-13 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMR-PILOTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-830(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILOTS UNION IN CONTEMPT, FINED AT LEAST $10 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ill., Fla., N.Y., Minn., Colo., Calif., Nicaragua,
Puerto Rico)   (Eds: Changes to reflect that fine is expected to be far more than
$10 million; other changes, tightening throughout.) 
(Eds: Also moving in `a' category.) 
(See also AMR-WORK; Also moving in `a' news file.) 
(jw) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge in Dallas cited the union representing American
Airlines pilots for contempt Saturday and fined it at least $10
million for ignoring his back-to-work order, as the pilots'
continued sickout stranded tens of thousands of passengers on a
busy holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Joe Kendall said the fine could ultimately
be far more than $10 million because it was intended in part to
reimburse American for the losses it had suffered from the weeklong
sickout. American estimates that the job action has cost it more
than $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   As the labor dispute dragged on, airline terminals grew even
more crowded and passengers' tempers grew shorter as their anger at
the pilots mounted.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, lawyers for American, the nation's second-largest
airline, asked Kendall to hold the pilots in contempt and to issue
``a coercive fine'' for failing to end the sickout despite his
Wednesday order directing them to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In a scathing written ruling, Kendall said, ``Unfortunately, the
radical element that appears to be in control of the Allied Pilots
Association seems determined to fly American Airlines into the side
of the mountain, taking themselves, the company, their co-workers
and their customers with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered the union to deposit $10 million with the
court on Tuesday pending his determination at a Wednesday hearing
of the level of damages American had suffered because of the
sickout.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall also found the union's president, Richard LaVoy, and its
vice president, Brian Mayhew, to be in contempt, stating that they
had acted only half-heartedly in telling pilots to end the sickout
following his Wednesday order.
</P>
<P>
   He directed LaVoy to deposit $10,000 with the court and Mayhew,
$5,000, although he suggested that these amounts as well as the $10
million deposit were ``much less than the probable actual damages''
that would be ordered.
</P>
<P>
   After the judge's ruling, several union leaders emphasized that
they were emphatically telling pilots to return to work. But other
union members said the rank and file was debating how to respond,
with some hard-liners suggesting that they continue their sickout
to pressure American in the union's dispute over the airline's
acquisition of Reno Air, a small carrier serving the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a split right now,'' said one pilot on the sick list,
who spoke only on the condition that he not be identified. ``Some
hard-liners are saying stay the course; others are saying it's time
to go back to work to support the union but fight the battle in
other ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Several pilots said they might support a fallback strategy, a
refusal to work overtime _ a move that would be less disruptive
than a sickout, but would still force American to cancel some
scheduled flights.
</P>
<P>
   American said at 7:30 a.m. Saturday that about 2,100 of its
pilots had called in sick, down slightly from Friday, but still
enough to cause the airline to cancel more than one-third of its
2,250 scheduled flights Saturday. At midday, American said the
number out sick had dropped to 1,700, representing about one-fifth
of the airline's 9,200 pilots.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said that 845 flights were canceled Saturday,
down from 1,102 on Friday. The airline also announced that more
than 400 flights scheduled for Sunday would be canceled and more
than 200 flights Monday would be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict grew out of American's purchase in December of Reno
Air. American has said that it intends to merge Reno Air, which has
25 planes and 300 pilots, into American's much larger network, but
that it will take as long as 18 months to refit Reno Air's planes
and retrain pilots at both carriers.
</P>
<P>
   But the union contends that American is violating a fundamental
clause in its contract, which requires that all flying at the
airline and any of its subsidiaries be performed by members of the
pilots' union. The pilots have voiced concern that American may
transfer some of its flying to pilots at Reno Air, who are paid
about half as much as American pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Many pilots also say that they are worried that if the union
does not make a stand now, it will have set a dangerous precedent
if American acquires an even larger airline in the future.
</P>
<P>
   The union has demanded that the company immediately raise the
Reno pilots' pay to the level of American pilots _ a move the
company estimates would cost $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is this court's view that a minor labor dispute has been
transformed into nothing more than a shakedown,'' Kendall wrote in
his ruling. ``Even though it may indeed be more economical for
American to cave in and pay, in the long run if you pay extortion
today, you typically have to pay it tomorrow. When the pitch is
`pay us what we want or we will cost you more,' it is the type of
negotiation one usually sees when doing business with one of the
five families in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides said Saturday that they hoped to resume
negotiations within days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the Friday hearing, Kendall frequently scoffed at the union's
leaders when they insisted that they were doing everything possible
to persuade their members to return to work. He said he found it
especially disturbing that 12 of the union's 18 board members had
called in sick that day.
</P>
<P>
   But LaVoy, the union's president, repeatedly told the judge that
he was doing his utmost to get the pilots to end their sickout.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's hearing, the union stepped up the urgency of its
messages calling on pilots to return to work. The union updated its
telephone message and its World Wide Web site on Friday night to
carry a statement by LaVoy, who said: ``I want to make a personal
plea to all of our pilots. The association's leadership needs your
help in complying with Judge Joe Kendall's order. We need to get
this airline back up and running at full capacity, and we need to
do so quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kendall said the union's efforts to tell pilots to return to
the cockpit were too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   At Friday's hearing, union representatives estimated that it had
about $38 million in assets.
</P>
<P>
   In a stern warning, Kendall's ruling, said, ``If the activity
and consequent damages continue, when all the dust clears, all the
assets of the union, including their strike war chest, will be
capable of being safely stored in the overhead bin of a Piper
Cub.''
</P>
<P>
   At O'Hare International Airport outside Chicago Saturday
morning, Del Dooling, 43, a tired, unshaven salesman from
Riverside, Calif., was so angry about the cancellation of his
Friday flight to San Juan that he vowed never to fly American
Airlines again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The service has been wretched,'' he said. ``It's just
horrible. Everything is going wrong.'' Dooling added that in his
view the pilots should face a harsh penalty for defying the judge's
order. ``It should be prison and a big fine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At Miami International Airport, Gertrudis Gonzalez, 21 a student
from Managua, Nicaragua, complained about being stranded for more
than a day because her Friday morning flight home was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went hungry, they gave us nothing to eat,'' she said. ``We
were left wondering along the passageways.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute forced passengers, travel agents and American
service representatives to show a lot of resourcefulness. Standing
in the American terminal Saturday morning at Kennedy International
Airport, Patrick Reed, a plumbing wholesaler from Albany, N.Y.,
complained about the cancellation of his flight from New York to
Vancouver. But he managed to make alternative arrangements on a TWA
flight to Chicago and then a Cathay Pacific link from Chicago to
Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   While relieved about his rerouting, Reed remained angry at
American's pilots, saying, ``I think the pilots have long since
made their point, and they're being very selfish.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kendall issued his ruling, the airline issued a statement,
saying, ``Regrettably, this illegal job action left American with
no options other than canceling thousands of flights with little or
no notice, which caused great hardship to tens of thousands of
travelers.''
</P>
<P>
   The airline added that it hoped to regain public confidence.
``But before we can do that, we need to restore our operations and
take care of our passengers,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Few analysts expect that American will suffer long-term damage,
despite pledges by some angry passengers never to fly the airline
again. ``Consumers have the attention spans of monkeys,'' said
Michael Boyd, an aviation consultant in Evergreen, Colo. ``They
just forget real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Fare reductions and other incentives will draw passengers back
once a settlement is reached, he said. ``When American does fly,
they are really pretty good at it,'' he added. ``It is a
high-quality airline. They are going to get a pretty fast
response.''
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Airlines was grounded for three weeks in September
after its pilots went on strike. The carrier suffered steep losses
through the end of the year, but has recently seen its traffic
return to normal levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long-term damage,'' Boyd said, referring to American, ``is
the continuing shattering of trust between the airline and its
pilots.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilots group, which is not part of the AFL-CIO, has received
little support from other unions or from its main rival, the Air
Line Pilots Association, from which it split three decades ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
