<HEADER>
A4451 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-IMPEACH14-COX     02-13 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IMPEACH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush story `yet to be written,' but character, leadership makes
him presidential front-runner, supporters say
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   And now, like trailer-park residents after a tornado, the
residents of Political America are sifting through the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Like natural disasters, this man-made one will leave a trail of
wounded and worse. It also will leave some to benefit from the
misfortune of others.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is: Who benefits most from the wreckage of a
hyperpartisan sex-and-lies scandal?
</P>
<P>
   How about a guy who preaches bipartisanship but can boast about
topping an unprecedented sweep for his party last year?
</P>
<P>
   How about a guy who bemoans the ``if it feels good, do it''
morals of the '60s but acknowledges enjoying a similar phase?
</P>
<P>
   How about a guy who can lay claim to the Washington outsider
label despite being a president's kid?
</P>
<P>
   Is this guy lucky or what?
</P>
<P>
   Critics say George W. Bush's luck began sometime around birth
when he began a life of privilege. His lucky streak certainly
continued when Bill met Monica.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the nonrunning front-runner, it all ads up to an
enviable position, according to political pros, professors and
practitioners who are becoming increasingly confident he will run
for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at a crossroads in our system of government and faith
in our political system is at an all-time low,'' said the members
of Congress who last week formed the Draft Bush 2000 Committee.
``Governor Bush is the only one equipped to restore that faith in
our government institutions and our core American values through
his compassionate conservative beliefs and limited, constructive
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the impeachment fracas, Bush positioned himself just
beyond the fringe, damning Clinton's conduct but declining to say
whether it merited removal from office. Others in the presidential
race _ notably Dan Quayle and Steve Forbes _ sided with the
throw-the-bum-out crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Bush stuck with a safe line, potentially offensive only to the
farther-to-the-right Republicans who embraced the removal effort as
something of a holy war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad it's over with,'' he said Friday after Clinton was
cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if acquittal was the right decision, Bush ducked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision was made. And that's the good news. It's off our
TV screens, hopefully, and we can look forward,'' he said, clinging
to a position of nonengagement that one Democratic critic predicted
will come back to haunt him in presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impeachment trial was begun by the radical right influence
in the Republican Party,'' said Texas Democratic Chairwoman Molly
Beth Malcolm, who does not believe Bush is presidential material.
``I hope Governor Bush is embarrassed how members of his own party
have acted. Those same radical righters don't trust George Bush,
and they are very likely to turn their hypocritical
self-righteousness on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in a move evidencing no tolerance for anyone who didn't
side firmly with senators who voted to convict, Christian Coalition
Executive Director Randy Tate said acquittal meant ``children now
have the lesson that lying, cheating and breaking the law are
permissible on the pathway to success.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Bush backers believe the entire impeachment episode
will fade quickly from the public psyche.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short run,'' said one, ``the Republicans are behind the
eight ball, because this is not a popular place to have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Opinsky _ an adviser to Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), the
only probable presidential candidate who cast a vote Friday _ said
it's too early to judge the effect on Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some time before people outside of Texas
have a clear understanding of what he stands for on a presidential
level,'' Opinsky said. ``I do think that character does still
count. People want a president they can be proud of. That's a
message that will be lasting out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Opinsky is sure that his guy _ who voted for conviction on both
the perjury and obstruction of justice articles _ passes moral
muster. But ``a lot of the Bush story is yet to be written,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush continues to decline to offer details of his ``young and
irresponsible'' past. He acknowledges drinking too much but won't
say if he used illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to talk about my private life,'' he said last
week. ``I said it's irrelevant to the future. I've made mistakes. I
learned from my mistakes, and it's time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it was, Bush insists it was nothing Clintonian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a loyal husband, a dedicated dad and a governor who
brought integrity to the office I've held,'' he said. ``People may
not agree with every decision I've made. I think they've agreed
universally that I've treated the office with respect and
dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Texas Legislature, leaders from both parties said there
is no downside of the Clinton-Lewinsky affair for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this helps Bush. He is well thought of. He has high
morals. He is a big family man, a real Christian,'' said Midland
Rep. Tom Craddick, a longtime leader of House Republicans. ``I
think the bottom line is: That's what the people really want.''
</P>
<P>
   Craddick said voters will be interested in candidates' personal
pasts _ not so much out of prurient interest but out of a desire to
avoid another prolonged event like Starr's Clinton inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a little difference between being married and
being single,'' Craddick said of the contrast between what Clinton
did and what Bush might have done.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic Caucus Chairman Pete Gallego of Alpine said
Bush scored points by steering clear of the fray, a move that
separates him from congressional Republicans, who ``will look like
they were interested in ostensibly a dirty little street fight that
didn't get anything done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the governor has really distanced himself from a lot
of that, and it wouldn't be a factor,'' said Gallego, who backs Al
Gore for the job but believes Bush would be a good president.
</P>
<P>
   From a vantage point near the border, political scientist Jerry
Polinard of the University of Texas-Pan American in Edinburg sees
Bush potentially benefiting from an electorate both forgiving and
eager to avoid examining personal foibles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have a general expectation that whoever seeks
office will not bring the baggage Clinton brought with him. And we
are willing to forgive and forget things 20 years ago, maybe 10
years ago,'' Polinard said. ``When the people voted in '92, they
knew Clinton had a zipper problem. I don't think we're going to be
quite that generous in the upcoming cycle. We expect somebody of
decent character. Not a saint, but not someone who brings to the
table a background that raises serious questions.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, a state awaiting its first Bush sighting of
the season, political science professor Dale Kuehne of St. Anselm
College said he sees voters viewing the field with a new focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are looking for depth, somebody who can engage their
souls,'' Kuehne said. ``We've gone to a different level of
disillusionment from Watergate. The world has changed. It is not
enough to just not be Bill Clinton and to be against taxes. They
want somebody who can help them re-create a nation for the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who will pitch himself as that somebody if he gets into
the race, got the word on the Clinton acquittal Friday when he
walked into aide Joe Allbaugh's office, where a muted TV was tuned
in to history.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened?'' Bush asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got acquitted. Both articles,'' Allbaugh told Bush, who
showed no immediate reaction to the news that means he probably
would have to run against an incumbent vice president, not an
incumbent president, if he enters the race.
</P>
<P>
   Allbaugh, a veteran of three presidential campaigns and the kind
of dad not happy about having his 11-year-old daughter ask him
about oral sex, believes the country needs his boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would be a great president. I hope he runs,'' Allbaugh
said. ``There is such a thirst for leadership. He understands the
definition of leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   On other TVs around the country last week, another Texan with
intimate knowledge of how the governor's office works predicted
Allbaugh will get his wish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is going to be the nominee because he's the only
one they've got,'' ex-Gov. Ann Richards, the woman who helped
launch Bush's political career, said on Larry King Live.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
