<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-LEGE14-COX     02-13 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-LEGE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Border counties push for Marshall Plan
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas border counties have long come to Austin
with hat in hand, only to be neglected by legislators and pushed
around in the political trenches by more powerful regions. They
haven't helped things, they admit, by bickering among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But now border leaders say their infighting is over, they are
working together for the first time, and they are ready to crank up
their new unified voice in this year's legislative session as they
push for a Border Marshall Plan modeled after the U.S. effort to
rebuild Europe after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   This Marshall Plan, suggested by a powerful Republican state
senator, would build up the state's most disadvantaged area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle cry has to be 'It is our turn. It is our time,'''
state Rep. Rene Oliveira, D-Brownsville, said at the coalition's
first meeting in November. ``I am tired of the border being treated
like we are a bad stepchild.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliveira spoke to a crowd of hundreds of border leaders packed
into an Austin hotel ballroom. The event took on the air of a pep
rally, as one speaker after another repeated their theme: Stick
together and we can win.
</P>
<P>
   The featured speakers were Gov. George W. Bush and the
lieutenant governor-elect, Rick Perry, giving his first speech
after the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the border region of the state of Texas succeeds, Texas
will succeed,'' Perry told the applauding crowd. ``You're going to
receive the credit, you're going to receive the attention, you're
going to receive the respect you deserve as long as I am lieutenant
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   On their way to sweeping statewide offices, the Republicans had
courted the Democratic strongholds on the border like never before.
And border leaders say the GOP's newfound interest in their growing
population is just one reason they believe the stars are lining up
in their favor as the Legislature begins its work again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no question that the focus is on the
border,'' said El Paso County Attorney Jose Rodriguez. ``Today I
think we're finally on the verge of breaking out of that status
we've been in. Our numbers are growing, the electoral power is
there, (state leaders) recognize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry and House Speaker Pete Laney obviously recognized it.
Laney put border lawmakers in charge of five committees, including
the powerful Ways and Means Committee that Oliveira chairs, and
border representatives also landed five seats on the powerful House
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Perry, meanwhile, created the Special Committee on Border
Affairs, headed by Sen. Eddie Lucio (D-Brownsville).
</P>
<P>
   Before the session began, border leaders' most important move
was to bury old rivalries to form the Border Infrastructure
Coalition, which brought mayors and county judges and economic
development gurus to the same table to push a meat-and-potatoes
agenda in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The group wants a bigger chunk of state job training dollars to
help them attack unemployment rates that top 25 percent in places,
tax credits to reward businesses that create jobs on the border,
and a larger cut of state highway dollars to help them handle the
surge in cross-border traffic since the North American Free Trade
Agreement took effect five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They are trying to make the rest of the state realize that
what's good for the border is good for the rest of the state, that
a better-trained border labor pool means more companies moving to
Texas, that less congestion in Laredo means goods flow faster to
Austin and other cities to the north.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest battle is in the hearts and minds of Texans,''
said state Sen. Elliot Shapleigh (D-El Paso). ``Until Dallas, Dumas
and Denton see their picture in that border crossing and their
future economy in Mexican trade, we can't get the investment in
infrastructure and work force training.''
</P>
<P>
   They have found an important ally in a Waco Republican: Sen.
David Sibley, chairman of the Senate Economic Development
Committee, who toured several border areas after the last
legislative session to gather information for a report on the
state's economy.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley saw the area's nagging problems, but he also saw its
potential. And he said his visits convinced him that something had
to be done now: a border Marshall Plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an area of the state that's devastated, not by war but
by neglect,'' Sibley said. ``They don't need another program, they
don't need more welfare benefits down there. What they need is
infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Sibley said the state has to make a long-term commitment to the
border. Everything can't be done at once, he said, but if the state
injects steady investment in the right places _ job training and
highways being two good examples _ Sibley said the border ``has the
ability to be the leader in prosperity 20 to 30 years from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Cuellar (D-Laredo), one of the border lawmakers on
the House Appropriations Committee, said he and others hope to
funnel money to the border by changing the formulas that determine
how much goes where.
</P>
<P>
   By giving more weight to things like unemployment rates, welfare
dependency, education level and income, Cuellar said, the state
could make sure money gets to where it's needed most. That would
help not just border communities but also other struggling areas
across the state, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, members of the new coalition say they will keep
pressing. ``Too many times what happens is that they pit one of us
against another on the border,'' said Rep. Pete Gallego (D-Alpine).
``Not anymore. It's our turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
