<HEADER>
A4463 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSINGCHILD14-COX     02-13 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSINGCHILD14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Search for Ohio 9-year-old continues
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The donut shop was open, but there was no sign of
a waitress.
</P>
<P>
   A concerned customer phoned police, and thus began the search in
1971 for 20-year-old Leorra Rose Looney of Lakewood, Colo. Her nude
body was found three days later, dumped in a field. She had been
raped, strangled and shot.
</P>
<P>
   The murder remained unsolved for several years, until a
thumbprint lifted from a coffee cup in the donut shop ultimately
put her killers, Sherman McCrary and Carl Taylor, in prison.
</P>
<P>
   That case taught a young cop named James O'Dell how to run a
methodical investigation over the long haul. Today, as Kettering
police chief, O'Dell said he's trying to apply the same principles
to the probe into the disappearance a week ago today of 9-year-old
Erica Baker.
</P>
<P>
   While Erica's fate remains unknown, O'Dell sees parallels with
the investigation of Looney's death.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, O'Dell was a young officer whose mentor was
then Lakewood Police Chief Pierce Brooks, the famed detective who
had previously cracked the brutal Los Angeles cop killing
chronicled in Joseph Wambaugh's 1973 book ``The Onion Field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The message to me from Chief Brooks (in the Looney case) was
`leave no stone unturned,''' O'Dell said in an interview Friday
with the Dayton Daily News. ``That's what we've tried to do here
(in Erica's case) _ be very purposeful, patient, exact.''
</P>
<P>
   With Friday's conclusion of the exhaustive but fruitless
five-day search for Erica by members of the Miami Valley Urban
Search and Rescue Task Force, police are ``switching into a
full-gear investigative mode,'' O'Dell said. By Friday, Kettering
police had already logged 1,200 manhours on the case and checked
700 leads. They are now prioritizing and checking the hundreds of
leads that remain.
</P>
<P>
   Despite hundreds of calls to a tip line, police acknowledge they
still have no physical evidence or eyewitness accounts to help them
find Erica, who vanished about 4 or 4:30 p.m. last Sunday. She was
last seen walking her dog near the retention pond behind the
Kettering Recreation Complex by a couple who later found the dog
dragging his leash outside of nearby Kettering Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   Erica, a third-grader at Indian Riffle Elementary School, and
her brothers had returned home from a weekend visit with their
father, Greg Baker, 33, of Huber Heights, at about 3 p.m. Her
mother, Melissa ``Misty'' Baker, 31, of Kettering, agreed to let
her walk the dog about 3:30. Misty Baker said she grew worried when
Erica didn't return after a couple of hours. She reported the girl
missing about 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   O'Dell decided to go to the scene personally when he learned of
the situation about an hour later. It didn't sound like a runaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case when I heard her age and there was a dog with
her, bells started going off,'' O'Dell said. ``I said, 'I'm going
on this one.'''
</P>
<P>
   There were 50 or 60 citizens on the scene who wanted to help.
``People want to help. If you don't give them something to do,
they'll do it themselves,'' O'Dell said. Despite ``tremendously
good intentions,'' he said, volunteers can divert police attention
from immediate investigative tasks. Volunteers eventually were
enlisted to circulate fliers about Erica's disappearance to homes
and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Kettering police Capt. David Woolf, who is in charge of
day-to-day operations in the investigation, said officials didn't
want civilians _ or even police who weren't specially trained in
search-and-rescue techniques _ to join in the search, because they
didn't want to risk tainting a crime scene or overlooking anything
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only get one shot at this,'' Woolf said. ``It's very
heartwarming to see our community coming together, but we wanted to
get a highly experienced team.''
</P>
<P>
   After an initial search last Sunday night by local police and
fire officials, the Miami Valley Urban Search and Rescue Task Force
took over the search Monday morning. Officials decided to drain the
retention pond, fearing Erica may have fallen in.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kettering pond yielded nothing, and the search spread
out to cover targeted areas _ woods, fields, old barns and
outbuildings _ in a 150-square-mile area in a seven-mile radius of
the recreation complex. Up to 100 specialists from as far away as
Cleveland joined the search throughout the week, along with 16
canine units, rangers on horseback and helicopter crews. Rangers
also searched the Five Rivers MetroParks' Germantown Reserve, after
park maintenance crews found a Winnie the Pooh sweatshirt
resembling the one Erica wore when she disappeared. The family said
the shirt was not Erica's and Friday's search of the park turned up
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Kettering's 20 detectives are being augmented by 30 or so
detectives from the Dayton, Centerville and Beavercreek police in
checking leads. O'Dell said police departments from the Miami
Valley and beyond have offered assistance. ``This is kind of like
when there's a death in the family and the neighbors call and ask
if they can bring food.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Dell even called the South Carolina cop who served as
spokesman during the Susan Smith case, for advice on how to deal
with the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Just last August, O'Dell attended a seminar on missing children
sponsored by the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children
in Washington, D.C., which outlined investigative protocols and
suspect profiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting there last August thinking, `Never in Kettering,
Ohio,''' O'Dell said. ``Lo and behold, here it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The seminar stressed the importance of quick action when a child
goes missing _ ``it's key to have the mindset of `time is our
enemy,''' O'Dell said. ``The more time that goes by, the less
chance the person will be returned safely.''
</P>
<P>
   National statistics show children often know their abductors.
Police spokesmen have said Erica's relatives have been cooperative
and are not suspected in her disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Dell said ``the rule of good investigation is, everybody's
a suspect. I like the words President Reagan used for
investigations: Trust, but verify.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he's still hoping police will get a tip that will solve
the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most crimes are solved,'' he said, ``not by brilliant police
work, but because somebody for whatever reason _ courage, fear,
guilt _ comes forward with information.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
