<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT BATTLE DEALT MEAGER SPOILS TO ALL SIDES 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Eds: Correct political affiliation of Rogan; changes throughout) 
 (ATTN: Maine, Ill., Miss., Texas, S.D., Conn., Wash., Mass., Utah,
La., Ky., Tenn., N.J., Iowa, Del., Ariz., Pa., Ohio, Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-AFTERMATH, IMPEACH-STARR,
IMPEACH-POLITICIANS, IMPEACH-SOCIETY, IMPEACH-LIVINGSTON,
IMPEACH-REAX, IMPEACH-LEGACY-REVIEW, EDIT-IMPEACH-AFTERMATH,
DOWD-COLUMN, IMPEACH-LEGAL, IMPEACH-SAGES) 
(jw) 
 This article was reported by Lizette Alvarez, John M. Broder and
Katharine Q. Seelye, and was written by Broder.  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Christmas was still six days away, but the holiday
mood evaporated on Dec. 19 for Sen. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, as she
watched the House of Representatives vote to impeach President
Clinton. From her coastal home in Falmouth, she felt a sense of
foreboding as she viewed the vicious partisan brawling that
preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that Christmas was over that day,'' Ms. Snowe, a
moderate, recalled on Friday after the Senate, and she herself, had
found Clinton not guilty of perjury and obstruction of justice. She
knew, too, that the Senate could not allow such a spectacle in its
dignified chambers.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers and top political advisers were also in
a grim mood on Dec. 19 as they gathered in the office of John
Podesta, the White House chief of staff. They were anticipating the
vote that day that would mark Clinton forever as only the second
American president to be impeached, and they were determined to
make a new assault on the charges. But they were not prepared for
the bombshell that came first: the announcement that Rep. Robert
Livingston, R-La., who was the Speaker-designate, was leaving the
House because of reports of marital infidelities, and that
Livingston was urging the president to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were shocked,'' said one senior member of the president's
legal team who was present as the group fell silent. ``I felt,
Jesus, we're at a point where we're eating our own. It genuinely
scared me. I was shaking. The whole thing seemed to me to be very,
very mean and very unstable.''
</P>
<P>
   The third set of actors in the Senate drama _ the 13 House
managers who presented the case against the president _ were in a
different mood over the holiday season. Just before New Year's,
they gathered in the Judiciary Committee conference room, called
``the War Room,'' to plan the prosecution. They were almost giddy
about the new role as prosecutors as they pictured a full trial
with witnesses galore, fiery cross-examinations and, finally, the
removal of the president.
</P>
<P>
   The three major players had differing objectives going into the
trial, and all achieved some of their goals. The senators, who
wanted a short and dignified trial, emerged less bloodied by the
five-week proceeding than the House. The president, after his
lawyers made a far more aggressive defense than they did in the
House, was acquitted by a wide margin but hardly vindicated. And
the managers made their defiant stand for principle but gained not
even a simple majority for their charges and did little to repair
the image of House Republicans as hellbent on embarrassing the
president.
</P>
<P>
   The House prosecution team walked away with the fewest spoils.
Their wish list of witnesses was whittled down to three _ Monica
Lewinsky, Vernon Jordan and Sidney Blumenthal
</P>
<P>
   None of the actors could claim victory after 13 months of
revelation and public revulsion. But the Constitution bore up well
under the strain, and the president and congressional leaders vowed
to try to forget the agony and the anger of the journey just ended.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a brief Rose Garden statement on Friday, called for
a time of ``reconciliation and renewal for America'' and indicated
he was prepared to forgive those who tried to get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, members traded congratulations on the floor and
said the trial might even have strengthened the institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we preserved the dignity of the Senate,'' said Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who voted to convict Clinton on both
impeachment charges. ``It ended as the founders intended it to.''
</P>
<P>
   Gathered with his prosecution team in the House Judiciary
Committee hearing room where the impeachment proceedings began last
fall, Henry Hyde, R-Ill., was bowed but not resentful. ``I have no
regrets,'' he said quietly.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   GOING TO TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   The telephone calls from jittery senators, haunted by the House
impeachment proceedings, followed Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., everywhere during the Christmas break. His cell
phone rang in the middle of the Cotton Bowl, where he sat with Sen.
Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, at his side. It rang as he bounced
his baby granddaughter on his knee at his son's house. It rang in
the car, in the office and at home in Pascagoula, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Lott spoke so often to Senate Minority Leader Thomas Daschle,
D-S.D., that the two practically had a hot line.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators insisted to Lott that they wanted a short trial
with no witnesses. Others wanted a full trial with live testimony.
All of them fretted about the impact on the Senate, and they
wondered if they could trust one another _ Republicans and
Democrats _ to keep it civilized.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., called an old friend, Sen. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash., and one of Lott's confidants, who was heading to
Hawaii with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before you say anything, I know why you called,'' Lieberman
remembers Gorton saying. ``I was about to call you for the same
reason. We have got to start talking about how the Senate handles
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The conversation was the genesis of a plan that would set the
tone of cooperation that Lott and Daschle hoped to establish.
</P>
<P>
   The details were in flux, but almost everyone agreed on the
goal: preserving the dignity of the Senate. Sen. Mitch McConnell,
R-Ky., said, ``Having a sense that the outcome was not in doubt, it
fell in two categories: Honor the Constitution and do as little
damage to the institution as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lieberman-Gorton dialogue had the quiet assent of Republican
and Democratic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The two, who talked five times a day over the holidays,
fashioned a plan that could perhaps avert a final vote on the
articles of impeachment by taking a test vote on the charges and
the evidence. The idea appealed to Lott, who found the thought of a
long trial with a slew of witnesses distasteful. ``He is a
realist,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate conservatives furiously rejected the proposal, and by
the time the new Senate reconvened the first week in January, the
plan was nearly doomed.
</P>
<P>
   At the first Republican caucus, conservatives refused to curtail
the trial in any way. ``People wanted a final vote on the articles,
even if it was a losing vote,'' said Sen. Robert Bennett, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   The trial would proceed, but first the two sides had to agree on
a framework.
</P>
<P>
   On. Jan. 7, a Thursday, Lott, Daschle and their lawyers tried to
work out a plan, but it foundered on the question of witnesses.
Republicans wanted the right to summon witnesses; Democrats wanted
none, or at most a sharply limited number.
</P>
<P>
   The next day 100 Democrats and Republican gathered in a
bipartisan caucus behind the closed doors of the ornate Old Senate
Chamber to salvage the process. Republicans were hoping the meeting
would soften Democrats, especially Daschle. Democrats were hoping
the conservative hard-liners would be moved by the history of the
moment and agree to their plan.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not until the very end of the caucus that a
breakthrough occurred.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing the two sides discuss their proposals for the
trial, Gramm stood up and called the two plans identical except for
the differences over witnesses. ``I rise today not as Massachusetts
man, or as a New Englander, but as American,'' Gramm said, quoting
Daniel Webster. He suggested that the Senate proceed with the
trial, postponing the question of which witnesses to call and how
many.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., agreed.
</P>
<P>
   With the liberal and the conservative in agreement, Lott seized
the moment. ``Let's put it in writing,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, in effect, put off the difficult question of witnesses
and began the historic proceeding with a 100-0 vote on procedure.
It was to be the last unanimous vote of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   DEALING WITH IMPEACHMENT
</P>
<P>
   As they sat that December morning in Podesta's office, the
president's men decided that something had to be done, and quickly,
to stop what they feared might become an avalanche of calls for
Clinton to follow the lead of Livingston and resign, as he had
himself suggested in his stunning remarks on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, bolted into the
Oval Office and asked the president what he wanted to say.
According to Lockhart's handwritten notes of the conversation,
Clinton wanted his spokesman to immediately issue a statement
urging Livingston to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a decent guy and doesn't deserve it,'' Lockhart remembers
the president's saying to him about Livingston. ``The politics of
personal destruction has to stop here,'' the president added.
</P>
<P>
   The shock waves of the Livingston resignation spread far beyond
the West Wing of the White House, and had a sobering effect on
members of Congress of both parties who might have been
contemplating calling for Clinton to step down in the aftermath of
the impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of the entire government unraveling, very few members of
Congress joined a clamor for Clinton's resignation. The president
had dodged one of the most potentially hazardous moments of the
entire impeachment battle.
</P>
<P>
   But still the trial lay ahead. Clinton's lawyers regrouped after
the impeachment vote and began to plot a strategy for defeating the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   There was agreement within both the legal and political councils
of the White House that they had botched the handling of the House
debate, underestimating the resolve of House Republicans and giving
insufficient attention to answering the legal charges raised by
Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   They vowed not to make that mistake again before the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we thought going into the trial was that we had to
aggressively make the case that the charges brought by the House
managers were a house of cards, and that's exactly what we did,''
said one senior White House official.
</P>
<P>
   THE WAR ROOM
</P>
<P>
   Although almost everyone in Washington was predicting that it
would be impossible to garner a two-thirds majority in the Senate
to convict the president, Hyde, who led the 13 House prosecutors,
had confidence in their case.
</P>
<P>
   He was less certain, however, of getting his way in the
notoriously self-important Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we were entering alien territory,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate did not want salacious testimony brought to its
hallowed chamber, the managers well knew. While the article of
impeachment charging the president with perjury was mired in the
lurid details of who touched whom and where, the managers, led by
Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., saw greater promise in the obstruction
case, the impeachment article that had drawn a weaker vote from
their House colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   They had hoped to call 15 to 18 witnesses, a roster that
included the stars as well as the bit players: The videographer who
had taped the president's deposition in the Paula Jones sexual
misconduct lawsuit, an expert on sexual harassment, Secret Service
agents, a judge and even Dick Morris, the sometime presidential
adviser. ``We were being very generous in those days,'' Rep. Ed
Bryant, R-Tenn., recalled wistfully in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   But word came, indirectly and almost immediately, that Lott was
unenthusiastic about witnesses. He was even considering ending the
trial before a vote on the final articles, an idea being floated in
his caucus.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first sign of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   HANDS OFF BY THE WHITE HOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the trial, Daschle kept the White House informed of
his strategy for handling the proceeding and keeping Democrats
united, but did not seek advice from the president or his advisers.
</P>
<P>
   He made it clear to Clinton that he should keep his distance
because any heavy-handed efforts to lobby senators would be seen as
tampering with the jury and would surely backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made mention of the fact at some point that I didn't want
calls made to senators,'' Daschle said on Friday. ``I just felt
there had to be some separation here and that lobbying in this case
would be unseemly, and they respected that. I don't know of one
call that the White House made to one senator.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said they took Daschle's advice and
deliberately avoided inserting themselves into Senate
deliberations. But there was a constant stream of contacts between
top White House political aides under the direction of Steve
Ricchetti, the deputy chief of staff, and Daschle and his aides.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also spoke frequently with a handful of Democratic
senators to ``take their pulse,'' as one aide put it. Clinton's
closest contacts were with Sen. Robert Torricelli of New Jersey,
Sen. Christopher Dodd of Connecticut, Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa and
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president wasn't disengaged or oblivious,'' a senior White
House staffer said. ``Everyone knew what he thought and wanted.
This wasn't a blind date. But everyone knew this was out of our
control. We were at best in the back seat with someone else
driving.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
