<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTEBOOK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Little E takes 14th after metal-twisting weekend
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ We interrupt this all-Earnhardt weekend
for a Little E update. Dale Earnhardt Jr. made it to his hauler
Saturday afternoon without crashing into anything.
</P>
<P>
   He'd already done enough damage out on the track and pit road.
</P>
<P>
   On the weekend so far dominated by his father, Dale Sr., Little
E seemed to have trouble staying out of the way of his competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, he opened defense of his Busch Grand National
points championship with a 14th place finish in the Napa Auto Parts
300 at Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   His car was damaged when he was caught up in the second accident
of the day on lap 78 that involved eight wildly-spinning cars. His
bigger problem was the car's transmission, however.
</P>
<P>
   ''We sat back early in the race, riding in the back just staying
out of trouble,'' Earnhardt said. ''We missed a couple of wrecks by
doing that. Then everytime we'd get our track position like we
needed, the thing wouldn't go into third gear. So we'd lose a lot
of spots on restarts. That was disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We finally got up to second, and the 35 (Lyndon Amick) car
broke a tranny or missed a shift and paused for a moment. I tried
to keep from hitting him. I got into him a little bit, didn't spin
him out, but the 44 (Terry Labonte) had nowhere to go and he punted
me and turned me around. I didn't think we got hit hard right there
at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Little E spent the weekend listening to the sound of metal
twisting. He crashed early on Friday and was eliminated from the
IROC race, prompting his father to say, ''It looked like to me his
plan was to run wide open until he hit something.''
</P>
<P>
   Then in the last Busch practice Friday, Little E bumped into
Curtis Markham on pit road, causing enough damage to his car to
require a backup.
</P>
<P>
   ''We went off into the corner and Michael Waltrip was pulling
out of the pits or was riding real slow, waiting on the pack. I
thought I could go between him and the guy in the 29 car. The 29
car wasn't abreast of the situation so I probably shouldn't have
stuck my nose in there. I should have backed off. I mean, it's
practice. We had a fast race car. We probably shouldn't have even
been on the race track. It's just a mistake on my part.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides he knows a good body shop. Long as my guys don't mind
fixing them,'' Earnhardt said, ''I don't mind getting in there.''
</P>
<P>
   CASEY GETS BATTERED
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Casey Atwood won't forget his first Busch car race, after
wrecking and tumbling upside down on the last lap.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure it wasn't a big deal,'' Atwood said. ''I was just
trying to stay right behind (Randy) LaJoie and get a good run and
wait for the last lap. We come out of (turn) 4 and I'm sure he
(Andy Hillenberg) was just trying to push me along. You bump draft
a little here, and he kind of caught it the wrong way and turned me
sideways. I felt myself sliding on the roof for a little while and
then it tumbled back up and took a few more hits. I'm just real
happy nobody hit me when I was upside down.''
</P>
<P>
   A FAMILY TRADITION
</P>
<P>
   Adam Petty didn't duplicate his father Kyle's feat of winning
his first Busch race. But Adam's sixth-place finish was impressive
enough, considering he started 21st and challenged for the lead in
the last five laps.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I had to race at this place every weekend I don't know if
I'd be a race car driver,'' Petty said. ''It gets pretty hairy
sometimes going three wide up there in turn 3 and coming out of
there in turn 4, it gets kind of tight. The good lord was with us
all day long, kept us safe and we're heading to Rockingham, man.''
</P>
<P>
   A LITTLE SPEED
</P>
<P>
   Chad Little's No. 97 Ford recorded the fastest lap, 46.789
seconds or 192.353 mph, in the final Winston Cup practice Saturday
for today's Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Labonte was second at 192.217, Bobby Hamilton third at
192.189, Steve Park fourth at 192.168 and Jeremy Mayfield fifth
fastest at 191.706. Pole-sitter was 10th fastest at 191.233.
Earnhardt's final practice best was 14th at 191.115.
</P>
<P>
   A POPULAR PICK
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt seems to be a popular choice in the garage area to win
today's race. Earnhardt had a stellar Speed Weeks, finishing 10th
in last week's first-round qualifying and then winning both
Thursday's Gatorade 125-mile qualifying race and Friday's IROC
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say Earnhardt is the guy to beat,'' owner Larry McClure
said. ``He wins the 125, the Clash and IROC or whatever he gets
into, (but) then he stumbles in the 500. Last year was different.
He's a strong horse again.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Earnhardt also is the favorite of his owner,
Richard Childress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale is my favorite pick,'' Childress said. ``We've got one of
the very best race cars we've ever brought down here. We've got a
car we haven't had to touch or work with a lot. I feel like if we
can get a little bit of luck to go with it, we can win
back-to-back.''
</P>
<P>
   Added driver Sterling Marlin: ``The No. 3 car (Earnhardt's) is
the favorite. His stuff will fly. I'll be he's got 20 more
horsepower than the closest guy to him. His stuff runs good. His
car drives good and he has more power than anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte also says Earnhardt's black Monte Carlo is the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Earnhardt is the favorite for Sunday,'' Labonte said.
``He was the quickest that I practiced with out there by a long
shot. I think he's got the fastest car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``LET'S GET IT ON!''
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay Packers quarterback Brett Favre was the grand marshal
of Saturday's Busch race. Rather than using the traditional,
``Gentlemen, start your engines,'' he screamed, ``Gentlemen, let's
get it on!''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first race, and I'm already finding out how big
this whole NASCAR circuit is,'' Favre said. ``Growing up in
Mississippi, I always thought that football was No. 1, but when
people found out I was starting the Daytona 500, no one wanted to
talk about Super Bowls or how we were going to do next year. They
wanted to talk about how I could get them tickets to get in the
pits.''
</P>
<P>
   Favre, the honorary starter for today's race, will join driver
Dale Jarrett in owning a Busch Grand National team, to be driven in
selected races by Kenny Irwin.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the garage were Kansas City Chiefs linebacker Derrick
Thomas and NFL Hall of Famer Jim Brown, who will join Willie Lanier
and Bill Futterer in forming Celebrity Motorsports, a group that
plans to enter Winston Cup racing in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Cubs third baseman Gary Gaetti, who owns a Busch team
with major-league players Pete Schourek, Hal Morris and Andy Benes,
also was in attendance. Their car, driven by Bobby Hillin Jr.,
finished fifth.
</P>
<P>
   SUPERSTITIONS
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's lucky penny glued to the dashboard _ he got it from
a little girl in a wheelchair last year during a Make-A-Wish
Foundation benefit, and then went out and won his first Daytona 500
_ isn't the only superstition on race day.
</P>
<P>
   Childress won't carry any $50 bills in his wallet on race day,
and he doesn't eat peanuts on pit row. Larry McReynolds, crew chief
for Mike Skinner and the No. 31 car, once got a ``lucky'' acorn
from his daughter, which he kept in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept that acorn the rest of the year until it was pretty
much nothing but crumbs,'' McReynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   Car owner Robert Yates tries to find the same parking space at a
track if his car won there the year before, and he never backs his
car into a parking space.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said if you're backing in, all you're worried about is
leaving and I don't plan on leaving early,'' McReynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like driver Labonte, don't believe in superstitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought this new Brickyard 400 Monte Carlo pace car,''
Labonte said. ``I picked it up and got it back to the shock and
somebody asked me what number it was. I couldn't find the number,
but when I looked on the dash, it was No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left the next day to go to Richmond (Va.) and ended up
winning the race, so I knew then there wasn't anything to this
superstition stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   LUCKY FOURS
</P>
<P>
   McClure, owner of the No. 4 Chevrolet of Bobby Hamilton, likes
his luck going into today's race. Morgan-McClure has already had
three Daytona 500 wins _ Ernie Irvan (1991) and Marlin (`94 and
`95).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've won it with Irvan and it was the second race he'd won,''
McClure said. ``We won it with Sterling and it was the first race
he'd won. Now, we're going to win it with Bobby. He's won three
races, two (at) Rockingham and one (at) Phoenix. So he's going for
his fourth win in the No. 4 car and we're going for our fourth
Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
