<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-BUSCH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LaJoie stays ahead of calamity
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ It's one of them racing deals: Stay far
enough ahead of the field and you probably won't get caught up in a
calamitous wreck.
</P>
<P>
   That was Randy LaJoie's simple strategy Saturday to win the
demolition derby otherwise known as the 41st NAPA Auto Parts 300 at
Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   LaJoie won the Busch Grand National season opener under caution,
a fitting situation for an afternoon of spectacular wrecks. Four
separate accidents eliminated 11 cars. None was hairier than the
end-over-end crash on the last of 120 laps that destroyed rookie
Casey Atwood's car and finally settled the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood, running neck and neck with eventual second-place
finisher Jeff Green, got bumped from behind by Andy Hillenburg and
went skyward, landing on his roof, sliding down the track and onto
the grass and flipping four more times. He was only shaken up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said the 27 (Atwood) and the 32 (Green) were going to
gang up on me,'' LaJoie said. ``I was just going to make that thing
as wide as all these white walls. I was watching and they got side
by side and allowed me to get away. I ... come off (turn 4) and
seen Atwood get turned around. I was just looking at the starter to
see if I was catching the yellow and the white. I could have swore
I did, but Jeff Green was still coming so I kept getting after
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was one of the crazier races he'd experienced,
LaJoie said, ``It started yesterday afternoon at `happy hour' (when
eight cars damaged each other in last-practice wrecks.) It was not
a pretty sight. You know, these race cars don't cause the
accidents, the drivers hitting each other cause the accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   LaJoie, driving a Chevrolet, led four times for 61 laps,
including the last 19. But he may have won the race at the halfway
point, when Johnny Benson, in the No. 26 Chevrolet, brought out a
caution flag after hitting the wall. That turned out to be a
crucial yellow for LaJoie, who was about to fall a lap down because
of problems with his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the deal,'' LaJoie said. ``We had a left rear tire
come loose and I picked up a bad vibration. Mark (Reno, his crew
chief) said, `You've got to bring it in.' I thought I was going to
get wrecked on down the backstretch trying to get out of the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come in and said, `Aw, the spotter said they're coming out
of (turn) 3, the caution's coming out. I don't think the leaders
took the caution.' We had to get after it to beat the guys back to
the line. It was Johnny Benson that did bring out the caution. He
might have won us the race.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been easy for LaJoie, the Busch series champion in
1996 and 1997, to feel like the forgotten old man here. All the
interest seemed to be in the new crop of Busch drivers who just
happen to have relatives in the business. Adam Petty (Kyle's kid,
Richard's grandson) was the most notable of the rookies, finishing
sixth after challenging for the lead with five laps to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good, they're real good,'' LaJoie said. ``I'm sure I'm
going to be chasing them more than they're going to be chasing me.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
