<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNHARDT APPEARS TO HAVE THE HORSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Two-time Daytona 500 champion Sterling
Marlin knows what it takes to reach Victory Lane at the 2.5-mile
Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   And Marlin says defending race-winner Dale Earnhardt has the
43-car field covered in his bid to repeat in NASCAR's Winston Cup
season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stuff will fly,'' said Marlin, referring to Earnhardt's
No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Plus Chevrolet Monte Carlo. ``I'll bet
he's got 20 more horsepower than the closest guy to him. His stuff
runs good.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, a seven-time Winston Cup champion, will start fourth
in the 43-car field after winning a record 10th consecutive Twin
125-mile qualifying race on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt also got the nod from native Texan Terry Labonte,
whose 0-for-20 futility streak in the Daytona 500 now is one year
longer than Earnhardt's infamous drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earnhardt was the quickest that I practiced with out there by
a long shot,'' said Labonte, driver of the No. 5 Kellogg's Chevy.
``Nobody could even pull up on him good in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry McReynolds, Earnhardt's crew chief when he won last year's
Daytona 500, also placed ``The Intimidator'' at the top of his
list.
</P>
<P>
   ``That 3 car has stayed covered up this week more than it has
been uncovered \Rduring practice sessions\S. That's probably a bad
sign for the competition,'' McReynolds said. ``They're very
confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt ran only five laps during yesterday's final Happy Hour
practice with a top speed of 191.115 mph. He was 14th overall.
Labonte's speed of 192.217 mph was second-fastest to Chad Little's
192.353 in the No. 97 John Deere Ford Taurus.
GORDON HAS HOT WHEELS
</P>
<P>
   Three-time and reigning Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon will
pace the field from the pole position today. And Gordon, the 1997
Daytona 500 champion, says his race car is a rocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a fast race car,'' said Gordon, who qualified the
No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevy at 195.067 mph last
weekend. ``I think we've got the combination to win the Daytona 500
_ the best I've ever had _ and I think we've got an even stronger
team than we had last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon posted a top speed of 191.233 mph during the final
practice, placing him 10th overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys are getting beat up out there \Rby ill-handling
cars\S,'' Gordon said. ``My car is not beating me up. To me,
restrictor-plate racing is an equalizer, but I do feel like we've
got the best car we've ever had here for the Daytona 500.''
WHOM DO YOU TRUST?
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Marlin, who won this race in 1994 and 1995 in the No. 4
Kodak Chevrolet, will start 17th and immediately begin looking for
a drafting partner he can trust. Marlin has a ready-made pal in
Sabco Racing teammate Joe Nemechek. But Marlin plans to hook up
with a driver from the rival Ford Taurus camp as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to work with Mark Martin, if I can,'' said
Marlin, driver of the No. 40 Coors Light Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
``When he tells you something, he usually does it. The rest of them
ain't nothing but a bunch of thieves.''
</P>
<P>
   Two-time Daytona 500 winner Dale Jarrett and crew chief Todd
Parrott have decided not to cut any deals to get to the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not trying to be hard-nosed about this, but if we don't
make a deal with anybody, then nobody can say anything about us,''
said Jarrett, driver of the No. 88 Quality Care/Ford Credit Taurus.
``We'll work with whoever we can to get us to the front. Then it's
every man for himself.''
FAVRE JOINS JARRETT
</P>
<P>
   Brett Favre's new-found involvement in NASCAR will go beyond his
duties as honorary starter of today's Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Bay Packers quarterback became an equity partner in
Winston Cup star Dale Jarrett's Busch Grand National Series team
during the racing off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the partners announced that Jarrett-Favre Motorsports
and primary sponsor Rayovac Batteries plan to make their BGN debut
during the Coca-Cola 300 at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth on
March 27.
</P>
<P>
   The team will enter 14 of 32 events this season, with Jarrett
scheduled for three races and Robert Yates Racing teammate Kenny
Irwin Jr. booked for 11. They will campaign the No. 11 Rayovac Ford
Taurus, which will be powered by engines provided by Yates.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin, whose NASCAR stock rose after he won his first Craftsman
Truck Series race on TMS' 1.5-mile trioval in June 1997, is
scheduled to drive the car in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Favre, who also served as grand marshal for yesterday's BGN NAPA
Auto Parts 300 season-opener, is attending his first NASCAR races
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone I've talked to said if you go to one race, you're
hooked,'' Favre said. ``I'm going to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett has operated his BGN team since 1982. When he decided to
cut back on his schedule in the series, he approached his
stablemate about taking over the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something interesting to do,'' said Irwin, the 1998
Winston Cup Raybestos rookie of the year. ``It's going to be a lot
more on my schedule, but like Dale said, the more \Rtrack\S time
the better it's going to be. And hopefully, now I can get some
tickets to some Packers games.''
INJURY UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   Two drivers injured in wrecks during the Discount Auto Parts 200
Goody's Dash Series race underwent successful surgery at Halifax
Medical Center on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Weaver of Shelby, N.C., had a rod placed into his left leg
to repair a fractured tibia. Doctors also discovered a stable neck
fracture in Weaver's second vertebrae.
</P>
<P>
   George Crenshaw of Lakeland, Fla., had surgery to repair a
fracture of the right femur. Doctors placed titanium rods in the
injured area. He suffered no other injuries.
LAST WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've seen here the last couple of days is a lot of pretty
wild driving. And it's made me really think about the part of
getting through the race with the car in one piece.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff Burton, on preparing for today's NASCAR Winston Cup
Daytona 500
</P>
</TEXT>
