<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RDP-NYT &LR;      02-13 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIALOGUE: BEHIND CLOSED DOORS, SENATORS SPOKE PLAINLY AND
POINTEDLY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANCIS X. CLINES and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Deep within the Senate's secrecy, resounding beyond
the boilerplate of printed statements submitted for history, the
impeachment jurists of President Clinton had their say as well in
some plain-spoken language of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must remember that the fooling around was between
consenting adults, both of them sexually experienced,'' Ernest
Hollings, Democrat of South Carolina, noted in his avuncular drawl,
speaking for himself, not his speechwriter, in the closed-door
company of his Senate peers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the folksiest of lawmakers, Hollings relaxed and honored
the trial court by employing that simpler term _ ``fooling around''
_ never used in the impeachment articles nor in the luridly
detailed accusations of the criminal prosecutors who pursued the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Such human glimpses of the senators' hidden deliberations have
been hard to come by. But as the closed trial proceedings were
further documented on Saturday in The congressional Record, some
began appearing in public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are seeing right now why I had to make my money selling
frozen peas,'' Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., a food wholesaler,
confessed, playing the humble businessmen agog at all the
constitutional lawyering going on about him.
</P>
<P>
   As senator after senator arose and gravely tolled the morality
stakes of the issue, from self-government to their own proud
procreation, Frank Murkowski, Republican of Alaska, could not
resist some ribbing of his fellow jurists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Chief Justice, it seems to be a prerequisite to speak
today for senators to indicate the number of grandchildren each
has,'' he began. ``I am proud to say Nancy and I have 11, but I
won't indulge you with naming each of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., scored those members with
``soap opera'' proclivities who regularly ``ran pell-mell'' to the
waiting television cameras during trial recesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit right there in the back row 15 feet from the
cloakroom,'' he noted of his desk quite near the exit doors. ``But
at each recess, by the time I walk to the cloakroom and glance at
the TV, some of my colleagues have already sprinted somewhere else
to be in front of the cameras. As you know, I used to be on the
U.S. Olympic Team, and I tell my speedy friends _ you could have
made the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the needed resorts to humor, a sense of the struggle in
the verdict deliberations clearly comes through, even when speakers
rambled beyond the Constitution. They grieved in midtrial at the
death in an auto accident of the Senate's beloved legislative
clerk, Scott Bates.
</P>
<P>
   ``His absence should serve as a reminder that although we have
been totally engrossed in this issue for far too long, there is
life outside of these doors,'' declared Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash.
Ms. Murray told of sharing the sidelines with Scott when their
daughters played soccer games in nearby Virginia. ``There are
friends to be hugged, kids to be educated, parents to take care
of,'' Ms. Murray emphasized before the impeachment court.
</P>
<P>
   For all the learned citations of the founding fathers culled by
dedicated staffers for the prepared speeches, the emerging trial
record seems richer when senators just got up and ruminated a bit
about their own histories as courthouse practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I tried cases, I learned from a man named Sid Balick,''
said Joseph R. Biden Jr., Democrat of Delaware. ``He used to say at
the outset to the jury: `Keep your eye on the ball. The issue is
not whether my client is a man you would want your daughter to
date, a man you would invite home to dinner. The issue is, did my
client kill Cock Robbin? Period.'''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., could be counted on for a
sonorous recitation of anonymous verse from memory. ``Mr. Chief
Justice,'' he began:
</P>
<P>
   I think my country sinks
</P>
<P>
   beneath the yoke, It weeps, it bleeds,
</P>
<P>
   And each new day,
</P>
<P>
   a gash is added to her wounds.
</P>
<P>
   But Byrd's classicist's taste seemed no match in the record for
another well-read senator, Byron Dorgan, Democrat of North Dakota,
who touched closer to the carnival spirit of the yearlong ordeal.
``Mark Twain once said, with tongue in cheek, that `the next best
thing to a lie is a true story no one will believe,''' Dorgan
reminded the chamber. ``Well, this sorry chapter in our rich
history embraces both. Lies, yes! And truth that is almost
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Historians who must sift through the carefully reasoned
contentions in yards of prepared verdict decisions would do well
not to overlook the aside of wonderment when Sen. Ron Wyden,
D-Ore., oratorically pinched himself. ``I had a lot of far-fetched
dreams as a boy,'' he said. ``But never once did I dream that I
could serve with all of you on the floor of the U.S. Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   The pain of the task, not the honor, was underlined by Charles
Grassley, Republican of Iowa, when he recounted a sorry note he
received from a school principal about an assembly devoted to
American heroes. It included an ``Attitude Is Everything'' video,
and at the first sight of Clinton, Grassley said, ``the entire
student body _ ages 11 to 14 _ snickered.''
</P>
<P>
   While the trial was of the president, some of the senior
politicians could not resist including their track records in the
record. Jesse Helms noted, as he so often does, that he was ``the
first Republican directly elected to the U.S. Senate by the people
of North Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was hardly deferred to by Blanche Lincoln, Democrat
newcomer from Arkansas, who, in her first speech to the Senate,
introduced herself ``as the youngest female senator in the history
of our country, as a farmer's daughter raised on the salt of the
earth with basic Christian values, and as a young mother whose
first priority in life is my family and the well-being of the world
that they live in.''
</P>
<P>
   Another freshman, John Edwards, Democrat of North Carolina, rose
and confidently told Chief Justice William Rehnquist that he was
putting aside his prepared remarks to speak from the heart. In
first praising the judge, Edwards recalled the last time he had
seen Rehnquist.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were leading a sing-along at the Fourth Circuit Judicial
Conference,'' the senator ad-libbed. ``I thought it might be a good
idea for this group.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief justice, no slave to the official record himself, got
a laugh when he shot back: ``A healing device.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
