<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PROPOSES US MILITARY ROLE IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton, finally free from a yearlong partisan
domestic crisis, turned his attention Saturday to foreign policy
controversies that appear likely to spark renewed battles with the
Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced he will send up to 4,000 American troops to
the Serbian province of Kosovo if the warring parties there reach a
peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawmakers have argued they must approve the deployment of
US military units, which would become part of a 28,000-member NATO
peacekeeping force composed mostly of units from Britain, France,
Germany, and other European nations. The White House rejects that
congressional view out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he anticipated a confrontation over the issue on Capitol
Hill, the president prepared for a quick visit Sunday to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The trip seems certain to generate debate on that nation's war
on drugs, which many members of Congress condemn as inadequate and
which provokes an annual dispute between the White House and
Congress over whether Mexico should be financially penalized for
taking inadequate measures.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used his weekly radio address to give a brief history of
the fighting in Kosovo between Serb forces and ethnic Albanian
rebels seeking independence for the province. And he asserted that
only a US presence can assure the combatants that the terms of any
peace agreement will be carried out.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this volatile region, violence we fail to oppose leads to
even greater violence we will have to oppose later, at greater
cost,'' the president said. Saying that ``America has a national
interest'' in achieving a settlement, he added: ``If the conflict
persists, there likely will be a tremendous loss of life and a
massive refugee crisis in the middle of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations between Serb and Albanian delegations began in
France a week ago, after the United States and other Western
nations threatened NATO airstrikes if the two sides refused to
meet. The talks appeared to be stalled Saturday as the Serbian
government's representatives awaited instructions from Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic on how to reply to a plan drafted by
Washington for ending the bloody Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright arrived in Paris
Saturday to assess the progress of the talks and to try to nudge
them forward personally beginning Sunday. Given the past
intransigence of the Serbs, and of some Albanians' expressed intent
to accept nothing less than full independence, a resolution is far
from certain.
</P>
<P>
   But if an agreement is ultimately reached, a senior American
official told reporters in Washington Saturday, an initial group of
Marines could arrive in Kosovo just 10 days later.
</P>
<P>
   The official said US Army troops, either from bases in Europe or
the United States, would follow. The vanguard force would come from
the 24th Marine Expeditionary Unit, which is aboard Navy ships
already in the Mediterranean Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Sending American soldiers into a conflict as violent as the one
in Kosovo could lead to problems, particularly if US forces suffer
injuries or deaths. Even before a US soldier is deployed, however,
Republican lawmakers have served notice they will oppose US
involvement in the southern Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
   In a preview of the fights Clinton faces, GOP members of the
House International Relations Committee insisted last week that the
War Powers Act mandates congressional approval before any American
soldiers are sent into harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about the constitutional process and whether
it's a vital national interest to devote such a large portion of
our military capabilities to keeping the peace at two places in the
Balkans,'' said Representative Doug Bereuter, a Republican of
Nebraska, noting that Clinton has already deployed peacekeeping
troops to Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have conceded that an American deployment in
Kosovo will be far riskier than the one in Bosnia. About 60,000
NATO troops, including 20,000 Americans, went to Bosnia in December
1995 as part of the Dayton peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton was unable to fulfill his vow to bring home the
Americans within a year, the US presence has fallen to less than
7,000, NATO's overall strength has dropped to 30,000, and the force
has generally been viewed as effective.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Pickering, the undersecretary of state for political
affairs, responded at a committee hearing that there was ``ample''
precedent for an administration deploying troops without
permission. To which Tom Campell, a California Republican, shot
back: ``Previous constitutional violations do not justify a
subsequent one.''
</P>
<P>
   The annual debate over American certification of Mexico as a
partner in fighting drug trafficking has been equally acrimonious,
and this year's discussions could prove testy given the hard
feelings engendered on both sides by a year of impeachment
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The president is due to report by March 1 on whether 30 nations,
including Mexico, have made sufficient progress in trying to
eradicate the production and distribution of drugs. A lack of
certification can result in economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, this country's second-largest trading partner by some
measures, has never received a failing grade. But the debate each
year is highly charged. Congress can overturn the president's
decision with a majority vote.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton spent some of Saturday
reading materials in anticipation of his trip to Mexico. Even with
the controversy over drug certification looming, he presumably can
use the visit to show that he is relaxed in the wake of his
impeachment trial, and ready to continue working on the diverse
affairs of state.
</P>
<P>
   The most prominent in the foreign affairs arena, by far, is the
decision to send troops to Kosovo. If they are deployed, the
American official said Saturday, the peacekeepers would be headed
by a British general in charge of NATO's Allied Rapid Reaction
Force.
</P>
<P>
   The chain of authority runs through the alliance's command for
southern Europe, headed by a US Navy admiral, and finally to the
Supreme Allied Commander Europe, US Army General Wesley Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his radio address, cited historical precedent for US
intervention in Europe. ``World War II taught us that America could
never be secure if Europe's future was in doubt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he tried to blunt criticism that the United
States might not be able to resist inserting itself into every
trouble spot that appears around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``America cannot be everywhere or do everything overseas,''
Clinton said. ``But we must act where important interests are at
stake and we can make a difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
