<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4489 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      02-13 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RELIEVED CLINTON PREPARES FOR TRIP TO MEXICO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The story around some circles in Mexico City went
like this: When one high-level government official heard several
weeks ago that President Clinton was coming to Mexico, his first
reaction was, ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   His second was, ``Will he still be president?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the latter question is yes, of course, after the
US Senate voted Friday to acquit Clinton of impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   And that might help answer the Mexican official's first
question. A relieved but contrite Clinton will arrive in Merida
Sunday for a quick visit that will probably do more to help begin
rebuilding his tarnished presidential image than it will to break
any new diplomatic ground in relations with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, US and Mexican officials say the daylong visit between
Clinton and Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, the eighth between
them, will cover topics such as immigration, the North American
Free Trade Agreement, and the struggle to fight the flow of drugs
across the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a good personal relationship, and they know it's
important to keep fluid communication on bilateral issues,'' said
David Najera, a Zedillo spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But both sides also recognize the visual and symbolic value of
having the president and first lady basking in the Yucatan sun only
days after Clinton survived an embarrassing attempt to remove him
from office. In addition to a few meetings Monday, the president
and Hillary Rodham Clinton are expected to make a quick trip to
some of the area's popular Mayan ruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no huge issues looming on the immediate horizon,''
said John H. Coatsworth, director of the David Rockefeller Center
for Latin American Studies at Harvard University. ``This would be a
good time for them to shake hands, smile, visit ruins, and tell
their aides to keep working.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Zedillo last met in New York City in June, during a
special UN conference on drugs. But the two have spoken regularly
since then by phone, Najera said, to discuss the growing economic
worries in Latin America and how to better coordinate recovery
efforts in Central America after Hurricane Mitch plowed through the
region last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Because bureaucrats from Mexico City and Washington regularly
consult with one another on a variety of topics, government
agencies routinely handle questions of commerce, immigration, and
law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there are prickly issues between the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans grumble that Washington's certification process, in
which the president and Congress annually determine which countries
have cooperated in drug-eradication efforts, is unfair and
patronizing.
</P>
<P>
   The Zedillo administration has made great efforts over the last
month, in anticipation of Clinton's visit and perhaps of the
certification debate, to demonstrate its commitment. Those efforts
have included a recently unveiled $500 million program over the
next three years for new airplanes, radars, and other drug-fighting
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican law enforcement agencies have also seized more than 260
tons of marijuana over the last four weeks. Nevertheless, US
authorities continue to argue that Mexico has failed to adequately
stem the tide of drugs coming from South America or to stop the
growth of powerful new cartels that have sprouted along the
US-Mexico border and in the state of Quintana Roo.
</P>
<P>
   There are also some unresolved disputes between the countries
over aspects of the 5-year-old free-trade agreement that links the
United States, Mexico, and Canada. For months, Mexican officials
have objected to the American ban against allowing Mexican
transport trucks across the border.
</P>
<P>
   US officials have also expressed concern over Mexico's economy
in light of the Brazilian economic crisis and the falling price of
petroleum, which forced the Zedillo government this year to impose
one of the country's most austere budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides acknowledge that a worsening economic situation in
Mexico would probably lead to more immigrants who try to enter the
US illegally. That is also a worry for Mexican human rights
officials, who have recently accused US border authorities of
mistreating migrants.
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials and experts say, it's unlikely that any major
new pacts will be signed during the visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a working meeting for a relationship which has matured
over the years,'' said Najera. ``There may be some symbolic aspects
as well, but I think this is a meaningful visit for both
governments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
