r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     02-13 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LETTING THE QUALIFIED SPEAK OF JOCKS, JESUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Randall Cunningham, forever a wayward quarterback in the NFL,
was also a self-described wayward person until he found his answer
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Lord.
</P>
<P>
   During a sensational career revival in Minnesota, Cunningham
referred to himself as a quarterback on fire, but he didn't
necessarily mean a hot passing hand. Randall was talking about the
``Holy Spirit.'' And he spoke constantly and feverishly on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know,'' he said the week of the NFC championship game, ``the
media doesn't care to hear it. You are here for football. I see
what happens when I bring it up. You guys close your notebooks, or
you click off your mikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider me among those guilty as charged. Religion on the
sports page makes me squirm, probably because I'm not qualified to
deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   Jocks and Jesus, however, have become a mushrooming partnership
over the last few years. It involves all sports, but for no
particular reason I can think of, the biggest impact has been in
NFL locker rooms.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Eugene Robinson scandal broke in Miami some 24
hours before the Super Bowl kickoff, I openly sneered, and I wasn't
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Here was one of those high-profile, jocks for Jesus prophets
caught looking for love in all the wrong places. Busted by Miami
vice, Robinson became an immediate disgrace to his family, his
team, and himself. His career as an NFL safety was winding down
anyway, but this probably ended it, and should have.
</P>
<P>
   Fraud and hypocrite _ that was my brand on Robinson. But there
it is again _ the unqualified passing judgment.
</P>
<P>
   In these cases, including the mystery conversion of Deion a year
ago, my best solution is seek immediate advice from those who live
the life.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, let John Weber explain it.
</P>
<P>
   Weber is an Arlington resident, an ordained minister and the
unofficial chaplain for the both the Rangers and Cowboys. For
years, he has worked the locker room and the clubhouse, and as I've
said before, the respect he has with the jocks is obvious.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good man.
</P>
<P>
   Weber, by the way, also is aligned with the national religious
group, Athletes in Action, the same organization that had bestowed
its Bart Starr Award on Robinson some 10 hours before he was
arrested in Miami. The award is given for high moral character.
</P>
<P>
   The joke, as it turned out, was not just on Robinson and the
Atlanta Falcons, but it also involved Athletes in Action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure that my work, going into the locker rooms and
speaking to the guys, was not made easier by this tragic event,''
said Weber. ``This can be presented as an example of how sin is a
subtle enemy. But it's one of the worst kind of examples, because
of what this did to Eugene and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do live in a skeptical, cynical world today, and there's no
doubt that's where the backlash comes over this kind of incident.
It will feed the fire on the question about just how sincere any of
us are, including the athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   While Weber was not in Miami for the Bart Starr Award
presentation, he knows Robinson and has heard him speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, Eugene had made a great positive impact on many
people, including his teammates, who spoke so highly of him even
after the arrest. But I talk often of the ripple effect a high
profile athlete can have in society. The only problem, however, it
works both ways _ the ripple can be good and evil.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess would be this is not the first time this had happened
with Eugene. Doing that the night before a Super Bowl wouldn't
suggest it's a first-time decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``So with this tragic decision, comes the need for Eugene to pay
very close attention to his life, including professional help. I
would only hope and pray he can hold his life together.''
</P>
<P>
   Weber said one of his favorite quotes is ``a man by himself is
in bad company.''
</P>
<P>
   And there was Robinson, driving that rental car down Biscayne
Boulevard in Miami on a Saturday night. He was alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can find it in my heart to forgive Eugene, certainly,''
added Weber. ``And so will our group. It was an embarrassment for
Athletes in Action, but I feel most terrible for Eugene and his
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only person man does not generally question is himself. We
see our pursuits as noble. But for all the skepticism and cynicism
created by this act, each of us would be better served by taking a
closer look at ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   With John Weber, the notebook is never closed when religion
mixes with sports. /
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
