<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4493 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-DAYTONA-PREVIEW-T     02-13 1512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE ALL IN PURSUIT OF GORDON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH Fla. _ Jeff Gordon won't be happy with anything
less than a fourth Winston Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Moore would be happy just to find a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin wants the title that eluded him when he finished
second to Gordon in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Falk wants to finish in the top 25 in points.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett has won 14 races the last three seasons, and
finished in the top three in points each year.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Marcis has won five races in a career that began in 1968,
and hasn't finished in the top-20 in points since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, Martin and Jarrett drive for the elite teams on the
Winston Cup circuit. They have the combination of talent, resources
and experience to be contenders week in and week out.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, Falk and Marcis are among the also-rans, owners and
drivers that are short of money, technology or personnel.
</P>
<P>
   As the 1999 season begins today with the Daytona 500, only a
handful of teams appear to be legitimate contenders for the
championship. A few others are a threat to win on any given
weekend. The majority of the cars that make up the field are little
more than brightly colored, high-speed revolving billboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win a race, you've got to focus on a single event,'' said
Robin Pemberton, Rusty Wallace's crew chief. ``To be able to pull a
championship off, you've got to have the resources and the manpower
to continue the same assault week after week. A smaller team can
have one great effort, one great battle, but the teams with more
resources can go into battle every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon drives for one of those teams. So do Martin and Jarrett.
As the season progresses, those three drivers once again are
favored to battle for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton and Wallace also are considered contenders. If
everything falls into place, Bobby Labonte and Jeremey Mayfield
might have a shot. Perhaps Dale Earnhardt can recapture the old
magic.
</P>
<P>
   A few more drivers _ Mike Skinner, Ken Schrader, Terry Labonte _
have the ability to win a race.
</P>
<P>
   However, most of the 59 cars that attempted to qualify for the
Daytona 500 have absolutely no chance to run for a championship,
and very little chance of even winning one of the 34 points-paying
races. Last year 11 drivers combined to win the 33 races, and only
five won more than once.
</P>
<P>
   The Winston Cup circuit is a lot like major-league baseball.
There are a lot of talented players in the big leagues, but few
teams have the capability of getting to the playoffs and winning
the World Series. There are a lot of talented drivers piloting
stock cars, but few teams have what it takes to compete for the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of those drivers that are in those cars, even though
they are good race car drivers they may not have the total package
to win,'' Jarrett said.
`A BIG SPORT'
</P>
<P>
   The teams that have the total package are the equivalent of
baseball's big-market clubs, the ones with the revenues to afford
the best players. The rest are the equivalent of the small-market
teams with the tiny payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, Martin and Jarrett drive for big-market owners Rick
Hendrick, Jack Roush and Robert Yates. Burton also works for Roush.
Wallace and Mayfield drive for the joint effort owned by Roger
Penske and Michael Kranefuss. Labonte drives for Joe Gibbs, and
Earnhardt for Richard Childress.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the owners and teams that have the resources to hire
the best crew chiefs, engineers and technicians. They can afford
the state-of-the-art technology, and employ the people who know how
to use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big sport now,'' Moore said. ``If you don't have the
money to hire the high-tech people, the engineers and stuff, to go
along with a good race team you're going to be in trouble. It takes
a lot of money to go racing in Winston Cup. It takes cubic dollars
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, the 73-year-old car owner who is one of the pioneer's of
the sport, lacks a major sponsor and doesn't have the money. While
the large, multicar teams on the circuit have over 200 employees,
Moore has five.
</P>
<P>
   Not even his legendary ability to make cars go fast can make up
for that deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what to do, but it takes money,'' said Moore, who
failed to get his car into the Daytona field.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Yates Racing has money. Jarrett's team made good use of
it in the sport's off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent a lot of hours in the wind tunnel,'' Jarrett said.
``We cut the body off the car after being in the wind tunnel and
built it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The wind tunnel gives teams invaluable data about the car's
aerodynamics, data they can use to shave difference-making tenths
of seconds off lap times. The wind tunnel is something Joe Falk can
only dream about.
</P>
<P>
   Falk owns the No. 91 Chevrolet driven by Steve Grissom. He also
lacks a primary sponsor so he puts Little Joe's, his own auto
dealership, on the side of the car.
</P>
<P>
   The dealership is lucrative, but doesn't make enough money to
allow Falk to compete with the big boys. He said he spent $3.5
million last year in a sport where it takes about $5 million to
field a team good enough just to finish in the top 25 or so in
points. The top team's budgets approach $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   So for Falk, the wind tunnel is a mere pipe dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Penske group, I think they've got 60 or 70 hours of wind
tunnel time,'' he said. ``Well, that's $2,000 an hour for that.
They've got the resources to make a big effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were here testing, and the 25 car, Wally Dallenbach \Rowned
by Hendrick\S, he had three crew chiefs working on that car. That's
three guys who are making big bucks working on that one car. That's
what you're having to compete with.''
</P>
<P>
   Under-funded owners like Falk can't afford the full-time
engineers and specialists that the top teams have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may build five sets of shocks a day, go out and practice,
come back in and take them apart, rebuild them and have them ready
for the next day,'' said Jeff Hammond, crew chief for the
Roush-owned car driven by Chad Little. ``What it costs is the man
who has to take it apart and put it back together. The man who's
really good at that is a specialist, so you wind up paying a
specialist to rebuild, rebuild, rebuild.''
RACING FOR DOLLARS
</P>
<P>
   One factor that separates the haves from the have-nots is the
difference in sponsorship dollars. The range between the top end
and bottom end is as much as $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   But while being on the high end obviously helps, it isn't the
only indicator of success. Money can purchase a lot of things, but
it cannot buy an instant championship.
</P>
<P>
   Texas millionaire Tim Beverly has money, and not just from his
Tyler Jet business. Beverly, who became a Winston Cup owner when he
purchased Darrell Waltrip's team last March, has a major sponsor in
Lucky Dog 10-10-345 for the car driven by Rich Bickle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to go big-time auto racing,'' Beverly said.
``We're not here just to ride around. We're not here to see if we
can finish in the top 20. You can get to that echelon, the top 10
in points, the top five in points.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Beverly realizes a top-20 finish in the team's first
full season would be a good result. The team can afford the best
equipment, but it takes time to build a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next two years, three years, we want to be in that
situation to where we're competing for that championship,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It should take at least that long to attract another necessary
ingredient for a championship run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having the right personnel is the most important thing,''
Burton said. ``There's not enough quality personnel to go around
for all 50 teams. It turns into a recruiting war, we will offer you
this much money and you're going to get this and that.''
</P>
<P>
   The right personnel includes a talented crew chief. Ray
Evernham, Todd Parrott and Jimmy Fennig, who run the teams for
Gordon, Jarrett and Martin, respectively, are among the best in the
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams have as much money as anybody else, but they
don't have that guy in charge who knows exactly what to do with the
money and how to get the right people in there,'' Jarrett said.
``Todd Parrott is definitely the backbone of this race team. He's
the one who came in and made all of this work.''
</P>
<P>
   A talented driver also is required, but in an era where
technology is so important, even the best driver can't make a slow
car go any faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drivers definitely make a difference, but you can't do it on
your own,'' Pemberton said. ``You have to have a good crew and
everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the ``everything else'' is people who want to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go down here and do a dollar by dollar breakdown of all
the teams, you'll find out there's enough dollars there to get the
job done,'' Hammond said. ``But the intangible is they just don't
have the will to do it. You've got to have the want to.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have the will, it doesn't matter how much other
stuff you've got.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
