<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-WINSTON-CUP-CAPSULES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINSTON CUP PROJECTED TOP 10
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1999 WINSTON CUP PROJECTED TOP 10 No. 1 Driver: Jeff Gordon Age:
27 Team: Hendrick Motorsports Car/sponsor: No. 24 DuPont Automotive
Finishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo Career highlights: Has won three of
the last four Winston Cup championships, including two in a row;
NASCAR's youngest three-time champion. 1998 finish: First, thanks
to a single-season record-tying 13 victories 1999 projected finish:
Still the one Scouting report: Gordon, crew chief Ray Evernham and
the Rainbow Warriors may not win another 13 races this season but
there is nothing to suggest this team is going to lose focus.
Gordon's seven poles and 13 victories were obvious keys to the
domination he exhibited during 1998. What's not so obvious? Gordon
finished in the top 10 _ and on the lead lap _ in the final 20
races of 1998. And Gordon will start today's season-opening Daytona
500 on the pole.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 Driver: Dale Jarrett Age: 42 Team: Robert Yates Racing
Car/sponsor: No. 88 Quality Care/Ford Credit Ford Taurus Career
highlights: Two-time winner of the Daytona 500 (1993 and 1996);
finished third or better in points for third consecutive year in
1998 1998 finish: Third, 345 points behind Mark Martin 1999
projected finish: Up to second Scouting report: Only Jarrett knows
how much his performance suffered last year while he battled a gall
bladder condition. Jarrett freely admits his team went into the
1998 season not knowing what to expect from the new Taurus. This
year, crew chief Todd Parrott has an inventory of cars at his
disposal. So like D.J.'s health, machinery is not an issue. Jarrett
said he and Parrott must either show up with the ``best car'' more
often or figure out how to adjust the car and/or make a late-race
strategy move to win more than the three races they bagged in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   No. 3 Driver: Mark Martin Age: 40 Team: Roush Racing
Car/sponsor: No. 6 Valvoline/Cummins Ford Taurus Career highlights:
Three-time Winston Cup points runnerup, including last year by 364
points to Jeff Gordon; won record fourth IROC championship 1998
finish: Second, despite career highs in wins (seven), top-fives
(22), top-10s (26) and winnings ($4.3 million). 1999 projected
finish: Down to third Scouting report: Nobody on the planet races
harder than Martin. But even with career numbers, he could not
catch the 24 car. Specifically, Martin scored 321 fewer points than
Gordon in the four carburetor restrictor plate races, accounting
for all but 43 points of his overall deficit. Martin's victory in
the Bud Shootout last Sunday definitely showed Roush has closed the
plate engine gap over the winter.
</P>
<P>
   No. 4 Driver: Rusty Wallace Age: 42 Team: Penske/Kranefuss
Racing Car/sponsor: No. 2 Miller Lite Ford Taurus Career
highlights: Winston Cup champion in 1989; has won a race for 13
consecutive years 1998 finish: Fifth, his best effort since placing
third in 1994 1999 projected finish: Up to fourth Scouting report:
Wallace's trademark enthusiasm took on real substance during the
off-season, when he posted the fastest overall speed (193.129 mph)
in winter testing. Wallace also cut his DNFs _ Did Not Finish
results _ from 11 in 1997 to two last year. Wallace started out hot
last year, leading the points chase for eight consecutive weeks. A
second season of working with teammate Jeremy Mayfield should
improve the performances of both in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   No. 5 Driver: Jeff Burton Age: 31 Team: Roush Racing
Car/sponsor: No. 99 Exide Batteries Ford Taurus Career highlights:
Won first three races of his career, including inaugural 500-mile
event at Texas Motor Speedway, in 1997 en route to fourth-place
points finish 1998 finish: Fifth, based on career-highs in
top-fives (18) and top-10s (23). 1999 projected finish: Idling in
fifth Scouting report: Mark Martin's stablemate and Jack Roush's
rising star was done-in by five finishes of 36th or worse last
season. Burton also must improve on his qualifying efforts if he
wants to be a bonafide frontrunner. He has not won a Cup pole since
since Aug. 16, 1996 at Michigan Speedway _ 75 races ago.
</P>
<P>
   No. 6 Driver: Bobby Labonte Age: 34 Team: Joe Gibbs Racing
Car/sponsor: No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac Grand Prix Career
highlights: Has won at least one race in each of his four seasons
with Gibbs' team; posted single-season high in winnings with $2.9
million last year 1998 finish: Career-best sixth, topped by three
poles and 18 top-10s 1999 projected finish: Stuck in sixth Scouting
report: Either with or without the carburetor restrictor plate,
Labonte has established himself as Pontiac's top driver and a
superspeedway superstar. Gibbs' plate engines are plenty powerful,
as Labonte proved while winning his Twin 125-mile qualifying race
on Thursday. Gibbs wants this team to move up three spots in the
standings this year, wishful thinking unless Labonte can cut his
six DNFs to one or two. Who knows, rookie teammate Tony Stewart may
even help as a drafting partner on the superspeedways.
</P>
<P>
   No. 7 Driver: Dale Earnhardt Age: 47 Team: Richard Childress
Racing Car/sponsor: No. 3 GM Goodwrench Service Plus Chevrolet
Monte Carlo Career highlights: NASCAR's second seven-time Winston
Cup champion; career earnings of $33,377,129 at the end of 1998
leads all forms of motorsports 1998 finish: Eighth, the sixth
consecutive year he's been among the top-10 and 18th overall 1999
projected finish: A wise-cracking seventh Scouting report:
Earnhardt has not won a Cup championship since 1994, but he always
looks like his old intimidating self at Daytona in February. This
time he's back as defending Daytona 500 champion for the first
time, and his record 10th consecutive Twin 125-mile qualifying race
victory Thursday marks him as a contender today. Earnhardt and
Childress insist they have retooled and reinvigorated their
programs and themselves over the winter _ in search of that elusive
eighth championship. Earnhardt's legions of fans want to believe.
</P>
<P>
   No. 8 Driver: Jeremy Mayfield Age: 29 Team: Penske/Kranefuss
Racing Car/sponsor: No. 12 Mobil 1 Ford Taurus Career highlight(s):
Scored first career victory at Pocono Raceway last June; led points
four times during the first 16 races of 1998. 1998 finish:
Career-best seventh 1999 projected finish: One step back to eighth
Scouting report: Mayfield reaped the benefits of his first year as
teammate to Rusty Wallace in 1998. Mayfield definitely was the hot
driver of the season's first half, when he was being touted as
someone who could challenge Jeff Gordon for the championship. But
after his victory at Pocono, Mayfield finished outside the top 15
in 11 of the final 18 races. Mayfield insists that Wallace is a
championship contender _ and so is he. Together, they could make
race day miserable for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   No. 9 Driver: Terry Labonte Age: 42 Team: Hendrick Motorsports
Car/sponsor: No. 5 Kellogg's Chevrolet Monte Carlo Career
highlights: Two-time Cup champion (1984 and 1996); NASCAR's Iron
Man will make his record 603rd consecutive start in the Daytona 500
1998 finish: Ninth, 27 points out of eighth 1999 projected finish:
Ninth again Scouting report: Labonte's consistency may not fire up
a lot of fans, but it has allowed him to finish in the top-10 for
five consecutive seasons. Labonte was ranked second in points after
10 races, but his top-fives (five) and top-10s (15) were his fewest
since 1993. The return of team owner Rick Hendrick should provide a
morale boost for Labonte and crew chief Andy Graves, who have spent
the last two years in the shadows cast by teammates Jeff Gordon and
Ray Evernham.
</P>
<P>
   No. 10 Driver: Mike Skinner Age: 41 Team: Richard Childress
Racing Car/sponsor: No. 31 Lowe's Chevrolet Monte Carlo Career
highlights: Won 1997 Daytona 500 pole in his 16th Cup start en
route to rookie of the year title; won third annual NASCAR
demonstration race in Japan 1998 finish: 21st, up nine spots from
1997 1999 projected finish: A breakthrough 10th Scouting report:
Skinner and veteran crew chief Larry McReynolds apparently have
found that elusive chemistry that McReynolds and Dale Earnhardt
never could locate. Skinner improved 15 points positions, to 21st,
over the season's final 20 races under McReynolds' guidance.
Skinner's eight top-10s and three top-fives all came after Larry
Mac replaced Kevin Hamlin. Skinner, the first NASCAR Craftsman
Truck Series champion in 1995, has only 76 Cup starts on his
resume. In McReynolds, he has the perfect mentor. McReynolds says
there is no reason this team can't finish among the top four in
points _ and win two or three races. Why not start with a huge
upset in the Daytona 500?
</P>
<P>
   Capsules by John Sturb, Star-Telegram Staff Writer
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
