<HEADER>
A4498 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-GORDON-HENDRICK-T     02-13 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GORDON-HENDRICK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENDRICK'S RETURN TO NASCAR DRIVES GORDON'S DESIRE TO EXCEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Jeff Gordon always had the motivation to
drive a race car. Through 42 victories and three NASCAR Winston Cup
championships, Gordon's almost hypnotic need to exceed largely has
been self-induced.
</P>
<P>
   His rivals and peers in the garage area have noticed. As the
start of the 1999 season awaits at Daytona International Speedway
today, few believe Gordon and that three-car crowd at Hendrick
Motorsports are about to self-destruct.
</P>
<P>
   Not with Gordon, NASCAR's youngest three-time champion, barely
entering his prime at 27.
</P>
<P>
   Not with workaholic crew chief Ray Evernham calling the shots.
</P>
<P>
   And not with the return of team founder Rick Hendrick.
</P>
<P>
   Battling bone-marrow cancer for the past two years, and after
serving a year of house arrest for a messy mail fraud charge,
Hendrick has returned to NASCAR's extended family.
</P>
<P>
   An emotional Gordon has noticed, as he prepares to drive in the
Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal of this whole organization is to take Rick to Victory
Lane,'' said Gordon, who will start the 200-lap race around the
high-banked, 2.5-mile trioval from the pole. ``We felt like we took
him to Victory Lane several times over the last few years. But he
wasn't there in the flesh. That's what's going to be very exciting
for us.''
MISSING HENDRICK
</P>
<P>
   Hendrick celebrated Gordon's first championship in 1995 and
native Texan Terry Labonte's heroic drive to the title despite a
broken finger in 1996. But Hendrick was diagnosed with bone marrow
cancer in February 1997 and missed the team's dramatic 1-2-3 sweep
of the Daytona 500 with Gordon, Labonte and then-teammate Ricky
Craven.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Hendrick also was up to his lawyers in a scandal
involving preferential treatment to American Honda executives from
his Charlotte-based Hendrick Automotive Group. He pled guilty to
one count of mail fraud, and in light of his deteriorating physical
condition, was placed on home detention for one year.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrick was barred from contact with his racing team in 1997
and 1998, years that ended with Gordon winning 10 and a
record-tying 13 races, respectively, and consecutive Winston Cup
points championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all feel like we missed Rick being here a lot,'' said
Gordon, who broke down into tears several times on the awards stage
at the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel in New York City while attempting to
talk about Hendrick in December 1997. ``We all feel pretty
fortunate to get through the things we got through the last few
years without him here. At the same time, it wasn't the same with
him gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say we're going to have a year like we had
last year. But I hope we can keep up some level of the competition
we've had over the last three or four years. Just for him, so we
can see the excitement on his face when he's standing in Victory
Lane. Just so he can be part of a championship battle. Just so he
can experience the things that he wasn't able to experience while
he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's at the Daytona 500 with one of his three teams. I
certainly feel like we've got a good shot at it.''
CRUISE CONTROL
</P>
<P>
   Despite Hendrick's legal and health setbacks, Hendrick
Motorsports enters this season having won a record four consecutive
driver's championships and 47 of 127 races since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been quite a cruise for this group,'' said Hendrick, who
turned over day-to-day operation of his race teams to brother John
Hendrick in 1998. John Hendrick carries the title of team president
this year. Rick Hendrick remains the team's chief executive
officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got, in my opinion, the best in the business right
here,'' said Rick, who is continuing chemotherapy. ``I've got some
wicked medicine that I think is doing a wicked job on the disease.
In a 500-mile race, I'm on lap about 400. ... Some days you're
lucky to get up. The goals keep changing. But if I stay with it,
there's a possibility and a probability maybe I could be cured.''
</P>
<P>
   Hendrick, 49, paused and added, ``I plan on having a lot of fun
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon could assure that with a season anywhere close to
approaching his 1998 numbers. His 13 victories tied Richard Petty's
record for most in NASCAR's modern era, which dates from 1972. En
route to his third title in four years, Gordon captured an
unprecedented fourth consecutive Pepsi Southern 500, became the
first two-time winner of the Brickyard 400 at Indianapolis, swept
the road-course events at Sonoma, Calif., and Watkins Glen, N.Y.,
claimed two $1 million bonuses in Winston's No Bull 5 program and a
record $9.3 million in winnings.
</P>
<P>
   He led the series with seven poles, 26 top-five and 28 top-10
finishes in 33 starts. After winning just three of the season's
first 15 events, he closed by capturing 10 of the final 18 and
three of the last four.
</P>
<P>
   In 189 career Cup starts, Gordon has earned $26,009,046, which
is fourth on the all-time list.
DRIVER OF THE YEAR
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, driver of the No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes
Chevrolet Monte Carlo, was the runaway choice for Driver of the
Year. He joined NASCAR's Darrell Waltrip and retired Indy-car and
Formula One hero Mario Andretti as three-time winners of that
honor.
</P>
<P>
   By season's end, Gordon and his Rainbow Warriors crew were being
named in the same sentence with record-setting home run slugger
Mark McGwire, the NBA's Chicago Bulls and World Series champion New
York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we accomplished last year was unbelieveable. I look back
at it and I shake my head,'' said Gordon, who is 13th on NASCAR's
all-time victory list. ``I'm probably one of the few people when
1998 came to the New Year's countdown _ that 10, nine, eight _ I
wasn't liking that. I wanted it to keep going. I wanted to live '98
for the rest of my life.
</P>
<P>
   ``But once '98 was over, we had new goals for 1999. Every year,
Ray and I look at what we've accomplished the year before and
during that year and we're trying to get better and better. We hope
we're going to raise the bar this year, but I don't know if that
means we're going to win 10 or 13 races. We've got the same team,
same morale and I think the same attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Evernham, who also will oversee Gordon's five-race Busch Grand
National Series schedule, said the gains his team can make each
year inside the NASCAR Winston Cup rulebook are getting smaller and
smaller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, everybody else is going to step it up, too,''
Evernham said. ``The bottom line is when that first wheel rolls,
nobody cares anymore. They don't care if you won 13, 14 or none.
It's Square One. You've got to work a little bit harder on top. But
on the other hand, we're not racing somebody else. We're racing
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   See Jeff run ``A comparison of the numbers rung up by Jeff
Gordon en route to his three NASCAR Winston Cup championships at
Hendrick Motorsports:'' Year Races Points lead Poles Wins Top fives
Top 10s DNFs 1995 31 34 8 7 17 23 3 1997 32 14 1 10 22 23 2 1998 33
364 7 13 26 28 2 Source: NASCAR Winston Cup Series 1999 updates
</P>
</TEXT>
