<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-OATES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OATES CAN SEE OWNER IS SERIOUS ABOUT SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers owner Tom Hicks drew a line in the
sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take a step backward,'' he said. ``I'm
realistic enough to know that only one team wins, but I want to
make sure that we continue to climb the ladder and ultimately win
the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   The economics of major-league baseball today demand his
position.
</P>
<P>
   The defending American League West champion's 1999 payroll
likely will exceed $80 million, and its owner projects the
franchise ``losing $5 (million) or $10 million'' despite an
increase in ticket prices for the third consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know I support them and give them the resources to do
their job,'' Hicks said of his management team. ``I expect
reasonable performance in return. People will be held accountable
as they should be and as they are in the real world every day.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves manager Johnny Oates the person most accountable for
the Rangers' on-field performance and Hicks' produce-or-perish
declaration.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as pressure goes, that's part of this job,'' said
Oates, who has led the team to division titles in two of the past
three years, the only championships in team history. ``We live in a
performance-oriented society. Nothing speaks greater volumes along
those lines than professional athletics. If you don't perform, it's
a tough profession.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' journey begins Thursday when pitchers and catchers
report to the organization's Port Charlotte, Fla., camp. The first
workout is scheduled Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Peppy optimism regarding a third division title in four seasons
permeates the organization. Hicks, who also owns the National
Hockey League's Stars, drew a comparison between his two
franchises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the Stars. We had a great team three years ago and got
upset in the first round,'' he said. ``We went deep in the playoffs
last year. Our fans probably will be disappointed this year if we
don't make it to the \RStanley\S Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty tough duty, but I think Rangers fans should be
disappointed _ as their owner would be _ if we don't repeat as AL
West champs, even though we've got a tough race ahead with the
Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks demonstrated his desire to win an AL West title during the
1998 season. The owner supported an additional $2.6 million in
players' salaries for the season's final two months with general
manager Doug Melvin's additions of right-hander Todd Stottlemyre,
shortstop Royce Clayton and third baseman Todd Zeile through two
July 31 trades.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers survived August and utilized five consecutive
September victories against the Angels to ensure their AL West
championship, but Hicks remained noncommittal regarding Oates'
future and offered hints of reservations during that period.
</P>
<P>
   Oates and members of his staff were antsy enough to inquire
about other employment possibilities during the season's final
week. Hicks waited until the morning after the Rangers clinched the
division title _ with two games remaining _ to extend his manager
an invitation to return for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was important for this franchise that we achieve
what we felt was a reasonable goal of winning the AL West once we
made those deals at the trade deadline,'' Hicks said then. ``It
doesn't mean they wouldn't have been back if they hadn't won it,
but I would have wanted some answers as to why.''
</P>
<P>
   The defending World Series champion New York Yankees will enter
this season as the prohibitive favorite to again represent the
American League in the World Series, but that did not prevent Hicks
from supporting the Rangers' escalating payroll this winter. The
Commissioner's Office computed the Rangers' final 1998 payroll as
the seventh-highest in baseball at $67,956,293. The final 1999
payroll likely will exceed $80 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to take this team to the next level,'' Hicks
said. ``The fact that we've won the AL West two of the past three
years is a huge change for this franchise. I want to keep that
momentum. We've got a solid foundation and the nucleus to have a
championship ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the decision to lose money this season to keep our
team intact so we'll stay at a championship-caliber level while we
wait for the younger players to develop that will bring our payroll
more in line with where it needs to be. We'll end up losing $5 or
$10 million, but that's OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I view that as an investment to keep the team at that
championship level. We've been around 3 million in attendance. I'd
love to see the attendance grow to 3.2 or 3.4 million. I think if
we give the fans the right product, there's a good chance that will
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   A time also will come when division titles no longer satisfy the
Rangers' owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, certainly not from my perspective as the owner,'' Hicks
said. ``I do want to win a World Series. I want to win the Stanley
Cup in hockey. There's a progression you make. You usually don't go
win it all the first year, but you climb the ladder a little bit
more each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, you eventually have a chance to win it all. There
are 29 disappointed owners and their fans who don't make it. I
think we've got a reasonable shot of getting there someday, and I'm
talking about within the next five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates echoed that view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want us to be satisfied or happy with division
championships,'' the manager said. ``I don't want our players
thinking that way. I don't want our fans thinking that way. I don't
want the media thinking that way. The goal in this business is not
to win the division, even though it took us a long time to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal now is whatever it takes to find a way to get to the
next level. We want that expectation of us. We don't want to be
satisfied with just being a division winner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
