<SLUG> BC-XXX-SLUG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS ROAD RACER BALANCES MOTHERHOOD WITH TRAINING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES CLINES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jody Hawkins loves to run. She has been doing it for more than
half her life, and she has run with and against the best in the
world. And she doesn't want to stop.
</P>
<P>
   She does slow down, though, for children.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three years, Hawkins, 32, gave birth to two sons. It
has made reaching the world-ranked status she enjoyed in 1993 and
'94 harder, but she doesn't mind. Hawkins wants to be a top woman
runner, but her top priority is being the best mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my tradeoff,'' said the Blooming Grove resident who fits
training around husband Mark and sons Skyler, 18 months, and
Hunter, 3 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can train full time and be the best there is, or you can
be the mother of two. I have two wonderful sons, and that's my
tradeoff. I'm not saying you can't be the best and be a mother, but
it's not easy,'' she said while preparing for the Cowtown 10K on
Feb. 27 in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Making her way back is Hawkins' agenda.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, she enjoyed her first injury-free year in almost eight
years and won the Avon National 10K championship. The 10-kilometer
title followed a 28th-place showing in the 1998 Half Marathon World
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Those showings were her best since she was ranked sixth in the
world on the roads by ``Runner's World'' magazine. This month, she
has continued to build on recent successes.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins placed eighth in the Women's National Championship Eight
Kilometer Road Race on Feb. 6 and won the 3M Half Marathon in
Austin the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The back-to-back races were part of her plan to qualify for the
2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   She has pegged Grandma's Marathon in June in Duluth, Minn., as
her first effort to qualify for the Olympic Trials at 26.2 miles.
</P>
<P>
   All this competition is a prelude to Hawkins' goal of qualifying
for the trials in the 10K and marathon. She's a strong bet for the
10K, but the marathon is an unknown.
</P>
<P>
   She said she's comfortable in longer runs, and it showed in
Austin with her half-marathon time of 1 hour, 14 minutes, 11
seconds after a disappointing 8K effort.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins has run many Fort Worth-Dallas area road races recently,
regaining a taste of what it's like to be back in the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Yet seeing his wife place among local runners was a new
experience for Mark. ``I was so used to seeing her winning or being
in the top finishers that it was a shock to see her finishing third
or even seventh against local athletes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But those races helped Hawkins' 5-kilometer times drop from the
18-minute range to the 16-minute range.
</P>
<P>
   ``After having babies, you just can't take for granted that the
16s are going to come like they used to,'' said Mark, a former NAIA
All-American at Wayland Baptist and an Olympic qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkinses moved to Blooming Grove, which is about 35 miles
south of Dallas, in 1995 to be near Jody's mother. ``This is a
great opportunity for us,'' Mark said. ``We wanted to get away from
the city, and we both like running on dirt roads to rehab our
bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Blooming Grove is where Jody Hawkins grew up, and much of her
family is there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lucky that my mom lives across the street and she can
watch the kids when I go running,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The comeback, then, is almost complete, said Mark: ``We're now
looking to be ranked again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
