<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-DALEEARNHARDT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNHARDT ENJOYING THE RIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The questions were different now. Winning
the Daytona 500 changes everything. Just ask Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat, microphone in hand, in a swivel chair perched atop a
platform in the press box at Daytona International Speedway
following his record 10th consecutive victory in Thursday's
Gatorade Twin 125s, Earnhardt knew he would no longer have to face
questions about his agonizing 0-for-19 streak in the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   As he swiveled right, left, then 180 degrees to take in the
panoramic view of the 2.5-mile high-banked trioval while waving to
fans below in the grandstands, Earnhardt seemed delighted to talk
about his long-overdue triumph last Feb. 15 in the crown jewel of
the NASCAR Winston Cup Series.
</P>
<P>
   No longer haunted by demons past, he seemed serenely confident
about winning his second Daytona 500 in his gleaming black No. 3
Goodwrench Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh definitely,'' said Earnhardt's wife, Teresa. ``You could
feel it the moment we got here. He's just having so much more fun
now. He's really enjoying himself here.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his well-documented disappointments at Daytona,
Earnhardt says he loves this place. Always has, always will. It is,
after all, where he has recorded more victories (33) than he has at
any other Winston Cup venue.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona had always seemed to be Earnhardt's domain, save for
Sundays. He has won 12 Gatorade Twin 125s; 7 Busch Grand National
300s; 6 Bud Shootouts; 5 International Race of Champions events; 2
Pepsi 400s; and, most precious of all, that one very elusive
Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love racing here,'' said Earnhardt, whose victory last
year snapped an overall winless streak of 59 races. ``It's always
been neat for me to race at speeds like we race here at Daytona.
Before restrictor plates, it was really fun, and it's still fun
with the restrictor plates, but you've got to really have a great
race car and a good-handling car, and I've been fortunate to be
with a team that's accomplished that every year.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, for all that hard work, Lady Luck had always frowned
upon Earnhardt and his Richard Childress Racing team on the day of
the big race. That was, of course, before Childress said he was
struck by a good omen while watching the 1998 Super Bowl. When he
saw Denver quarterback John Elway exorcise his demons by guiding
the Broncos to their first Super Bowl title, Childress was
ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw Elway win the Super Bowl,'' Childress said, ``I
called Dale and told him that it was an omen. He was due to win
his, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Other indicators were not as positive. It was a season in which
Earnhardt recorded only five Top 5 finishes, plus three DNFs, and
wound up a distant eighth in the points race _ his worst effort
this decade _ behind repeat series champion Jeff Gordon,
Earnhardt's nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make you proud to have a season like we did,''
Earnhardt said. ``You're not totally out of it because you finished
in the Top 10 in points, but still, it's a situation where you
can't win the championship if you're not competitive, if you don't
finish in the Top 5, if you don't race for the wins. That's where
our team is working hard to get back to.''
</P>
<P>
   To make matters more difficult, Earnhardt's team underwent a
midseason shakeup when Childress switched crew chiefs of his
two-car outfit, pairing Earnhardt with Kevin Hamlin and Larry
McReynolds, the veteran who was Earnhardt's crew chief at Daytona,
with driver Mike Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Earnhardt's victory with Hamlin Thursday was
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like for it to have been about the 10th victory with
him,'' Earnhardt said. ``We've got to get our program together, and
I think Kevin and myself have gotten better and better as we've
gone along. I feel good working with Kevin, and Kevin and I were
confident all week.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that when Earnhardt pulled into the pits after
turning several crisp practice laps, he asked Hamlin if he wanted
him to continue practicing.
</P>
<P>
   Hamlin shrugged and said, ``Do you?''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt shrugged back. ``What do we need to make changes
for?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Hamlin replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't either,'' Earnhardt said. ``So let's leave it alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Earnhardt later, ``I feel good about what we're seeing. I
was really proud for him to win his first race with me. That makes
me proud. We've won a lot of races with different people, but it
makes a lot of difference, the crew chief does, with how hard they
work and what they put into it and how prepared you are.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it helps to have a little luck on your side, too.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt was made acutely aware of that the day before last
year's race as he smoldered in his garage over an engine problem
that necessitated a complete overhaul. So he was not in the best
mood to meet with some young fans as part of a Make-A-Wish
Foundation event.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's disposition went from sour to sunny when Wessa
Miller, a 6-year-old cancer patient from Kentucky, approached him
and presented him with a penny.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is your lucky penny,'' she said, handing the coin to
Earnhardt, ``and you're going to win the Daytona 500.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt graciously accepted the coin, went back to the garage
area, and glued the lucky charm to the dashboard of his car, which
has since been enshrined, penny and all, in the Daytona USA
motorsports museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here they were, about four or five kids . . . just pretty
happy to be there,'' he said. ``And Wessa was just all smiles,
giving me a penny and wishing me good luck. Here I was, worried
about a bum-runnin' motor and she's got a lot bigger problems than
I have. It made you feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Did the gesture send a chill up the Intimidator's spine?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, a little,'' Earnhardt said. ``I felt a lot better when I
walked out of there. I told the guys, `You get that thing right and
we'll win this race.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Earnhardt's car has run strong this week, and
it's good to know that Wessa Miller will be rooting for him again
this year. But something still seemed to be missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to put in a fresh engine for the race,'' he said,
``and hopefully we'll get that race car out of the museum over
there and pry that penny off the damn dash and glue it on the dash
of that sucker and go. I've got that penny marked, and I'll know if
it's the same one or not. I've got it insured for a million.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference was drawing to a close, and the moderator
announced there was time for one last question. There were no
takers.
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating a return visit to Victory Lane and Daytona's
towering press box, Earnhardt drew the microphone close to his
lips, grinned, and drawled, ``Save some for Sunday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 2103EST &QL; 
