<SLUG> BC-BKC-OKLAHOMA-TEXAS-TECH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOONERS' VICTORY SERVED ON TREYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORMAN, Okla. _ To say that Oklahoma made yesterday's 102-75
victory over Texas A&AMP;M look easy would be as obvious as saying TV
soap opera fans were tired of the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from a victory at Texas and looking ahead to games with
fellow Big 12 contenders Missouri and Kansas, the Sooners blew past
the Aggies from the get-go for their fifth consecutive victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're back on top of their game and they'll probably finish
it out that way,'' A&AMP;M coach Melvin Watkins predicted.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners (18-7, 9-3) are certainly on top of their long-range
shooting game. The league's most prolific 3-point shooting team
followed Wednesday night's 13-trey performance in a one-point win
over the Longhorns by draining 15 long-range bombs, two shy of the
school record. OU equaled a 102-point performance against Western
Carolina in November.
</P>
<P>
   Five Sooners players hit at least two threes. Tim Heskett came
off the bench to connect on 5-of-7 on his way to 17 points. OU also
got 17 from reserve center Victor Avila and a game-high 22 from
point guard Michael Johnson on a 7-for-10 performance that included
a trio of 3-pointers in five attempts.
</P>
<P>
   OU is 28-for-54 from beynd the arc in its last two games and has
netted 104-of-273 in Big 12 action. The Sooners shot a season-best
.582 overall yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a good shooting team,'' coach Kelvin Sampson said. ``We
knew if we kept taking good shots they'd start falling. Sometimes
when you're making shots, you look a little better than you are and
the other team doesn't look as good as they are. A&AMP;M is a better
team than they showed today. We have a good team, but by no stretch
can we start saying we're really good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners now look to a big week with an ESPN ``Big Monday''
game at Missouri before returning home for Kansas on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people say that for the last month,'' Sampson said.
``Those games last week were huge games. We're on a five-game
wining streak. The more you win, the bigger they get. You just
don't get carried away one way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing with confidence now,'' said guard Eric Martin,
whose only three buckets were threes. ``But if anything, we need to
raise our level as we go into Missouri and the game after that.
Just because we had a big win today or at Texas, we can't let up.
Coach has done a great job of making us realize that. And we
realize that ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 2109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
