<SLUG> BC-SKI-ALPINESKIING-SLALOM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US HOPES TAKE SPILL IN SLALOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ ``No! No! This is not happening to me,'' wailed
Kristina Koznick as she spun off the slalom course in the
second-to-last race of the World Alpine Championships Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up this morning thinking I would have a medal around my
neck in a few hours,'' said the 23-year-old Burnsville, Minn.,
skier. ``All last night I was thinking, `It's my time for a medal.'
''
</P>
<P>
   And so it's down to one last chance, one race, one hope left
Sunday for the Americans to be more than genial hosts _ and virtual
spectators _ at this gathering. Bode Miller, the 24-year-old from
Franconia, N.H., and Carrabassett Valley Academy in Maine, skis the
men's slalom, the final event of these games, and the final chance
for a US medal.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's slalom winner was Australia's Zali Steggall, who put
together two solid runs down the ever-changing International
course, with the afternoon run strong enough to bump leader
Pernilla Wiberg of Sweden onto the silver podium step, and Norway's
early leader, Trine Bakke, to the bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway through the second run, Steggall was behind Wiberg by
more than three-10ths of a second, but then went for broke, taking
every risk down the three steep faces and several technical,
cranking turns. Steggall outskied Wiberg by eight-10ths of a
second, meaning that she was faster by more than a full second
through the last 25 gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think my first run was that good, so in the second
run I had nothing to lose,'' said Steggall, 30, who won a slalom
bronze medal at the Nagano Olympics. ``I just took all risks and
didn't think of anything, just going for it.''
</P>
<P>
   On every race day through the two weeks of these ``off-year
Olympics,'' the winning nation has heard its national anthem played
in the square at Vail Village. Almost daily the Austrian and
Norwegian anthems have rung though the frosty, festive air, leaving
thousands of American fans longing just once to hear ``The
Star-Spangled Banner.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, those hopes were pinned on Koznick, who wanted more
than anything to make up for a disappointing Olympic debut last
year when she got buried early in the first run and never came
back.
</P>
<P>
   But, alas, the best-laid plans in ski racing snap in an instant.
At 10:37 a.m., with American flags fluttering below as Koznick
started her race, it was over in an instant with a spray of snow.
Ten gates into the 45-gate race, Koznick caught an edge and was
down so fast she couldn't remember what happened. ``I just remember
thinking I wanted to get up and start over,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
