</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-WOHLABAUGH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOHLABAUGH STILL FREE _ FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Patriots dodged a big bullet Saturday, and maybe their luck
is beginning to change.
</P>
<P>
   Free agent center Dave Wohlabaugh turned down an offer from the
Cleveland Browns, although they are still in the lead for his
services.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots also got lucky when the New Orleans Saints, who
were very interested in Wohlabaugh and wanted him to visit with
head coach Mike Ditka, changed directions and re-signed veteran
center Jerry Fontenot.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Patriots are not in the clear. Wohlabaugh
reportedly is on the list of the Miami Dolphins and ready to visit
with head coach Jimmy Johnson. Wohlabaugh is a favorite of former
Patriots offensive line coach Paul Boudreau, who is now with the
Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   The offer Wohlabaugh got from the Browns was highly unusual.
Reportedly, it was for seven years and averaged more than $3.5
million, which would have made him the highest-paid center in
league history.
</P>
<P>
   But Wohlabaugh had a good reason for turning it down.
Reportedly, the offer did not include a signing bonus or guarantees
against injuries. Almost every lucrative free agent contract these
days contains a large signing bonus, which the player gets
immediately, and guarantees on the annual salary, usually for about
half of the length of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   So it is on to Miami for Wohlabaugh, and the Patriots again will
have to hold their breath. If he becomes a Dolphin, he'd be playing
in the same division, against the Patriots twice a year _ a double
whammy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Foxborough, Patriots vice president of business
operations Andy Wasynczuk was hoping he would have the chance to
match any offer Wohlabaugh got.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in touch with Alan Herman (Wohlabaugh's agent) on a
daily basis and we have that understanding,'' said Wasynczuk.
</P>
<P>
   But if Herman is to make Wohlabaugh the highest-paid center in
the NFL, a matching New England offer would seem to be out of the
question.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots had a similar understanding about matching offers
with the agent for punter Tom Tupa, Neil Cornrich, but they were in
no way inclined to match the four-year, $6.1 million deal (which
included a $1.8 million signing bonus) that Tupa agreed to with the
Jets on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It's the largest contract in football for a kicker or punter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Bill (Parcells) has it in mind that Tom will be his
backup quarterback as well,'' said Wasynczuk. ``We hated to lose
Tom. He's a good player, a wonderful guy, and we would have loved
to have had him. But during the season, when we needed to turn to
another quarterback when Drew (Bledsoe) was down, it wasn't Tom we
turned to.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he is tired of the Jets raiding the Patriots, Wasynczuk
said, ``There's a familiarity with our players, and with
familiarity there is a comfort level that Bill has with those
players. That's understandable.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasynczuk added, however, that he is not going to make it a
practice to restructure contracts as often as the Jets do. ``It's
like a credit card,'' said Wasynczuk. ``At some point, the payment
comes due.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasynczuk recently did reorganize the contracts of Willie
McGinest and Vincent Brisby, as well as releasing Ferric Collons,
who was scheduled to earn $2.1 million, as the Patriots try to
maneuver for salary cap room.
</P>
<P>
   Wasynczuk hopes to get something done with defensive tackle
Henry Thomas, though he knows the veteran will get other offers.
``We want Henry and I know Henry wants to be here,'' said
Wasynczuk. ``I know the agent will come back to us if he feels
Henry has received an offer that we need to be aware of. But again,
we have to look at how that would impact our team not only now but
in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is being pursued by seven teams, five in the AFC.
</P>
<P>
   Special teamer Larry Whigham and defensive end Devin Wyman, both
unrestricted free agents, will visit with the Minnesota Vikings
Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
