</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-SALARYCAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGHT CAP CAUSING HEADACHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By RON BORGES 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was not a good week for the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   If embattled head coach Pete Carroll didn't have enough to worry
about already, he learned Friday that running back Robert Edwards's
knee injury might well end his career, punter Tom Tupa is the
latest defector to the Jets, and center Dave Wohlabaugh will be
testing the free agent waters where they are deepest, in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing the Patriots can do about Edwards but pray that
the nerve damage and three torn ligaments he suffered in a touch
football game will somehow heal, and there may not be much more
than prayer available when it comes to Wohlabaugh, either, if their
claims earlier in the week of being $5 million over the salary cap
are to be believed.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots renegotiated several contracts to get under the cap
number of $57.288 million by the NFL deadline but that left them
with little room to operate. The Browns, meanwhile, have nearly $30
million in cap room at their disposal, far more than any
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland head coach Chris Palmer recognizes that center is one
of the key positions in the game and is willing to pay to fill it,
a lesson New England learned in the years before Wohlabaugh's
emergence when then head coach Bill Parcells used to lament, ``That
position is holding us hostage.'' Parcells faced the same problem
in New York when he arrived, so he went out last year and overpaid
Seattle free agent Kevin Mawae, a move that drove up the price of
centers even before Wohlabaugh went on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Patriots have little firepower to combat a run at
Wohlabaugh by the Browns and could be hit with the additional
whammy of Bronco Pro Bowler Tom Nalen having his contract extended
another four years for an average of around $4 million a season.
</P>
<P>
   That would set the market for the position and make Wohlabaugh a
$3 million- to $3.5 million-a-year player at a time when the
Patriots are struggling to find cap room and Cleveland is rolling
in dough.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Cleveland wants a free agent, they'll get him,'' said New
Orleans Saints president Bill Kuharich Friday. ``If you get in a
competition with them, you've got a problem. They can pay almost
any price and for you to compete with them your roster is going to
be affected. You may be able to sign someone but you'll pay so much
you'll have to get rid of several other players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised New England didn't get Wohlabaugh done before
he became a free agent because he's the best center available. If
he gets on the open market, he's gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it becomes a domino situation. If New England loses him,
they have to get someone, so they take a guy like (the Giants'
Lance) Scott or (Washington's) Cory Raymer from the next tier down
and have to overpay him, and that escalates everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It also would weaken an offensive line already struggling with
age and a lack of productivity. The Patriots know this, of course,
but the question is can they do anything about it?
</P>
<P>
   If Wohlabaugh goes, the dismantling of a team that was in the
Super Bowl three years ago will have continued, and there is a
point at which such defections reach critical mass, as the Steelers
finally learned last year. New England may not be there yet, but it
may not be far off.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Browns' plan for building their franchise became obvious in
the expansion draft. Cleveland took 37 players but only two had a
salary cap value greater than $1 million, and the total expenditure
was just over $18 million. That has left the Browns with so much
room under the cap that it puzzled a man who knows a thing or two
about building a team from scratch. ``They took a slightly
different approach than we did,'' said Michael Huyghue, the
Jacksonville Jaguars' senior vice president for football
operations. ``We had a view with youth in mind, as they do, but we
felt the greatest strength was in the college draft, then free
agency, then the expansion draft. They perhaps put more emphasis on
free agency first, judging by their approach to the expansion list.
No one has ever been able to spend $30 million in cap room in a
year because you'd be spending more than double that (in
contracts), but they have that kind of room. You'd have to do a
very heavy amount of spending to eat up even $20 million in cap
room. When we did it, we felt (the expansion draft) was an
opportunity to experiment with a few veteran players where you
could only pay the cash portion of their salary and cut them at the
end of camp if things didn't work out.'' Instead, Cleveland went
almost exclusively with youth, drafting only one player over 30 _
San Francisco linebacker James Williams. Beyond that, they went for
players who cost little and primarily played one of two positions _
offensive line or defensive back. Of the Browns' 37 selections, 10
were defensive backs and nine offensive linemen. Jim Pyne will
forever be remembered as the first of the new Browns, being their
No. 1 selection after starting 16 games for the Lions last year at
center. But center may not be his position in Cleveland because he
is considered a better guard (which he played in Tampa Bay), even
though he prefers being over the ball. If the Browns sign
Wohlabaugh, they would shift Pyne to guard and have 40 percent of a
good line in place . . . The Ravens were not among the teams making
last-minute decisions to put franchise tags on their top free
agents, in part because of the acrimonious results of doing so with
offensive lineman Wally Williams a year ago. Baltimore considered
putting the tag back on Williams or on offensive tackle Orlando
Brown, a move that would have guaranteed one of them $3.369 million
in 1999. Instead, Baltimore let both go on the open market, and new
head coach Brian Billick wasn't happy about it. ``I don't think any
player likes being franchised, which is a little irritating,''
Billick said. ``All these guys signed off on the collective
bargaining agreement and I haven't heard any player say, `Gee, it's
great that I'm a franchise player.' They're all squealing like
stuck pigs the minute you put that tag on them but that's part of
the deal.'' So is such players receiving no signing bonus but
rather 16 equal salary payments, which explains part of their
disgruntlement . . . The Tennessee Titans are interested in talking
with defensive linemen Mark Wheeler and Henry Thomas, two Patriot
free agents . . . Billick's efforts to land Minnesota quarterback
Brad Johnson are cooling, although he said he expects a decision to
be made early this week. Minnesota reportedly opened trade talks by
asking for the Ravens' No. 1 pick (10th overall) and defensive end
Michael McCrary, who was second in the AFC with 14 1/2 sacks last
year. Baltimore rejected that, and six other offers have since been
made between the teams. Wearying of this, Baltimore is now
considering a deal with Detroit for Scott Mitchell, who would cost
Baltimore only a second-round pick . . . If anyone thought free
agency would not be as insane as always, the Eagles proved
otherwise when they made a preemptive signing Thursday of former
Boston College All-America defensive end Mike Mamula. To avoid
letting Mamula enter free agency, the Eagles agreed to pay him a
little more than $11 million over the next four years plus
incentives that could push his deal over $14 million. What had
Mamula done last year to convince the Eagles he was worth such a
ransom? How about tear his knee to shreds and miss the entire
season? Well then, you might say, what did he do in 1997 that
convinced the Eagles he could be their next great pass rusher? How
about make four sacks? In the four seasons since Mamula became
Philadelphia's surprise No. 1 draft pick, he has averaged 4.6 sacks
and made his biggest headline in a barroom rather than on the
field, when he was accused of exposing himself to a waitress while
in a drunken stupor. But agent Brad Blank convinced the
Philadelphia brass that teaming a healthy Mamula with Hugh Douglas
(12 sacks last season) could bring him back to the form he showed
in his first two seasons, when he had a total of 14 sacks while
teamed with William Fuller . . . Wasn't it just about this time
last year that doom was predicted for the Jets because of the
signing of Curtis Martin to a $36 million offer sheet? Weren't they
supposed to be burdened with salary cap problems for years, while
the Patriots were home free? So what happened? Today the Jets have
$5 million-$6 million to spend while New England is saying it can't
afford to do anything. Now, with Edwards's injury, New England not
only has no money, it also has no running back . . . According to
sources, former Chiefs quarterback (and Patriots draftee) Rich
Gannon has been signed by the Raiders, whose erstwhile quarterback,
Jeff George, will be in St. Louis Monday talking to the Rams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
