<SLUG> BC-BBO-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING TRAINING IS LESS THAN ROMANTIC FOR SOME PITCHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Pitchers and catchers report'' are supposedly some of the most
romantic words that can be uttered in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But for Kevin Appier, Ken Hill and many other pitchers, the next
seven weeks will be a deadly serious time after they report to
spring training. Their success is crucial to both their team and
their career, and how they pitch in spring training will watched
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   At look at some pivotal pitchers and what they're facing this
spring:
</P>
<P>
   ]Appier: The Royals righthander is trying to comeback from
arthroscopic shoulder surgery a year ago. He made three starts in
September and allowed 13 runs in 15 innings.
</P>
<P>
   He'll make $4.8 million this year, and the Royals would love to
trade him for two or three prospects. But he must show he's
healthy. The Rangers will have some interest as do the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ]Hill: The Angels righthander missed two months last year
because of elbow surgery and was 1-1 with a 4.44 earned-run average
in five starts when he returned. He has not had a good season since
helping the Rangers win the division in 1996. The Angels can't win
without him.
</P>
<P>
   ]John Burkett: He had a bad year in 1998 until his last two
starts when he delivered two crucial victories over Oakland and
Anaheim. He's 34, but he should still be a solid, dependable
starter. The Rangers need that.
</P>
<P>
   ]Roger Clemens: The Blue Jays believe he'll be in camp with the
rest of the staff next week. But a deal is still likely, with the
Astros and Indians the leading candidates. If he does show up in
the Blue Jays' camp, he'll have to deal with the wrath of Pat
Hentgen and other Blue Jays teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ]Hideo Nomo: He has rapidly regressed since his terrific rookie
season in 1995. The Mets took a chance on him with a mid-season
trade last year and he was 4-5 with a 4.82 ERA in 17 appearances.
He was 1-4 with a 6.18 ERA in the final two months.
</P>
<P>
   The reports say he has lost some confidence, resulting in
control problems. He walked 5.4 batters per nine innings last year.
The Mets signed Allen Watson in the off-season, giving them a
fifth-starter alternative if Nomo is still struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ]Mark Wohlers: The Braves reliever, plagued by injuries and
personal problems, fell apart last year and couldn't throw the ball
over the plate. He has still been erratic in winter workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ]Chris Holt: The Astros are hoping the former Dallas Baptist
star can compete for a fifth spot in the rotation. He missed all of
last year with shoulder surgery after going 8-12 with a 3.52 ERA as
a rookie in 1997. He had some control problems pitching in winter
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ]Kerry Wood: The Cubs Rookie of the Year sensation stepped up
his off-season conditioning program and says he is over the elbow
problems that bothered him at the end of last year. New pitching
coach Marty McDermitt worked closely with him in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ]Jim Abbott: He was 5-0 with a 4.55 ERA in five starts with the
White Sox late last year, his first appearance in the major leagues
since 1996. Now he's with the Brewers, who are desperate. He could
be their Opening Day pitcher, which says more about how bad the
Brewers are than how far back Abbott has come.
</P>
<P>
   ]Dave Mlicki: This guy is a decent starter, but he doesn't
figure into the Dodgers' rotation. A spring trade is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ]Shawn Estes: If the Giants are going to contend, then their
19-game winner from 1997 must be better than 7-12 with a 5.06 ERA,
his numbers in '98.
</P>
<P>
   ]Brian Anderson: The pitching-rich Arizona Diamondbacks are
likely to trade this lefthander before the spring is over. He was
12-13 with a 4.33 ERA last year and makes $1.8 million. The
Diamondbacks want a corner outfielder who can hit.
</P>
<P>
   ]Ken Cloude: The Mariners do a poor job of developing young
pitchers. They thought Cloude would be special, but he's 12-12 with
a 6.06 ERA in 40 major-league games.
</P>
<P>
   ]Blake Stein: The Athletics' second-year righthander carries the
burden of being what's left from the Mark McGwire trade. He was 5-9
with a 6.37 ERA as a rookie but has a good arm.
</P>
<P>
   ]Jaret Wright: He was great for the Indians in the 1997
playoffs, but visions of being a No. 1 starter were dampened last
year when he went 12-10 with a 4.72 ERA. The talent is still there
for a breakthrough season.
</P>
<P>
   ]Justin Thompson: The Tigers lefthander struggled last year to
overcome elbow problems. He should be stronger this year and a
legitimate All-Star candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ]Hideki Irabu: The Japanese Nolan Ryan has turned into just
another fifth starter in America. He was 13-9 with a 4.06 ERA
during the regular season but completely ignored in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ]Bobby Witt: He's in camp with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays on a
minor-league contract, trying to crack a rotation of Rolando
Arrojo, Wilson Alvarez, Tony Saunders, Julio Santana, Bryan Rekar.
It could be his last stand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
