<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-TYSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELF-INFLICTED WOUNDS HURT TYSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The guy who says he never gets a break got his 100th
second chance last week but he may need a 101st to keep his boxing
career alive.
</P>
<P>
   When Mike Tyson was told he could serve 60 days of his one-year
sentence for misdemeanor assault and then enter a work-release
program that would allow him to train and fight, no one was more
relieved than executives at Showtime and promoters Mat Tinley and
Dan Goossen. But their relief could be temporary.
</P>
<P>
   Showtime is said to have advanced Tyson between $13 million and
$23 million (depending on whom you believe) against future
earnings, in addition to the $10 million it paid him for his Jan.
16 fight with Frans Botha, so he could pay off back taxes and other
bills. Goossen's company, America Presents, is on the hook for
another $5 million in advances.
</P>
<P>
   Both stood to be chasing that money for some time if Tyson was
unable to fight for another year, and they still stand to lose it
if Tyson's probation is revoked in Indiana and he is forced to
complete the four years left on his 1992 rape sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's probation officer, George Walker, said last week from
Indianapolis that he will ask the Indiana judge to consider
revoking probation as a result of Tyson's pleading no contest to
the two counts of misdemeanor assault that landed him back in jail.
If that happens, all bets are off on his future. But Judge Patricia
Gifford could simply extend his probation beyond its scheduled end
next month rather than lock him up.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the relative minor nature of Tyson's offenses in
Maryland, she might well do that, and once again Tyson would be off
the hook. But either way, his April 24 fight will be postponed and
the earliest it could be rescheduled would be this summer, so until
that time his list of creditors grows.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson apologists continue to claim he was railroaded in Maryland
because of his celebrity, but the fact is, were he not a celebrity,
his probation would have been revoked and he would have been
rousted out of bed to face Gifford within hours of the initial
assaults. That is what happens to ex-cons on parole or probation
for violent acts, especially those with a long record of scrapes
with the law. If they get into trouble, they go to jail, not to Las
Vegas to fight for $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   That this latest chapter in his tortured life ended with his
arms handcuffed behind his back as he was pushed into a police
wagon and taken to the Montgomery County Detention Center was sadly
predictable. Unfortunately, so was the Maryland court's decision to
soften his sentence and bend over backward for Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of when Tyson goes back into training or fights
again, he will be broke and past his prime, a fighter with so much
ring rust on him that it is difficult to believe he can ever
approach the great promise he once showed when he became the
youngest man in history to win the heavyweight title.
</P>
<P>
   He will still be something else, too. He will still be the
person most responsible for his own demise.
</P>
<P>
   That Tyson has been used and abused for much of his life is
obvious. He is the product of a difficult childhood, a hard
neighborhood, and a profession that has used him like a donkey
throughout his adult life and is using him still.
</P>
<P>
   Even one of his harshest critics concedes that. But Teddy Atlas,
Tyson's trainer during much of his amateur career, adds the proper
perspective, ``Sure he was exploited. Absolutely. But he exploited
himself, too. People conveniently forget the choices he's made. He
always wanted to just be able to do what he wanted. He was
exploited by a lot of people, but it was a joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never had to live a real life where he had to make
decisions and face the consequences because financially things
always ended sunny-side up. No matter what choice he made, somebody
was always there to straighten things out for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never was asked to develop emotionally or socially. You see
guys like (Shelly) Finkel, apologists for Tyson, and you ask
yourself what would they be saying about what he's done if a
disease suddenly took control of both his arms. See what his
apologists would say then. See if they'd still be there or if
they'd be off with some other guy like (Fernando) Vargas or (David)
Tua.''
</P>
<P>
   As Maryland assistant state attorney Carol Crawford said, ``The
dark cloud of money has hung over this case from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the day Tyson arrived at Cus D'Amato's house as a teenage
tough in reform school with a gift for causing concussions,
everything about him has been colored by money. It is why every
moment of his life has been bathed in the bright lights of scrutiny
no man could long survive but it is also why he continues to make
millions long after he should have been ignored as a loser in
life's battle.
</P>
<P>
   But now Tyson cannot fight the way he once did. Now he cannot
pack arenas with fans as he once did or sell pay-per-view buys as
he once did. Through his own actions and decisions, he has
transformed himself from a great boxer into a circus act, but he is
not even a clown or a high-wire act anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson has become the guy who climbs into the cannon and is shot
across the big top, helpless to affect what is to come. In such a
circumstance, people pay to see the crash, not the man involved in
it.
</P>
<P>
   That's a sad way for the youngest heavyweight champion in boxing
history to end up, but there he is  &UR; today &LR;  _ broke, beaten down by
life and Evander Holyfield, jailed, and almost certain to end up
one fight short of paying off his bills. One fight short of getting
what he most needs from boxing _ out of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
