<HEADLINE>
WHERE WOULD MAVS FIT INTO HICKS EMPIRE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever deal may be brewing between Ross Perot Jr. and Tom
Hicks, it's not likely that Perot will give up his majority
interest in the Mavericks, causing insiders to wonder exactly what
the two business moguls are planning.
</P>
<P>
   The initial report indicated that Hicks would purchase 10 to 15
percent interest in the Mavs. It's not likely all of that would
come from Perot, who owns somewhere between 53 and 54 percent of
the club.
</P>
<P>
   If Perot gives up anything more than 4 percent, he'll no longer
have majority interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not going to happen,'' says one Mavs insider.
</P>
<P>
   Auto dealership magnate David McDavid is the second largest
shareholder with 14 percent and Richard Rainwater, the former Fort
Worth entrepreneur, owns 12 percent. There's been some speculation
that Hicks might be buying Rainwater's percentage, leaving Perot as
majority shareholder, but that has not been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, a renowned wheeler-dealer, is not a man who generally
wants a minority interest in anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not his style either,'' the source says.
</P>
<P>
   As for Hicks wanting a small piece of the Mavs' to enhance his
chances of adding the Mavs to his TV programming empire, that's a
possibility, but with Perot still the majority owner, there's no
guarantee that would make a difference.
MR. HICKS' NEIGHBORHOOD
</P>
<P>
   Hicks on Rangers economics: ``We thought Randy Johnson could
make enough of a difference that we convinced ourselves that it was
worth the investment. We did the same thing in trying to work a
deal to get Roger Clemens. It's the reality of the sport today. The
economics are being driven by a handful of large-market teams. The
Texas Rangers are kind of on the fringe of that group. We can't
compete heads up with them, but we can stay in the neighborhood.''
COVER BOY
</P>
<P>
   TCU head coach Dennis Franchione has been notified by Dave
Campbell's Texas Football magazine that he and Texas coach Mack
Brown will be featured on next year's cover under the headline,
``Changing the Face of Texas Football.'' First time TCU has been on
the mag's cover since Jim Wacker and Kenneth Davis graced it in
1985. Then again, maybe we shouldn't have mentioned that part.
ROCKET'S RED GLARE
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Roger Clemens to show up with Toronto's pitchers
and catchers at Dunedin, Fla., any time soon, even though the Blue
Jays open camp this week. There's no benefit to Clemens to try to
settle into a situation in such disarray, especially with some
insiders saying that a deal with Houston has already been reached
and that the only thing holding up an announcement is the
commissioner's office concluding its investigation of Astros' owner
Drayton MacLane for tampering.
STOMACH MUSCLE
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to replace Mo Vaughn, the Red Sox have at least
gone for bulk by signing Bob Hamelin. When Hamelin played with a
mostly anonymous team in Kansas City a couple of years ago, a
Rangers' coach referred to the Royals as ``eight nobodies and a
bartender.'' Finally, a replacement for Sam at Cheers.
COMINGS AND GOINGS
</P>
<P>
   Mike Capps, who gave up a career as a CNN reporter to pursue an
announcing career in baseball, has moved his home from Dallas to
New York and will do play-by-play for the Atlantic City Surf in the
independent Atlantic League (former Rangers GM Joe Klein is
president) this season. In the meantime, Capps is doing free-lance
work for WNBC-TV in New York.
RIBBITS
</P>
<P>
   Franchione has apparently had a sit down with
receiver-turned-quarterback Patrick Batteaux and told him he will
be moving back to wide receiver next season. He's cool with that.
... Two disturbing notes from the TCU basketball stat sheet: The
Frogs have turned the ball over more times than their opponents
this season, and their foes have taken more shots. When was the
last time that happened to a Billy Tubbs team? ... Word from NBA
scouts is that TCU's Lee Nailon is being projected as a first-round
pick in the next draft, probably somewhere between 10 and 15.
CHIPS AND DIPS
</P>
<P>
   Good news for Port Charlotte dispatchers: the famed 776
Restaurant and Lounge, closed down since last summer, has been sold
to new owners and hopes to re-open by March 1. Cross your fingers.
... Biggest non-Mavs related ovation at Reunion Arena Thursday
night was for Rangers catcher Pudge Rodriguez and wife Maribel.
Better than the one for Emmitt Smith even. ... Mariners' manager
Lou Piniella says he expects his team to be picked third in AL
West: ``But I know this: We're not going to finish third. We're
going to finish on top.''
</P>
<P>
   REVO'S RIMSHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Williams hires Master P as his agent and makes the
announcement from a Baton Rouge casino? Uh oh, sounds like one of
Tom Hicks' kids is in trouble again.
</P>
<P>
   This IOC dirty business of bribes and payoffs is beginning to
make the old Southwest Conference scandals of the '80s look like
kids playing Candyland.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mavs' first four games, poor Steve Nash bit through his
tongue, broke his nose, missed almost every shot he's taken and
blamed himself after every loss. Maybe he should change his name to
Steve Gnash.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe's Peter Gammons says a National League scout
once filed this report on hefty new Red Sox DH Bob Hamelin: ``His
best tool is his fork.'' Ba-da-boom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
