<HEADLINE>
HARTFORD A TORCH BEARER FOR SPIRIT OF BUYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And the winning bid for the 2008 Summer Olympic Games goes to .
. .
</P>
<P>
   HARTFORD, CONNECTICUT!!!!!!
</P>
<P>
   Perfect. How come it took so long to arrive at this natural
merger of need and greed?
</P>
<P>
   Disclosures of the last month taught us that the Olympics can be
bought. We know that those sanctimonious members of the
International Olympic Committee will gladly give the Games to the
highest bidder. We also know that the state of Connecticut will pay
any price to feel ``big league.'' So now the Lords of the Rings
have chosen Hartford for 2008. And it's a natural.
</P>
<P>
   What a time this is for the once-maligned capital city of the
Nutmeg State. Hartford's remarkable renaissance has become global
news.
</P>
<P>
   And to think that it all started with the announcement that Bob
Kraft was moving his football team to Hartford. That broke the
logjam. Shortly after Kraft revealed his plan, Hartford was awarded
the 2000 Democratic National Convention, the 2004 World's Fair, and
the 2003 Ryder Cup. There also will be a visit from the Pope, but
Vatican officials warned that His Holiness will not kiss any of the
contaminated soil around the Yo-Adriaen's Landing site.
</P>
<P>
   There's more. Hartford this summer will be the site of the
Beatles reunion concert, and officials in France are expected to
announce that the annual Cannes Film Festival will be permanently
moved to Showcase Cinema in East Hartford and renamed the Hartford
Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say we have an inferiority complex,'' quipped Hartford
Mayor Mike Peters. ``Well, I guess this will shut them up.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement that the 2008 Games will be going to Hartford
came after all IOC members received free million-dollar life
insurance policies from Hartford Olympic Committee members (don't
laugh; you think it's easy getting a term-life policy for Juan
Antonio Samaranch?), scholarships to Yale for their kids, and
genuine Hartford cigar wrappers. With sheeplike precision, the
Connecticut Legislature also was active in the bidding, promising
IOC members Super Bowl tickets and ``walking-around money,'' which
was casually requested in random e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland also announced that the new Yale Bowl will serve as
soccer stadium for the 2008 Olympics. Cycling will be held in
nearby Avon, Conn., and Hartford's Colt Park will be Hartford's
version of Atlanta's Centennial Park.
</P>
<P>
   Having bought the Olympics, the Democratic Convention, the
World's Fair, the Ryder Cup, the Beatles, the Cannes Film Festival,
and the Patriots, Hartford now has its sights set on future Super
Bowls, but that can't happen until there is a football stadium, and
it's still not clear when the Patriots will begin playing in their
new $375 million playpen. Connecticut Gov. John Rowland and Kraft
have been greco-roman wrestling on the carpet of the governor's
mansion in their efforts to resolve potential problems over a steam
plant and removal of toxic waste.
</P>
<P>
   In accordance with the latest round of negotiations between the
Patriots and Rowland, the team is expected to start playing games
in Hartford sometime around 2009 _ or the year after the Red Sox
win their next World Series, whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the governor and Kraft are still saying nice
things. After winning the Olympic Games, Rowland went out of his
way to recognize Kraft, a man who loves to be recognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We owe a lot of this to Robert Kraft,'' said the governor.
``He was the first one to believe in us. Once we got the Patriots,
other people started to take Hartford seriously again. Plus, we
found out that if you fork over ridiculous sums to make the rich
richer, they'll come to your city no matter how dreadful it appears
to be. Hey, it worked for Atlanta. Why not us?''
</P>
<P>
   Hartford citizens applauded the announcement. IOC officials
expressed their glee by rattling their jewelry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
