<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-GORDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON READY TO PUT UP ANOTHER STRONG FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ At almost every race in the NASCAR Winston
Cup Series, Jeff Gordon has come to be regarded as the man to beat.
When the the 51st season kicks off with Sunday's Daytona 500, it
will be no different for the two-time defending (and three-time
overall) Winston Cup champion from Pittsboro, Ind., who will start
from the pole position in an all-Hoosier front row alongside Tony
Stewart, a rookie from Rushville, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderboy don't bother me none down here,'' quipped Dale
Earnhardt, the 1998 Daytona 500 winner who ranks as the winningest
driver at Daytona International Speedway with 33 career victories
to his name.
</P>
<P>
   But Earnhardt's jocularity gave way to a certain resignation
when he added, ``He'll be tough just the same, just like the rest
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe even tougher.
</P>
<P>
   When Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas gives the command,
``Gentlemen, start your engines!'' and Green Bay Packers
quarterback Brett Favre unfurls the green flag as the honorary
starter, Gordon is likely to be the man everyone will be gunning
for. The posted purse is an estimated $8 million, with $1.1 million
set aside for the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every race we go to, there's a certain amount of pressure we
put on ourselves,'' said Gordon, who last year tied Richard Petty's
modern record with 13 victories and is attempting to become only
the second three-peat Winston Cup champion, after Cale Yarborough
(1976-78). ``I don't really pay attention to what's written in the
papers or what's on TV. I'm on the pole, and we've got a fast race
car. I think we've got the combination to win the Daytona 500 this
year, the best I've ever had, and I think we've got an even
stronger team than we had last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pressure I'm putting on myself, that we're putting on
ourselves. It's not you're on the pole; it's you should win.''
</P>
<P>
   As an added incentive, Gordon will be one of five drivers _
along with Dale Jarrett, Terry Labonte, Jimmy Spencer, and Jeremy
Mayfield _ vying for the $1 million Winston No Bull 5 bonus, which
also will be paid to one of five select fans whose driver wins the
race. Gordon qualified for the bonus by finishing in the Top 5 at
the previous No Bull 5 event, Oct. 11 at Talladega, Ala., won by
Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gordon won two of the three No Bull 5 bonuses he was
eligible for, all of which bolstered his season winnings to a
record $9,306,584.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's already a big enough race,'' Gordon said. ``And you put
an extra million dollars out there for the drivers and you put an
extra million dollars out there for the fans, I can't think of a
better way to get the season started. We've got a good car. We'll
see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon can expect stiff opposition from the No. 6 Valvoline Ford
Taurus of Mark Martin, runner-up to Gordon in last year's points
chase who gave a glimpse of his strength when he won last Sunday's
Bud Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who will start ninth, is among seven drivers in the Top
10 starting positions gunning for their first Daytona 500 victory.
The others: Stewart, on the outside pole; 1998 runner-up Bobby
Labonte, Stewart's stablemate with Joe Gibbs Racing who will start
third; Jeff Burton, who will start fifth; No. 6 starter Mayfield,
who recorded his best career finish in the Daytona 500 last year
with a third-place effort; Ken Schrader, who will start seventh;
and No. 10 starter Rusty Wallace, Mayfield's Penske-Kranefuss
teammate who also recorded his best 500 finish with a fifth last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting out front and staying there is important,'' Gordon
said. ``There's going to be some shuffling going on and there's
certain times in the race when that stuff's OK, but after you get
past the halfway point of the race, you want to get the lead and
keep it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means you have to have good pit stops to be able to stay
out front and you've got to work hard to stay in front of those
guys and not let them get a run on you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
