<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS </SLUG>
 TECH-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas Tech compounds Kansas' free fall
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JODY GOLDSTEIN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LUBBOCK _ It became apparent it was going to be a strange game
Saturday when a Texas Tech cheerleader was ejected for mouthing off
to a referee in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   YoungIt became stranger when the Texas Tech Red Raiders rallied
from a 14-point second-half deficit to knock off the No. 24-ranked
Kansas Jayhawks 90-84 for the first time in school history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a will to win,'' said junior point guard Rayford Young,
who had a career-high 41 points. ``I wanted to win this game so
bad. It's been a tough year. At the beginning of the year, I
circled the Kansas game (on the schedule). I figured we'd win all
the other games, then get to Kansas and upset them. We didn't do
that, but we took care of this one.''
</P>
<P>
   The win hurts Kansas (16-8, 8-4 in the Big 12) more than it
helps Texas Tech. An ugly loss at home to unranked Nebraska on
Wednesday night, coupled with this one, the fifth loss in nine
games, nearly guarantees the Jayhawks will go into the Big 12
tournament unranked.
</P>
<P>
   Young was outstanding, particularly down the stretch, when he
accounted for Tech's final 10 points, going 10-for-10 from the
free-throw line. He also hit the 3-pointer that put Tech (12-13,
4-8) on top 70-69 with 4:20 left. That 3 came in the midst of 15
consecutive points by Young.
</P>
<P>
   Young was 9-for-17 from the field, including 5-for-7 from
3-point range. He made all 18 free-throw attempts, pulled down
three rebounds and had one steal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing a better job in our four-out, one-in passing
game,'' Tech coach James Dickey said. ``That gives us more
potential options on the perimeter. Rayford did a good job picking
spots. We did a good job realizing he was hot and getting the ball
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-half turnaround began at the 10:08 mark when Tech
mounted a 9-1 run that began on a tip-in by Andy Ellis (12 points),
then continued as Young hit a 3-pointer, followed by a layup and
two free throws to cut a 62-48 Kansas edge to 63-57. Young, who
scored 15 consecutive points for the Raiders and 18-of-20 during
this stint, nailed back-to-back 3s and two free throws, cutting the
lead to three. After a jump shot by Ellis, he canned the 3-pointer
that gave Texas Tech its first lead of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can get the ball inside, get a couple of buckets
and fouls, you have to drop down on us,'' Ellis said. ``And when
you do that and Ray is hitting on the outside, you have to choose
one or the other. They left Ray and that was the wrong choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders outscored Kansas 60-48 in the second half, including
a 19-5 run over 5:23 to make up the 14-point margin. But even a
seven-point edge with 58 seconds left was threatened, saved only by
the hot hand of Young. Kansas freshman guard Jeff Boschee hit three
consecutive 3 pointers in only 22 seconds, the final one cutting
the lead to two.
</P>
<P>
   Young made all 12 free throws in the final two minutes to ice
the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Tech had led through most of the first half, but never could
stretch it to more than five. But Kansas scored 12 of the final 14
points to give the Jayhawks a six-point edge, 36-30 at the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't feel good to be on this side of a comeback,'' said
Kansas coach Roy Williams, whose Jayhawks rallied from a 14-point
deficit for a 86-77 victory the last time they played in Lubbock
(1997). ``Give them credit for being something in the second half.
We've got to get better and quit being so tentative. We have got to
learn to finish games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders have won two consecutive games after beating Baylor
on Wednesday night. They took a six-game losing streak into the
Baylor contest and have won only four times in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as a conference performance, this was a big, big,
game,'' Dickey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 2203EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
