<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4557 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS &LR;      02-13 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS </SLUG>
 A&AMP;M-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas A&AMP;M gets caught in OU's line of fire
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Following a turnover on his team's first possession that led to a
basket, Clifton Cook did not hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   The junior guard came down the floor and stroked a 3-pointer to
put Texas A&AMP;M on top.
</P>
<P>
   With three seconds left in the first half, Cook pulled a repeat
on the offensive end, this time dribbling past a screen to drain
another trey from just right of the circle.
</P>
<P>
   Both shots were beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   What happened between the two shots was very ugly for the
Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M, which after an 0-5 start had won four of its last six games
to gain some respect in the Big 12 Conference, slipped back to the
bad old days with an all-too-forgettable performance against
Oklahoma, falling 102-75 Saturday at the Lloyd Noble Center.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma, which beat first-place Texas on Michael Johnson's late
jumper Wednesday, got more heroics from the senior point guard
against the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson hit 5 of 7 shots from the floor in the first half,
including three 3-pointers, and finished with a game-high 22
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate to get an easy steal from the start,'' Johnson
said. ``The opportunity came for me to shoot the ball, and that's
what I did. I didn't come out looking forward to scoring, but hey,
the opportunities were there and I took it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies didn't do much with their opportunities. A&AMP;M missed
nine consecutive shots after Cook's opening 3-pointer and
eventually fell behind by as many as 23 before Cook's final basket
of the half left the Aggies facing a 48-28 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We threw the kitchen sink out there. It just didn't work
today,'' A&AMP;M coach Melvin Watkins said. ``But we're a better
basketball team than that. They've got good players and they hit
shots. That pretty much sums it up.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no way A&AMP;M, which hit just 27 percent of its shots in
the first half (9-of-33), could be this bad. Conversely, there is
no way Oklahoma could be this good.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help matters that two of A&AMP;M's starters _ Shanne Jones
and Jerald Brown _ were slowed by the flu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team is such that there's not too much room for error,''
said Watkins, whose team fell to 11-11. ``When two of your starters
are sick, you become awfully, awfully thin. It's not too pretty
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no complaining from Oklahoma. The Sooners hit a
season-high 58 percent from the floor (32-for-55), which included
scorching the nets for a season-high 15 3-pointers in 25 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Five Sooners hit at least two 3-pointers and six players scored
in double figures for Oklahoma, which improved to 18-7 overall and
9-3 in conference play, a half game behind first-place Texas, which
plays at Oklahoma State today.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just caught us on the wrong day,'' said Oklahoma coach
Kelvin Sampson, whose team has a five-game winning streak after
losing four in a row. ``When the ball goes in, it makes us all look
a lot better.
</P>
<P>
   ``People overreact when things go good and overreact when things
go bad. We're not as good as we looked today, or as bad as we
looked when we were on that losing streak.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M had only 13 turnovers, but hit just 24-of-64 from the field
and made only 7 of 26 3-point tries.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson led the defensive charge out front, harassing Cook from
the start and contributing to a 4-of-18 afternoon with 12 points
for A&AMP;M's leading scorer. Jones led the Aggies with 14 points, but
he did not fare well from the floor either, going 4-for-12.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Schmidt contributed 13 points and Aaron Jack had a nice
day off the bench with 12 points on 4-for-5 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   But that was far too little against the hot-shooting Sooners.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were bombing,'' Watkins said. ``We were thinking about
putting a sixth man out there. Some of them were NBA 3s. That's
confidence. When you hit early, your confidence really gets
going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 2204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 22:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4558 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-13 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
McNair at Tagliabue's mercy for Houston team
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WHAT we have here is a failure to communicate. Some NFL owners
hoping to place the next expansion team in Los Angeles have pledged
to do ``whatever it takes'' to get it there, to quote one longtime
owner.
</P>
<P>
   Others have been wowed by Houston's NFL expansion effort, which
has only been perfect every step of the way, and say Houston leads
the race. Still others say they feel strongly both ways, or are
reluctant to expand. This is mostly the old guard, which lives up
to its name by guarding things closely _ like their lucrative
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue seems to tell everyone
exactly what they want to hear. One moment, Tagliabue voices
support for a league-imposed plan similar to the one that put a
team in Cleveland. The next, he tells the Houston group there is no
such plan and his comments about the effort were misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   And in the middle of it all is Houston billionaire and expansion
leader Bob McNair. Cool Hand Bob.
</P>
<P>
   His personality has greatly impressed the NFL inmates. His
attention to detail, his answering of every challenge, his charisma
and leadership abilities have endeared him to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   But despite it all, what is McNair to believe? Like Luke, Cool
Hand Bob remains a prisoner of the warden's notions no matter how
much everyone in this expansion drama is pulling for him.
</P>
<P>
   McNair confident he'll win
</P>
<P>
   He is shackled by the massive Los Angeles market, unable to
escape its value to the NFL and Tagliabue's vision. He is unable to
distinguish whether those owners telling him they are on his side
might be patting him on the back with one hand but have a knife
placed in the other by Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   McNair has been unable to use his powers of persuasion to break
through the bars that surround the Houston bid. He is confident the
team will come to Houston and in a perfect world he should be
confident. He has a diligent righthand man in Steve Patterson
working every moment of every day toward the expansion bid.
</P>
<P>
   He has a strong television market _ the 11th-largest, which is
bigger than 21 existing teams. He has corporate support and a
football passion in this city that opinion polls say consistently
ranks higher than that in LA. The Houston bid is so much better, so
much more airtight than LA's, it shouldn't even be a contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done everything the NFL has asked of us,'' McNair said.
``We've met all the requirements they've set forth for us and quite
frankly, Los Angeles has not. It's going to be very difficult for
prudent business people to turn that down.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tagliabue, suddenly the most powerful commissioner in all of
sports, is the warden. He holds the keys for all the NFL's business
people, prudent or not.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue can tell Houston one thing and LA another because it's
his game. The NFL is his world. He can nudge this owner in a
certain direction, swing a deal with another, threaten another and
always get his way, especially when it comes to wrangling the
numerous new ownership groups that have profited handsomely from
Tagliabue's recent decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1987, Tagliabue has kept labor peace within the league.
The current NFL television contract is a whopping $87 billion deal,
which puts on average $70 million a year in each owner's pockets.
He has tried to make the NFL product attractive. And he handled the
brilliant move to quickly get Cleveland another franchise _ a
nearly $1 billion coup.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tagliabue will make the call on expansion. No matter how
much charisma McNair flashes, no matter anything, no one will carry
more clout in the expansion sweepstakes than the warden. And it's
tough fighting the warden when you're in shackles.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue exerts undue influence
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue has seen TV ratings in Los Angeles fall since the Rams
moved out of LA. With the NFL's TV negotiations likely to reopen in
2002, it is easy to see why Tagliabue might be more inclined to
work the backdoor and covertly push for a team in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he is worried civic support in Houston and the lack
thereof in Los Angeles would be a worry for him, Tagliabue said,
``In short, no.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners meeting scheduled for Wednesday likely will not end
with a vote on expansion. Instead, Tagliabue will try to gather
support for expansion and then put the issue to a vote between
Houston and LA at the March 14-18 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   McNair likely will be the most deserving potential owner. But
the call will be Tagliabue's and the inmates likely will do what
the warden says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're being strung out,'' Patterson said of
Tagliabue's public accolades for Houston but reported deal-making
for Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Said McNair: ``I know we're the underdogs and I don't mind that
at all. The prospect of them saying we can't do it is enough to
spur me on. We have to find a way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston group has communicated its case perfectly to the
owners. But more than anything, it has to convince Tagliabue, and
that is a trick no less impressive than breaking out of shackles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
