<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4560 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBANOTES-HORNETS-     02-13 1745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-HORNETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNETS HURTING MORE THAN ANYONE ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Bass figured he had it all in place. He had a mobile front
line, players who could handle the ball as well as post up. He'd
taken some heat for signing Derrick Coleman, but he liked the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see us being every bit as good as we were last year,
even better,'' said the Charlotte Hornets' basketball boss. ``Then,
in a matter of about five days, we were wiped out.''
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice? Gone for a month, perhaps forever. Anthony Mason?
Gone for the year. That mobile, ball-handling, post-up front line?
Say hello to Chuck Person and J.R. Reid, two calcified vets.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries have dramatically altered the landscape in the Eastern
Conference, though you may recall it was a lot worse last year in
terms of missing star power leaguewide. Alonzo Mourning, John
Stockton, and Scottie Pippen all started last season hors de combat
and were soon joined for extended absences by Shaquille O'Neal,
Patrick Ewing, Hakeem Olajuwon, Penny Hardaway, and half the
Milwaukee Bucks. It isn't that bad this year _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have lost Latrell Sprewell. The Heat, like the
Hornets, have lost 40 percent of their starting lineup and a lot of
their pop. The Nets are nicked. But no one got blindsided worse
than the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   First, they lost both of their free agent centers, which, of
course, has nothing to do with injuries and everything to do with
team management. But losing Rice and then Mason turned them from a
playoff contender _ they won 51 games last year _ into a lottery
lock.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dave Cowens has to go with Reid, Person, and Chucky Brown,
all of whom were penciled in as bench players, which is charitable
but accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liked our bench,'' Bass said. ``But now I don't like it so
much now because it's our starting lineup. I've seen injuries
before, but nothing like this, nothing like losing your top two
players at the same time. That's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither injury is lockout-related, although Bass believes that
Rice's elbow problems would have been taken care of over the summer
had teams been allowed to contact players. Mason tore a biceps
during practice (similar to Ted Johnson's injury) and already has
had surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, you think after a lockout that guys will have
tendinitis, or they'll be overweight, or there'll be swelling of
the joints,'' Bass said. ``Or a guy will turn an ankle. But that
wasn't the case with Mase. It was a freak thing, a complete
detachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Bass says he has no clue how to right the ship, if it can be
righted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't got this solved yet,'' he said. ``I haven't come up
with any plan.''
</P>
<P>
   He has company a few hours south in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat can relate. They haven't lost their top two, although
Mourning and Tim Hardaway, who are 1-2, looked like 11-12 against
the Celtics last week. But Voshon Lenard (stress fracture in his
leg) finally had surgery Friday and could be out for the year.
Jamal Mashburn? Who can say? He's out indefinitely with a bad bone
bruise and he has a Royal Doulton frame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a roll of the dice,'' says Miami GM Randy Pfund. ``Just
ask Chris Ford. If Milwaukee stayed healthy last year, he'd
probably still be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mashburn came to camp in sensational shape and everything was
pointing toward a terrific year. The Heat even resisted efforts
from a lot of teams _ including the Celtics _ to pry away the
ex-Kentuckian. (We're also told that Cleveland, Philadelphia, and
Portland were interested.)
</P>
<P>
   Lenard was undeniably the weakest of the starting five, but
nonetheless capable of explosive bursts that could turn games
around. More to the point, the Heat don't have anyone ready to step
into either position to provide scoring, although Pat Riley is
looking at old friend Blue Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we have players who can fill their minutes, they don't
have the capability to score like Mash and Voshon,'' Pfund said.
</P>
<P>
   What does this mean in the big picture? Who knows? Miami can't
seriously be seen as the division favorite anymore, but will Riley
allow them to fall? Riley always has been able to get players to
give more because he could convince them that the rewards were
available. Will the players still buy that?
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will plod along until Sprewell returns and the Nets,
if they don't fall too far astern, should be interesting if they
get healthy. Say goodbye to the Hornets, though. And, as you'll see
below, their problems with Rice go a lot further than simply a bum
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics' current six-day respite between games is tied for
the longest in the league this abbreviated season. Only one other
team, the Wizards, has a similar six-day break; eight teams have no
breaks longer than two days between games. Everyone pays, of
course, and the Wizards will play 16 times in 24 days after their
respite. ``This may be the last time this season that we are going
to have any extended contact in terms of practice time,'' said
Wizards coach Bernie Bickerstaff. ``This break really comes at a
crucial time for us because we basically had four guys who had
little or no training camp. This will give them an opportunity to
get in the work that they need.'' One of those, of course, is point
guard Rod Strickland, who signed at the end of camp. How big is he?
``As he goes, we go,'' Bickerstaff said. ``There's no rhythm right
now, especially on offense.'' Bickerstaff put the Wizards through
three-a-days in training camp, although he said the middle session
was ``on-floor review of what we did in the morning and a preview
of what we were to do at night.'' . . . Some other schedule
oddities: Milwaukee is one of those teams with no break longer than
two days, the only one in the East. The Bucks have four such breaks
this month, but pay for it next month when they play 19 games in 31
days, including two sets of three-in-three days. Seattle has 12 of
the first 24 days off, but then has a hideous stretch in late March
and early April when it plays five times in six days, all on the
road. The best schedule? Try Portland. The Blazers have at least
two days between games twice each month, and once in May. And while
they play two sets of three-in-three, one of those is the Texas
three-step and the other is two home games with a short trip to
Vancouver in the middle . . . As for Rice, his situation with
Charlotte may be beyond repair. Agent David Falk already is
``suggesting'' that the Hornets trade Rice because they don't want
to pay him. Falk did the same thing a few years back with Mourning
and worked the deal with Miami, which saw Rice go to Charlotte.
Rice isn't even rehabbing in Charlotte; he's in Miami doing
childbirth duty in between elbow lifts. ``It's hard for us to
monitor his progress,'' Bass said. ``It'd be a lot easier if he was
here.'' There also was a deal with the Lakers that Rice apparently
didn't want, although we can't see the downside for him there. Can
Bass repair this thing? ``We're going to make every effort to do
it,'' Bass said. ``Am I confident that we can? I don't have an
answer to that. But we are going to make the effort.'' Commissioner
David Stern even weighed in on the situation. ``If I could give
some advice to Glen, I would say he should worry about healing,''
the commissioner said. ``This whole notion of a player or his agent
shopping what an owner will or will not do in order to put pressure
on an owner to either make the trade or sign the contract is
ultimately destructive either to the team or the player.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Early returns on the first set of three-in-threes? Not good.
Atlanta, Detroit, and Miami all lost playing their third game in
three nights. The Hawks probably looked the worst, scoring 69
points against the Nets while shooting 29.5 percent. Detroit lost
in Philadelphia but scored 86 points and shot 43.2 percent. Miami
was home against the Celtics, who, lest we forget, were themselves
playing their fourth game in five nights. Maybe the Heat would have
won had Riley figured out what was obvious to everyone else: Dan
Majerle can't guard Paul Pierce . . . Speaking of the Celtics'
offense, former Boston assistant and general man-about-town Don
Casey watched the Miami game and liked what he saw. ``I like what
they're doing a lot,'' he said. ``No one else moves the players
around like he does. It's something that the rest of the league
simply isn't used to seeing. Everyone talks about his defense, but
I like what he's doing at the other end.'' . . . The season is 10
days old and we already have a leader in the clubhouse for first
coach to be fired: Gregg Popovich of the Spurs. San Antonio made
some quality additions, got Sean Elliott back, and is still
struggling (there was a bad loss at home to the Lakers). Why San
Antonio insists on starting Jaren Jackson is another head-scratcher
. . . What does this say about the NBA? Now that Hersey Hawkins's
streak of 461 consecutive starts has ended (he's been supplanted by
Billy Owens) and Michael Jordan has retired, the new leader for
consecutive starts is Seattle's Gary Payton, at 190. However, three
of the next four iron men are Kevin Garnett, Ray Allen, and Antoine
Walker, who among them have seven years of NBA experience. Walker
entered the season having started 136 straight games and is now at
140 and counting, good for fifth. Allen, who came in the same year,
began the season with 153 straight starts . . . Stern was asked if
this year's conference-oriented schedule might be instituted in
future seasons. That would mean perhaps sacrificing some
nonconference games (and opponents) for more games with rivals.
Could he envision such a thing? ``I really can't,'' the commish
said. ``I think we like the interleague-play notion that we have. I
think that we, at least in the short run, plan to continue that and
not to take that single game away from our fans.'' . . . The
Celtics used the occasion of Valentine's Day to send out reminders
to former season ticket-holders. According to one, Doug Tyrrell,
the message went thusly: ``Roses are red, sugar is sweet, we can't
wait to see you back in your seat.'' It had no impact on Tyrrell.
``I was quite choked up, but I'm not coming back to my seat,'' he
said. ``I'm canceling my season tickets, which I have had since
1981, because it hasn't been the same since they moved into the
FleetCenter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
