<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BARKLEY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Barkley out 3 to 4 weeks
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Charles Barkley was just playing too well not to have surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the league in rebounding and off to the second-best
individual rebounding start ever in the NBA, Barkley could not
allow his injured left knee to bring his play back toward last
season's frustrating limp. Too much more had become possible to
risk that.
</P>
<P>
   When his knee discomfort at Saturday's practice became
unbearable and his play unacceptable, Barkley called Rockets team
physician Dr. Bruce Moseley to Westside Tennis Club, and after an
examination of the partially torn medial meniscus in Barkley's left
knee, arthroscopic surgery was scheduled for 3 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to miss three to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to do it now than wait until later,'' Barkley
said. ``We have a grueling schedule coming up. We play seven games
in nine (actually 10) days. If I didn't do this, it was only going
to get worse. I made the mistake last year with the hernia, not
getting it done when I should have. I don't want to make the same
mistake twice.''
</P>
<P>
   Through five games, possibly all played with the knee injury,
Barkley has averaged 19.2 points, four assists and a league-best 17
rebounds. His five consecutive games with at least 15 rebounds to
start the season is second in NBA history only to Wilt
Chamberlain's 11-game streak to begin the 1970 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always frustrating when you get hurt,'' Barkley, 35, said
of the interruption to his rapid start. ``There's no such thing as
minor surgery, unless they're doing it on somebody else. It's not a
major, major deal that will hinder me in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to stay optimistic. Life is about ups and downs. I can
either walk around miserable about it or I can keep a stiff upper
lip. This is just a small obstacle for me. I put too much time into
this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Moseley said the work Barkley put in to prepare for the season,
besides showing in his play, will help him rehabilitate and remain
strong when he returns. Barkley has added daily workouts with
Scottie Pippen and his trainer Tim Grover, including one before
Saturday's practice, and can resume as soon as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The swelling hasn't really gone up, but now when he runs up
and down the court, he feels it,'' Moseley said. ``If it's not
going to have any symptoms, we can watch it. But if it's going to
have symptoms, it needs to be taken care of.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the nice things about small cartilage tears.
For the first day or so, he'll have to take it easy. But then, he
can start to rehab, to push hard without worrying about tearing
anything else. He can be as quickly as Monday morning on the
exercise bike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think (three to four weeks) is a very reasonable time
estimation. But it's one of those deals as soon as he feels
comfortable on the court again he could be back. Charles is in
great shape. We don't intend for him to lose any of that. The
stronger you start, the more strength you keep and the more quickly
you get your strength back. With that being the case, we're going
to push this thing hard and go as fast as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich: ``He'll be in good shape.
He'll take care of his body. He's been doing real well. I just feel
he's going to have a good recovery. That's just a gut feeling. It's
not a medical feeling. It's just a feeling with the way he was
working.''
</P>
<P>
   But instead of using the few days off to prepare for a grueling
stretch of nine games in 13 days that begins Tuesday against the
Suns, the Rockets will have to use a good deal of their time to
adjust to the loss of Barkley. Othella Harrington could be the
choice to replace Barkley in the starting lineup, but Tomjanovich
could prefer to keep Harrington in his current role to maintain the
energy lift he has provided off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich said he hasn't decided about the lineup change
Barkley's injury requires. But as well as Harrington has played,
Barkley's loss is certain to be felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's tough, especially with the way he has been playing,''
Rockets center Hakeem Olajuwon said. ``He has been a major factor
for our success. As the coach was saying before the season, we're
going to face adversity and we have to respond to that. Everybody
has to respond to the situation and grow closer to compensate.
</P>
<P>
   ``To lose a player like Charles Barkley, obviously that's going
to have an impact on the team. But to have a championship
character, you have to respond and compensate to keep it going
until he gets back.''
</P>
<P>
   But it would have been worse, Barkley said, to allow his game to
deteriorate while time passed in which he could have repaired the
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been bothering me,'' Barkley said before leaving for Las
Vegas to attend the Oscar De La Hoya-Ike Quartey fight. ``I've been
having a hard time. But we're going to do the surgery. It's
unfortunate that I have to miss games, because my only goal really
was to play in every game. The problem really was my other leg was
getting sore from overcompensating, which always happens. They
didn't want me to take any chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get it done and go forward. I never complain
about missing games. People have more serious problems than that.
But these guys can keep it together. This is a fun team to play on.
They'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   So will Barkley, something he could not say a year ago when he
played unhappily with pain. Having seen the way things could be for
the past week, sacrificing three weeks seemed an easy choice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
