<DOCNO> NYT19990213.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4743 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-DAYTONA-STEWART-H     02-13 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DAYTONA-STEWART-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Learning process begins for rookie Stewart
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Starting up front in the Daytona 500 is one
thing; finishing up front is something else.
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be the message most of the drivers have for rookie
Tony Stewart, who is the first person since Houston's A.J. Foyt to
start on the front row for both the Daytona 500 and the
Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   When the green flag waves today for the start of the 41st
Daytona 500, Stewart will be side-by-side with pole-sitter Jeff
Gordon, a man he raced against as a teen-ager on short tracks in
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the icon of the series,'' Stewart said of Gordon. ``But
the thing I remember about him is he helped me get one of my first
good midget rides years ago. I didn't even know Jeff and he did
that on his own. It shows the type of person he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Both drivers are 27, but Gordon has six years of experience in
Winston Cup racing, including three championships in the last four
years. Stewart, a former Indy Racing League champion, is learning
the ropes in NASCAR's premiere series after spending last year
splitting his time between the IRL and the Busch Grand National
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew a long time ago that Tony was going to be a great
race-car driver,'' Gordon said. ``We've had similar paths, and it's
great to see him here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I told Tony I got schooled quite a bit when I was a rookie
in 1993. I told him he's going to learn a lot. I think Dale
(Earnhardt) is going to be schooling him some at the start of this
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt gave Stewart a few lessons Thursday in one of the Twin
125 qualifying races. Earnhardt won the race by moving past
Stewart, but Earnhardt believed Stewart was using some dangerous
tactics to try to block Earnhardt and a line of cars from moving to
the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a mirror-driving son of a gun,'' Earnhardt said of
Stewart. ``He was holding me up a bit, and if your car is not
strong enough you just can't do that. He forced me down on the
apron on the backstretch. If that had been the last lap of the
Daytona 500, he would have found himself spinning around in
circles. But he has a good car and he'll learn.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Earnhardt will start on the outside of Row 2
today, directly behind Stewart. Bobby Labonte, Stewart's teammate,
will start on the inside of Row 2 behind Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony did a good job of staying out of trouble in the
qualifying race,'' Labonte said. ``He fell back to ninth, then
moved back up to sixth. That's what he needed to do. We know we
will be racing close together at the start Sunday and we'll try to
team up as much as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said he had no intentions of taking any chances in the
qualifier since he knew his starting spot was assured.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a chance for me to focus on learning,'' Stewart said.
``I didn't have to stick my nose in a place where I might end up in
the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get ganged up on like I did Thursday, all you can do
is look for the first available hole and try to slip back in line.
I learned a lot, but I'm not going to say what I learned because I
don't want these other guys to know. And Bobby makes sure I know
everything I need to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte said the other drivers already have learned that Stewart
has what it takes to push his car to the limit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people knew Tony had talent,'' Labonte said. ``But I
think they were surprised to see what he did in qualifying.''
</P>
<P>
   One person who wasn't surprised was Joe Gibbs, who hired Stewart
last season and gave him a year on the Busch circuit before making
him Labonte's teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any limit on Tony,'' Gibbs said. ``Of
course, he has some things he has to learn, but the guy is a racer.
He's going to be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Gibbs already had one top driver in Labonte, who proved last
year that he is a contender for a Winston Cup title. But it remains
to be seen how the multicar setup will affect him.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that Labonte wasn't keen on the idea of having a
rookie teammate, but he insists he no longer feels that way after
working with Stewart over the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Labonte, Bobby's older brother, still thinks Bobby will
suffer initially by having Stewart on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new team brings down the first team,'' Terry said. ``Nothing
against Tony, but I think it will be hard for Bobby to have as much
success as he had last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart earned a reputation in the IRL of being a bit of a
hothead who sometimes pushed his car beyond its limits. But he has
been humble and unassuming the last two weeks at Daytona, saying he
plans to take a more conservative approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to take this race, and this season, as a time to learn
everything I can,'' Stewart said. ``In this race, I want to gain as
much knowledge as possible and stay out of trouble. I don't want to
be the guy that starts a 20-car pileup. You are going to see me be
real patient out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart could have stayed in open-wheel racing and had a
successful career, but he said he wanted to challenge himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt all along this is the right decision for me because I
wanted to be in the No. 1 racing series in the world,'' Stewart
said. ``But I wanted to make sure I had the right pieces in place
before I did it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
