<HEADER>
A4776 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-RIENDEAU     02-13 1857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-RIENDEAU-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIENDEAU IN RUSSIA, AND TENDS TO LIKE IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henry David Thoreau went to the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Cousin Vinny Riendeau went to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? Because I've always thought of this as a magical place,''
said the former Bruins netminder, reached Friday by telephone in
Togliatti, some 600 miles west of Moscow. ``And the truth is, it is
magical.''
</P>
<P>
   Riendeau, 32, played his last game with the Bruins, and his last
in the NHL, in the 1994-95 season. In the last three-plus seasons,
he has played for two clubs in Germany, one Switzerland, another in
Winnipeg (IHL), and he began this season playing in Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Ayr, the only team in Scotland,'' he said. ``I guess you
could say I'm a traveling man.''
</P>
<P>
   Riendeau's Quebec-based agent, Alain Tanguay, called him a
couple of weeks ago, asking if he knew of a goalie who would like
to play in Russia. Riendeau initially said no, only to reconsider
when he began to blend some childhood memories with his own spirit
of adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remembered back to '72, when I was a boy in school,'' he
said. ``Canada played Russia, and it was such a big deal. They
stopped school for us to watch it. Right from then, I was always
interested in the Russian players. I was amazed at the skills the
Russians had. There was just something magical about them, how they
played.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon suiting up in Togliatti, for a club sponsored by the
automaker Lata, Riendeau became the first North American-born
ex-NHLer ever to play in the top Russian League. He has played in
two games, won both (4-1, 9-0) and expects to stay in net through
at least one round of the playoffs. Togliatti ranks sixth in the
22-team league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a kid again,'' said Riendeau. ``It's total hockey;
I am at the rink all day. We have two hours at the rink in the
morning, running and lifting weights, and then two hours on the ice
each night. If I was 19 years old, thinking about doing this for 10
years, I might not feel the same about the whole thing. I might not
like that. But the day goes fast. I come back at night after
practice, eat, make calls, and that's about it. It's lonely. It was
lonely last year in Lugano, too. But, it's not like you are going
off to war, not knowing if you're ever coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll be back in Quebec in the spring, reunited with his wife
and three children (all adopted from Acapulco). Next year, he might
return to Europe; a couple of German clubs have inquired about his
services. He's not looking at Russia as some great steppingstone,
just a stop along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where it leads, I can't predict,'' he said. ``I did it for the
experience, that's all. I like to do that, try something that I
never would have experienced otherwise. Just a once-in-a-lifetime
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the experience is strange. A few teammates speak some
basic English, and he can communicate in broken German with his
coach. Otherwise, he spends much of his time in silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy's in the room, yelling or bitching, I've got no idea
what he's saying,'' said Riendeau. ``I don't read Russian, so I
don't know if the papers are saying good things or bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Does his team have a nickname?
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't tell you,'' said Riendeau. ``How would I know?
Everything's in Russian.''
</P>
<P>
   What he knows is what he sees. He sees magic. He sees everything
he expected and more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions are not great in Russia,'' he said. ``For me,
it's fine. I see the hotel and the arena. But for many people it's
a hard life here, and for them, hockey is special. It's special for
the kids, the fans, the players. You see it in their eyes. It's the
chance for a kid to dream of a better life. If you are successful
in sport and hockey, it's a better life. For a lot of people, it's
a chance to get out of a difficult country. When they are at the
rink, their eyes are big.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Travel section in last Sunday's Globe carried word that a
new cruise ship, Voyager of the Seas, will include a
240-square-foot skating rink, used for passenger skating and ice
shows. That's roughly the size of the neutral zone, right? Wonder
what happens if (1) A ship with a neutral-zone trap sails through
the Bermuda Triangle; (2) Jacques Lemaire just happens to be on
board. Personally, I'd take my chances on the good ship Titanic
Redux, thank you . . . Pavel Bure's new deal, agreed to last week
in Florida, could bring him another $11 million if it is stretched
to a sixth season (2004-05), grossing a total of $58 million. Sets
the bar pretty high for some of this summer's big Group 2
(high-compensation) free agents: Eric Lindros, Paul Kariya, and
Peter Forsberg. The trailer on the play is Ottawa's Alexei Yashin,
who will make $3.3 million next season, the final year of a
five-year pact . . . Rocket Richard was in Molson Centre last
Saturday night to show the Montreal crowd the new trophy in his
name, which will be awarded annually to the league's top goal
scorer. The Rocket, now 77, has shown some renewed pep after coming
down with abdominal cancer last year . . . The old Montreal Forum,
at the corner of Ste. Catherine and Atwater Streets, is still being
converted into a multimedia complex that will include 30 movie
screens, arcades, and an interactive hockey exhibit. Construction
workers say that each night, shortly after 10 p.m., a ghost bangs
aimlessly around the debris, muttering, ``Too many men, too many
men . . .'' . . . Now that he's cracked 400 wins, Avalanche
netminder Patrick Roy can take aim on Glenn Hall (407) for the No.
4 spot in career wins. The others ahead of St. Patrick: Terry
Sawchuk (447), Jacques Plante (434), and Tony Esposito (423).
Colorado defenseman Sylvain Lefebvre equates 400 victories for a
netminder to 600 goals for a forward. It's close, but 10 players
have cracked 600, including Mark Messier this season . . . Fred
Cusick appears to be headed back to the broadcast booth, to be
joined by ex-Bruin defenseman Brad Park. If the deal gets done this
week, the duo will handle nine of the Lowell Lock Monsters AHL
broadcasts on Media One, the cable outlet that serves the Merrimack
Valley and parts of Cape Cod. Another ex-Bruin, Brian Propp,
recently joined the Flyers' broadcast team. At least two other
former Bruins, Peter McNab (Avalanche) and Charlie Simmer (Coyotes)
also work the mike, not to mention Phil Esposito handling
anchor-desk duties for Fox. Locally, of course, four more ex-Bruins
_ Bob Beers and John Bucyk (WBZ radio), Gord Kluzak (NESN), and
Andy Brickley (Channel 38) _ have traded spots on the bench for
seats in the broadcast booth . . . Lightning owner Art Williams has
found the sea of red ink too deep for his liking and is looking for
a partner to buy up to 49 percent of the Bolts. He says he has two
candidates, one with prior NHL ownership experience (is that you
again, Richard Gordon?). Meanwhile, Alexandre Daigle's new deal in
Tampa calls for a base of about $1 million, with incentives that
would almost double it . . . The holes in his defensive game aside,
Calgary defenseman Phil Housley went into weekend action in need of
only five goals to reach 300. Only three other blue liners have hit
the plateau: Paul Coffey, Ray Bourque, and Denis Potvin . . . That
one-year deal Steve Smith signed to come back with the Flames this
season has a no-trade clause. He says he won't go anywhere.
Translation: If someone wants to acquire him and add another year
at $1 million or more, perhaps he'd listen.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad farewell for Ron Francis at Maple Leaf Gardens
Wednesday night. Flanked by Gary Roberts and Sami Kapanen, the
veteran pivot, who grew up in Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario, popped in
two goals and three assists in the Hurricanes' 6-5 win over the
Leafs. The Leafs played their final game in the Gardens Saturday
night _ vs. the sad sack Blackhawks _ and open their new Air Canada
Centre Saturday against the Habs. Leafs goalie Curtis Joseph wore a
special mask, one painted with a picture of the Gardens, for the
occasion. He planned to wear it only Saturday night . . . Hockey's
World Championships, the annual spring vacation for NHLers not in
the Stanley Cup hunt, will be in Oslo this spring and St.
Petersburg (ex-Soviet Union) the following April. But the IIHF is
expected to slot the 2001 tournament for February, a move that all
but prohibits NHL participation _ unless clubs want to furlough
their minor leaguers. If the February format is adopted, look for
the World Championships not to be held in 2002, when the Olympics
take center stage that month . . . Randy Cunneyworth's goal for the
Sabres Thursday night, in a 5-2 pasting of the Habs, was his first
in a Buffalo uniform since Nov. 15, 1981, the longest such drought
(he's been elsewhere, folks) in NHL history . . . Lemaire, soon
after he was hired in Montreal as GM Rejean Houle's top aide, said
he was interested in moving into the top job. ``I see all the paper
on Rejean's desk and it reminds me of Serge Savard's desk when he
was GM,'' said Lemaire. ``I'm not one for paperwork.'' As the Habs
continue their freefall, however, Houle looks destined for the
heave-ho. If Lemaire can't hack the paper weight, maybe the Habs
will split the job, leaving Lemaire the most important work _
deciding who can play _ and letting someone else battle it out with
agents . . . Wendel Clark's offensive touch has all but disappeared
in Tampa, but his name will get hot around the March 23 trading
deadline. One rumor had the Sabres' Matthew Barnaby, who has
requested a trade, heading to the Bolts, but word around Tampa is
that there have been no inquiries from western New York. Detroit
and St. Louis are expected to take a run at the 32-year-old left
wing . . . Alexei Zhamnov is in the Dirk Graham doghouse in
Chicago, after being benched last Saturday in Phoenix and then
coming down with a bad back two days later in practice. There won't
be many suitors, but possible landing spots are the Rangers or
Maple Leafs, both of whom can use legitimate scoring depth and can
afford to pay him $3 million for each of the next two seasons. Look
for the Hawks to deal Chris Chelios, possibly to the Flyers for
20-year-old wing Dainius Zubrus. It won't be a popular move, but
it's rare that a club can cash in a 37-year-old warhorse for a
youngster with true upside. Here in Boston that would be like
sending Bourque to the Red Wings for, say, Mathieu Dandenault (23)
and Tomas Holmstrom (26) _ terribly unsavory but tantalizing . . .
Ex-Oiler backup Fred Brathwaite was in the Flames' net last week
for a 3-2 win over his old teammates. Last summer, torn between two
offers (Europe or the Canadian national squad), Brathwaite phoned
Oiler boss Glen Sather and asked for advice. Forget Europe, said
Sather, because it would take the hard-working goalie out of the
loop. Brathwaite stayed with Team Maple Leaf and, sure enough, got
his shot with the Flames amid all their netminding injuries. Great
counseling by Sather, even if it did take 2 points out of his
pocket.
</P>
</TEXT>
