<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMM HAPPY TO TAKE THE STAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE -- The queen of U.S. women's soccer is much more than
her charming good looks, endorsement appeal or her witty sense of
humor -- she also happens to be the world's best player, too.
</P>
<P>
   Mia Hamm not only carries the future of U.S. women's soccer on
her shoulders, she carries the torch throughout the world as well.
</P>
<P>
   So when the four-time U.S. player of the year was given the
microphone in front of a room of reporters before Saturday's final
press conference promoting today's match pitting the U.S. National
team against the FIFA World All-Stars at San Jose's Spartan Stadium
beginning at 5 p.m. -- she was ready to make a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In short, when the FIFA women's World Cup begins this summer in
the United States and ends July 10 in the final at the Rose Bowl,
Hamm is hoping women's soccer will leave a legacy and pave the way
for many more little Hamm's to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Today's game, coupled with the World Cup draw at halftime, is
just the beginning of this event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on a stage now where I think we always should have
been,'' Hamm said of the World Cup. ``We're getting the respect
that we deserve. No longer is the World Cup a tournament, it is an
event. It is an event to showcase the best players in the world and
I think you have that here today.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamm, playing the ambassador role well, said it's time to give
women's soccer the support it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the players have invested their time and now I think
it's time for you the media to make this a breakthrough event,''
Hamm said. ``Let's do what's right and make this (world cup) an
opportunity of a lifetime for others who have dreamed like we
have.''
</P>
<P>
   At the half of today's game, a stage will be assembled at
midfield to announce the final draw which will place all 16
qualifying countries into groups of four. It will also determine
first round opponents and the cities and stadiums in which they
will play.
</P>
<P>
   China, Germany, Norway (1995 World cup champion) and the U.S.
have been chosen as the top seeds and will head the four groups.
The remaining 12 teams will be placed into three ``pots as
determined by FIFA criteria.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any team none of the four seeds want to draw in
their group it is the improving Brazillian team. It is already
believed whoever draws Brazil will be dubbed the group of death.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. defender Bradi Chastain, however, said she doesn't care how
this chips fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lotto, hopefully we will come out winners,'' she said.
``To make it to the final you have to play the best teams in the
world. If we have to play Brazil in our own bracket, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time a women's all-star team has ever been
assembled. On the surface, it seems like nothing more than a
friendly, but it has become spirited the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   The FIFA team is made up of one player from each of the 16
qualifying teams and a few others from other countries. With the
U.S. team recognized as the top team in the World, the all-stars
don't want to be upstaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are highly motivated,'' said Graziele of Brazil. ``Every
girl on this team would like to beat the United States. It's a
dream for all of us to be here, but to beat them would be something
special because a lot of us won't have much of a chance when the
tournament starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain shook her head when someone asked if the game will
represent a typical unorganized all-star affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the Pro Bowl, this isn't where guys have gone
through their whole season and now they're on the beach having a
few mai tai's before the game,'' Chastain said. ``This is a very
competitive game and a chance for us to sharpen our skills. I can
guarantee, it's going to be competitive. The fans deserve a
competitive game and we're going to give them one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
