<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' PLAYERS YAWN OVER RODMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Lakers got a glimpse of their potential future
Saturday: Reporters swarming around, peppering players with
questions about a guy who was nowhere near the premises.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly as it might be if Dennis Rodman indeed joins the team
and sticks with old habits _ namely skipping practices while
teammates deal with the distraction of explaining his absence.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman, according to some media reports, has decided to join the
Lakers. But a team spokesman said no deal has been signed, and
there hasn't been a peep out of Rodman or his fleet of agents.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-dressing former Chicago Bull has been mulling whether
to accept Lakers owner Jerry Buss' offer to play for the veterans'
minimum salary, $610,000 for the shortened season. Buss himself
said recently he thought it was ``doubtful'' Rodman, who earned $18
million over the last two seasons, would play for that relatively
small sum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have mentioned many times that we wanted him, I think it's
up to him. I think the situation is very close,'' said Shaquille
O'Neal, a former Rodman critic who now advocates acquiring the
seven-time rebounding champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays with a lot of determination,'' O'Neal said. ``He does
what he does well. He plays good defense and he rebounds the ball
well. . . . I'm not really concerned with what he does off the
court.''
</P>
<P>
   But is Rodman coming? No one wearing purple and gold seemed to
know or be particularly concerned about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There ain't no telling about him. He might be doing this just
to keep his name alive,'' said Lakers forward Robert Horry, who
added that Rodman hasn't been much on players' minds. ``I don't
think it really matters to us. It matters to the media, because the
media wants to know what he's going to do. To us, we don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowtime: That plodding, methodical team that appears to be
masquerading as the Lakers is, alas, the Lakers, sans ``Showtime''
pyrotechnics. Through five games, the Lakers are averaging a paltry
89.6 points, 20th in the NBA, and about 17 points below last year's
league-leading average.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is the running game, which is nearly nonexistent.
So far the Lakers are scoring just 5.2 points per game off the fast
break, a decidedly un-Lakerlike statistic.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is conditioning after a shortened training
camp and exhibition schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would still be in preseason, normally, and we just don't
have the habits yet,'' coach Del Harris said. ``Running is a hard
thing. That's why very few teams really have much of a running
game. It takes a lot of work and a lot of coaching, a lot of timing
and a total commitment on the part of the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Horry said teams are anticipating the fast breaks and setting up
quickly, but he also admitted players' tendency to go the less
strenuous route.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got such a good set-up game with Shaq that sometimes you
figure, hell, why should we push it? We'll just post the big fella
up and get easy baskets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
