A4781 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SKATING-MEN-HNS &LR;      02-13 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SKATING-MEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Given an opening, Weiss gains men's skating title
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SALT LAKE CITY _ In other years, he often as not found himself
skating for second place, lost in the shadow of a more celebrated
rival.
</P>
<P>
   This was different, and cast in the favorite's role, Michael
Weiss was ready to move up the chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been close to it the last couple of years,'' the
22-year-old Fairfax, Va., native said after winning his first
United States Figure Skating Association title Saturday afternoon
at the Delta Center. ``It feels great to be the champion of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put in a lot of hard work. Now, I can go out and
celebrate and have a pizza tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, who finished second to Todd Eldredge the past two years,
becomes the top U.S. hope heading into next month's world
championships in Helsinki, Finland. He is joined on the world team
by Trifun Zivanovic, 23, from Los Angeles, and Timothy Goebel, 18,
of Rolling Meadows, Ill., who placed second and third.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, though, it was a competition that called more for
pepperoni than caviar.
</P>
<P>
   If there was the expectation for something sensational, it did
not materialize. Weiss, the heavy favorite after Eldredge chose not
to compete, fell on his first jump (a quad toe), but recovered to
land eight triples and earned four 5.9s on his artistic line from
the nine-judge panel.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a surprise, it was Zivanovic, who never had
finished better than seventh in two previous senior nationals. Not
only was he a solid second here, but he was placed first by judge
Janet McLeod of Norwalk, Calif. (Weiss got the other eight No. 1s.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Uplifting, one of the greatest feelings in my whole life,'' he
said after getting a standing ovation from the crowd of
approximately 4,220. ``A dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was controversy, meanwhile, it was over the bronze
medal, where Goebel barely edged Matthew Savoie of Peoria, Ill.,
getting five No. 3 placements to four for Savoie (who also got a
second and a fifth).
</P>
<P>
   Goebel fell twice and had to throw in a triple axel late in his
program to make up for an earlier miss. In a close call, he might
have gotten the edge for the final spot on the world team as the
first American man to land a quadruple jump in competition and a
consensus better prospect for down the road.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
