<HEADER>
A4789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-SABRES-     02-13 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-SABRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS TIE SABRES, 2-2  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ For Tommy Salo, it was an opportunity, one that
he never could have expected to see again as an Islander.
</P>
<P>
   The trade that brought Felix Potvin to New York supposedly
sealed Salo's departure. Salo was not traded, as he anticipated
when the deal for Potvin was made, but he was relegated to fill-in
duty, starting just five games since the Jan. 9 deal. And when
Potvin suffered a strained groin on Friday night, the door opened
for Salo again.
</P>
<P>
   The injury to Potvin gave Salo an opportunity, for whatever it
is worth, to play for what could be a five-game stretch. In the
first game of that span, Salo was solid Saturday night, stopping 24
shots and matching Buffalo's Dominik Hasek, acrobatic save for
acrobatic save. He was good enough to earn the Islanders a 2-2 tie
with the Sabres at Marine Midland Arena. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't easy, as Salo faced repeated threats late in the game
and the Islanders had to kill a two-minute hooking penalty on
Zigmund Palffy beginning with 2 minutes 7 seconds remaining in the
overtime session. With just 40 seconds left in regulation, Miroslav
Satan charged to the net and fired a shot from close range, but
Salo deflected the puck, sending it safely over the net. Aleksei
Zhitnik fired a blast from the right circle with 30 seconds left in
overtime that Salo knocked away, and then Salo smothered a rebound
attempt by Michael Peca.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders trailed by 2-1 entering the final period, but they
pulled even when Mariusz Czerkawski carried the puck into the
Sabres' zone along the left side, faked once, then fired a shot
from the left circle that beat Hasek to the near post at 5:41 of
the period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders fell behind at 6:18 of the first period when Satan
scored his 23rd goal of the season on a nice feed from Derek
Plante. But two minutes later, after Palffy was sent off for a
four-minute high-sticking penalty, the Islanders evened the score
with a short-handed goal when Robert Reichel swiped the puck from
Darryl Shannon just inside the Buffalo blue line and charged in
alone against Hasek. Reichel carried the puck all the way to the
net, faking and then slipping a backhand around the glove of Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   In the first period, the Islanders stymied the Sabres for six
minutes while playing a man down. Salo had a lot to do with that,
making a spectacular save on a point-blank shot by Michal Grosek.
</P>
<P>
   But Salo's failure to clear the puck early in the second period
put the Islanders back in a hole. He tried to send the puck around
the boards, but it was kept in by Randy Cunneyworth, who fed the
former Islander Paul Kruse. Kruse beat Salo to his glove side, his
second goal of the season and second in the last two games, and the
Sabres led by 2-1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Kruse left New York in a trade for Jason Dawe on March 24,
1998, he was critical of Mike Milbury, then the Islanders' coach
and general manager. With Milbury serving as just the general
manager now, Kruse still was critical. He was quoted in The Buffalo
News Saturday as saying: ``Mike is a hard guy to understand. I
didn't understand him too well. I don't know if he did what he had
to do. The guys didn't really have any direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Kruse went on: ``It was very negative around the rink all the
time. There were trade rumors every day. It was hard showing up at
the rink, listening to the press, and hearing what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems likely that negative thoughts have floated through
Salo's mind since the trade that brought Potvin to the Islanders.
The job is Salo's for now, with Potvin's struggles taking a turn
for the worse on Friday night. In dropping his record to 1-6-1
since joining the Islanders, Potvin suffered a groin strain late in
the 2-1 loss to the Nashville Predators, and it will sideline him
for 7 to 10 days. Wade Flaherty was called up from Lowell and
joined the team Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were taking a shot from the boards in the third period,''
Potvin said of Friday night's game. ``I kicked my leg out to stop
it and the puck got tipped before it came to me, and I kind of
twisted. It was hurting. It wasn't too bad when the game was going.
When I was going down it was hurting, but I was trying to stay in
the game. This is the first time it ever happened to me. During the
game, I wasn't too sure if it was bad or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Potvin should have assumed that it would be, as most things have
been for him since he joined the Islanders on Jan. 9. Embroiled in
controversy since the team has been unable to trade Salo, the
incumbent goaltender, Potvin has been singed for a 3.86 goals
against average. ``They say bad things make you stronger,'' Potvin
said. ``They told me 7 to 10 days, but we'll go for seven and make
sure it feels good when I come back. There is no doubt that it's
not what I was hoping for, coming back. It makes it harder, but
again, you can't get down on yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to work and eventually it's going to come back to
normal. I'll keep working hard. I feel like it will come back. I
feel like I'm making some good saves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 2306EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
