<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BC-RUTGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTGERS BEATS BOSTON COLLEGE, 75-62  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ Rutgers has talked about earning a berth in
the National Collegiate Athletic Association tournament for its
seniors, Geoff Billet and Rob Hodgson. Saturday night, the Scarlet
Knights' underclassmen's actions spoke louder than words.
</P>
<P>
   While Billet and Hodgson played minor roles in the 75-62 victory
over Boston College, the sophomore Jeff Greer and his young
teammates turned ferocious. Rutgers shot 69 percent in the second
half, blasting through B.C.'s wilting defense. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Scarlet Knights opened the second half with a 15-4 burst to
turn a 10-point halftime deficit into a 37-36 lead after a tip-in
by Dahntay Jones, a freshman guard whose energetic play resulted in
8 points in the game and a shift in momentum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Greer's turn. Swooping inside and showing a deft
touch outside, Greer scored 15 points in a six-minute span, hitting
all of his shots from the field, to build the lead to 53-44. He
finished with 21 points (making 4 of 6 on 3-point attempts) and a
game-high nine rebounds as Rutgers improved to 17-7 over all and
9-5 in the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College, which fell to 5-17 and 3-11, received 21 points
from Kenny Walls, who went 5 of 8 on 3-pointers. Michael Cotton
added 18 points. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joel Salvi, the Rutgers freshman center who had 10 points and
six rebounds in 16 inspired minutes, hit two free throws, and
Rashod Kent, the freshman starting center who collected 16 points
and several crowd-pleasing floor burns, made a double-clutch layup
on a breakaway to increase the lead to 57-44. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With just under two minutes left, the Rutgers students began
chanting: ``We want UConn. We want UConn.'' Rutgers, riding a
three-game winning streak, will play the first-place Huskies in
Storrs, Conn., on Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Billet, who had 9 quiet points against B.C., and
Hodgson, who scored 7, can take heart that their less experienced
teammates might provide support to give Rutgers a realistic chance
at an upset against the Huskies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers already has its most victories since 1990-91, when it
earned its last tournament berth, and has beaten 12 opponents by
double digits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before a sellout crowd, the icy-shooting Knights struggled to
stay within double digits of the Eagles in the first half. They
trailed by 32-22 at halftime, reeling from 28 percent field-goal
shooting (8 of 29). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers' drive toward a post-season tournament is winning over
even more fans. More than 100 shivered in line 90 minutes before
game time to buy tickets returned by Boston College. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fans might have been wondering if it was worth the hardship
early on. Boston College, which had a three-game winning streak
snapped by Connecticut on Wednesday, launched an 8-0 run capped by
Kenny Walls' 3-pointer to give B.C. a 21-13 lead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jones' jumper in the lane closed the gap to 21-15, and a blocked
shot that looked more like a volleyball spike by Kent seemed to
give Rutgers momentum. But the Scarlet Knights threw up two clunky
shots and a poor alley-oop pass on three straight possessions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mostly unchallenged, Walls burned the Knights with consecutive
3-pointers to push B.C. ahead by 27-15. Walls' hot hand (4 of 6
from 3-point range) compensated for the absence of guard Kenny
Harley, the conference's best 3-point shooter at 47 percent, who
was suspended for fighting in the UConn game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers had managed just one field goal in nearly nine minutes,
but was down just 28-20 after Salvi's dunk with 2 minutes 35
seconds left. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All Rutgers could muster after that was two free throws by
Salvi. Meanwhile, Brian Bross and Willie Deane floated in jumpers
to give the Eagles a 10-point lead heading into the locker room. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-13-99 2309EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
