<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-HURRICANES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS BEAT HURRICANES, 6-4  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils committed several
transgressions Saturday night, such as the rare double of taking
two penalties in the same period for having too many men on the
ice. They also preoccupied themselves at times with taunting the
opposing bench rather than focusing on playing hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their lack of discipline _ which included Vadim
Sharifijanov's taking three penalties in a row and Randy McKay's
drawing a 10-minute misconduct for no reason _ the Devils ended a
four-game streak at home without a victory with a 6-4 triumph over
the Carolina Hurricanes at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Niedermayer, Krzysztof Oliwa, Brendan Morrison, Petr
Sykora, Jay Pandolfo and McKay scored the goals, in that order, for
the Devils (30-18-6), who ended their longest streak without a
victory at home since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the goals in the game, played before a crowd of 17,023,
came in the last three minutes on a night of sluggish and
undisciplined hockey by two teams that fancy themselves as
contenders for the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ranheim had two goals and Bates Battaglia and Ron Francis
one each for the Hurricanes (25-21-9) against Martin Brodeur, who
made 26 saves in his 46th appearance of the season. Brodeur ended a
three-game losing streak and improved his record to 24-16-6. Four
of his victories have come in four meetings with the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed after losing their three previous games at home, the
Devils started with enthusiasm Saturday night and forced the
Hurricanes into their zone from the opening face-off. The Devils
scored first, but they failed to sustain their attack and the
Hurricanes took the next six shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils took the lead twice in the first 5 minutes 16 seconds
on goals by Niedermayer and Oliwa, but the Hurricanes came back to
tie each time, despite playing without Keith Primeau, their captain
and leading scorer.
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer's goal came just 36 seconds after the opening
face-off on the first shot of the game, a blistering slap shot from
near the top of the right circle to the far upper corner of the
net. It was his sixth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Battaglia tied it at 1-1 just seconds after he stepped out of
the penalty box. He broke away alone and beat Brodeur with a simple
backhander for his third goal of the season, at 4:56.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils grabbed a 2-1 lead just 20 seconds later, when Oliwa
stepped in front of the crease on the left side and deflected Ken
Daneyko's shot from the left point past Trevor Kidd for his fifth
goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hurricanes tied it again, this time when Francis beat
Brodeur from the low slot after the Devils blew two chances to
clear the puck. The goal, at 10:06, was the 11th of the season for
Francis and gave him his 1,466th point, 2 short of passing Stan
Mikita for eighth place on the career scoring list.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison and Sykora gave the Devils a 4-2 lead in the second
period. Morrison's goal was his seventh of the season and his first
in nine games, while Sykora's came on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Ranheim narrowed the gap to 4-3 with 69 seconds left in the
second period. It was his sixth goal of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
