<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Feb. 21)  
(lb) 
 By SCOTT VEALE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A MOTHER'S PLACE: CHOOSING WORK AND FAMILY WITHOUT GUILT OR
BLAME &LR;  By Susan Chira. Harper Perennial, $13. Chira, the deputy
foreign editor of The New York Times, argues that parenting and
working are compatible and helpful to mothers and children, and
that day care is not harmful. In 1998 the Times reviewer Carol
Tavris said this ``splendid book ... makes an eloquent,
well-documented case that motherhood does not require martyrdom.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RIVEN ROCK &LR;  By T. Coraghessan Boyle. Penguin, $13.95. Stanley
McCormick is a rich schizoid who spends 20 years holed up in his
California mansion out of sight of women because he both loves and
hates them too much. That includes his wife, a scientist,
suffragist and lifelong virgin who remains loyal to her husband
through all his years of madness. Surprisingly, both characters in
this ambitious novel are based on actual early-20th-century
figures. In 1998 D.M. Thomas wrote that even though the prose
strayed toward the purple, ``the book is filled with good writing
and richly observed scenes; it has humanity and humor in
abundance.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAINTING BY NUMBERS: KOMAR AND MELAMID'S SCIENTIFIC GUIDE TO
ART &LR;  Edited by JoAnn Wypijewski. University of California, $24.95.
Noting the gap between a democratic culture and its elitist art
world, two mischievous Soviet exiles, Vitaly Komar and Alexander
Melamid, conducted opinion polls to find out what people prefer to
see in paintings, and then set out to give the public what it
wants. Their audacious project is ``funny, prickly, complex,
humane, dense with implications and a baited trap for ideologues
and hypocrites,'' Luc Sante wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANET'S MODERNISM: OR, THE FACE OF PAINTING IN THE 1860S &LR;  By
Michael Fried. University of Chicago, $35. This book explains the
pioneering quality of Manet's work, which was considered to be ugly
and obscure in its day. In 1996 Arthur C. Danto called this ``art
history of the highest originality and distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TURN, MAGIC WHEEL &LR;  By Dawn Powell. Steerforth, $14. In this
comic novel set in prewar New York, a young writer betrays a close
friend by publishing a book that trashes her former husband, a
famous novelist living abroad, and exposes her as sadly delusional
about her past. In 1936 in The New York Times Book Review, Edith H.
Walton called this ``a barbed and immensely entertaining satire on
a certain phase of New York's literary life.'' The same publisher
has reissued one of Powell's earlier novels,  &UR; DANCE NIGHT &LR;  ($14), a
love story about two sensitive teen-agers who dream of escaping
their working-class Ohio town, where all the social life takes
place at the local dance hall. ``Out of `Dance Night' emerge
unforgettably real people, drawn with an unerring instinct for
characterization,'' the Times Book Review said in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE OTHER SIDE OF THE RIVER: A STORY OF TWO TOWNS, A DEATH, AND
AMERICA'S DILEMMA &LR;  By Alex Kotlowitz. Anchor/Doubleday, $14.95. A
Wall Street Journal reporter probes the death of a black teen-ager
in Michigan, revealing a sharp divide between the local black and
white communities and a mystery full of contradictions. The result
is ``a chronicle of American racial attitudes seen through the
lenses of a signal event and a specimen landscape,'' Alec Wilkinson
wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT'S GOING ON: PERSONAL ESSAYS &LR;  By Nathan McCall. Vintage,
$11. This takes on such topical subjects as the African-American
middle class and the culture of pickup basketball. In 1997 the
reviewer Michael E. Ross found the terrain to be somewhat familiar,
but praised the author's ``moral authority.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JESUS SAVES &LR;  By Darcey Steinke. Grove, $12. The parallel
stories of two troubled girls _ a teen-ager abducted from summer
camp and a Lutheran minister's daughter with a seriously twisted
boyfriend _ give the author an opportunity to explore the
strip-mall culture and Gothic religious sensibility of the suburban
South. In 1997 Catherine Texier called this ``a consistently and
disturbingly beautiful'' novel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE VIEW FROM POMPEY'S HEAD &LR;  By Hamilton Basso. Louisiana State
University, $16.95. Anson Page is a young Wall Street lawyer
dispatched to his Southern hometown to solve a thorny business
crisis; revisiting his roots, he discovers he abandoned a part of
himself when he moved to the city. The reviewer John Brooks called
this ``the most pleasantly and sensibly romantic novel to come my
way in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HERMITS: THE INSIGHTS OF SOLITUDE &LR;  By Peter France. St.
Martin's Griffin, $13.95. The author finds much to admire in the
lives of famous hermits through the ages, notably their redemptive
spirit and formidable skills of discernment. In 1997 the reviewer
Carol Zaleski called this ``a gently understated affirmation of the
solitude for which many of us long.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SALT &LR;  By Earl Lovelace. Persea, $15. This Trinidadian novel
revolves around a spinner of folk tales who represents the island's
native values, and a teacher turned politician whose adherence to
European ideals consigns him to a life of disillusionment. In 1997
the reviewer William Ferguson praised the book's ``generous,
torrential prose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
