<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LEASE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO LEASE BACK SELLERS OF TEN LOSE CARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT KOSSAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glendale resident Robert Haran drove his truck to a Phoenix
leasing company, desperate for a $500 loan.
</P>
<P>
   After a flurry of paper signing, he drove out with money, daily
lease payments for the truck he no longer owned and, if the deal is
figured like a loan, an annual interest rate of nearly 260 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Haran, like thousands of Arizonans unable to get loans from
banks, credit unions, family or friends, is turning to a growing
state industry of sale/lease-back businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising in Valley newspapers and offering quick cash for car
titles, the sale/lease-back companies say they're meeting a market
need: They give money to people no one else will help.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer groups say the companies _ 65 statewide and 40 in
the Valley _ are preying on financially troubled people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to get out of debt by doing this and you get deeper,''
said Rosemary Shahan, president of a non-profit California consumer
group, CARS. ``It's like quicksand.''
</P>
<P>
   The deals are a license to steal people's cars, Shahan says.
</P>
<P>
   And the Arizona attorney general says one of the companies is
breaking state usury laws that protect the public from too-high
interest rates. If prosecutors win the case _ apparently the first
of its kind in Arizona _ it would be an ominous signal to the
industry. &QL; 
PRICE FOR BAD CREDIT
</P>
<P>
   But these companies do have their satisfied customers.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Peter Hackstedde was down and out, strapped for
cash &UR; and flat out of credit. And he had to pay off an income tax
debt. The 46-year-old stockbroker signed over title to his paid-off
1992 Volkswagen Cabriolet, at the time worth about $11,000.
Phoenix's SAL Leasing gave him $2,500. He then leased his car back
for $9 a day.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of two months he paid back the $2,500 to purchase his
car back _ plus $540 in lease payments _ or a 131 percent annual
interest fee, if calculated like a loan.
</P>
<P>
   Hackstedde said he went back twice again to SAL Leasing for
money and still has his car.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is they don't offer an alternative,'' Hackstedde
said. ``The little guy needs this. If you have bad credit it's the
price you have to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix attorney Ronald Meyer is defending SAL Leasing against
the attorney general's suit but is blunt about the service the
company is providing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a device, just like a pawnshop, to give people
liquidity,'' he said. ``The people who go through this process have
no credit. Granted, the interest rate is high. It's that or
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest rate sounds ominous, but it accurately reflects
the risk of the market. If you close that (market) off, the
individuals will simply move on to something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said it's time the state recognized the need and regulated
the high-risk loan business.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyist Kevin DeMenna said opposition to making high-risk
car-title loans legal ``limits consumer choice under the mantle of
consumer protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, DeMenna unsuccessfully pushed a bill for an
out-of-state car-title loan company that would have raised the
state's legal interest rate on small loans to 300 percent for
car-title loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we fail to understand is a demographic element exists
between no credit and extensive credit,'' DeMenna said. ``The point
is real simple: These individuals who have title to their vehicle
have some element of creditworthiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Hugh Hegyi, along with consumer
advocates, calls that reasoning ``ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all sorts of businesses advertising that they'll
give you a loan if you have no credit or bad credit _ and they'll
do it at a legal rate,'' said Hegyi. The legal high-risk,
high-interest finance companies charge about 29.9 percent, an
interest rate permitted by state law, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a very high interest rate,'' Hegyi said. ``And these
places are making money hand over fist.''
</P>
<P>
   These legal high-risk finance companies must also comply with
the state's Consumer Lending Act, and explain the loan to their
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with sale/lease back is also the whole deceptive
nature of what they do,'' said Todd Lang, Community Legal Services'
consumer attorney. Clients come into his office who never
understood their sale/lease back deals and are horrified that they
lost a car valued at $7,000 or $9,000 for a $1,500 loan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they pretend it's not a loan, they don't disclose
anything,'' Lang said about the sale/lease back companies. &QL; 
NOT ALL HAPPY STORIES
</P>
<P>
   The deal Haran struck cost him his truck.
</P>
<P>
   He got behind on the payments to SAL Leasing and late fees
mounted. According to Haran's contract, once a payment was three
days late a $25 fee was assessed and his lease payments nearly
doubled.
</P>
<P>
   Haran suddenly found himself faced with swelling debt, no way to
pay it back, no way to repurchase his truck and a threatening
letter from the company demanding his 1994 truck and telling him it
had already been reported stolen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a dam broke,'' said Haran, who now drives a 1988
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I didn't read it thoroughly enough. Maybe I should have
taken the papers home. They tell you to do that,'' said Haran, 47,
a Marine veteran of the Vietnam War and Legislative District 17's
Republican chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it should be legal. If you're going to advertise
as a loan, make it a loan. I wish I never went down there.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure how many people lose their cars in
sale/lease-back deals. The attorney general's research into one
company shows about one out of seven customers loses the car. &QL; 
LOAN OR LEASE?
</P>
<P>
   Lending money on a vehicle title is not illegal _ as long as
lenders are licensed and charge less than 36 percent annual
interest. State law caps interest at 36 percent for one-time loans
under $10,000 and credit cards. It also applies to revolving loans
under $25,000 that are secured by home equity.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of the law is to make sure finance companies do not
take advantage of people who need money, Hegyi said.
</P>
<P>
   Sale/lease-back businesses get a higher return and attempt to
avoid usury laws by structuring their deals as leases, not loans,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deals are simple and require little more from the customer
than a paid-off car, a license, an extra car key and proof of an
address. Most are completed in an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The customer sells the car to the company for about 10 to 20
percent of its retail Blue Book value. The company keeps the title
it now owns.
</P>
<P>
   The customer leases back the car for a daily rate. If the
customer makes all the payments, he can buy back his car for the
original purchase price within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Lease payments are made twice a month and the customer is
responsible for maintaining liability insurance on the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The state Attorney General's Office calculated that the rate at
SAL Leasing ranged from $5 to $14 a day. If it is calculated as a
loan, the company charged an average of 214 percent annual interest
rate. &QL; 
CHANGES PROPOSED
</P>
<P>
   The high-risk, high-interest loan industry serves low-income
people with no credit or bad credit. Under Arizona's usury laws,
these finance companies must be licensed and keep their interest
rates within the legal 36 percent cap.
</P>
<P>
   Many finance companies want that interest cap to be removed, and
the idea has support at the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the proposed &UR; bill, to allow 300 percent interest on
car-title loans, passed the House before it was stopped by the
attorney general's complaints. This year, there are no specific
car-title loan bills, but at least two bills being considered by
lawmakers would remove interest limits on small loans.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, national consumer groups and some state
attorneys general have fought to preserve usury laws and stop the
spread of high interest title loans or similarly structured
sale/lease-back deals.
</P>
<P>
   Title loans are legal in about 25 states, but interest rates
companies are allowed to charge vary from 30 percent a year to 264
percent. They flourish, advocates say, only in states that permit
very high interest limits or have no usury laws and, therefore, no
cap on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They target people who are living hand to mouth, who are
financially vulnerable, and they know they're easy prey,'' said
CARS' Shahan.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Burkholder, an attorney and executive director of the
Consumer Law Center of the South, has been tracking the growth of
the legal car-title loan business, which she calls ``legalized
extortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Those in the car-title loan industry like to say they are
meeting a big need and taking a big risk, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the risk? There are two kinds of car-title loan
businesses: places that want to take your car _ they're hoping
you'll miss a payment _ and others who just want to keep you in
debt.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
