<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK'S STAND LEAVES HIM SITTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Coyotes'  &UR; Keith Tkachuk has been folded and
mutilated in front of the crease all year and decided enough was
enough in Saturday's 4-1 win over Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a two-minute instigating penalty, a five-minute
major for pummeling Colorado's  &UR; Sylvain Lefebvre and a 10-minute
misconduct. It sidelined him for all but four minutes of the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   It also wiped out the final 41 seconds of a Coyotes'
first-period power play chance, which would normally infuriate
Coach
 &UR; Jim Schoenfeld, who wasn't the least bit upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to make a stand sometimes,'' Schoenfeld said. ``He's
big and strong enough to take care of himself. He can't put himself
in a position to allow opposition players to take liberties with
him at the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does, No. 1, he can't play his game. No. 2, he'll be on
the injury shelf all the time because of the cross checks and other
nonsense that goes on there.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk was puzzled over the instigator and misconduct penalties
levied by referee  &UR; Don Koharski. The incident started after he was
cross checked several times on the back of his bare neck by
Lefebvre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when you go to the front of the net a lot of stuff
happens,'' said Tkachuk, who has had to play with broken ribs
acquired in net skirmishes. ``I've had too many injuries this year
by cross checks, especially my ribs, and I'm just sick of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld said the Coyotes will review the tape and likely
appeal the instigator penalty. Three instigator penalties means a
one game suspension. &QL; 
No foul
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes also weren't pleased with the two holding calls by
Koharski that gave Colorado a two-man advantage for 1:29 in the
final period with Phoenix ahead 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad call,'' said  &UR; Juha Ylonen, who was whistled for
holding behind the net for the first penalty. ``I knocked the guy
down in front of the net. He got up and we were digging for the
puck. He fell down on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   Just 31 seconds later, fellow Finn  &UR; Teppo Numminen joined Ylonen
in the sin bin for holding superstar  &UR; Peter Forsberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a weak call, but it happens when you're playing against
the best players,'' Numminen said. &QL; 
Staying focused
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes often follow big wins with lackluster efforts
against sub .500 teams, which means today's game with Anaheim,
which is 1-0-2 vs. Phoenix, could be testy.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we look past them?'' quizzed Tkachuk. ``Why would we?
We haven't beaten them this year. They have one of the best 1-2
punches in the league in  &UR; (Paul) Kariya and  &UR; (Teemu) Selanne and
are a solid team. We have to prove something to them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
