</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GAME OF ARENA CHICKEN WITH HOCKEY ON THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two basic tenets about sports franchises:
</P>
<P>
   You never know how much you want them until they leave. And once
they're gone, it costs twice as much to get them back.
</P>
<P>
   That in mind, what to make of Richard Burke's ``Plan B''? A
revelation from the Coyotes' owner that the only alternative to an
unsuccessful referendum is taking his hockey team to another state?
</P>
<P>
   Or of his Saturday correction that there is no ``Plan B''?
</P>
<P>
   Very likely, nothing but the realization that a hostage game
will not go over well in a state that has kept Bill Bidwill on an
11-year waiting list. A state where guns are in, government is out
and taxes are treated like instruments of the devil. A state full
of migrants who have fled communal backgrounds, with some of them
arriving here only to put up walls, to live in selfish isolation,
to mind their own business without any mandated participation.
</P>
<P>
   So the game of chicken has taken another turn. From veiled
threats to backpedals to not-so-fond farewells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under these circumstances, I wish Mr. Burke well,'' Jerry
Colangelo said on Saturday. ``Be it in Arizona or elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Look, no one wants the Coyotes to leave Arizona. No one wants
the Cardinals to leave. No one wants a demotion to the minor league
of sports towns once you've reached the big time.
</P>
<P>
   For precedent, take a look at Houston, a locale that refused to
build the Oilers a stadium, standing firm on principle as their
football team packed for Tennessee. And look how badly they're
trying to reacquire a franchise.
</P>
<P>
   When there is no other alternative, you do what you must to keep
your sports teams from leaving. And when you cut away all the
rhetoric and political maneuvering and self-serving chatter, that
is the real issue facing the Coyotes, the city of Phoenix and those
who will vote in a May 18 referendum in Scottsdale that will open
the doors to the Los Arcos project.
</P>
<P>
   Is there no other alternative?
</P>
<P>
   Burke claims there isn't, but every opinion on this matter must
be weighed against vested interest. Of course, the Coyotes want
their own arena. Of course, Burke wants out from under Colangelo's
roof. Of course, they'll tell you there is no other option.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the Coyotes are also convinced that Arizona's
embrace of hockey is a residue of their slick marketing efforts and
their self-lauded business acumen. What they don't realize is this:
</P>
<P>
   Part of their acceptance is a result of their current address.
By sharing a building with the Suns, by playing next door to the
Diamondbacks, they are part of the triangle. Part of the sporting
renaissance in the Valley. Part of the athletic epicenter that
helps define a new identity.
</P>
<P>
   They are part of something bigger than just hockey, a feeling
that has translated into some mass-market appeal. Maybe not in
tickets sold, but in the public conscience.
</P>
<P>
   On Scottsdale and McDowell roads, they will be a hockey team and
nothing more. Certainly good enough for the puck-heads, but if the
team is not largely successful on the ice, they will slip back into
the shadows of a cult following. Bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   If the Coyotes move to Scottsdale, Colangelo will likely bring
in a minor league hockey team to America West Arena. To fulfill the
required amount of dates for his suite-holders. To spite Burke, as
if that weren't reason enough. You can bet on that, too.
</P>
<P>
   It is times like this when you know who is representing whom and
just how much backbone your politicians possess. If America West
Arena is really owned by the city of Phoenix, couldn't the mayor
step in and work something out? Find a way to make two men
financially cohabit under one roof?
</P>
<P>
   When the plans are unveiled in the near future, we will know
whether the city's $10 million reconfiguration plan is a viable
option or just a crude slap in the face, a way to say they tried to
make things work.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, it's just as interesting that Burke has dismissed the
idea out of hand, vowing Friday that under no circumstances will he
remain at America West Arena once his lease expires in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised and disappointed by Mr. Burke's comments
regarding the fact that the Coyotes are finished at America West
Arena,'' Colangelo said. ``I was happy to bring the NHL to Phoenix,
and my goal was for it to remain there as long as there was a
hockey team in Arizona. But that's totally out of my control now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but you can't convince me that there isn't a way to divvy
up the revenue streams floating through AWA if the seating problem
is corrected. That is, if the city really owns the building, if
it's really serving the constituents and not just Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   It is a time like this that a city steps up or bows its head in
shame.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, this battle is getting crazy, with behind-the-scenes
posturing starting to slip into our lives. Now that Burke has
sought out newspaper space to deny ``unpublished'' rumors, what's
next? A claymation confrontation between Colangelo and Burke on
MTV's ``Celebrity Death Match''?
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the mysterious disappearance of `Plan B`, where
could Burke go? The NHL is a party keg that's nearly tapped, with
teams already popping up in the strangest outposts. In two years,
they'll be at 30 teams. Unless Burke wants to return to Canada,
where their dollar is worth 56 cents here, the options aren't good.
</P>
<P>
   It's both funny and sad what Colangelo's power does to people.
No doubt, part of Burke's reluctance to hang around AWA is the
creeping suspicion that he'll never get a fair shake; the paranoia
that emerges when you believe everyone in town bows to King Jerry.
And at the end of the day, maybe they do.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Mr. Burke, meet Mr. Bidwill.
</P>
<P>
   For now, there may be no better spectator sport than the
dynamics of ownership in Arizona. If not for the consequences. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
