<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-PITCHERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACES AT HEART: D-BACKS HAVE ALL THE CARDS FOR GOOD STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Remember the feeling you had as a kid? Flying down the
road on your bicycles, cards attached to the spokes with
clothespins. Free as the breeze, hardly a care in the world.
Flap-flap-flap.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks pitching coach Mark Connor is starting to have that
feeling. He's ready to put on his purple jacket, sunglasses and cap
and go for a ride when pitchers and catchers report to Tucson
Electric Park on Wednesday and begin workouts Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the deep pockets of Managing General Partner Jerry
Colangelo, the pitching staff was upgraded in a big way over the
winter. That will allow Connor to attach several aces to his spokes
and maybe even a wild card or two.
</P>
<P>
   The new arrivals are left-hander Randy Johnson, right-hander
Todd Stottlemyre, right-hander Armando Reynoso, all starters, and
left-handed middle reliever Greg Swindell. Reliables returning from
the inaugural rotation are right-hander Andy Benes and left-hander
Omar Daal.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Gregg Olson returns as the closer after his 30
saves resurrected his career.
</P>
<P>
   And Connor's primary wild card will be left-hander Brian
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The club's top pick in the expansion draft, Anderson finished
12-13 in 32 starts. Because of the recent additions, rumors have
been circulating regarding his possible trade. But he's not likely
to go until later in the spring, after other clubs have assessed
their needs and the Diamondbacks have done likewise.
</P>
<P>
   If Anderson stays, he probably would go to the bullpen, although
Connor says he will get starters' innings in the spring. Simply
put, Anderson provides flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Arizona will have the best rotation in the National
League, other than Atlanta. That remains to be seen. No one is more
anxious to find out than Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a group of guys with proven track records, but
they still have to go out and perform,'' Connor said. ``It does
make you feel a little more secure.''
</P>
<P>
   Connor will monitor 30 pitchers, including 10 non-roster
invitees. He has seen Johnson, Stottlemyre, Reynoso and Swindell
from the opposing dugout over the years, but will sit down with
each and talk about what throwing approach allows them to get the
most out of their spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to go out there to try and kill somebody,''
Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our rotation is somewhat set, but we do have that flexibility.
Anderson has started, as has Amaury Telemaco (the right-hander had
18 starts for Arizona in 1998). It reminds me of one year when I
was with the Yankees. We had seven or eight guys capable of
starting and wondered what would happen, but it all shook out by
the end of the spring and that took care of it. That should happen
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 35, has a career record of 143-79 with a 3.36 ERA and
2,329 strikeouts. Connor knows there aren't many new things he can
impart to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a case of me moving in and showing him all these
things, but what he needs me to do for him, such as look at his
mechanics and making sure he maintains his consistency,'' Connor
said. ``He knows what he has to do. It's more a matter of me
putting the ball in his hand and giving him a pat on the back.''
</P>
<P>
   Connor said Stottlemyre, who was a combined 14-13 for St. Louis
and Texas in 1998, has many similarities to Benes, who was 14-13
for Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd can locate three or four pitches very well, he's durable
and is a great athlete,'' Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks will be careful with Reynoso, who was 7-3 with
the New York Mets last season as he rebounded from shoulder and
elbow surgeries. Connor has watched Reynoso on tape and said he has
a very solid delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a power guy, but he can change speeds very
effectively,'' Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   Swindell, 32, is a one-time starter who had added length to his
career with the move to the bullpen. Swindell pitched in a combined
81 games (90 innings) for Minnesota and Boston and says he is
capable of pitching in at least 100 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that will happen, but Greg will be a very
valuable addition. He's been around, and he knows how to pitch,''
Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   Daal, who recently signed a new two-year contract, finished
fifth in the NL in ERA at 2.88 despite an 8-12 record. He pitched
about 60 innings over the winter in his native Venezuela, and
Connor expects him to be the same type pitcher he was in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Telemaco came to Arizona from the Chicago Cubs via the waiver
wire in May, was put in the bullpen and then became a starter. The
club likes him better in the bullpen, where Connor said he threw
4-5 mph faster than he did as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Olson long has been known for a nasty curveball, but Connor said
the key to his resurgence has been an ability to rely on other
pitches when the curve isn't working and his continual adjustment
to hitters and situations.
</P>
<P>
   If Olson struggles, young right-hander Ben Ford (13 saves at
Triple-A Tucson) or Cuban right-hander Vladimir Nunez could step
in. Connor said the 6-foot-7, 23-year-old Ford needs better command
of his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Since defecting from Cuba and coming to Arizona as a free agent
in 1996, Nunez has matured as a person and as a pitcher, Connor
said. He has added a split-finger pitch and a stint in the Arizona
Fall League in 1998 should add to his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Buck Showalter figures to have six men in the bullpen.
With Olson and Swindell locked in for two spots, that leaves
Telemaco, Ford, Nunez, right-handers Bobby Chouinard, Aaron Small,
Clint Sodowsky, left-hander Brian Shouse and non-roster
right-handers Frank Castillo and Dan Carlson to battle for the
other four.
</P>
<P>
   The team's top three young pitching prospects _ right-handers
Brad Penny and John Patterson and left-hander Nick Bierbrodt _ also
will be in camp as non-roster invitees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to take innings away from the other guys,
but they'll get a good look. They think they belong here, and
they're going to see what it's really like. It will be good
experience for them,'' Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   This will be quite a different camp from 1998. Connor wants to
hear the flap-flap-flap of those aces on the spokes and will keep
his fingers crossed that the tires don't go flat-flat-flat. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
