<HEADLINE>
BACK TO SQUARE 1 MOST LIKELY MOVE FOR BLACKHAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Toronto Maple Leafs and the rest of the NHL said goodbye to
storied Maple Leaf Gardens on Saturday night. How fitting it was to
see the woeful Chicago Blackhawks on hand for the farewell.
</P>
<P>
   This once-proud franchise has hit absolute rock bottom and is on
the verge of saying goodbye again, this time to more of its
underachieving players. Chicago took a seven-game losing streak
into Saturday's game at Toronto, and General Manager  &UR; Bob Murray
promised changes are on the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to do something, we're going to do it now,'' he
said. ``I don't believe in waiting for the (March 23 trading)
deadline. A team like Detroit can do that and add a player. But we
can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray must decide whether his team still has any kind of shot
at making the playoffs. If not, then he will scrap the season,
pawning off high-priced and veteran players in exchange for
prospects and draft picks to start a total rebuilding process.
</P>
<P>
   Expect the latter. There already has been talk about dealing
captain  &UR; Chris Chelios and promising forwards  &UR; Eric Daze, Ethan
Moreau and former Coyotes  &UR; Alexei Zhamnov and  &UR; Chad Kilger. And
now, veteran center  &UR; Doug Gilmour, for whom the club shelled out
$16 million over three years this summer as one of the most
sought-after free agents on the market, reportedly is on the block.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I heard it,'' a grim-faced Gilmour said.
</P>
<P>
   Chelios is so steammed that his name keeps being mentioned in
trade rumors that he requested a one-on-one meeting with Blackhawks
Owner  &UR; Bill Wirtz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I signed here for three years to retire here,'' Chelios said.
``I'm a Blackhawk, and I want to stay here. I'm not the type of guy
who wants out when things get tough.''
</P>
<P>
   He may have no choice, but the club obviously will treat Chelios
a little differently than others. Players like Zhamnov and Gilmour
could be less fortunate. Coach  &UR; Dirk Graham benched Zhamnov during
the first period of Chicago's 3-0 loss to the Coyotes last weekend
in Phoenix, and Zhamnov showed up for practice the next day with a
mysterious back ailment.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted all sorts of questions in Chicago, mainly if
players like Zhamnov have already quit on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't lie about injuries,'' Zhamnov said.
</P>
<P>
   A perplexed-looking Graham, whose first-year job status also is
in question, stood by Zhamnov's story. Defenseman  &UR; Dave Manson said
he hasn't seen any signs _ yet _ of a player revolt or tanking on
the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knock on wood,'' he said. ``So far, nothing like that has
really happened. For the most part, the guys have been really good
at sticking together and trying to make it work. It hasn't been
easy, but at least everybody's trying.'' &QL; 
Nearing Sawchuk's record
</P>
<P>
   Colorado goalie  &UR; Patrick Roy became just the fifth netminder in
NHL history to reach the 400-victory milestone last week and is
well within shot of catching  &UR; Terry Sawchuk for the most wins ever.
</P>
<P>
   Sawchuk finished with 447 career victories, followed by  &UR; Jaques
 &UR; Plantes (434),  &UR; Tony Esposito (423) and  &UR; Glenn Hall (407).
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's been a great career,'' said Roy, 33, who began
the season doubting himself and his abilities after a 1-6-1 start.
``I never thought I'd get to 400 wins and now I have a chance to
catch the No. 1 guy. That's my objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy could catch Sawchuk's win total at some point late next
season. &QL; 
Dino's dilemma
</P>
<P>
   Chronic back problems once again have knocked  &UR; Dino Ciccarelli
out of commission with the Florida Panthers. He went back on the
injured list for the fourth time this season on Monday, his 39th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' he said. ``I'm not playing the way I want
to play and I'm not happy with it. I want to get better for the
home stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Ciccarelli, who has been limited to 14 games this season,
dismissed talk of potential retirement, saying he's not ready to
leave the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried at all about this ending my career,'' said
Ciccarelli, who has 608 goals and 1,200 points in 1,232 career
games. ``There's still a lot of fire in this body. I still enjoy
the game and can contribute.'' &QL; 
Ready Freddie
</P>
<P>
   Veteran defenseman  &UR; Fredrik Olausson of the Mighty Ducks of
Anaheim is on pace for one of his best seasons ever with 14 goals
and 38 points entering today's game against the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   His 14 goals already have tied  &UR; Bill Houlder's &UR; Anaheim
single-season record by a defenseman, and he's just eight points
shy of setting the single-season points record set by  &UR; Dmitri
Mironov.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, Olausson last weekend joined the 500-point club,
becoming just the 37th blueliner in history to reach the milestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty much subdued everything,'' teammate  &UR; Kevin Haller
said. ``But that's an amazing accomplishment that a lot of
defenseman, myself included, won't do.''
</P>
<P>
   Olausson, who scored two goals and had two assists during a 5-3
win on Wednesday over Philadelphia, has the second-most points of
any NHL defenseman born outside North America. He trails only Hall
of Famer  &UR; Borje Salming, who retired in 1990 with 787 points.
</P>
<P>
   Can he catch Salming?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's way up there,'' Olausson said, ``but if I get four points
every night I might.'' &QL; 
Calgary's stampede
</P>
<P>
   They're in danger of not making the playoffs. They're in danger
of losing their star forward,  &UR; Theo Fleury, to a trade or free
agency. But the ho-hum Calgary Flames are dangerous themselves when
it comes to upending teams that are on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   Back on Dec. 18, they beat New Jersey, 5-2, to snap the Devils'
eight-game unbeaten streak. On Jan. 8, they snuffed Dallas, 1-0, to
snap the Stars' 15-game unbeaten streak. And on Tuesday, they shut
down Colorado, 2-1, ending a franchise-record 12-game winning
streak by the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   One would think a little trend like that might put an extra jump
in the Flames' skates. Well, Coach  &UR; Brian Sutter didn't seem too
impressed when asked about it the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't give a (expletive) about that or who we're playing,''
he sniffed. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602-444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
