<HEADLINE>
MUSIC AT HEART OF SKATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY - Figure skating is the Valentine's Day of
sports.
</P>
<P>
   It's hugs and kisses. Hearts and flowers, red roses mostly,
laced with baby's breath. Bouquets sailed onto the ice Saturday
night like arrows shot from a winged archer's bow.
</P>
<P>
   When Michelle Kwan finished skating and flashed her winning
smile, here came the flowers, armloads of them. The Delta Center
never smelled so good.
</P>
<P>
   The sustained applause for the champion was an elaborate
heart-shaped greeting card. Inside, its sentimental message read,
``We love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Guys read this and gag. Most couldn't care less about figure
skating. The male mind can't understand how skating can be the most
popular Winter Olympics sport. Or why the finals of the U.S. Figure
Skating Championships drew a huge television audience, as they do
every year.
</P>
<P>
   The event had little suspense. The outcome was almost
preordained. In a class by herself, Kwan was certain to repeat as
champion unless she froze with stage fright or fell down during her
four-minute routine and couldn't get up. No chance of that. So why
the universal appeal?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the theatrical element,'' said Dick Button, the TV
announcer and former Olympic gold medalist. ``Skating has beauty.
It has choreography. It has personality.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the ``music,'' Cupid.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine sequinned pixies revolving around the rink in total
silence. What would the sport be like without the accompaniment of
harps and crying violins? Show tunes and rhapsodies fill the arena
and energize the skaters and transform a check list of technical
spins and jumps into a ``performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Operas. Symphonies. Concertos. Ballets. Tchaikovsky. Beethoven.
Strauss. You can't get that kind of culture at a Coyotes game or at
BOB.
</P>
<P>
   Want to win a sports bar bet? Ask a friend to name the music
Kwan selected for her freestyle program. When the guy stops
laughing and says, ``Yeah, like ``you'' know,'' you slap down a
bill and deliver the answer. ``Ariane.'' By Jules Massenet.
</P>
<P>
   No one was going to beat Kwan after she double-axeled and
triple-lutz-double-toe-looped her way through the short program to
the music of ``Carmen''.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that most guys were unimpressed with Michelle's
characterization because they've never seen ``Carmen,'' which, I
discovered after some serious research, is a famous opera, by
Bizet.
</P>
<P>
   Act I. Carmen is a cigarette girl. She rolls smokes, regular
size and king. One day outside the factory, she meets a soldier
named Don Jose. Don Jose falls in love. Later, Carmen stabs a
fellow female worker, who files a grievance with the union.
Soldiers handcuff Carmen and leave her in Don Jose's custody. Don
Jose lets her go. Carmen runs away.
</P>
<P>
   Act II. A tavern. Carmen is wearing an off-the-shoulder blouse
and clicking her castanets. The great bullfighter Escamillo walks
in. He orders a margarita. Rocks. No salt. Carmen, who isn't shy,
slides up to the famous toreador. ``Hi, sailor. Like some
company?'' Escamillo is smitten. But he has a bull to fight. He
needs his sleep. He leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a court martial, Don Jose appears. He is lovesick. Don
Jose deserts and follows his temptress into the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Act III. The mountains. Carmen is tired of Don Jose. She no
longer dances for him. She won't even fix him breakfast. She can't
get her mind off the bullfighter. Escamillo comes looking for her.
He and Don Jose exchange words. Don Jose leaves to be with his
dying mother. Escamillo goes off to fight another bull.
</P>
<P>
   Act IV. A square in Seville. It is the day of the bullfight.
Escamillo appears, with Carmen on his arm. Giving her a kiss and
assuring this won't take long, he parades into the ring. The crowd
cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Don Jose shows up. He pleads for Carmen's love and gives her a
Valentine's gift _ a nightie from Victoria's Secret. Carmen tells
Don Jose to get lost. ``Please,'' Don Jose begs. Beat it, Carmen
says. Don Jose, a sore loser, stabs Carmen in the back. Carmen
dies. &QL; 
The End. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
