</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-AVALANCHE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES BACK IN FORM  
 KHABIBULIN FINALLY BEATS COLORADO, ROY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Statistically, it was a game between teams going
opposite directions _ one toward elite status and the other
seemingly bent toward a return to the mediocrity that has been its
history.
</P>
<P>
   A team that was 16-6-1 in its past 23 games and winner of 12 of
its past 13 vs. one that started fast but was 9-8-6 in its past 23.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? Statistics do lie. And the term mediocrity wasn't in
the Coyotes' vocabulary Saturday as they whipped the red-hot
Colorado Avalanche and goalie Patrick Roy, 4-1. The victory kept
the Coyotes two points behind front-running Dallas in the Pacific
Division.
</P>
<P>
   By no means was it easy, although the Coyotes showed serious
signs of returning to early-season form with a solid,
tight-checking, defensive game to run their record to 3-0-1 against
the Avalanche this year.
</P>
<P>
   To wit:
</P>
<P>
   In whipping Roy for the first time in his career, Coyotes goalie
Nikolai Khabibulin stopped 25 of 26 shots and, with his 117th
career victory, became the franchise's all-time winning netminder.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes received scoring from unexpected sources. Defenseman
Deron Quint tied the game at 1 with his second goal of the season
in the second period, and Juha Ylonen, with his sixth goal,
provided a needed third-period insurance score.
</P>
<P>
   They were without captain Keith Tkachuk for all but four minutes
of the second period. He was whistled for pummeling Colorado's
Sylvain Lefebvre. He was also handed an instigating penalty and a
10-minute misconduct at the end of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant captain Jeremy Roenick made up for Tkachuk's absence
with a goal against Roy at 19:05 of the second period to provide a
huge momentum boost.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Greg Adams kept up his torrid pace _ 12 points in his
last 10 games _ with two key assists.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes had to protect a 2-1 lead for 1:29 in the third
period against a power play that has executed at 24 percent over
the last 13 games. They didn't give up a shot, thanks to the
absence of the injured Sandis Ozolinsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the biggest penalty kill we've had all year,'' Roenick
said of Colorado's two-man edge. ``We're up a goal, and they have a
two-man edge for nearly two minutes, and they didn't get a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys on the bench had a good feeling after that. We
talked before the game about using this game as a propellent for
the tough stretch we have coming up. It's great to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes will face stiff challenges at home from Anaheim
tonight and Philadelphia on Tuesday before embarking on a
seven-game, 14-day road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a solid team effort,'' Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld
said. ``We were a little tentative at the start because we've
beaten them twice this year, but never with all their players, and
we wondered how we would really match up with them. From the second
half of the first period, though, we played well.''
</P>
<P>
   The only time Colorado cracked Khabibulin came just 18 seconds
into Colorado's first power play at 7:15 of the first, when Joe
Sakic knocked home a rebound directed right at Khabibulin off
Claude Lemieux's slap shot. Say bye, Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting the franchise record is nice, but the win for the team
is bigger,'' said Khabibulin, who now has a career 3-9-1 record
against Colorado. ``This was also the first time I've ever beaten
Patrick, so that really makes me feel good. I haven't played well
against this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``But everybody played very consistent in front of me. This is
the kind of hockey we played earlier this year. We played hard and
smart.''
</P>
<P>
   In his last seven games, Khabibulin has a 0.99 goals-against
average and a 5-1-1 record with two shutouts, making him a
candidate for NHL player of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Quint, too, was excited about beating Roy.
</P>
<P>
   He took advantage of a rare moment of indecision by Adam Foote
to cancel out Sakic's goal just 31 seconds into a second-period
power play, beating Roy with a wrister into the upper corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised when Foote didn't come over on me
quicker, so I took the shot,'' Quint said. ``When I have kids, I
can tell 'em I got one against the greatest goalie who ever
played.''
</P>
<P>
   Roenick took Teppo Numminen's pass that hopped over Lefebvre's
stick just before the red line and skated in on Roy unmolested for
the game winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick played it great,'' Schoenfeld said. ``It was just a
tremendous goal. He didn't give much of an angle, but Jeremy took
the puck from the angle he was on and pulled it back before he
shot. Without the nifty hand movement, Roy had it shut down.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
