<HEADER>
A4817 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEIGHBOR-AZR &LR;      02-13 1847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEIGHBOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX NEIGHBORHOOD'S HOPEFUL SIGNS LOST IN SPASMS OF VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS FISCUS  
 and WILLIAM HERMANN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tidy homes with flowerpots on fence posts. Inviting benches
under shade trees. A neighborhood barbershop.
</P>
<P>
   This is a community where federal dollars help neighbors better
themselves, like the $40,000 loan that helped Marc Rogers expand
his business.
</P>
<P>
   It's a community where crime statistics have dropped
significantly since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   And it's the same community that saw nine people gunned down in
less than 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The toll: six dead, three injured and a week's worth of glare in
the media spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood near Broadway Road is neither all good or all
bad, but an unusual _ and extreme _ blend of both. Well-kept homes
owned by couples who have lived here for decades sit next to rows
of vacant lots filled with broken glass. A house the size of a shed
sits just down the block from new homes that are the pride of the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of dollars and untold hours of sweat have been poured
into improving the area, but the list of needs is as long as, or
perhaps longer than, the list of accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The problems facing this neighborhood mirror the challenges
faced in other urban areas around the Valley _ and around the
country _ where police, city leaders and some residents struggle to
turn things around.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix area in the spotlight is roughly between 16th and
32nd streets, Broadway and Roeser roads, in south-central Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to picture the whole area as crack houses and
burned-out and boarded-up homes. It's easy to picture criminals
passing the time until they decide to go shoot someone.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality has shades of a neighborhood trying to shake the
coat of despair, of law-abiding citizens who have lived here for
decades, of a community abounding in churches. There are three at
one intersection, and about 25 to 30 in the surrounding area.
</P>
<P>
   And crime is down between 20th and 28th streets, Roeser Road and
Elwood Street. According to police, violent crime in 1998 was down
29 percent from 1996; total crime dropped 18 percent; gang-involved
crime is down 64 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Councilman Cody Williams grew up blocks from the recent
shootings. He walks through vacant lot after vacant lot littered
with endless broken glass. But when he closes his eyes he sees what
the area could be.
</P>
<P>
   It's like dealing with a weed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``If you scrape the top off, it looks good for a while but it's
going to come back unless you deal with the root.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; That means more is needed than a police crackdown, he says.
It's about the ``need to see dirt turned'' to build on vacant lots,
bring in more homeowners rather than renters, and attract more
businesses to add more jobs. &QL; 
AID FOR THE AREA
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix has funneled considerable money into trying to stabilize
the area.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, more than $3 million in various federal funds and
some city bond funds has been committed to a ``neighborhood
initiative area'' between 24th and 32nd streets, from the Salt
River to Roeser Road.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, workers have renovated 35 houses, the
city has donated 231 gallons of paint, and volunteers and city
crews removed graffiti from 143 buildings or walls.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three years, the federal government has handed out
about $250,000 to run various jobs programs in the community and
invested another $500,000 in a 20-square mile area that includes
the neighborhood. Additionally, $200,000 in private funds has been
commited to keep the jobs programs going.
</P>
<P>
   Also near Broadway and 24th street, Phoenix and property owners
demolished at least 49 structures in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix bought the Rainbow Market at 24th Street and Broadway,
considered by many to be a crime magnet, and plans to demolish it.
But it remains open while a court fight continues.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's help like a $40,000 loan through a federal program
that helped Marc Rogers expand his neighborhood barbershop. He has
hired three barbers and a cosmetologist thanks to the loan for his
shop at 17th street and Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; And there's the $3,000 in federal dollars that allowed Denise
Rogers to finish beauty school. &QL; 
NEW HOMES GOING UP
</P>
<P>
   There's something else in the neighborhood: new homes, being
built through the Community Excellence Project.
</P>
<P>
   The non-profit community development corporation was formed in
1990. It is &UR; funded with municipal, state, federal and private
sector assistance.
</P>
<P>
   CEP has built three new homes in the neighborhood, with three
more under construction.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Estes, 31, recently moved into a CEP house with his two
children and his wife-to-be. His house is a freshly painted gray,
with green trim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so glad to be here, so glad to have such a nice place,''
Estes says as he prepares dinner for himself and his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``To own your own home means a lot. I've lived in this area a
long time, worked hard for a long time, and now feel like I'm
getting somewhere. I'm also glad my kids will have their own home,
have the same sense of pride I have.''
</P>
<P>
   New homes benefit more than just the new residents; they also
boost neighborhood pride. Jennifer Baker was in the neighborhood to
visit her grandmother, who lives across the street from Estes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those new houses are where shacks once were,'' Baker says.
``Giving people help to get into houses like those is about the
best thing anyone can do. You see what it has done for this
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Tisha Laddell, 14, lives in a neat and trim ranch-style house
next door to a CEP house.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel safer when their houses look nice,`' Tisha says,
tossing a football outside with her 9-year-old brother, Gyrell.
</P>
<P>
   But for every fresh new home there are countless dilapidated
places.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see that there are more vacant lots here than there
are houses. Period,'' Williams says of the neighborhood. ``I doubt
there's a place anywhere where you can count 10 houses contiguously
in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Phoenix City Councilman Phil Gordon, a member of the council's
housing and neighborhoods subcommittee, says, ``This is a wake-up
call.'' Rather than ``peanut-buttering the problem,'' he says the
city and others need to go deeper.
</P>
<P>
   Williams talks of more than $200 million set aside by the state
for matching funds for desert preservation. He wonders why even 10
percent of that could not be set aside to address critical needs in
neighborhoods like this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any cactus that's in jeopardy right now. . . .
You know, these people are talking about the fear for their lives
and their safety in this community.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, 24th street seems to divide two worlds.
</P>
<P>
   On one side of 24th Street are master-planned lots and homes
with garages and carports. On the other side are shed-size homes,
some of which lack even a driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem: Many of the homes east of 24th Street were
annexed into the city, and the homes and streets and lots were not
master-planned, or designed to city standards.
</P>
<P>
   Adding quality homes to the area is the goal of CEP Director
Gail Knight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buyers have to be in the lower to moderate income bracket,
have reasonable credit, be employed,'' she says. ``We also hope to
attract people who are, like, 25 years old to their 40s, because
there are so many older people already here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessie Jackson, 61, and her husband have lived in the same
well-kept house on Corona Avenue for 31 years. All of their six
children, they say, have made successful lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``New houses alone are not going to do it!'' she says. ``Young
people in this neighborhood have to be made to stay in school and
have to be helped to find jobs when they aren't in school, so they
will be busy working and learning about responsibility and not be
out on the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   The CEP is also involved in employment training, crime
prevention and care services for young people and families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, `Where are the parents of these young girls
and boys who go wrong?' '' Knight says. ``What is happening in
their homes that we are subjected to this behavior? Where is the
responsibility?'' &QL; 
MONEY NOT ALWAYS ANSWER
</P>
<P>
   Serious crime and problems persist in the Broadway neighborhood
_ and in other troubled areas _ despite all of the dollars and
programs designed to help.
</P>
<P>
   The city has established half a dozen ``neighborhood initiative
areas'' in the 1990s, pledging to remove blighted properties, fill
vacant lots with new homes, improve infrastructure and beef up code
enforcement in trouble spots. The city also pushes youth programs
and social services. The targeted areas range from Sunnyslope to
south-central Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   One area _ the Longview neighborhood _ received $4.7 million in
funding, and city officials point to several successes there: a
$1.4 million community center, 33 new homes and 70 remodeled ones,
10 new streetlights and about 100 gallons of paint used to fight
graffiti.
</P>
<P>
   And since 1993, about $6 million in federal funds and some city
bonds have gone into the Garfield area.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still trash and there's still junk cars, but I think
all the vacant boarded-up buildings are down,'' says Maryann
Ustick, director of Phoenix's Neighborhood Services department.
</P>
<P>
   Ustick said that nationwide, the average time to turn around a
neighborhood is 7 to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's minimum,'' she says. &QL; 
HOPE FOR THE FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   As for the Broadway neighborhood, as bad as some parts of the
area seem, many hold out hope.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the hope rests in the work of CEP.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the hope rests in the city's ``Four Corners'' project,
which it sees as a way to revitalize the four corners of the 24th
Street and Broadway intersection. Problem properties or vacant land
could become retail shops or other developments.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix has also hired a consultant and is looking at financing
options for a housing and commercial redevelopment in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Improvements can happen.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Williams stands in a dirt lot and looks at a building
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``That used to be the most notorious drug hangout in the state
of Arizona,'' he says. ``People were shot, stabbed, robbed and in
some cases killed.''
</P>
<P>
   But the police and city cracked down on the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shut down this community once before . . . and stopped
preachers, teachers, pimps and pushers until all we stopped were
preachers and teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   A non-profit took over the building and turned it into a
community center.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to the present, and Phoenix police will have an
increased presence in the neighborhood for a couple of weeks. Then
what happens?
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't have a coordinated community, city and private
effort, we'll be back dealing with similar issues in the future,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must systemically change the existing conditions of this
community and give the residents a fighting chance for a better
quality of life.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
