<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN: A PRISONER OF AMBITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sen. John Sidney McCain III is no longer a prisoner of war, but
for the next two years he'll play one on TV. And in the newspapers.
And on radio. And billboards. And bumper stickers. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   The 5{ years McCain spent in a Vietnamese prison camp sets him
apart from all the other candidates. They're his ticket to power
and, even better, his shield from criticism.
</P>
<P>
   On a radio talk show 10 years ago, the future presidential
candidate slipped up and said, ``One of the things I've never tried
to do is exploit my Vietnam service to my country, because it would
be totally inappropriate to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't true at the time.
</P>
<P>
   It's even less so now.
</P>
<P>
   The only way McCain gets into the White House is if the story of
McCain never gets out of the Hanoi Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   And it won't.
</P>
<P>
   Not if the toadies at places like the ``New York Times'' and the
``Wall Street Journal'' and the major TV networks have their way.
</P>
<P>
   Even ``60 Minutes'' tough guy Mike Wallace is among McCain's
media bootlickers, saying, ``I'm thinking I may quit my job if he
gets the (Republican) nomination. I'm impressed by his
independence, by his willingness to take on tough ones. By his
honesty about himself.'' &QL; 
DON'T EXPECT MUCH
</P>
<P>
   They're smitten with the fact McCain was a POW.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, don't expect reporters outside of Arizona to
ask McCain much about the $112,000 in campaign contributions he
took from S&AMP;L kingpin Charlie Keating, returning it only after
publicity made it too embarrassing to keep.
</P>
<P>
   Or about the vacations McCain and his family took at Charlie's
hideaway in the Bahamas. Or about the shopping-center venture
McCain's wife, Cindy, and her father had with Charlie.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect them to ask McCain about Cindy's little problem
stealing drugs meant for impoverished children.
</P>
<P>
   They may praise McCain for fighting Big Tobacco, but don't
expect them to ask him why he doesn't complain about Big Alcohol,
or if it has anything to with his father-in-law's beer
distributorship.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect them to ask McCain why he has accepted speaking
invitations from fringe groups like the gay-bashing Oregon Citizens
Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Or why he didn't come to the defense of Barry Goldwater when
Arizona Republicans wanted to remove Goldwater's name from state
party headquarters for saying Congress should lay off Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Or about his first marriage, in which McCain acted a lot like
McClinton.
</P>
<P>
   Or about his known temper tantrums.
</P>
<P>
   It's not easy to question McCain. &QL; 
SOMETHING TO FALL BACK ON
</P>
<P>
   Reporters who try it can expect him to reach into his past and
throw down his get-out-of-a-jam-free card. It happened once to some
writers grilling McCain about Keating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the Vietnamese didn't question my ethics,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   You can't beat that.
</P>
<P>
   So, don't expect anyone outside Arizona to ask what happened to
the McCain who told a wire service reporter 10 years ago, ``I'm
devoting all my efforts to being the Arizona senator and not the
POW senator.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's even subtly worked his prisoner-of-war experience into
the statement he released about voting to convict Clinton at the
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my former profession,'' he said, ``those who violated their
sworn oath were punished severely and considered outcasts from our
society. . . . Although I may admit to failure in my private life,
I have at all times, and to the best of my ability, kept faith with
every oath I have ever sworn to this country. I have known some men
who kept that faith at the cost of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain suffered horribly in Vietnam. He earned the right to use
that experience any way he wants, and that includes getting
elected.
</P>
<P>
   Why be coy?
</P>
<P>
   Be upfront. Be direct. Make the ``McCain for President''
campaign slogan:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a POW for 5{ years; you people owe me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
