<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOB-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LENDING-RATE BILL FLIRTED WITH ACCUSED MOB FIGURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAT KOSSAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona legislators came perilously close to opening the state
to a Georgia-based lending company with alleged ties to organized
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Two Valley lawmakers introduced a bill last year that would have
let the lenders charge annual interest rates as high as 300 percent
on loans secured by car titles _ more than eight times the current
cap.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed by Title Loans of America, an Atlanta company, and two
well-known Arizona lobbyists, the bill was championed by its
backers as a free enterprise issue.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation passed the House 31-25, but died in the Senate
after an attack by the Attorney General's Office, which opposed the
bill because of the high interest rates it would have allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Organized crime issues did not surface at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Title Loans of America is leading an effort to get similar bills
passed in state legislatures, buying up lobbyists and spreading
campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   A principal owner of Title Loans of America is Alvin Malnik,
banned from New Jersey casinos in 1993 because, officials there
alleged, he had ties to organized criminal activities and
participated in illegal transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Malnik did not respond to requests for interviews at Title Loans
of America's Georgia offices or at a restaurant he owns in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Malnik told ``Consumer Reports'' magazine in July that the
allegations by the New Jersey Casino Commission are ``entirely
baseless.''
</P>
<P>
   Malnik, now in his 60s, who lives on a lavish 22-acre estate in
Boca Raton, Fla., was cleared of tax evasion charges in 1985 and
remains a member in good standing of the Florida Bar Association,
according to a March story in Florida's ``Sun-Sentinel'' newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   A 1980 report by the New Jersey Gaming Commission called Malnik
``a close business associate of Meyer Lansky and other reputed
organized crime figures. Moreover, the federal law enforcement
authorities have long believed Mr. Malnik to be involved in
organized crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Lansky grew from small-time bootlegging to the leader of a crime
corporation active in Cuba, Las Vegas and Miami during the 1950s
and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The two Arizona lawmakers who co-sponsored the bill, Reps. Wes
Marsh, R-Scottsdale, and Jim Weiers, R-north Phoenix, said they did
not know about the alleged organized crime connection.
</P>
<P>
   Weiers _ then Rules chairman and now House majority whip _
laughed when asked if he knew who owned the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously not,'' said Weiers. The lawmaker said he was
approached by a Title Loans of America lobbyist who is a former
member of the Florida Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Weiers said he is in the business of making high-risk,
high-interest loans to people with poor or no credit through
dealerships of new and used cars, but said the bill was designed
only for those in the title-loan business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it was explained to me, I thought, `Why should
government be interfering with free enterprise?' '' Weiers said.
``Would I put my name on anything like this again? No.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marsh, a health care consultant, said he didn't have a clue
about the connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to protect consumers and allow access to capital,''
Marsh said. ``I think there was good intentions on my part. I was
truly trying t help people.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiers said he is returning a $150 campaign contribution made
last January by a part-owner of the company. Marsh said if he finds
a contribution from Title Loans of America was made to his
campaign, he also will return it.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he was pushing the legislation, Weiers said that
passing the bill was the only way Atlanta-based Title Loans of
America would do business in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I understand it, if they don't get these kinds of
percentage rates, they're not going to come into the state,''
Weiers told ``The Arizona Republic'' in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists Kevin DeMenna and Steven Betts, an attorney at
Gallagher &AMP; Kennedy, said they were hired by former Florida
legislator Don Tucker on behalf of Title Loans of America to lobby
for the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker was reached at his office phone number and identified
himself, but hung up when asked about Title Loans of America.
Tucker failed to respond to numerous messages left on his answering
machine.
</P>
<P>
   DeMenna denied he knew who owned the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``My firm and my advocacy will not be associated with gaming
interests of any type, tobacco or the licensed beverage industry.
It takes me to a place I'm not comfortable going,'' DeMenna said.
</P>
<P>
   Betts said he has no comment about the ownership of Title Loans
of America, but would investigate if the company approached him
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we didn't know,'' Betts said. ``We did some checking
on the company, and other states gave them a clean bill of
health.''
</P>
<P>
   Title Loans of America is leading a state-by-state effort to
legalize the high-interest deals.
</P>
<P>
   Its lobbyists say it operates in 18 states. Consumer advocates
say it operates under different names in about 12 to 15 states.
</P>
<P>
   Title loans are legal in about 25 states, including Arizona, but
interest rates companies are allowed to charge vary from 30 percent
a year to 264 percent. In Arizona the cap is 36 percent. Some
states that permit title loans have no usury laws and, therefore,
no cap on interest-rates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The company offers small loans, in exchange for the title to a
customer's paid-off car.
</P>
<P>
   It charges very high interest rates and lets the customer drive
the car. If a customer cannot make the loan payments, the company
picks up the automobile it owns.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyist Betts said he supported the Arizona legislation as a
way to give an indigent person a chance to pay a medical bill or
purchase tools for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usury laws in general are the result of overzealous consumer
protection advocates,'' DeMenna said.
</P>
<P>
   Then-Arizona Attorney General Grant Woods opposed the Arizona
bill and said high-interest car-title loans would be dangerous for
people out of cash and credit, who would be overwhelmed by payments
and quickly lose their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Title Loans of America has unsuccessfully tried to raise
interest caps in California, Oklahoma and Arizona and set up shop.
But it succeeded in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go in, buy a few legislators off, and they set up the law
and move their business in,'' said Lynn Drysdale, a staff attorney
with Florida Legal Services. In 1995 the Florida Legislature passed
a title-lending law allowing an annual interest rate of 264
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Title Loans of America hired a former Florida state legislator
to lobby the bill through and the ``Florida Times-Union'' in
Jacksonville reported last month that the growing industry as a
whole gave at least $122,000 in campaign contributions during a
two-year period that began Nov. 1, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Two attempts to rescind the Florida law have failed, and some
Florida cities and counties are now trying to outlaw the loans.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, Title Loans of America owners and executives made
about $2,000 in campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Terry E. Fields, listed by the Georgia secretary of state as
chief financial officer of Title Loans of America, donated $760 to
Tom McGovern's failed campaign for attorney general, Arizona
election reports show.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Aycox, a part-owner of Title Loans of America and listed as
CEO, donated $500 to Gov. Jane Hull's campaign; $200 to Rep. Jeff
Groscost, an East Valley Republican and speaker of the House; $150
each to the campaigns of Sen. John Wettaw, a Flagstaff Republican,
Sen. Scott Bundgaard, a Glendale Republican, and Weiers; and $125
to Rep. Linda Gray, a Glendale Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Aycox's legislative contribution showed him as an executive,
then CEO/president, and then an owner of a company called Tel-Link,
a company with the same Georgia address as Title Loans of America.
</P>
<P>
   In a January 1997 sworn deposition for a Georgia civil action,
Aycox, then president and part-owner of Title Loans of America,
revealed Malnik as an owner of U.S. Title Trust, which owns 50
percent of Title Loans of America.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In the same deposition, Aycox reported that he is a 33 percent
owner and Kenneth Partiss of Atlanta was a 17 percent owner.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983 Partiss was among 84 defendants indicted in Miami after
a U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration drug-smuggling probe that
covered 20 states. He was acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Aycox and Partiss did not respond to requests for interviews
left at Atlanta headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after Malnik's 1959 graduation from the University of
Miami Law School he moved into offices of Metro Mortgage Loan Co.,
a reputed front corporation for Alfred Mones, an alleged
``principal member of the Mafia's bookmaking and loan-sharking
organization,'' said a 1980 report by the New Jersey Division of
Gaming Enforcement. The report quotes federal witnesses who called
Malnik an employee of Lansky.
</P>
<P>
   The report states that in 1961 Malnik and a partner started the
Bank of World Commerce, a shell bank that secretly funneled
millions of dollars into Bahamian banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the nation's top gangsters were involved with BWC,''
the report said. Malnik was charged in Florida in 1969 with
underreporting his income and was acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966 a fraud indictment resulted from another business deal
with organized crime figures but was never prosecuted. Malnik then
became a business partner with Samuel E. Cohen, who was convicted
in 1971 of conspiring to violate the Commodity Exchange Act. The
same year, Cohen was indicted along with Lansky for a skimming
operation at a Las Vegas casino. Cohen pleaded guilty to filing
false income tax returns and served one year in jail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
