<SLUG> BC-ART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM ADDITIONS BROADEN PHOENIX ART SCENE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the $10 million Scottsdale Museum of Contemporary Art opens
today _ and the $18.2 million Heard Museum expansion opens in two
weeks _ perhaps Phoenix will finally begin to put to rest the
inferiority complex that has plagued it over its supposed lack of
cultural scope and sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed at how the cultural landscape of the Valley has
grown,'' says Robert Knight, the new director of the Scottsdale
Museum. ``We're just starting to come into our own.''
</P>
<P>
   The openings cap a time of nearly frenzied expansion. In the
space of three years _ beginning with the 1996 opening of the
enlarged Phoenix Art Museum _ three of the four most important
mainstream art venues in the Valley will have doubled their
exhibition space. It is an astonishing vote of confidence by museum
boards, administrators and the voters who started the whole process
in 1988 with the passage of the $1 billion bond referendum that, in
part, allowed the Phoenix Art Museum to begin its expansion and
redesign.
</P>
<P>
   Knight points out that the Valley may be reaching what has
always been called a ``critical mass.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, the more cultural institutions, the better.
That's what makes a community great. That's why I go to New York,
L.A., Chicago or San Francisco. I can see more than one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers that tell the story of the Valley's arts growth are
astonishing. In 1988, the Phoenix Art Museum saw 177,808 people
enter its doors; in 1998, that number increased to 324,976, fueled
by its massive ``Splendors of Ancient Egypt'' exhibit. The
Scottsdale Center counted 61,000 visits to its galleries in the
1988-89 season; by '96-'97, it was 136,000.
</P>
<P>
   There are now 239 art galleries listed in the Yellow Pages.
There are 59 producing theater companies, almost triple what
existed 10 years ago. There are even 10 contemporary dance
companies in the Valley. And the same bond issue that funded the
art museum expansion helped fund the new Central Library, science
center and history museum, and the restoration of the Orpheum and
Phoenix theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is interesting to look back 10 years,'' said Shelley Cohn,
director of the Arizona Commission on the Arts. ``Back then, in the
winter of 1989, we had three of our major performing-arts
institutions who said they wouldn't open the following fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Things looked bleak. The symphony, the ballet and Arizona
Theater Company were all on the edge of bankruptcy. Today, they are
all strong.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the health of the arts cannot be judged only by numbers. Art
is a stubbornly subjective thing, and it is difficult to determine
just when numbers correlate to quality.
</P>
<P>
   Heard Museum Director Martin Sullivan has a sense. ``We're
absolutely ready to be taken as big city,'' he said, pointing out
that over the next year four national arts professional groups have
chosen the Valley as the site for their annual meetings, including
the National Museum Trustee Association and the Association of Art
Museum Directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't only the general public, but our peers in the
industry that are curious and interested in seeing for themselves
what we are doing in Phoenix,'' Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix Art Museum Director Jim Ballinger agrees. ``Absolutely.
As we enter the 21st century, Phoenix has become a place people are
interested in and want to find out about, to see what is going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expansion has seen us able to attract an Egypt and a
Monet,'' Ballinger said. ``The same thing will happen to the Heard
and to the Scottsdale museum,'' Ballinger said. ``It creates a
tremendous synergy.''
</P>
<P>
   And with locally curated shows, such as the Phoenix Art Museum's
current ``Copper as Canvas'' show, going elsewhere to be seen _ it
travels to the Hague when it closes here _ Ballinger said, ``not
only is the world coming to Phoenix, but we're sending things to
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   At Arizona State University's Art Museum, Director Marilyn
Zeitlin agrees about the growth but warns that buildings aren't
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all need to work on our collections. If collections and
programs are weak, it doesn't matter how big your building is.
That's where we'll all be working. With the exception of the Heard,
which already has a world-class collection, we all have a lot of
work to do in collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of mediocrity, frankly. And it's tough to move
to the next level with collections. But if we're all smart, we're
not all going to go after the same work. A degree of specialization
in each museum helps.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see where the new Scottsdale museum
goes, in terms of its collection and programs, Zeitlin said. ``I've
always admired their commitment to local artists. That has been
their great strength, and I hope that will continue. It is
important for us to have specialties, to divide things up, and it
would be nice to coordinate some shows _ we already have several
such projects lined up.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight agrees. ``I hate competition among museums. I think
you'll see us working more collaboratively with the Phoenix Art
Museum, ASU and the Heard to create programs and projects that will
have significance Valley-wide, something bigger and better than any
one of us could do individually.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that has changed over the past decade is the
attitude of newcomers to the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be the bane of local museums that people who moved
here from the Midwest often maintained their loyalty to their
former states, often giving money back there rather than here. But
that pattern is changing, and recent residents have begun seeing
Phoenix as a place worth investing both time and money in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing people come here, buy homes, put beautiful work
into the homes, and then participate on our boards and offer
financial support,'' Zeitlin said. ``There's a huge change in
perception of us as a place for good, good work and not just
leftovers. Some of that message we've intentionally promulgated.''
</P>
<P>
   New residents used to come largely from the upper Midwest,
Ballinger said, but now many Southern Californians are coming, and
others from the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``That only enriches what the art community might see and do,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the Valley has faced the problem that corporate giving was
also often aimed at home-office states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be realistic about not having too many Fortune-500
headquarters in town,'' Ballinger said. ``We tend to focus on big
companies, but we have to get the mid-size companies, the new ones,
to be more involved in what is happening here. And that will
probably happen.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that will help, they all agree, is the state arts
endowment, which passed the Legislature in 1996 and puts aside $2
million per year for 10 years. That money is deposited into the
state treasury and its income is administered by the Arizona
Commission on the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all this growth and development, funding for arts is
still and always will be fragile,'' Cohn said. ``It demands a
strong partnership between the private sector and government to
assure the arts are available to all our citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The end result can be a brighter, more vibrant city and a place
people will want to make their homes for the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said that when there are too many things to do at
night, so you have to miss some of the things you want to see, the
place is turning into a real city,'' Zeitlin said. ``That is
starting to happen here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
