<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Feb. 14. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEIGHBOR (Phoenix) _ Tidy homes with flower pots on fence posts.
Inviting benches under shade trees. A neighborhood barber shop.
This is a community where federal dollars help neighbors better
themselves, like the $40,000 loan that helped Marc Rogers expand
his business. It's a community where crime statistics have dropped
significantly since 1996. And it's the same community that saw nine
people gunned down in less than 72 hours. The toll: six dead, three
injured and a week's worth of glare in the media spotlight. BY
CHRIS FISCUS. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CAR-LEASE (undated) _ Glendale resident Robert Haran drove his
truck to a Phoenix leasing company, desperate for a $500 loan.
After a flurry of paper signing, he drove out with money, daily
lease payments for the truck he no longer owned and, if the deal is
figured like a loan, an annual interest rate of nearly 260 percent.
Haran, like thousands of Arizonans unable to get loans from banks,
credit unions, family or friends, is turning to a growing state
industry of sale/lease-back businesses. By PAT KOSSAN. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CARMOB _ Arizona legislators came perilously close to opening the
state to a Georgia-based lending company with alleged ties to
organized crime. Two Valley lawmakers introduced a bill last year
that would have let the lenders charge annual interest rates as
high as 300 percent on loans secured by car titles _ more than
eight times the current cap. By PAT KOSSAN. Story will move in the
``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ART _ As the $10 million Scottsdale Museum of Contemporary Art
opens Sunday _ and the $18.2 million Heard Museum expansion opens
in two weeks _ perhaps Phoenix will finally begin to put to rest
the inferiority complex that has plagued it over its supposed lack
of cultural scope and sophistication. By RICHARD NILSEN. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NUDE-CAR (New River, Ariz.) _ What now in Arizona? A car show at a
nudist colony, giving new meaning to the term, Cruisin'. By RICHARD
RUELAS. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Undated) _ Arizona Sen. John Sidney McCain III is
no longer a prisoner of war, but for the next two years he'll play
one on TV. And in the newpapers. And on radio. And billboards. And
bumper stickers. And campaign buttons. And so on. The one thing
McCain desparately wants to become _ president _ is completely
dependant on the one thing McCain desparately wanted to avoid
becoming _ a POW. By E.J. MONTINI Story will move in the ``A'' and
``K'' categories. &QL;
</P>
