<HEADLINE>
CAR BUFFS IN THE BUFF; RESORT PUTS ITS LIFESTYLE ON ON DISPLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW RIVER, Ariz. _ Only one convertible, but several tops down
Saturday at the nudist car show.
</P>
<P>
   And some bottoms too.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day to display bodies down at the Shangri-La Nudist
Resort in New River. Most were bright, shiny and attractive. The
ones on the cars, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not bashful,'' said Wes Prescott, in a huge
understatement. Technically, the 70-year-old wasn't nude _ loafers
covered his feet and socks sheltered his legs up to the knees. ``I
think human bodies are the most beautiful things in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   A close second in his admiration Saturday was a cherry-red 1929
Ford Model A _ a car just as old as he.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's broken down more times in its life than I
have,'' he chuckled.
</P>
<P>
   More than 580 buttoned-up types showed up at the nudist colony,
said Horst Kraus, the resort's owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest influx of textiled (clothed) folks we've ever
had,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the most fabric at the nudist resort is the huge
American flag flapping in the breeze. But Kraus said all the
clothes on display at Saturday's car show didn't chap the nudists'
hide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't give a hoot,'' he said. ``To us, it's a natural way
of living.''
</P>
<P>
   The nudists did have something up their sleeves. The resort
owner thought that auto enthusiasts lured to the resort would
cotton to life without clothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could happen,'' said Garrett Beckman, 18, of Phoenix. ``But
not today.''
</P>
<P>
   Leilani Hill, 19, of Phoenix, was giggling non-stop, the sight
of bare bodies, keeping her in stitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no,'' she said when asked about getting in the altogether.
``Maybe if I was in Hawaii.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kraus said that even if he didn't sell anybody a membership
to the resort, it's worth it to expose the bare facts about the
nudist lifestyle to the public: They're not a bunch of young,
taut-bodied, nymphomaniacs.
</P>
<P>
   Much to the disappointment of some.
</P>
<P>
   The nudist resort has strict requirements for entry and
membership, Kraus said. Gawkers and pickup artists are not allowed.
Saturday's car show was probably the only time someone could
compliment the condition of someone's seat and not be kicked out.
</P>
<P>
   Nudists also got a chance to wax poetic about being in the buff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids who grow up here learn to look you straight in the
face,'' said Don Morse, 57, of Peoria, ``and they're very polite.''
</P>
<P>
   Car owners often found themselves jawing with naked men. But
that seemed to be lost among the talk of buying stripped-down cars
and investing a pound of flesh to restore them.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Gomez, 67, of Phoenix, gladly accepted Morse's naked
compliment on his 1935 Ford pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez offered a compliment of his own: ``I like your tan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's dull right now,'' Morse said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will get better,'' Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   As a car show, it wasn't much. Only about 25 cars had their
hoods up for inspection. Owners showed up for the same reason
others did: curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect it to be as open as it is,'' said Rich
Kragner, 37, of Phoenix, sitting next to his 1966 Dodge Charger.
``It's not for me, but its OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Kragner said he might consider doffing his duds if he wasn't
surrounded by other auto buffs he'd see at the next car show.
</P>
<P>
   But he did learn something in his hours at the resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder to keep a (human) body up. It's easier to keep a
car up.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ruelas can be reached at 444-8473 or at
richard.ruelas(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
S
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
