<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-DAYTONA-NB-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTH BRINGING IMPRESSIVE SKILLS TO NASCAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ NASCAR's future looks promising.
</P>
<P>
   Along with youngsters  &UR; Dale Earnhardt Jr. and  &UR; Matt Kenseth,
teenagers such as  &UR; Adam Petty and  &UR; Casey Atwood appear to have the
potential to be rising stars.
</P>
<P>
   Petty and Atwood each are 18 years old, and each driver spent
much of Saturday's NASCAR Busch Series race racing mightily with
the front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   Even race winner  &UR; Randy LaJoie, a two-time series champion, was
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good, real good,'' LaJoie said. ``I think I'll be
chasing them more than they'll be chasing me this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwood and Petty still were running second and third as late as
Lap 116 of the 120-lap race. Then, Petty fell out of the draft and
dropped back, finishing sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood was tagged from behind by  &UR; Andy Hillenburg on Lap 119 and
crashed hard near the start-finish line, winding up 17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming down to the white flag, it was show time,'' Hillenburg
said. ``I punched the 27 car (Atwood) to get him going because I
pretty much was figuring on shooting him to the lead and me going
to second, then try to put the same move on him down there in Turn
1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hated that we got into him, but, man, coming down to the
white flag at Daytona, you just don't back off. He lifted and I hit
him square. I didn't want to turn him because I could have turned
myself, too.'' &QL; 
Injury update &QL; 
Thankfully, there was only one serious injury from all the crashes
during Saturday's NASCAR Busch Series race.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Andy Santerre suffered a lower right leg fracture and will fly
home to Charlotte, N.C., where he likely will undergo surgery. &QL; 
Happy hour &QL; 
 &UR; Chad Little was Chad Big during the final NASCAR Winston Cup
practice late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Little went 192.353 mph, the fastest of all drivers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Terry Labonte was next at 192.217 and Bobby Hamilton was third
fastest at 192.189 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Pole-sitter  &UR; Jeff Gordon went 191.233 mph (10th fastest), and
defending champion  &UR; Dale Earnhardt was 14th at 191.115 mph. &QL; 
Passing interest &QL; 
Green Bay quarterback  &UR; Brett Favre and  &UR; Dale Jarrett have formed a
NASCAR Busch Series team in which Jarrett will drive in 11 races
and Winston Cup teammate  &UR; Kenny Irwin Jr. will start three.
</P>
<P>
   One of the targeted races is Nov. 6 at Phoenix International
Raceway, but it's uncertain who will drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up in Mississippi, I always thought that football was
Number 1, but when people found out I was going to the Daytona 500,
no one wanted to talk about Super Bowls or how we were going to do
next year,'' Favre said. ``They wanted to talk about how I could
get them tickets to get in the pits.'' &QL; 
Sterling and `The Duke' &QL; 
To aid the  &UR; John Wayne Cancer Institute, The Duke's likeness will
appear on the hood of  &UR; Sterling Marlin's car in two races this
season _ at the Nov. 7 race at Phoenix International Raceway and
the March 28 race at Texas Motor Speedway. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
