<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4827 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-DAYTONA-AD     02-13 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-DAYTONA-ADV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MISSION IMPOSSIBLE?  
 DAYTONA ROOKIE ACCEPTS CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ This is where it all started. This is
where NASCAR founder Bill France gathered together several friends
in a hotel lounge more than a half century ago and collectively
inhaled stock-car racing's first breath of salty air.
</P>
<P>
   My, how it's changed.
</P>
<P>
   But today in the Daytona 500 at Daytona International Speedway,
Tony Stewart could change it forever.
</P>
<P>
   By winning in front of the largest mass of humanity this side of
the Indianapolis 500, Stewart could become the first rookie in
NASCAR history to capture ``The Great American Race.''
</P>
<P>
   Some have made valiant efforts. All have failed.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Stewart will be different. Maybe, but not likely.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the talented newcomer nearly grabbed the pole position,
only to lose it to Jeff Gordon (195.067 mph), the final driver to
make a qualifying attempt.
</P>
<P>
   But qualifying and a 500-mile race are as different as a lamb
next to a wolf.
</P>
<P>
   In one, a driver is alone for two laps on a 2.5-mile paved oval,
alone to battle the asphalt and a ticking clock.
</P>
<P>
   In the other, a driver is forced to endure a near three-hour,
high-speed chase against 42 other cars, knowing the slightest
hiccup or wrong move could trigger an avalanche of crumpled
machinery.
</P>
<P>
   It's a daunting assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's one Stewart has waited nearly an entire life to tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always believed if you're a good race-car driver, you can
drive anything,'' said Stewart, whose credentials are impeccable
after collaring U.S. Auto Club's ``Triple Crown (Silver Bullet,
sprint and midget championships) in 1995 and, then, the Indy Racing
League crown two years later. ``There are a lot of good race
drivers that have done that. Jeff's (Gordon) one of them. He drove
quarter-midgets, sprint cars and midgets, then came (to NASCAR) and
was successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did the same thing and went to Indy cars from those things.
I didn't go up through Indy Lights. I think with a good race
driver, you put him in the right equipment, he's going to show what
he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 27, has a bullfighter's bravado. If he's frightened or
even somewhat leery of the immediate task, it's hidden beneath
steely eyes.
</P>
<P>
   No, Stewart can't be intimidated. But he can be beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was snookered by one of the sport's all-time bests, if
not the best, in a Twin 125 qualifying race Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt easily pushed by Stewart to take the lead early
in the race, then watched in his rear-view mirror as Stewart was
shuffled backwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot,'' said Stewart, who, with car owner Joe
Gibbs' blessing, also will make an effort to win May's Indy 500.
``(But) if I told you what I learned, I'd be telling everybody else
what I'd learned and I'm not going to help them any.''
</P>
<P>
   What Stewart learned is what everybody learns the first time he
is placed in the dicey throes of a restrictor plate race.
</P>
<P>
   One bobble and it's bye-bye baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll learn,'' Earnhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, everyone learns.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone wins the Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   It took Earnhardt 20 miserable years to finally end the one
mountain he had failed to scale.
</P>
<P>
   It took Darrell Waltrip 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace never has won it and he's been driving full-time
since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto Terry Labonte, whose Daytona skunkings go back to 1979.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget Mark Martin. Although one of the sport's most
proficient and respected drivers, Martin can't seem to buy a
respectable Daytona showing.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, however, refuses to let one race spoil an entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is one memory of Daytona that stands out, it would be
disappointment,'' Martin said. ``I haven't had the triumphs that I
would be looking for here.
</P>
<P>
   ``But to win would just be another trophy on the mantel. I
wouldn't put any additional emphasis on it. I race every race to
win. Whether we win them all, run second in them all or run last in
them all, we still give our best effort every race.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens to Martin, to Wallace, to Labonte or even to
Stewart this year, there always will be next year. And the year
after that.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart knows it. So does Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this (season) is going to be a tough step, a big step
for us,'' said Gibbs, a three-time Super Bowl-winning coach with
the Washington Redskins. ``But we looked long and hard to try and
find the right driver, and we think we found him.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember hearing Tony Stewart's name quite a bit and knew he
was really going to be a great race car driver,'' Gordon said. ``I
think it's a great asset to NASCAR Winston Cup racing to have him
in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being involved with Joe Gibbs Racing and having good sponsors,
that gives him the same opportunities that I had in (1993) when I
was a rookie and look how it's paid off for me. I think the same
things are going to come for Tony.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, just maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to get schooled a lot,'' said Stewart. ``It's those
lessons that you learn that you have to remember in order to be
successful in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me, it's a big book. It's bigger than the
``Encyclopaedia Britannica.'' There's chapter after chapter that
must be learned in order to be good in this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Stewart has learned nearly enough to be good enough to
win the Daytona 500 is a question yet to be answered. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
