<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-DAY-BUSCH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUTION FLAG HELPS LAJOIE WIN NAPA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ About the only undamaged piece of hardware
to survive the crash-filled NAPA Auto Parts 300 on Saturday at
Daytona International Speedway was the trophy Randy LaJoie held
aloft in victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   Five accidents, including a spectacular wreck that somehow
spared teenage whiz Casey Atwood injury, marred the season-opening
NASCAR Busch Series race.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one was seriously injured, NASCAR's garage looked
like a junkyard afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the crashes involved multiple vehicles. Five in one,
eight in another and a whopping 10 in a third.
</P>
<P>
   But the most frightening accident involved only Atwood, who took
a hit from a trailing Andy Hillenburg as the field neared the start
of the final lap.
</P>
<P>
   The impact sent Atwood, who had been running second to LaJoie,
into the wall and upside down on the Chevrolet Monte Carlo's roof.
The car continued sliding on its roof until it reached the grassy
infield, which lifted the machine and sent it into a series of four
barrel rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood's mangled heap came to rest right-side up 40 feet past
the finish line, and a second later, he crawled out and waved to
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wondered what that felt like (flipping),'' Atwood
said. ``Now I know. I don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The accident forced the 120-lap race to end under the shield of
a caution flag, which probably suited LaJoie and the remaining
survivors from the original 43-car starting field just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Atwood go for his ride (in my mirror),'' LaJoie said.
``Wow.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Adam Petty, son of Kyle Petty and grandson of the great
Richard Petty, was running third late in the race until faulty
handling dropped him to sixth at the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   When Petty spotted Atwood, he grew concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably my best friend at the racetrack,'' said Petty,
who like Atwood, is only 18 and deemed a rising star. ``Some of the
moves (drivers) were making, I wouldn't even make on a computer
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Hillin, who finished fifth, also didn't like what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had to do this (restrictor-plate racing) every week, I
don't know if I'd be a race-car driver,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   LaJoie was just happy to finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured somebody would make a run at me,'' said LaJoie, who
passed runner-up Jeff Green on Lap 101. ``I thought I could keep
them at bay a little bit, but I was going to make my car wide if I
had to there at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   LaJoie didn't have to, but he did need the help of a Lap 59
caution flag.
</P>
<P>
   LaJoie, who was on pit road getting serviced for a loose rear
tire, was able to remain on the lead lap because of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a break,'' LaJoie said. ``That saved our day. Our left
rear tire came loose and I thought I was going to wreck on the
backstretch. Then, we came in, got the (caution) flag and we're
able to stay on the lead lap.''
</P>
<P>
   An eight-car, Lap 78 accident ended an impressive run by
defending series champion Dale Earnhardt Jr. Earnhardt, who crashed
during happy hour practice Friday, had to start at the rear in a
back-up car.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
