<SLUG> BC-R-GA-BLACK-DOCTOR-1100-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR RETURNS HOME TO SAVANNAH TO SERVE THE POOR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to correct coding)   By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Dr. Debbie Davis recently burst into an
examining room of the Westside Urban Health Center on the ragged
stretch of Bay Street, about four miles west of the historic
district's cobblestones and serene Colonial squares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me get my hug,'' she told Mary Gray, 73, a retired mental
home housemother who beamed and threw out her arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for my Christmas present,'' Dr. Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling up her stool, squeezing her patient's knee, Dr. Davis
asked ``What is it today?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rashes,'' said Ms. Gray, who has some hypertension and
arthritis chronically.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor examined the rash on Ms. Gray's arms, declared it
hives, then moved to other issues. ``Your blood pressure looks
fabulous,'' Dr. Davis said. ``Your weight is OK. You're looking
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor made Ms. Gray an appointment for a pap smear. ``For
the rashes,'' Dr. Davis said, ``we'll go with the shot, the salve
and the pill.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Phoenix-Davis is an exuberant but harried pioneer in
minority and indigent medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Like many poor urban neighborhoods and rural communities, those
served by the three Westside Urban Health Center clinics are short
of doctors, black or white. There are few African-American doctors
relative to the nation's black population.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, in a population that is 13 percent black, less than
4 percent of all doctors are black. In Savannah, where more than 50
percent of the 137,000 residents are black, 30 of 540 physicians
are black, or less than 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the disparities have stirred concern among advocates of
African-Americans, as well as historically black medical schools
like Morehouse, especially in the face of new research showing
disparities in the health of black and white Americans. Blacks have
shorter productive lives than whites and experience more prostate
cancer, strokes, heart disease, AIDS and obesity and deaths from
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Davis understands the way they live, the flaws in their
diets and the financial constraints that sometimes make health care
a low priority. The patients say they find her easy to talk to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not taking the position that the problem of
African-Americans need be solved only by having more black
physicians,'' said Dr. Louis Sullivan, the president of Morehouse,
who was Secretary of Health and Human Services in the Bush
Administration. ``A white physician can be just as effective.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sullivan said familiarity with patients' race and heritage
led to better care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's knowing what questions to ask,'' Sullivan said. ``It's
knowing that if you prescribe a $50 medicine, the patient might not
have the funds. And it's trust, communication, things that affect
compliance. Coming back to the doctor when they should. Taking
medicine when they should.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Davis rose from this largely black neighborhood of housing
projects to become student body president at Savannah High School
and graduate fourth in her class of 400. With scholarships and
loans she went on to graduate from Emory University and the
Morehouse School of Medicine. Seven years ago, the mother of two,
Dr. Davis returned to serve the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one black surgeon in Savannah,'' Dr. Davis said, ``no
black nephrologist, one black gastroenterologist, two black
pediatricians, both women, no black dermatologists.''
</P>
<P>
   A visit in one of Dr. Davis' examining rooms is an occasion to
chat about family members, and for the many who share her Christian
faith, a moment to celebrate the healing powers of the Lord. An
ordained Pentacostal minister, Dr. Davis jokes that she dispenses
``Gospills'' and writes ``prescriptures.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinics like those where Dr. Davis works are straining these
days as the number of the uninsured people grows, to more than 43
million now, according to the Census Bureau, about 12 million more
than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Savannah, the poor, the uninsured and the underinsured can
turn to the Westside clinics, which, with the support of federal
and Chatham County subsidies, charge $12 a visit and nothing at all
to penniless patients.
</P>
<P>
   For patients in need of specialists, except in immediate
life-threatening cases, Dr. Davis said: ``I have to send them to
specialty clinics because the doctors won't see them in their
offices. And they have clinics only once a week or once a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, however, impedes the care of Osborne Lemon, 62, for
whom Dr. Davis has become more than the crutch supporting his
health. Retired two years ago as a maintenance man for the local
housing authority, he is diabetic and blind in one eye and has
congestive heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was instrumental in helping me obtain my disability,''
Lemon said. ``She wrote them a letter.'' He was deemed eligible for
a Social Security disability check, of $697 a month, and that made
him eligible for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a crimson beret, jeans and a Van Gogh beard, ashen-faced
with fear, Lemon sat one day in a clinic examining room. He had
gained 20 pounds in a week and that morning he had awakened
coughing and gasping.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Davis told him that because of his heart condition, his
lungs were filling with fluid. Pills would not do. He needed high
doses of an intravenous diuretic, and for that he would have to go
to Candler General Hospital. ``This is mild and it's early,'' she
assured him.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Davis says she perseveres. She attributes that to her
parents, now divorced. Her father, a laborer for a trucking
company, rues having dropped out of high school. Her mother, an
elementary school teacher, earned a master's degree in education.
``They stressed education,'' Dr. Davis said. ``Stressed it,
stressed it, stressed it.''
</P>
<P>
   The summer after her freshman year at Emory, it all seemed for
naught. ``I got pregnant,'' she said. ``I was depressed. I was
going to call it all quits. But my mom told me to move past it, and
she took my son so I could finish school.''
</P>
<P>
   A month after the birth of her son, now a freshman at Georgia
Tech, the doctor said, ``I got saved and gave my life to Christ.''
She married in medical school, had her daughter, now 11, and was
divorced five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a student, she came to know the debt and dunning notices that
ravage the poor. Her biggest debt now is the $80,000 she owes for
medical school, which she is paying off at a rate of $1,000 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   A lesson learned about debt, she bought her red eight-year-old
Ford Explorer used, for $10,000 cash. She and her daughter live in
a black subdivision, in a 2,400-square-foot house with three
bedrooms and two-and-a-half baths that she bought three years ago
for $96,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Davis' salary is $112,000, of which she gives 10 percent to
her church. She said she had never given a thought to a
better-paying career in private medicine because a salaried job
allows her to spend more time with patients. Hefty, at 5 feet 5
inches, Dr. Davis relates to obesity among black women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier to bring about change when you are part of what
you are trying to change,'' she said. ``I was raised on pigs' feet
and pigs' tails. Cottage cheese? Get real.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   She opened the door to an examining room and greeted a
43-year-old patient, a woman near tears. ``Knees are hurting,'' she
told the doctor. ``The weight got them.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman weighed 414 pounds. The doctor discussed diet pills
and nutrition with the patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm down to 235 from 265 in two years,'' Dr. Davis said. ``If
I can do it, you can do it. If you get to 250-260, that's
reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients here discuss their preference for Dr. Davis not in
terms of race but in those of manner and style.
</P>
<P>
   Annie Kearse, 69, who is black and suffers from hypertension,
has watched Dr. Davis from childhood. ``I just like what she is,''
Mrs. Kearse said. ``I'm so proud of her. She comes from out of my
neighborhood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
