<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-13 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-STJOHNS-VILLANOVA     02-13 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHNS-VILLANOVA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S BEATS VILLANOVA, 82-75  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Jarvis stood on the baseline for a few minutes
during the game Saturday night, his hands on his hips, surrounded
by the St. John's cheerleaders, looking like an overgrown,
overdressed pep squad member with little to celebrate. The Red
Storm was struggling to establish its offense in the first half
against Villanova and only much later, when his team was up by 15
late in the second half and Villanova had taken its second timeout
within a minute, did Jarvis seem to relax.
</P>
<P>
   Not for long. No. 11 St. John's blew a large lead late in the
second half, a troubling pattern lately, before beating Villanova,
82-75, with the breathtaking passes and powerful rebounds now
expected of a team marching toward the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any bad news from this game, it came near the end,
when Bootsy Thornton left the court doubled over in pain after
re-aggravating a sprain of his left thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, playing with his thumb heavily taped, had 14 points
and 17 rebounds Saturday night, but it was unclear what his
condition would be for St. John's game Monday against Providence.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's (20-6, 11-3) received a boost from Tyrone Grant
returning to the starting lineup at center. Grant had 8 points and
grabbed nine rebounds in the first half. He had missed a month with
a fracture in his right wrist, a time that Grant found frustrating
as he watched his teammates squander leads as they came close to
beating Duke and Connecticut, a phenomenon Coach Mike Jarvis
blamed, in part, on exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   With Grant's return, St. John's was back to full strength _ and
a full complement of offensive options _ with just five games left
in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides the obvious that he's going to get you 10 rebounds and
10 points, he gives you a presence that we really don't have,''
Jarvis said before the game. ``He's a legitimate inside scoring
threat. Forget about the fact that he's not really a center, that's
how we have to play him. And he gives us another heady veteran who
really knows the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Villanova (18-7, 9-6) has been one of the hottest Big East teams
over the last month. The Wildcats point guard John Celestand leads
the league in assists in Big East games (he had 26 assists to five
turnovers in his previous three games). Villanova had won seven of
its last eight before Saturday night, and seems assured of
receiving an invitation to the National Collegiate Athletic
Association Tournament just one year after going 12-17 in the wake
of the sudden departure of Tim Thomas for the National Basketball
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Steve Lappas' switch to a smaller, more mobile lineup _
center Rafal Bigus was sent to the bench, Malik Allen moved to
center from power forward and freshman Brooks Sales took over at
power forward _ has meant better ball-handling and defensive
matchups. Villanova's rise from the middle of the pack with no
stars to a league power was obvious in a 75-60 humbling of Syracuse
in the Carrier Dome, when the Wildcats held the Orangemen to 32.3
percent shooting from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Villanova is still a bigger team than St. John's, a fact that
gave Lappas little comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to box out,'' he said before the game. ``They're a
tremendous offensive rebounding team. When people talk about teams
being big, they're athletic and quick and that's what makes them
such great, tenacious rebounders. The big thing is to limit them to
one shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Villanova did that for the early part of the first half. St.
John's played poorly at both ends of the court early, failing to
solve Villanova's zone defense (they shot just 37.5 percent from
the field and were 3 of 16 from 3-point range) and compounded the
problem by not pounding the offensive boards until midway through
the first half. The Red Storm fell behind by 15-6 and seemed unable
to deal with Villanova's fine perimeter shooters.
</P>
<P>
   On one of his two first-half 3-pointers, the closest member of
the St. John's team to Brian Lynch was Jarvis. A Ron Artest
3-pointer and Reggie Jessie layup closed the gap, but they quickly
faded to an 8-point deficit, 26-18, with 8:24 left.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's seemed to be in trouble then, with Artest and Erick
Barkley both on the bench with two fouls and Villanova still
hitting from outside. They were 7 of 16 on 3-pointers, including 3
of 4 from Celestand. Jarvis even had St. John's playing a zone
defense for a while.
</P>
<P>
   But St. John's seemed to find its offensive rhythm and its
toughness on the boards when Barkley and Artest returned to the
game with 8:14 left. Artest, who had eight first-half points, had a
lay-in, Grant had a layup and finished the 3-point play and after a
3-pointer by Jermaine Medley, Jessie grabbed an offensive rebound
and layup to close the Villanova lead to 3 points.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's finished the first half with 11 offensive rebounds
and had 10 second chance points in the first half as they rallied
to lead at the half by 37-36 when Thornton tipped in a Chudney Gray
miss at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   The start of the second half was like watching a recent NBA
game: lots of fouls, little scoring.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's had five team fouls with 15:00 left and Villanova did
not score in the first five minutes of the half. Then again, St.
John's got only a layup from Lavor Postell to hold its lead at
39-38.
</P>
<P>
   An Artest offensive rebound and layup and an Artest layup on a
three-on-one following a Jessie rebound opened St. John's biggest
lead, 53-48, with 13:54 left to play.
</P>
<P>
   The run went on from there, with Jessie leading three straight
possessions with three magnificent passes.
</P>
<P>
   But St. John's, which has struggled to put away recent opponents
even after gaining a big lead, withered again.
</P>
<P>
   After a few missed foul shots, a bad foul by Barkley on
Celestand for a 3-point play and a Lynch 3-pointer, the lead was
down to 76-71 with :28.3 left.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
